export const LEGACY_BLOG_POSTS: LegacyBlogPost[] = [{"slug":"best-innoveyes-lasik-in-delhi-2026-cost-top-doctors-complete-guide","date":"2026-03-11","title":"Best InnovEyes LASIK in Delhi (2026): Cost, Top Doctors & Complete Guide","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2026/03/11/best-innoveyes-lasik-in-delhi-2026-cost-top-doctors-complete-guide","contentHtml":"<h1 data-section-id=\"1dudm71\" data-start=\"0\" data-end=\"74\">Best InnovEyes LASIK in Delhi (2026): Cost, Top Doctors &amp; Complete Guide</h1>\n<p data-start=\"76\" data-end=\"388\">Laser vision correction has advanced significantly in recent years, and <strong data-start=\"148\" data-end=\"167\">InnovEyes LASIK</strong> is now considered one of the most advanced procedures for permanent specs removal. Patients in Delhi now have access to this cutting-edge technology at select eye hospitals that specialize in advanced refractive surgery.</p>\n<p data-start=\"390\" data-end=\"560\">If you are searching for the <strong data-start=\"419\" data-end=\"452\">best InnovEyes LASIK in Delhi</strong>, this guide explains the procedure, cost, benefits, recovery, and leading hospitals offering the treatment.</p>\n<h2 data-section-id=\"1tcpsoc\" data-start=\"567\" data-end=\"594\">What is InnovEyes LASIK?</h2>\n<p data-start=\"596\" data-end=\"882\"><strong data-start=\"596\" data-end=\"637\">InnovEyes (WaveLight® Plus InnovEyes)</strong> is the latest generation of laser vision correction technology developed by Alcon. It uses <strong data-start=\"729\" data-end=\"766\">AI-powered ray-tracing technology</strong> to analyse the entire optical system of the eye instead of just the cornea.</p>\n<p data-start=\"884\" data-end=\"1143\">The system creates a <strong data-start=\"905\" data-end=\"947\">3D digital model of the eye (EyeVatar)</strong> and simulates the surgery before the laser treatment begins. This allows surgeons to deliver highly personalized vision correction with improved precision.</p>\n<p data-start=\"1145\" data-end=\"1166\">Key features include:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"1168\" data-end=\"1358\">\n<li data-section-id=\"c66vtw\" data-start=\"1168\" data-end=\"1194\">\n<p data-start=\"1170\" data-end=\"1194\">AI-driven eye analysis</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"112sokf\" data-start=\"1195\" data-end=\"1225\">\n<p data-start=\"1197\" data-end=\"1225\">Ray-tracing laser planning</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"u0mcbe\" data-start=\"1226\" data-end=\"1266\">\n<p data-start=\"1228\" data-end=\"1266\">Fully personalized vision correction</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"70uxa6\" data-start=\"1267\" data-end=\"1318\">\n<p data-start=\"1269\" data-end=\"1318\">Potential to achieve better than <strong data-start=\"1302\" data-end=\"1316\">6/6 vision</strong></p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"6idgya\" data-start=\"1319\" data-end=\"1358\">\n<p data-start=\"1321\" data-end=\"1358\">Reduced glare and better night vision</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"1360\" data-end=\"1495\">Because of these advanced capabilities, InnovEyes is considered one of the <strong data-start=\"1435\" data-end=\"1494\">most advanced LASIK procedures available globally today</strong>.</p>\n<h2 data-section-id=\"ucn8w4\" data-start=\"1502\" data-end=\"1541\">InnovEyes LASIK Cost in Delhi (2026)</h2>\n<p data-start=\"1543\" data-end=\"1642\">The cost of InnovEyes LASIK depends on the hospital, technology platform, and surgeon’s experience.</p>\n<p data-start=\"1644\" data-end=\"1673\">Typical price range in Delhi:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"1675\" data-end=\"1812\">\n<li data-section-id=\"j2vrup\" data-start=\"1675\" data-end=\"1756\">\n<p data-start=\"1677\" data-end=\"1756\"><strong data-start=\"1677\" data-end=\"1716\">₹1,20,000 – ₹1,50,000 for both eyes</strong></p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"1lpa208\" data-start=\"1757\" data-end=\"1812\">\n<p data-start=\"1759\" data-end=\"1812\">Some centres may charge <strong data-start=\"1783\" data-end=\"1812\">₹65,000 – ₹85,000 per eye</strong></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 data-section-id=\"c2vec2\" data-start=\"1814\" data-end=\"1859\">Comparison with Other Laser Eye Surgeries</h3>\n<div class=\"TyagGW_tableContainer\">\n<div class=\"group TyagGW_tableWrapper flex flex-col-reverse w-fit\" tabindex=\"-1\">\n<table class=\"w-fit min-w-(--thread-content-width)\" data-start=\"1861\" data-end=\"2125\">\n<thead data-start=\"1861\" data-end=\"1900\">\n<tr data-start=\"1861\" data-end=\"1900\">\n<th class=\"\" data-start=\"1861\" data-end=\"1873\" data-col-size=\"sm\">Procedure</th>\n<th class=\"\" data-start=\"1873\" data-end=\"1900\" data-col-size=\"sm\">Approx Cost (Both Eyes)</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody data-start=\"1911\" data-end=\"2125\">\n<tr data-start=\"1911\" data-end=\"1953\">\n<td data-start=\"1911\" data-end=\"1932\" data-col-size=\"sm\">Conventional LASIK</td>\n<td data-col-size=\"sm\" data-start=\"1932\" data-end=\"1953\">₹30,000 – ₹70,000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr data-start=\"1954\" data-end=\"1991\">\n<td data-start=\"1954\" data-end=\"1968\" data-col-size=\"sm\">Femto LASIK</td>\n<td data-col-size=\"sm\" data-start=\"1968\" data-end=\"1991\">₹80,000 – ₹1,00,000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr data-start=\"1992\" data-end=\"2033\">\n<td data-start=\"1992\" data-end=\"2010\" data-col-size=\"sm\">Contoura Vision</td>\n<td data-col-size=\"sm\" data-start=\"2010\" data-end=\"2033\">₹95,000 – ₹1,05,000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr data-start=\"2034\" data-end=\"2073\">\n<td data-start=\"2034\" data-end=\"2050\" data-col-size=\"sm\">SMILE Surgery</td>\n<td data-col-size=\"sm\" data-start=\"2050\" data-end=\"2073\">₹90,000 – ₹1,30,000</td>\n</tr>\n<tr data-start=\"2074\" data-end=\"2125\">\n<td data-start=\"2074\" data-end=\"2096\" data-col-size=\"sm\"><strong data-start=\"2076\" data-end=\"2095\">InnovEyes LASIK</strong></td>\n<td data-col-size=\"sm\" data-start=\"2096\" data-end=\"2125\"><strong data-start=\"2098\" data-end=\"2123\">₹1,20,000 – ₹1,50,000</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p data-start=\"2127\" data-end=\"2265\">The higher cost reflects the <strong data-start=\"2156\" data-end=\"2246\">advanced diagnostics, AI-based treatment planning, and high-precision laser technology</strong>used in InnovEyes.</p>\n<h1 data-section-id=\"1fpflyl\" data-start=\"2272\" data-end=\"2321\">Eye Hospitals Offering InnovEyes LASIK in Delhi</h1>\n<p data-start=\"2323\" data-end=\"2422\">Several advanced eye centres in Delhi NCR have introduced this latest technology for specs removal.</p>\n<h2 data-section-id=\"x00cns\" data-start=\"2424\" data-end=\"2464\"><span class=\"\" data-state=\"closed\"><span class=\"hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline\"><span class=\"whitespace-normal\">Eye7 Chaudhary Eye Centre</span></span></span></h2>\n<p data-start=\"2466\" data-end=\"2803\">One of the most well-known refractive surgery centres in Delhi, Eye7 offers <strong data-start=\"2542\" data-end=\"2577\">WaveLight® Plus InnovEyes LASIK</strong> along with Contoura Vision, SILK, and ICL procedures. The hospital introduced InnovEyes in 2024 and highlights AI-powered ray-tracing diagnostics for fully personalized laser treatment.</p>\n<p data-start=\"2805\" data-end=\"2820\">Key highlights:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"2822\" data-end=\"2967\">\n<li data-section-id=\"1nnc2go\" data-start=\"2822\" data-end=\"2860\">\n<p data-start=\"2824\" data-end=\"2860\">Advanced AI-based LASIK technology</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"xbghuh\" data-start=\"2861\" data-end=\"2896\">\n<p data-start=\"2863\" data-end=\"2896\">Experienced refractive surgeons</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"1c7vr2m\" data-start=\"2897\" data-end=\"2931\">\n<p data-start=\"2899\" data-end=\"2931\">Multiple branches in Delhi NCR</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"h2zbcu\" data-start=\"2932\" data-end=\"2967\">\n<p data-start=\"2934\" data-end=\"2967\">Comprehensive pre-LASIK screening</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"2969\" data-end=\"3064\">Eye7 is widely known for treating patients seeking <strong data-start=\"3020\" data-end=\"3063\">high-precision specs removal procedures</strong>.</p>\n<h2 data-section-id=\"jjcmag\" data-start=\"3071\" data-end=\"3111\"><span class=\"\" data-state=\"closed\"><span class=\"hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline\"><span class=\"whitespace-normal\">Healing Touch Eye Centre</span></span></span></h2>\n<p data-start=\"3113\" data-end=\"3396\">Healing Touch Eye Centre is another advanced refractive surgery centre offering <strong data-start=\"3193\" data-end=\"3227\">WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK</strong> in Delhi. The procedure combines AI diagnostics and ray-tracing technology to deliver highly customized laser vision correction.</p>\n<p data-start=\"3398\" data-end=\"3609\">The centre is led by experienced ophthalmologists including <strong data-start=\"3458\" data-end=\"3478\">Dr. Piyush Kapur</strong>, a high-volume refractive surgeon with extensive experience in LASIK and cataract surgery.</p>\n<p data-start=\"3611\" data-end=\"3624\">Key features:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"3626\" data-end=\"3785\">\n<li data-section-id=\"1i1b8ct\" data-start=\"3626\" data-end=\"3675\">\n<p data-start=\"3628\" data-end=\"3675\">Advanced laser vision correction technologies</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"xbghuh\" data-start=\"3676\" data-end=\"3711\">\n<p data-start=\"3678\" data-end=\"3711\">Experienced refractive surgeons</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"61u4ro\" data-start=\"3712\" data-end=\"3741\">\n<p data-start=\"3714\" data-end=\"3741\">Personalized patient care</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"13gf3q1\" data-start=\"3742\" data-end=\"3785\">\n<p data-start=\"3744\" data-end=\"3785\">LASIK, ICL, and cataract surgery services</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 data-section-id=\"1k85mm0\" data-start=\"3792\" data-end=\"3832\"><span class=\"\" data-state=\"closed\"><span class=\"hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline\"><span class=\"whitespace-normal\">ICARE Eye Hospital</span></span></span></h2>\n<p data-start=\"3834\" data-end=\"4012\">ICARE Eye Hospital is a <strong data-start=\"3858\" data-end=\"3913\">tertiary eye care institute in the Delhi NCR region</strong> known for advanced diagnostic and surgical infrastructure.</p>\n<p data-start=\"4014\" data-end=\"4038\">The hospital focuses on:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"4040\" data-end=\"4179\">\n<li data-section-id=\"1dlzw1e\" data-start=\"4040\" data-end=\"4077\">\n<p data-start=\"4042\" data-end=\"4077\">Advanced eye surgery technologies</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"vs5lqy\" data-start=\"4078\" data-end=\"4118\">\n<p data-start=\"4080\" data-end=\"4118\">Sub-specialty ophthalmology services</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"19vlcz1\" data-start=\"4119\" data-end=\"4149\">\n<p data-start=\"4121\" data-end=\"4149\">NABH-accredited facilities</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"ux45ru\" data-start=\"4150\" data-end=\"4179\">\n<p data-start=\"4152\" data-end=\"4179\">Modern diagnostic equipment</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"4181\" data-end=\"4305\">Many patients from Delhi and NCR visit ICARE for <strong data-start=\"4230\" data-end=\"4277\">advanced laser vision correction procedures</strong> and comprehensive eye care.</p>\n<h2 data-section-id=\"ao38gq\" data-start=\"4312\" data-end=\"4359\">Who is a Good Candidate for InnovEyes LASIK?</h2>\n<p data-start=\"4361\" data-end=\"4408\">You may be suitable for InnovEyes LASIK if you:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"4410\" data-end=\"4590\">\n<li data-section-id=\"4tzs06\" data-start=\"4410\" data-end=\"4437\">\n<p data-start=\"4412\" data-end=\"4437\">Are <strong data-start=\"4416\" data-end=\"4437\">18 years or older</strong></p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"4bb4u2\" data-start=\"4438\" data-end=\"4467\">\n<p data-start=\"4440\" data-end=\"4467\">Have stable spectacle power</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"5t12ne\" data-start=\"4468\" data-end=\"4508\">\n<p data-start=\"4470\" data-end=\"4508\">Have myopia, hyperopia, or astigmatism</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"kkz8w8\" data-start=\"4509\" data-end=\"4542\">\n<p data-start=\"4511\" data-end=\"4542\">Have adequate corneal thickness</p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"mzilhd\" data-start=\"4543\" data-end=\"4590\">\n<p data-start=\"4545\" data-end=\"4590\">Do not have severe dry eye or corneal disease</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"4592\" data-end=\"4663\">A detailed <strong data-start=\"4603\" data-end=\"4626\">pre-LASIK screening</strong> is essential to confirm eligibility.</p>\n<h2 data-section-id=\"1ii51bi\" data-start=\"4670\" data-end=\"4700\">Benefits of InnovEyes LASIK</h2>\n<h3 data-section-id=\"z3139\" data-start=\"4702\" data-end=\"4743\">Highly Personalized Vision Correction</h3>\n<p data-start=\"4744\" data-end=\"4847\">InnovEyes analyses thousands of optical data points and customizes treatment specifically for each eye.</p>\n<h3 data-section-id=\"1yb6yve\" data-start=\"4849\" data-end=\"4876\">Superior Visual Quality</h3>\n<p data-start=\"4877\" data-end=\"4959\">Many patients achieve <strong data-start=\"4899\" data-end=\"4923\">6/6 vision or better</strong> with improved clarity and contrast.</p>\n<h3 data-section-id=\"voje1x\" data-start=\"4961\" data-end=\"4978\">Fast Recovery</h3>\n<p data-start=\"4979\" data-end=\"5077\">Most patients experience clear vision within <strong data-start=\"5024\" data-end=\"5036\">24 hours</strong> and return to normal activities quickly.</p>\n<h3 data-section-id=\"1iubbgw\" data-start=\"5079\" data-end=\"5110\">Reduced Night Vision Issues</h3>\n<p data-start=\"5111\" data-end=\"5206\">The advanced mapping technology helps reduce <strong data-start=\"5156\" data-end=\"5175\">halos and glare</strong> compared to traditional LASIK.</p>\n<h2 data-section-id=\"16dl6ec\" data-start=\"5213\" data-end=\"5246\">Recovery After InnovEyes LASIK</h2>\n<p data-start=\"5248\" data-end=\"5274\">Recovery is usually quick.</p>\n<p data-start=\"5276\" data-end=\"5302\">Typical recovery timeline:</p>\n<p data-start=\"5304\" data-end=\"5486\"><strong data-start=\"5304\" data-end=\"5314\">Day 1:</strong> Mild irritation and light sensitivity<br data-start=\"5352\" data-end=\"5355\" /><strong data-start=\"5355\" data-end=\"5368\">24 Hours:</strong> Vision improves significantly<br data-start=\"5398\" data-end=\"5401\" /><strong data-start=\"5401\" data-end=\"5414\">3–5 Days:</strong> Resume work and daily activities<br data-start=\"5447\" data-end=\"5450\" /><strong data-start=\"5450\" data-end=\"5462\">1 Month:</strong> Vision stabilizes fully</p>\n<p data-start=\"5488\" data-end=\"5590\">Doctors usually recommend <strong data-start=\"5514\" data-end=\"5564\">lubricating eye drops and avoiding eye rubbing</strong> during the healing phase.</p>\n<p data-start=\"5615\" data-end=\"5900\">InnovEyes LASIK is currently one of the <strong data-start=\"5655\" data-end=\"5733\">most advanced laser vision correction procedures available in Delhi (2026)</strong>. With AI-powered diagnostics and ray-tracing technology, it provides extremely precise and personalized treatment for patients seeking permanent freedom from glasses.</p>\n<p data-start=\"5902\" data-end=\"5966\">Leading eye hospitals offering InnovEyes LASIK in Delhi include:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"5968\" data-end=\"6099\">\n<li data-section-id=\"x79p85\" data-start=\"5968\" data-end=\"6011\">\n<p data-start=\"5970\" data-end=\"6011\"><span class=\"\" data-state=\"closed\"><span class=\"hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline\"><span class=\"whitespace-normal\">Eye7 Chaudhary Eye Centre</span></span></span></p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"bgd20l\" data-start=\"6012\" data-end=\"6055\">\n<p data-start=\"6014\" data-end=\"6055\"><span class=\"\" data-state=\"closed\"><span class=\"hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline\"><span class=\"whitespace-normal\">Healing Touch Eye Centre</span></span></span></p>\n</li>\n<li data-section-id=\"1y51851\" data-start=\"6056\" data-end=\"6099\">\n<p data-start=\"6058\" data-end=\"6099\"><span class=\"\" data-state=\"closed\"><span class=\"hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline\"><span class=\"whitespace-normal\">ICARE Eye Hospital</span></span></span></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"6101\" data-end=\"6221\">Choosing an experienced surgeon and a centre with advanced diagnostics is essential to achieve the best visual outcomes.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Discover the best InnovEyes LASIK clinics in Delhi with a complete guide to costs, top doctors, and tips for choosing the right eye care center for advanced laser vision correction.</p>\n"},{"slug":"side-effects-of-wavelight-plus-innoveyes-lasik-what-you-need-to-know-before-surgery","date":"2026-02-25","title":"Side Effects of WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK: What You Need to Know Before Surgery","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2026/02/25/side-effects-of-wavelight-plus-innoveyes-lasik-what-you-need-to-know-before-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>LASIK eye surgery has evolved dramatically over the past few decades, and the combination of Alcon&#8217;s WaveLight EX500 excimer laser platform with InnovEyes technology represents one of the most advanced refractive surgery systems available today. While this cutting-edge laser system delivers exceptional precision and faster treatment times, it&#8217;s important for prospective patients to understand the potential side effects. In this comprehensive guide, we&#8217;ll explore the common, less common, and rare side effects associated with WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK so you can make a fully informed decision.</p>\n<h2>Understanding the WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK Platform</h2>\n<p>The WaveLight laser system, manufactured by Alcon, is renowned for its speed and accuracy. Operating at 500 Hz, the EX500 excimer laser is one of the fastest available, reducing overall treatment time and minimizing corneal dehydration during the procedure. When paired with InnovEyes diagnostic and planning technology, the system creates a highly personalized treatment map based on each patient&#8217;s unique corneal topography and wavefront measurements.</p>\n<p>Despite these technological advantages, LASIK—regardless of the platform used—carries inherent risks and side effects. The WaveLight Plus InnovEyes system may reduce certain complications compared to older technologies, but patients should still be aware of what to expect during recovery and beyond.</p>\n<h2>Common Side Effects After WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK</h2>\n<p>Most patients experience some degree of temporary side effects following their procedure. These are typically mild and resolve within days to weeks as the eyes heal.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Dry Eyes:</strong> This is the most frequently reported side effect after LASIK. The creation of the corneal flap temporarily disrupts nerves responsible for tear production. Patients may experience dryness, grittiness, or a burning sensation for several weeks to months. Artificial tears and prescription eye drops are commonly prescribed to manage symptoms.</li>\n<li><strong>Visual Fluctuations:</strong> In the first few days and weeks post-surgery, vision may fluctuate, especially during tasks like reading or screen use. The cornea is still stabilizing, and these fluctuations typically resolve as healing progresses.</li>\n<li><strong>Light Sensitivity:</strong> Increased sensitivity to bright lights, including sunlight and artificial lighting, is common in the initial recovery period. Wearing sunglasses outdoors is strongly recommended during this phase.</li>\n<li><strong>Halos and Glare:</strong> Many patients notice halos around lights or increased glare, particularly at night. While the WaveLight system&#8217;s advanced wavefront-optimized and topography-guided treatment profiles are specifically designed to reduce these aberrations, some patients may still experience them temporarily.</li>\n<li><strong>Mild Discomfort or Tearing:</strong> A mild scratchy sensation, watery eyes, or slight discomfort is normal within the first 24 to 48 hours after surgery. These symptoms typically subside quickly with proper rest and prescribed medications.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Less Common and Rare Side Effects</h2>\n<p>While the WaveLight Plus InnovEyes platform is designed to minimize complications, less common side effects can still occur in a small percentage of patients.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Undercorrection or Overcorrection:</strong> In some cases, the laser may remove too little or too much corneal tissue, resulting in residual refractive error. Enhancement procedures can often address these issues once the eyes have fully stabilized, typically after three to six months.</li>\n<li><strong>Regression:</strong> Some patients may experience a gradual return of their original prescription over time. This is more common in patients with higher degrees of myopia or hyperopia and may require a follow-up enhancement.</li>\n<li><strong>Flap Complications:</strong> Although rare with modern microkeratomes and femtosecond lasers, complications related to the corneal flap—such as wrinkles, displacement, or epithelial ingrowth—can occur. Proper post-operative care and follow-up appointments help detect and address these issues early.</li>\n<li><strong>Chronic Dry Eye:</strong> While most dry eye symptoms resolve within a few months, a small number of patients may develop persistent dry eye that requires ongoing treatment with lubricating drops, punctal plugs, or other therapies.</li>\n<li><strong>Diffuse Lamellar Keratitis (DLK):</strong> Also known as &#8220;Sands of the Sahara,&#8221; this inflammatory condition can develop under the corneal flap. It is typically detected during early post-operative visits and responds well to steroid eye drops when caught promptly.</li>\n<li><strong>Infection:</strong> Post-surgical infection is extremely rare but remains a possibility with any surgical procedure. Strict adherence to prescribed antibiotic eye drops and hygiene protocols significantly reduces this risk.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>How the WaveLight Plus InnovEyes System Minimizes Side Effects</h2>\n<p>One of the key advantages of the WaveLight Plus InnovEyes combination is its ability to reduce the likelihood and severity of certain side effects. The system achieves this through several technological innovations:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Topography-Guided Treatment:</strong> By mapping the cornea with extreme precision, the system corrects not only the patient&#8217;s refractive error but also subtle corneal irregularities that can contribute to higher-order aberrations like halos and glare.</li>\n<li><strong>High-Speed Laser Delivery:</strong> The 500 Hz pulse rate means less time on the treatment bed and reduced corneal exposure, which can decrease the risk of dehydration-related complications.</li>\n<li><strong>Advanced Eye Tracking:</strong> Real-time multidimensional eye tracking ensures that each laser pulse lands precisely where intended, even if the patient&#8217;s eye moves during the procedure. This reduces the chance of decentered ablations, which can cause visual distortions.</li>\n<li><strong>Wavefront-Optimized Profiles:</strong> These treatment profiles are designed to preserve the natural shape of the cornea, reducing the induction of spherical aberration that commonly causes night vision disturbances.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Conclusion: Making an Informed Decision</h2>\n<p>The WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK system represents a significant advancement in laser vision correction technology, offering faster procedures, enhanced precision, and treatment profiles specifically designed to minimize common side effects. However, like any surgical procedure, it carries some risks. Most side effects are temporary and manageable, resolving within the normal healing timeline. Serious complications are rare but possible.</p>\n<p>Before committing to LASIK, schedule a thorough consultation with a qualified refractive surgeon who uses the WaveLight Plus InnovEyes platform. Discuss your individual risk factors, medical history, and expectations openly. A comprehensive pre-operative evaluation will help determine whether you are a suitable candidate and what side effects you may be most likely to experience. With the right preparation and realistic expectations, WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK can be a life-changing procedure with overwhelmingly positive outcomes.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Considering WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK? Learn about the common, less common, and rare side effects associated with this advanced laser vision correction system, and discover how its technology is designed to minimize complications.</p>\n"},{"slug":"lasik-vs-glasses-comparing-the-long-term-risks-you-need-to-know-in-2025","date":"2026-02-25","title":"LASIK vs Glasses: Comparing the Long-Term Risks You Need to Know in 2025","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2026/02/25/lasik-vs-glasses-comparing-the-long-term-risks-you-need-to-know-in-2025","contentHtml":"<p>For millions of people living with nearsightedness, farsightedness, or astigmatism, the decision between LASIK eye surgery and traditional corrective glasses is a significant one. While both options effectively address vision problems, each carries its own set of long-term risks and considerations. Understanding these risks is essential for making an informed choice about your eye health and quality of life.</p>\n<p>In this comprehensive guide, we&#8217;ll break down the long-term risks associated with LASIK laser eye surgery and prescription glasses, helping you weigh the pros and cons of each option.</p>\n<h2>Understanding LASIK: How Laser Technology Reshapes Your Vision</h2>\n<p>LASIK (Laser-Assisted In Situ Keratomileusis) is a refractive surgery that uses a precise excimer laser to reshape the cornea, permanently correcting how light enters the eye. The procedure typically takes less than 30 minutes and offers rapid recovery times, with most patients experiencing improved vision within 24 hours.</p>\n<p>While LASIK technology has advanced dramatically since its FDA approval in 1999, it remains a surgical procedure — and all surgeries carry inherent risks. Modern femtosecond lasers and wavefront-guided technology have significantly reduced complication rates, but long-term risks still deserve careful consideration.</p>\n<h2>Long-Term Risks of LASIK Surgery</h2>\n<p>LASIK boasts an impressive satisfaction rate of over 96%, according to peer-reviewed studies. However, the following long-term risks should be on your radar:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Dry Eye Syndrome:</strong> One of the most common long-term side effects, chronic dry eye can persist for months or even years after LASIK. The laser procedure can damage corneal nerves responsible for tear production, leading to discomfort, irritation, and blurred vision.</li>\n<li><strong>Regression:</strong> Over time, some patients experience a gradual return of their original refractive error. This is more common in patients with high prescriptions and may require enhancement procedures or a return to corrective lenses.</li>\n<li><strong>Halos, Glare, and Starbursts:</strong> Some patients report persistent visual disturbances, especially at night. These symptoms can affect driving and other low-light activities and may not fully resolve over time.</li>\n<li><strong>Corneal Ectasia:</strong> In rare cases, the cornea can progressively thin and bulge after LASIK, leading to a condition similar to keratoconus. This serious complication may require corneal cross-linking or even a corneal transplant.</li>\n<li><strong>Flap Complications:</strong> The corneal flap created during LASIK never fully heals. Years after surgery, trauma to the eye can dislodge or damage the flap, requiring emergency medical attention.</li>\n<li><strong>Presbyopia Still Occurs:</strong> LASIK does not prevent age-related presbyopia. Most patients will still need reading glasses after age 40, regardless of whether they had laser correction.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Long-Term Risks of Wearing Glasses</h2>\n<p>Glasses are often considered the safest vision correction option, and for good reason. They are non-invasive and completely reversible. However, long-term glasses use is not entirely without drawbacks:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Eye Strain and Fatigue:</strong> Outdated prescriptions or poorly fitted lenses can cause chronic eye strain, headaches, and fatigue. Regular eye exams are essential to keep prescriptions current.</li>\n<li><strong>Peripheral Vision Limitations:</strong> Glasses only correct vision within the lens area, leaving peripheral vision uncorrected. This can impact spatial awareness and may pose safety concerns during physical activities or driving.</li>\n<li><strong>Physical Discomfort:</strong> Long-term use of glasses can cause pressure sores on the nose and behind the ears, skin irritation, and even indentations in the skin over time.</li>\n<li><strong>Dependency and Vulnerability:</strong> Glasses can break, fog up, or become lost at critical moments. Dependence on a physical device creates an ongoing vulnerability that LASIK eliminates.</li>\n<li><strong>Impact on Lifestyle:</strong> Active individuals may find glasses restrictive during sports, exercise, and outdoor activities. Over decades, this limitation can affect fitness habits and overall well-being.</li>\n<li><strong>Accumulated Cost:</strong> While glasses seem affordable in the short term, the cumulative cost of frames, lenses, coatings, and replacements over a lifetime can rival or exceed the one-time cost of LASIK.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>LASIK vs Glasses: Which Is Right for You?</h2>\n<p>The best choice depends on your individual circumstances, including your prescription strength, corneal thickness, lifestyle, age, and risk tolerance. Here are some key factors to consider:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Candidates with thin corneas or autoimmune conditions</strong> may not qualify for LASIK and should stick with glasses or explore alternative procedures like PRK or ICL.</li>\n<li><strong>Young professionals and athletes</strong> often benefit most from LASIK due to the lifestyle freedom it provides.</li>\n<li><strong>Patients over 40</strong> should understand that LASIK won&#8217;t eliminate the need for reading glasses as presbyopia develops.</li>\n<li><strong>Risk-averse individuals</strong> may prefer the safety and simplicity of glasses, especially if their prescription is stable and manageable.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Consulting with a qualified ophthalmologist who specializes in refractive surgery is the best first step. A thorough eye examination will determine your candidacy and help you understand the specific risks based on your eye anatomy.</p>\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>Both LASIK and glasses offer effective long-term vision correction, but neither option is completely risk-free. LASIK delivers remarkable convenience and visual freedom but comes with surgical risks that can have lasting effects. Glasses provide a safe, non-invasive solution but introduce lifestyle limitations and ongoing costs over time.</p>\n<p>As laser technology continues to evolve, the safety profile of procedures like LASIK improves with each generation. Stay informed, consult trusted eye care professionals, and choose the option that best aligns with your health, lifestyle, and long-term vision goals.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Deciding between LASIK and glasses involves understanding the long-term risks of each option. This guide compares surgical complications, lifestyle impacts, and costs to help you make an informed vision correction choice.</p>\n"},{"slug":"innoveyes-lasik-in-kolkata-cost-clinics-offers-everything-you-need-to-know-in-2026","date":"2026-02-25","title":"InnovEyes LASIK in Kolkata – Cost, Clinics, Offers & Everything You Need to Know in 2026","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2026/02/25/innoveyes-lasik-in-kolkata-cost-clinics-offers-everything-you-need-to-know-in-2026","contentHtml":"<h3>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes in Kolkata – Complete Guide to Advanced AI-Based LASIK Surgery</h3>\n<p>If you are considering LASIK eye surgery in Kolkata, <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> is among the most advanced technologies available today for laser vision correction. Designed by Alcon, this next-generation platform uses <strong>artificial intelligence and 3D eye modeling</strong> to deliver highly personalized and precise visual outcomes.</p>\n<p>Available at select premium eye hospitals in Kolkata, InnovEyes is gaining popularity among patients seeking superior visual quality, especially for night vision, contrast, and long-term stability.</p>\n<h4>What Is WaveLight Plus InnovEyes?</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> is an advanced <strong>AI-driven LASIK technology</strong> that goes beyond traditional laser vision correction methods. Instead of only correcting the glasses number or corneal surface, it creates a <strong>complete 3D digital model of the eye</strong>.</p>\n<p>This allows surgeons to customize treatment based on how light travels through your entire optical system, resulting in sharper and more natural vision.</p>\n<p>It is considered a significant upgrade over conventional LASIK and even topography-guided treatments like Contoura Vision.</p>\n<h4>Conditions Treated</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Myopia (near-sightedness)</li>\n<li>Hyperopia (far-sightedness)</li>\n<li>Astigmatism</li>\n<li>Select cases of presbyopia (based on suitability)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Eligibility depends on corneal thickness, eye health, and detailed diagnostic evaluation.</p>\n<h4>InnovEyes vs Other LASIK Technologies</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Standard LASIK:</strong> Based on glasses power</li>\n<li><strong>Contoura Vision:</strong> Based on corneal surface mapping</li>\n<li><strong>InnovEyes:</strong> AI-based full eye modeling for highly customized correction</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This makes InnovEyes one of the most advanced and premium LASIK options available globally.</p>\n<h4>Procedure Overview</h4>\n<p>InnovEyes treatment is performed using a <strong>bladeless Femto LASIK approach</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Step 1: Creation of a corneal flap using femtosecond laser</li>\n<li>Step 2: AI-guided excimer laser reshapes the cornea using 3D eye data</li>\n<li>Step 3: Flap repositioned naturally without stitches</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The procedure is painless and typically completed within <strong>10–15 minutes for both eyes</strong>.</p>\n<h4>Cost of InnovEyes in Kolkata</h4>\n<p>As a premium and highly advanced technology, the cost of InnovEyes LASIK in Kolkata generally ranges between:</p>\n<p><strong>₹1,20,000 to ₹1,80,000 for both eyes</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cost varies based on hospital, surgeon expertise, and diagnostic complexity</li>\n<li>Usually not covered under standard insurance plans</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Key Benefits of InnovEyes</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>AI-driven <strong>personalized treatment</strong></li>\n<li>Better <strong>night vision and contrast sensitivity</strong></li>\n<li>Reduced glare and halos</li>\n<li>Higher precision than standard LASIK</li>\n<li>Quick recovery and minimal discomfort</li>\n<li>Improved quality of vision, not just clarity</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Technology &amp; Diagnostics</h4>\n<p>Hospitals offering InnovEyes in Kolkata are equipped with advanced diagnostic systems such as:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Corneal topography and tomography (Pentacam)</li>\n<li>Wavefront aberrometry</li>\n<li>Dry eye assessment tools</li>\n<li>Optical coherence tomography (OCT)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These tests ensure precise eligibility assessment and treatment planning.</p>\n<h4>Recovery Timeline</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Day 1:</strong> Clear vision begins within 24 hours</li>\n<li><strong>Week 1:</strong> Basic precautions (no rubbing, avoid water exposure)</li>\n<li><strong>1 Month:</strong> Vision stabilizes significantly</li>\n<li><strong>3 Months:</strong> Final outcomes achieved</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Why Choose InnovEyes in Kolkata?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Availability at select advanced eye hospitals</li>\n<li>Experienced refractive surgeons</li>\n<li>Access to latest Alcon laser platforms</li>\n<li>Competitive pricing compared to metro cities</li>\n<li>Comprehensive pre-operative screening</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Important Considerations</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Not all patients are eligible — detailed screening is essential</li>\n<li>Dry eye evaluation is critical before surgery</li>\n<li>Surgeon expertise plays a key role in outcomes</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> represents the future of laser vision correction by combining AI, advanced optics, and precision laser technology. For patients in Kolkata looking for a premium alternative to traditional LASIK, InnovEyes offers highly customized treatment with excellent visual outcomes.</p>\n<p>If you are planning to remove your glasses permanently, consult a qualified refractive surgeon in Kolkata and undergo a detailed evaluation to determine your suitability.</p>\n<p><strong>Book your InnovEyes evaluation today and experience next-generation vision correction.</strong></p>\n<p>&#8220;`</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Explore InnovEyes LASIK in Kolkata with our detailed guide covering procedure costs, clinic facilities, current offers, and financing options to help you make an informed decision about laser vision correction.</p>\n"},{"slug":"best-lasik-surgeon-for-innoveyes-in-mumbai-your-complete-guide-to-superior-vision-correction","date":"2026-02-25","title":"Best LASIK Surgeon for InnovEyes in Mumbai: Your Complete Guide to Superior Vision Correction","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2026/02/25/best-lasik-surgeon-for-innoveyes-in-mumbai-your-complete-guide-to-superior-vision-correction","contentHtml":"<p>Finding the best LASIK surgeon for <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> technology in Mumbai is a critical decision for anyone planning laser vision correction. With Mumbai being home to some of India’s most advanced eye hospitals, patients now have access to this next-generation, AI-powered LASIK technology that offers exceptional precision, safety, and visual quality.</p>\n<p>In this guide, we help you understand InnovEyes technology and how to choose the right refractive surgeon in Mumbai for optimal results.</p>\n<h4>What Is WaveLight Plus InnovEyes?</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> is an advanced <strong>AI-driven laser vision correction technology developed by Alcon</strong>. It uses <strong>3D eye modeling and advanced diagnostics</strong> to create a highly personalized treatment plan for each patient.</p>\n<p>Unlike conventional LASIK or topography-guided treatments, InnovEyes analyzes how light travels through the entire eye, allowing for more precise and customized correction.</p>\n<h4>Key Advantages of InnovEyes Technology</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>AI-based personalization:</strong> Treatment tailored to your unique eye structure</li>\n<li><strong>Enhanced visual quality:</strong> Better night vision and contrast sensitivity</li>\n<li><strong>High precision:</strong> Advanced excimer laser with eye-tracking technology</li>\n<li><strong>Reduced glare and halos:</strong> Especially beneficial for night driving</li>\n<li><strong>Faster recovery:</strong> Minimal discomfort and quick visual improvement</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Since InnovEyes is a highly advanced platform, the surgeon’s expertise plays a crucial role in achieving the best outcomes.</p>\n<h4>What Makes the Best LASIK Surgeon for InnovEyes in Mumbai?</h4>\n<p>Not every LASIK surgeon has extensive experience with InnovEyes technology. When selecting a specialist, consider the following factors:</p>\n<h4>1. Specialized Training and Experience</h4>\n<p>The ideal surgeon should have strong experience in <strong>advanced LASIK and refractive surgery</strong>, including working with modern excimer and femtosecond laser platforms. Familiarity with AI-based treatment planning is essential for achieving optimal InnovEyes outcomes.</p>\n<h4>2. High Surgical Volume and Track Record</h4>\n<p>Experienced surgeons who have performed a large number of LASIK procedures generally deliver more consistent results. Look for surgeons with strong patient outcomes, low complication rates, and high satisfaction levels.</p>\n<h4>3. Advanced Diagnostic Infrastructure</h4>\n<p>The best eye hospitals in Mumbai offering InnovEyes are equipped with:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Corneal topography and tomography (Pentacam)</li>\n<li>Wavefront aberrometry</li>\n<li>Dry eye evaluation systems</li>\n<li>Optical coherence tomography (OCT)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Accurate diagnostics are essential for proper case selection and treatment planning.</p>\n<h4>4. Transparent Consultation and Patient Education</h4>\n<p>A good surgeon will clearly explain your eligibility, expected outcomes, and limitations. They will recommend the most suitable procedure — whether InnovEyes, Contoura, SMILE, or another option — based on your eye condition.</p>\n<h4>Key Factors to Evaluate Before Surgery</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Check patient reviews:</strong> Look at Google and healthcare platforms for real feedback</li>\n<li><strong>Compare consultations:</strong> Visit 2–3 clinics before finalizing</li>\n<li><strong>Verify credentials:</strong> Ensure the surgeon is qualified and experienced in refractive surgery</li>\n<li><strong>Understand post-op care:</strong> Follow-up is critical for best outcomes</li>\n<li><strong>Evaluate cost:</strong> InnovEyes typically ranges between <strong>₹1,20,000 to ₹1,80,000 (both eyes)</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Why Mumbai for InnovEyes LASIK?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Access to top-tier eye hospitals and experienced surgeons</li>\n<li>Availability of latest Alcon laser platforms</li>\n<li>High standards of surgical safety and protocols</li>\n<li>Excellent connectivity for patients across India</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p>Choosing the right surgeon for <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> in Mumbai is essential to achieving the best visual outcomes. The combination of advanced technology and an experienced refractive surgeon ensures safety, precision, and long-term satisfaction.</p>\n<p>If you are planning to remove your glasses permanently, schedule a detailed evaluation with a qualified LASIK surgeon in Mumbai and explore whether InnovEyes is the right option for you.</p>\n<p><strong>Book your InnovEyes consultation today and take the first step toward clearer, sharper vision.</strong></p>\n<p>&#8220;`</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Discover how to find the best LASIK surgeon for InnovEyes technology in Mumbai, including key factors like specialized training, proven track records, and state-of-the-art clinic infrastructure for superior vision correction outcomes.</p>\n"},{"slug":"top-lasik-clinics-offering-innoveyes-near-me-your-complete-2026-guide","date":"2026-02-25","title":"Top LASIK Clinics Offering InnovEyes Near Me: Your Complete 2026 Guide","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2026/02/25/top-lasik-clinics-offering-innoveyes-near-me-your-complete-2026-guide","contentHtml":"<h3>LASIK Clinics Offering WaveLight Plus InnovEyes Near Me – Complete Guide</h3>\n<p>If you are searching for <strong>LASIK clinics offering WaveLight Plus InnovEyes near you</strong>, you are exploring one of the most advanced technologies available in laser vision correction today. This next-generation, AI-driven platform is designed to deliver highly personalized treatment with superior precision and visual quality.</p>\n<p>In this guide, we explain what InnovEyes technology is, how to find the right clinic, what to look for in a surgeon, and what to expect from the procedure.</p>\n<h4>What Is WaveLight Plus InnovEyes?</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> is an advanced <strong>AI-based laser vision correction technology developed by Alcon</strong>. It uses <strong>3D eye modeling</strong> to analyze how light travels through the entire eye, enabling highly customized treatment planning.</p>\n<p>Unlike conventional LASIK or topography-guided treatments, InnovEyes focuses on the complete optical system of the eye, resulting in better quality of vision, especially in low-light conditions.</p>\n<h4>Key Benefits of InnovEyes Technology</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>AI-driven personalization:</strong> Treatment tailored to your unique eye structure</li>\n<li><strong>Enhanced precision:</strong> Advanced excimer laser with real-time eye tracking</li>\n<li><strong>Improved visual quality:</strong> Better contrast sensitivity and night vision</li>\n<li><strong>Reduced glare and halos</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Fast recovery:</strong> Minimal discomfort and quicker visual improvement</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>How to Find LASIK Clinics Offering InnovEyes Near You</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Search locally:</strong> Use keywords like “InnovEyes LASIK near me” or “InnovEyes in [your city]”</li>\n<li><strong>Visit hospital websites:</strong> Check for availability of Alcon WaveLight platforms</li>\n<li><strong>Ask your eye doctor:</strong> Get referrals from trusted ophthalmologists</li>\n<li><strong>Read patient reviews:</strong> Evaluate real experiences and outcomes</li>\n<li><strong>Consult multiple clinics:</strong> Compare diagnosis, pricing, and surgeon expertise</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>What to Look for in an InnovEyes LASIK Clinic</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Experienced refractive surgeon</strong> with high surgical volume</li>\n<li><strong>Advanced diagnostics:</strong> Pentacam, wavefront aberrometry, dry eye evaluation</li>\n<li><strong>Modern laser platforms</strong> with proper maintenance protocols</li>\n<li><strong>Transparent consultation</strong> and realistic expectations</li>\n<li><strong>Structured post-operative care</strong> with multiple follow-ups</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>What to Expect During InnovEyes LASIK</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Pre-operative evaluation:</strong> Detailed eye mapping and eligibility check</li>\n<li><strong>Procedure:</strong> Bladeless Femto LASIK using AI-guided laser treatment</li>\n<li><strong>Duration:</strong> 10–15 minutes for both eyes</li>\n<li><strong>Recovery:</strong> Vision improves within 24–48 hours</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> represents the future of laser vision correction, combining artificial intelligence with advanced laser precision. Choosing the right clinic and surgeon is essential to achieving the best outcomes.</p>\n<p>If you are planning to remove your glasses permanently, schedule a detailed evaluation at a certified center offering InnovEyes technology near you.</p>\n<p><strong>Take the first step toward clearer, sharper vision today.</strong></p>\n<h3>Eye Hospitals in India Offering WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</h3>\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"8\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Clinic Name</th>\n<th>Address</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Wavikar Eye Institute</td>\n<td>4th &amp; 5th Floor, Amber Arcade, Near Lodha Paradise Bhivandi Bypass Road, Majiwada, Thane, Maharashtra 400601</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Eye7 Chaudhary Eye Centre</td>\n<td>34, Inner Ring Road, Dayanand Colony, Lajpat Nagar IV, New Delhi 110024</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Shroff Eye Hospital</td>\n<td>222, Swami Vivekananda Rd, near Suburbia Movie Theatre, Bandra West, Mumbai, Maharashtra 400050</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>ICARE Eye Hospital</td>\n<td>E3A, ICARE Eye Hospital Rd, Block E, Sector 26, Noida, Uttar Pradesh 201301</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>The Healing Touch Super Speciality Eye Care</td>\n<td>C-2/390, Pankha Road, Janakpuri, New Delhi 110058</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Rohit Eye Hospital &amp; Child Care Centre</td>\n<td>E-1, HIG Main Rd, near LIG Square, LIG Colony, Indore, Madhya Pradesh 452001</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Envision LASIK Centre</td>\n<td>2nd Floor, Plot 185, Road No 1, Aswini Colony, West Marredpally, Secunderabad, Telangana 500026</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Mitra Eye Hospital &amp; Lasik Laser Centre</td>\n<td>Patel Nagar, Hargobind Nagar, Phagwara, Punjab 144401</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Smart Vision Eye Hospitals</td>\n<td>Plot No 143, Srinagar Colony Main Rd, Banjara Hills, Hyderabad, Telangana 500073</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Rajan Eye Care</td>\n<td>5, 2nd Cross Street, Vidyodaya East, T. Nagar, Chennai, Tamil Nadu 600017</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Narayana Nethralaya, Rajajinagar</td>\n<td>121/C, Chord Road, 1st R Block, Rajajinagar, Bengaluru, Karnataka 560010</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Narayana Nethralaya, Bannerghatta Road</td>\n<td>No.63, Bannerghatta Road, Hulimavu, Bengaluru, Karnataka 560076</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Isha Netralaya</td>\n<td>Dev Corpora, Ground Floor, B-Wing, Eastern Express Highway, Khopat, Thane West, Mumbai 400601</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Asian Eye Hospital and Laser Institute</td>\n<td>Sakar 10, 3rd Floor, Opp Jehangir Nursing Home, Sasoon Road, Pune, Maharashtra 411001</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Sohana Hospital</td>\n<td>Sector 77, Sahibzada Ajit Singh Nagar, Punjab 140308</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Giridhar Eye Institute</td>\n<td>Ponneth Temple Road, Kadavanthra, Kochi, Kerala 682020</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Discover how to find top-rated LASIK clinics offering InnovEyes technology near you. This guide covers what InnovEyes is, how to evaluate providers, and what to expect from this advanced laser vision correction procedure.</p>\n"},{"slug":"free-lasik-consultation-what-to-expect-during-your-first-visit","date":"2026-02-25","title":"Free LASIK Consultation – What to Expect During Your First Visit","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2026/02/25/free-lasik-consultation-what-to-expect-during-your-first-visit","contentHtml":"<p>If you&#8217;re considering LASIK eye surgery, the first step on your journey to clearer vision is scheduling a free consultation. But what exactly happens during this initial appointment? Understanding what to expect can help ease your nerves and ensure you&#8217;re fully prepared. In this comprehensive guide, we&#8217;ll walk you through every aspect of a free LASIK consultation so you can approach it with confidence.</p>\n<h2>Why Do LASIK Providers Offer Free Consultations?</h2>\n<p>Most reputable LASIK centers offer complimentary consultations as a way to help potential patients determine whether they&#8217;re good candidates for the procedure. Since not everyone qualifies for LASIK, these consultations serve as a critical screening process. They also give you the opportunity to meet the surgical team, ask questions, and understand the technology involved — all without any financial commitment.</p>\n<p>Free consultations benefit both patients and providers. You get valuable medical insight into your eye health, while the clinic can build trust and demonstrate their expertise. It&#8217;s a win-win situation that removes the financial barrier to exploring your vision correction options.</p>\n<h2>What Happens During a Free LASIK Consultation?</h2>\n<p>A typical free LASIK consultation lasts between 60 and 90 minutes and involves several key steps. Here&#8217;s a detailed breakdown of what you can expect:</p>\n<h3>1. Comprehensive Eye Examination</h3>\n<p>The consultation begins with a thorough eye exam that goes far beyond a standard vision test. The clinical team will evaluate multiple aspects of your eye health, including:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Visual acuity testing</strong> – to measure how well you see at various distances</li>\n<li><strong>Corneal topography</strong> – a mapping of the surface of your cornea to detect irregularities</li>\n<li><strong>Corneal pachymetry</strong> – measuring corneal thickness, which is essential for determining LASIK eligibility</li>\n<li><strong>Pupil dilation</strong> – to examine the internal structures of your eye, including the retina and optic nerve</li>\n<li><strong>Wavefront analysis</strong> – advanced laser technology that creates a detailed map of how light travels through your eye</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These diagnostic tests use cutting-edge laser and imaging technology to build a complete picture of your eye&#8217;s unique characteristics. The data collected will determine whether LASIK, PRK, or another vision correction procedure is the best fit for you.</p>\n<h3>2. Candidacy Assessment</h3>\n<p>Not everyone is a suitable candidate for LASIK surgery. During the consultation, your eye care specialist will evaluate several factors to determine your eligibility:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Age</strong> – You must be at least 18 years old, though most surgeons prefer patients to be 21 or older</li>\n<li><strong>Prescription stability</strong> – Your vision prescription should have remained stable for at least 12 months</li>\n<li><strong>Corneal health and thickness</strong> – Thin or irregularly shaped corneas may disqualify you from traditional LASIK</li>\n<li><strong>Overall eye health</strong> – Conditions like severe dry eye, glaucoma, cataracts, or keratoconus can affect eligibility</li>\n<li><strong>General health</strong> – Autoimmune disorders and certain medications may impact healing</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you&#8217;re not a candidate for LASIK, don&#8217;t be discouraged. Your specialist may recommend alternative procedures such as PRK, SMILE, or implantable contact lenses that could still help you achieve clearer vision.</p>\n<h3>3. Discussion With the Surgeon or Clinical Team</h3>\n<p>One of the most valuable parts of the free consultation is the opportunity to speak directly with the surgeon or an experienced clinical advisor. This is your chance to ask important questions such as:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>What type of laser technology will be used during my procedure?</li>\n<li>What are the potential risks and side effects?</li>\n<li>What results can I realistically expect?</li>\n<li>How long is the recovery period?</li>\n<li>What is the total cost, and are financing options available?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>A trustworthy LASIK provider will give you honest, transparent answers. They should never pressure you into making an immediate decision. Take your time to process the information and do additional research if needed.</p>\n<h3>4. Cost Breakdown and Financing Options</h3>\n<p>Although the consultation itself is free, the actual LASIK procedure is an investment. During your visit, the clinic will typically provide a clear breakdown of costs, which may include pre-operative care, the surgery itself, and post-operative follow-up appointments. Many clinics offer flexible financing plans, FSA/HSA payment options, and sometimes promotional pricing to make the procedure more accessible.</p>\n<h2>How to Prepare for Your Free LASIK Consultation</h2>\n<p>To get the most out of your appointment, follow these preparation tips:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Stop wearing contact lenses</strong> – Soft contacts should be removed at least 3-7 days before your consultation, and hard or rigid gas-permeable lenses at least 2-4 weeks prior, as they can alter corneal shape</li>\n<li><strong>Bring your current prescription</strong> – Along with any previous eye exam records</li>\n<li><strong>Prepare a list of questions</strong> – Write down everything you want to know beforehand</li>\n<li><strong>Arrange transportation</strong> – Since your eyes may be dilated during the exam, it&#8217;s wise to have someone drive you home</li>\n<li><strong>Be honest about your medical history</strong> – Disclose all medications, health conditions, and previous eye surgeries</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Conclusion: Take the First Step Toward Clearer Vision</h2>\n<p>A free LASIK consultation is a no-obligation, informative first step toward potentially life-changing vision correction. From advanced diagnostic testing to personalized candidacy assessments and transparent cost discussions, you&#8217;ll walk away with a clear understanding of whether LASIK is right for you. The technology behind modern LASIK procedures has never been more precise or safer, and the consultation process reflects that commitment to excellence.</p>\n<p>Don&#8217;t let uncertainty hold you back. Schedule your free LASIK consultation today and discover what cutting-edge laser technology can do for your vision. Your future self — free from glasses and contacts — will thank you.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Wondering what happens during a free LASIK consultation? Learn about the comprehensive eye exams, candidacy assessments, and key questions to ask so you can prepare confidently for your first appointment.</p>\n"},{"slug":"step-by-step-wavelight-plus-innoveyes-procedure-a-complete-guide-to-advanced-laser-eye-surgery","date":"2026-02-25","title":"Step-by-Step WaveLight Plus InnovEyes Procedure: A Complete Guide to Advanced Laser Eye Surgery","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2026/02/25/step-by-step-wavelight-plus-innoveyes-procedure-a-complete-guide-to-advanced-laser-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>The <strong>WaveLight Plus laser platform combined with InnovEyes technology by Alcon</strong> represents one of the most advanced systems in refractive surgery today. This next-generation approach delivers highly precise, AI-driven, and personalized laser vision correction with superior visual quality outcomes.</p>\n<p>Whether you are a patient exploring LASIK or a professional seeking deeper understanding, this guide explains the complete WaveLight Plus InnovEyes procedure step by step.</p>\n<h4>What Is WaveLight Plus InnovEyes?</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus</strong> is an advanced excimer laser system developed by Alcon, known for its speed, accuracy, and safety in LASIK and PRK procedures.</p>\n<p><strong>InnovEyes</strong> enhances this system by introducing <strong>AI-based 3D eye modeling</strong>. Instead of focusing only on corneal shape or glasses power, it analyzes how light travels through the entire eye to create a highly personalized treatment plan.</p>\n<p>This combination allows for better visual quality, improved contrast sensitivity, and reduced visual disturbances such as glare and halos.</p>\n<h4>Pre-Procedure: Diagnostic Evaluation &#038; Treatment Planning</h4>\n<h4>Step 1: Comprehensive Eye Examination</h4>\n<p>A detailed eye evaluation is performed using advanced diagnostic tools:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Corneal Topography/Tomography:</strong> Maps corneal shape and curvature</li>\n<li><strong>Wavefront Aberrometry:</strong> Detects higher-order aberrations</li>\n<li><strong>Pachymetry:</strong> Measures corneal thickness</li>\n<li><strong>Dry Eye Assessment:</strong> Evaluates tear film quality</li>\n<li><strong>Pupil Analysis:</strong> Assesses pupil size in different lighting conditions</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Step 2: 3D Eye Modeling with InnovEyes</h4>\n<p>InnovEyes creates a <strong>3D digital model of the entire eye</strong>, analyzing the complete optical pathway. This allows surgeons to plan treatment based on real visual behavior rather than only surface measurements.</p>\n<h4>Step 3: Personalized Treatment Planning</h4>\n<p>The surgeon designs a customized laser treatment using the WaveLight Plus system. The goal is not only to correct refractive error but also to optimize overall visual quality.</p>\n<h4>The Surgical Procedure: Step-by-Step</h4>\n<h4>Step 4: Patient Preparation</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Numbing eye drops are applied</li>\n<li>The eye is cleaned and prepared</li>\n<li>A lid speculum is used to keep the eye open</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The procedure is painless and takes only a few minutes.</p>\n<h4>Step 5: Corneal Flap Creation (Femto LASIK)</h4>\n<p>A femtosecond laser creates a thin, precise corneal flap. This step is bladeless and highly accurate.</p>\n<p>For PRK, no flap is created and the surface layer is gently removed.</p>\n<h4>Step 6: Excimer Laser Treatment</h4>\n<p>The <strong>WaveLight Plus excimer laser</strong> reshapes the cornea based on the InnovEyes treatment plan.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>High-speed laser delivery:</strong> Reduces treatment time</li>\n<li><strong>Advanced eye tracking:</strong> Ensures precision even with micro eye movements</li>\n<li><strong>Optimized ablation profile:</strong> Preserves corneal shape and improves visual quality</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Step 7: Flap Repositioning</h4>\n<p>After laser correction, the corneal flap is repositioned naturally without stitches. It adheres on its own within minutes.</p>\n<h4>Post-Procedure: Recovery &#038; Follow-Up</h4>\n<h4>Step 8: Immediate Recovery</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Vision begins improving within 24 hours</li>\n<li>Mild watering, light sensitivity, or irritation may occur temporarily</li>\n<li>Protective eye shields and medicated drops are prescribed</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Step 9: Follow-Up Care</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Day 1:</strong> Initial vision check</li>\n<li><strong>1 Week:</strong> Healing assessment</li>\n<li><strong>1 Month:</strong> Vision stabilization review</li>\n<li><strong>3 Months:</strong> Final outcome evaluation</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Regular follow-up ensures optimal healing and long-term results.</p>\n<h4>Key Benefits of WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>AI-driven <strong>personalized vision correction</strong></li>\n<li>Superior <strong>night vision and contrast</strong></li>\n<li>Reduced glare and halos</li>\n<li>High precision and safety</li>\n<li>Quick recovery and minimal downtime</li>\n<li>Improved overall visual quality, not just clarity</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p>The <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes procedure</strong> represents the future of laser vision correction by combining advanced laser precision with AI-based eye modeling. Every step — from diagnosis to treatment — is optimized for accuracy, safety, and superior visual outcomes.</p>\n<p>If you are considering LASIK or advanced vision correction, consult an experienced refractive surgeon to determine your suitability for InnovEyes technology.</p>\n<p><strong>Take the next step toward clear, high-quality vision with next-generation laser technology.</strong></p>\n<p>&#8220;`</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Discover the complete step-by-step WaveLight Plus InnovEyes laser eye surgery procedure, from diagnostic evaluation and digital treatment planning to excimer laser ablation and post-operative recovery.</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-to-prepare-for-lasik-surgery-your-complete-step-by-step-guide","date":"2026-02-25","title":"How to Prepare for LASIK Surgery: Your Complete Step-by-Step Guide","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2026/02/25/how-to-prepare-for-lasik-surgery-your-complete-step-by-step-guide","contentHtml":"<p>LASIK surgery has transformed the lives of millions of people worldwide, offering freedom from glasses and contact lenses through the precision of advanced laser technology. However, the success of your procedure doesn&#8217;t begin in the operating room — it starts with proper preparation. Whether your surgery is weeks away or you&#8217;re just beginning to explore the possibility, knowing how to prepare for LASIK surgery is essential for achieving the best possible outcome.</p>\n<p>In this comprehensive guide, we&#8217;ll walk you through everything you need to do before your LASIK procedure, from your initial consultation to the morning of surgery.</p>\n<h2>1. Schedule a Thorough Pre-Operative Consultation</h2>\n<p>The first and most important step in preparing for LASIK is a detailed eye examination with a qualified ophthalmologist. This consultation determines whether you&#8217;re a suitable candidate for the procedure and establishes a baseline for your eye health.</p>\n<p>During your pre-operative consultation, your doctor will typically:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Measure your corneal thickness and shape</strong> using advanced topography mapping technology</li>\n<li><strong>Evaluate your pupil size</strong> in both light and dark conditions</li>\n<li><strong>Assess your overall eye health</strong>, checking for conditions like dry eye syndrome, glaucoma, or cataracts</li>\n<li><strong>Determine your exact refractive error</strong>, including nearsightedness, farsightedness, and astigmatism</li>\n<li><strong>Review your medical history</strong> to identify any conditions that could affect healing</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Be completely transparent with your doctor about your medical history, medications, and lifestyle. Conditions such as autoimmune disorders, diabetes, or pregnancy can affect your eligibility and timing for LASIK surgery.</p>\n<h2>2. Follow Pre-Surgery Instructions Carefully</h2>\n<p>Once you&#8217;ve been approved for LASIK, your surgeon will provide a specific set of pre-operative instructions. Following these guidelines precisely is critical for ensuring accurate measurements and a smooth procedure.</p>\n<h3>Stop Wearing Contact Lenses</h3>\n<p>This is one of the most important — and often surprising — preparation steps. Contact lenses can temporarily alter the shape of your cornea, which can lead to inaccurate measurements and suboptimal results. Your doctor will typically advise you to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Stop wearing <strong>soft contact lenses</strong> at least 1-2 weeks before your evaluation and surgery</li>\n<li>Stop wearing <strong>toric (astigmatism) soft lenses</strong> at least 2-3 weeks prior</li>\n<li>Stop wearing <strong>rigid gas-permeable (RGP) lenses</strong> at least 3-4 weeks prior</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Avoid Certain Products and Medications</h3>\n<p>In the days leading up to your surgery, you should:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Avoid eye makeup, lotions, creams, and perfumes for at least 24-48 hours before the procedure, as residue can increase the risk of infection</li>\n<li>Discuss all medications and supplements with your surgeon, as some blood thinners and certain supplements may need to be temporarily discontinued</li>\n<li>Refrain from using any eye drops not specifically approved by your doctor</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>3. Prepare for Surgery Day and Recovery</h2>\n<p>Proper planning for the day of your procedure will reduce stress and set the stage for a comfortable recovery.</p>\n<h3>Arrange Transportation</h3>\n<p>You will not be able to drive yourself home after LASIK surgery. Your vision will be blurry immediately following the procedure, and you may experience light sensitivity. Arrange for a friend or family member to drive you to and from the surgical center.</p>\n<h3>Dress Comfortably</h3>\n<p>Wear comfortable, casual clothing on surgery day. Avoid anything that produces lint or fibers, such as wool sweaters, which could irritate your eyes in the sterile surgical environment.</p>\n<h3>Set Up Your Recovery Space</h3>\n<p>Before you leave for surgery, prepare your home for a restful recovery:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Fill any prescribed eye drop prescriptions in advance</li>\n<li>Have quality sunglasses ready for light sensitivity</li>\n<li>Download audiobooks or podcasts, as you&#8217;ll need to limit screen time for the first 24-48 hours</li>\n<li>Stock up on easy-to-prepare meals and snacks</li>\n<li>Ensure your bedroom can be darkened for comfortable resting</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Eat a Light Meal</h3>\n<p>Unlike some surgical procedures, LASIK typically does not require fasting. Eat a light, healthy meal before your appointment to keep your energy levels stable and reduce any anxiety.</p>\n<h2>4. Manage Your Expectations and Mental Preparation</h2>\n<p>Mental readiness is just as important as physical preparation. Understanding what to expect during and after LASIK can significantly reduce pre-surgery anxiety.</p>\n<p>The LASIK procedure itself typically takes only <strong>10-15 minutes for both eyes</strong>, with the laser application lasting less than a minute per eye. Most patients report feeling only mild pressure and no pain during the procedure, thanks to numbing eye drops.</p>\n<p>Keep in mind that while many patients notice improved vision almost immediately, full stabilization can take <strong>3-6 months</strong>. Temporary side effects such as dry eyes, halos around lights, and minor fluctuations in vision are normal during the healing process.</p>\n<p>Don&#8217;t hesitate to write down questions for your surgeon and discuss any concerns during your pre-operative appointments. A well-informed patient is a confident patient.</p>\n<h2>Conclusion: Preparation Is the Foundation of LASIK Success</h2>\n<p>Preparing for LASIK surgery involves more than just showing up on the day of your procedure. From discontinuing contact lenses and attending a thorough consultation to setting up your recovery space and managing expectations, each step plays a vital role in achieving the clear vision you&#8217;ve been dreaming of. By following your surgeon&#8217;s instructions carefully and taking the time to plan ahead, you&#8217;ll be giving yourself the best possible chance for a successful outcome.</p>\n<p>At <strong>laser.fyi</strong>, we&#8217;re dedicated to helping you understand the laser technologies that are shaping modern medicine and everyday life. If you&#8217;re considering LASIK, use this guide as your roadmap — and step confidently toward a future with clearer vision.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Preparing for LASIK surgery is essential for achieving the best results. Learn the key steps, from your pre-operative consultation and discontinuing contact lenses to planning for a smooth recovery day.</p>\n"},{"slug":"lasik-recovery-timeline-a-complete-day-by-day-guide-to-healing","date":"2026-02-25","title":"LASIK Recovery Timeline – A Complete Day-by-Day Guide to Healing","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2026/02/25/lasik-recovery-timeline-a-complete-day-by-day-guide-to-healing","contentHtml":"<p>LASIK eye surgery is one of the most popular elective procedures in the world, with millions of people achieving clearer vision every year. But once the laser has done its work, what exactly happens during recovery? Understanding the LASIK recovery timeline day by day can help ease anxiety, set realistic expectations, and ensure you&#8217;re prepared for every stage of the healing process.</p>\n<p>In this comprehensive guide, we&#8217;ll walk you through exactly what to expect from the moment you leave the surgical center through your full recovery — so you can plan ahead and focus on healing.</p>\n<h2>Day 0: Surgery Day – What to Expect Immediately After LASIK</h2>\n<p>LASIK surgery itself is remarkably quick, typically lasting only 10 to 15 minutes for both eyes. However, the hours immediately following the procedure are critical for your recovery.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Blurry or hazy vision:</strong> Your vision will likely be foggy or cloudy immediately after surgery. This is completely normal as your corneal flap begins to heal.</li>\n<li><strong>Burning, tearing, or itching:</strong> Many patients experience mild discomfort, a gritty sensation, or watery eyes for several hours post-surgery. Resist the urge to rub your eyes.</li>\n<li><strong>Light sensitivity:</strong> Bright lights may feel uncomfortable. Wearing the protective sunglasses provided by your surgeon is essential.</li>\n<li><strong>Rest is crucial:</strong> Most surgeons recommend going home, closing your eyes, and sleeping for several hours. Your doctor will provide medicated eye drops — typically antibiotic and anti-inflammatory drops — to prevent infection and reduce swelling.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You&#8217;ll also be given protective eye shields to wear while sleeping to prevent accidental rubbing or pressure on your eyes during the night.</p>\n<h2>Days 1–3: Early Recovery – Rapid Improvement Begins</h2>\n<p>The first few days after LASIK are when the most dramatic improvements occur. Many patients are amazed at how quickly their vision sharpens.</p>\n<h3>Day 1</h3>\n<p>Most patients notice a significant improvement in vision within the first 24 hours. You&#8217;ll attend a follow-up appointment where your surgeon will check the corneal flap, measure your visual acuity, and ensure there are no complications. Many people can already see well enough to drive, though it&#8217;s wise to have someone accompany you to this appointment.</p>\n<h3>Days 2–3</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Vision continues to stabilize:</strong> While your sight will be noticeably clearer, you may still experience mild fluctuations in visual clarity throughout the day.</li>\n<li><strong>Dry eyes:</strong> This is one of the most common side effects during early recovery. Use preservative-free artificial tears frequently as recommended by your doctor.</li>\n<li><strong>Halos and glare:</strong> You may notice halos around lights at night or increased glare. These symptoms are temporary for the vast majority of patients.</li>\n<li><strong>Continue eye drops:</strong> Follow your prescribed drop schedule diligently to support healing and prevent infection.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Most patients can return to desk work and light daily activities by day two or three, though strenuous exercise and swimming should still be avoided.</p>\n<h2>Days 4–14: The Intermediate Recovery Phase</h2>\n<p>During the first two weeks, your eyes continue healing beneath the surface even though you may feel completely normal.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Vision sharpens further:</strong> Many patients achieve 20/20 vision or better within the first week. However, slight blurriness or dryness can persist.</li>\n<li><strong>Avoid eye makeup:</strong> Cosmetics around the eyes should be avoided for at least one to two weeks to minimize infection risk.</li>\n<li><strong>No contact sports:</strong> Activities that risk impact to the face or eyes — such as basketball, martial arts, or soccer — should be postponed for at least two weeks.</li>\n<li><strong>Screen use:</strong> While you can use computers and phones, take frequent breaks using the 20-20-20 rule: every 20 minutes, look at something 20 feet away for 20 seconds.</li>\n<li><strong>Follow-up visits:</strong> Most surgeons schedule a one-week post-op appointment to monitor your progress and adjust your eye drop regimen if needed.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>By the end of week two, the corneal flap is significantly more secure, and most daily activity restrictions are lifted.</p>\n<h2>Weeks 3–12: Long-Term Healing and Final Stabilization</h2>\n<p>While most patients feel fully recovered within the first couple of weeks, the complete healing process can take up to three to six months.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Dry eye symptoms diminish:</strong> Tear production gradually returns to normal levels. Some patients may need artificial tears for several months.</li>\n<li><strong>Night vision improves:</strong> Halos, starbursts, and glare around lights at night typically fade significantly by the one- to three-month mark.</li>\n<li><strong>Vision prescription stabilizes:</strong> Your final visual acuity may not be fully established until approximately three months post-surgery. Additional follow-up appointments at one month and three months help your surgeon track this stabilization.</li>\n<li><strong>Enhancement procedures:</strong> In rare cases where vision hasn&#8217;t reached the desired outcome, a LASIK enhancement or touch-up procedure may be discussed after the three-month mark once your eyes have fully stabilized.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Throughout this period, continue protecting your eyes from UV exposure with quality sunglasses and attend all scheduled follow-up appointments.</p>\n<h2>Conclusion: Patience and Proper Care Lead to Optimal Results</h2>\n<p>The LASIK recovery timeline is generally fast and straightforward, with most patients experiencing dramatically improved vision within just 24 hours. However, complete healing is a gradual process that unfolds over weeks and months. By following your surgeon&#8217;s post-operative instructions, attending all follow-up appointments, and being patient with your body&#8217;s natural healing process, you give yourself the best chance of achieving outstanding long-term results.</p>\n<p>LASIK remains one of the most effective and well-studied applications of laser technology in medicine. If you&#8217;re considering the procedure or are currently recovering, understanding each phase of the recovery timeline empowers you to make informed decisions and enjoy the journey to clearer, sharper vision.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Wondering what to expect after LASIK surgery? This day-by-day recovery timeline covers everything from surgery day through full healing, including vision changes, side effects, and tips for a smooth recovery.</p>\n"},{"slug":"when-can-you-use-mobile-after-lasik-a-complete-recovery-guide","date":"2026-02-25","title":"When Can You Use Mobile After LASIK? A Complete Recovery Guide","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2026/02/25/when-can-you-use-mobile-after-lasik-a-complete-recovery-guide","contentHtml":"<p>LASIK eye surgery is one of the most popular and effective laser vision correction procedures in the world. But in our screen-dominated lives, one of the first questions patients ask after surgery is: <strong>when can I use my mobile phone after LASIK?</strong> It&#8217;s a fair question — most of us rely on our smartphones for communication, work, and entertainment every single day.</p>\n<p>In this comprehensive guide, we&#8217;ll walk you through the recommended timeline for mobile phone use after LASIK, explain why screen time matters during recovery, and share expert tips for protecting your eyes as they heal.</p>\n<h2>The General Timeline for Mobile Use After LASIK</h2>\n<p>The good news is that you won&#8217;t have to stay away from your phone for very long. However, the first 24 hours after LASIK are absolutely critical for your recovery. Here&#8217;s a general timeline most ophthalmologists recommend:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>First 2-4 hours:</strong> Avoid all screen use entirely. Your eyes will be sensitive, watery, and you&#8217;ll likely want to keep them closed. Rest and sleep are strongly encouraged during this period.</li>\n<li><strong>After 24 hours:</strong> Most patients can begin using their mobile phones for short intervals — typically 10 to 15 minutes at a time. Pay close attention to how your eyes feel and stop immediately if you notice discomfort, dryness, or strain.</li>\n<li><strong>After 48-72 hours:</strong> You can gradually increase your screen time. Many patients feel comfortable using their phones for moderate periods by the third day, though frequent breaks are still important.</li>\n<li><strong>After one week:</strong> Most patients can resume normal mobile phone use, though it&#8217;s wise to continue practicing good screen habits and using lubricating eye drops as needed.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Keep in mind that every patient heals differently. Your surgeon&#8217;s specific instructions should always take priority over general guidelines.</p>\n<h2>Why You Should Limit Screen Time After LASIK</h2>\n<p>You might wonder why something as simple as looking at your phone could affect LASIK recovery. There are several important reasons:</p>\n<h3>Reduced Blink Rate</h3>\n<p>When we stare at screens, our blink rate drops by as much as 60%. Blinking is essential because it spreads a fresh layer of tears across the corneal surface. After LASIK, your corneas are already more vulnerable to dryness because the procedure temporarily disrupts the nerves that trigger tear production. Combining reduced blinking with compromised tear production can lead to significant dry eye discomfort and may even slow healing.</p>\n<h3>Eye Strain and Fatigue</h3>\n<p>The muscles in your eyes work hard to focus on the small text and bright pixels of a mobile screen. During the early stages of recovery, your visual system is still stabilizing. Excessive strain can cause headaches, blurred vision, and general discomfort that may make your recovery feel more difficult than it needs to be.</p>\n<h3>Blue Light Exposure</h3>\n<p>Mobile phones emit blue light, which can contribute to eye fatigue and discomfort — especially when your corneas are still healing. While the long-term effects of blue light are still debated, minimizing exposure during the sensitive recovery window is a smart precaution.</p>\n<h2>Tips for Safe Mobile Use During LASIK Recovery</h2>\n<p>When you do start using your phone again, follow these practical tips to protect your healing eyes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Follow the 20-20-20 rule:</strong> Every 20 minutes, look at something 20 feet away for at least 20 seconds. This simple habit reduces eye strain significantly.</li>\n<li><strong>Lower your screen brightness:</strong> A dimmer screen puts less stress on your eyes. Most phones also have a &#8220;night mode&#8221; or &#8220;comfort mode&#8221; that reduces blue light emission — enable it.</li>\n<li><strong>Increase font size:</strong> Larger text means your eyes don&#8217;t have to work as hard to focus, reducing strain during recovery.</li>\n<li><strong>Use lubricating eye drops:</strong> Keep preservative-free artificial tears nearby and apply them frequently, especially before and after screen use.</li>\n<li><strong>Limit sessions to short bursts:</strong> Even if your eyes feel fine, stick to 10-15 minute intervals during the first few days and gradually increase from there.</li>\n<li><strong>Hold your phone at a comfortable distance:</strong> Keeping your screen at least 16-18 inches from your face minimizes the focusing effort required by your eyes.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>When to Contact Your Doctor</h2>\n<p>While mild dryness and slight fluctuations in vision are normal during the first week of recovery, certain symptoms warrant immediate medical attention. Contact your LASIK surgeon if you experience:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Severe or worsening eye pain after screen use</li>\n<li>Sudden significant changes in vision</li>\n<li>Excessive tearing or discharge</li>\n<li>Persistent redness that doesn&#8217;t improve with rest</li>\n<li>Sensitivity to light that intensifies rather than subsides</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These could be signs of complications that require prompt evaluation and treatment.</p>\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>Most LASIK patients can start using their mobile phones within 24 hours of surgery, with a gradual return to normal screen habits over the first week. The key is patience and mindfulness — give your eyes the rest they need in the first critical hours, then ease back into screen time with proper precautions. By following your surgeon&#8217;s advice, using lubricating drops, and practicing the 20-20-20 rule, you&#8217;ll set yourself up for a smooth recovery and enjoy the clear vision that LASIK technology delivers.</p>\n<p>For more insights into laser technology and its applications in modern medicine, stay tuned to <strong>laser.fyi</strong> — your trusted resource for all things laser.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Wondering when you can safely use your mobile phone after LASIK surgery? Learn the recommended timeline, why screen time matters during recovery, and expert tips for protecting your healing eyes.</p>\n"},{"slug":"wavelight-plus-innoveyes-lasik-cost-in-india-2026-guide","date":"2026-02-24","title":"Wavelight Plus InnovEyes LASIK – Cost in India (2026 Guide)","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2026/02/24/wavelight-plus-innoveyes-lasik-cost-in-india-2026-guide","contentHtml":"<p>If you are considering laser vision correction in India, <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK</strong> is among the most advanced options available in 2026. This technology combines Alcon’s high-precision excimer laser with <strong>AI-based 3D eye modeling</strong> to deliver highly personalized vision correction.</p>\n<p>In this guide, we explain the cost of InnovEyes LASIK in India, what affects pricing, and what you can expect from this premium procedure.</p>\n<h4>What Is WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK?</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus</strong> is an advanced excimer laser system known for its speed and accuracy in LASIK procedures.</p>\n<p><strong>InnovEyes</strong> enhances this by creating a <strong>3D model of the eye</strong>, allowing surgeons to plan treatment based on how light travels through the entire optical system — not just the cornea.</p>\n<p>The procedure is performed using <strong>Femto LASIK (bladeless LASIK)</strong>, ensuring precision and faster recovery.</p>\n<h4>Cost of InnovEyes LASIK in India (2026)</h4>\n<p>The cost of WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK in India typically ranges between:</p>\n<p><strong>₹1,20,000 to ₹1,80,000 (both eyes)</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Per eye cost: approximately ₹60,000 – ₹90,000</li>\n<li>Premium centers in metro cities may charge higher</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Most packages include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Pre-LASIK evaluation and diagnostics</li>\n<li>Surgical procedure</li>\n<li>Post-operative medications</li>\n<li>Follow-up visits</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Factors That Affect Cost</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>City:</strong> Mumbai, Delhi, Bengaluru, Hyderabad tend to be more expensive</li>\n<li><strong>Surgeon expertise:</strong> Highly experienced surgeons may charge more</li>\n<li><strong>Hospital infrastructure:</strong> Premium eye hospitals have higher pricing</li>\n<li><strong>Complexity of case:</strong> Higher numbers or special conditions may require advanced planning</li>\n<li><strong>Package inclusions:</strong> Some clinics offer all-inclusive care</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Why Is InnovEyes More Expensive?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Advanced <strong>AI-based customization</strong></li>\n<li>Improved <strong>visual quality (contrast, night vision)</strong></li>\n<li>Latest generation laser technology</li>\n<li>Premium diagnostic evaluation</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This makes it a <strong>premium LASIK option</strong> compared to standard LASIK.</p>\n<h4>Recovery and Results</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Vision improves within <strong>24 hours</strong> in most cases</li>\n<li>Stabilization occurs over a few weeks</li>\n<li>More than <strong>95% of patients achieve 6/6 vision or better</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Many patients also report better comfort during night driving and screen use.</p>\n<h4>Tips for Choosing the Right Clinic</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Choose an <strong>experienced refractive surgeon</strong></li>\n<li>Ensure availability of advanced diagnostic testing</li>\n<li>Check real patient reviews and outcomes</li>\n<li>Understand full package cost (avoid hidden charges)</li>\n<li>Always undergo a detailed pre-LASIK evaluation</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK is a premium vision correction procedure in India</strong>, offering highly personalized treatment and excellent visual outcomes.</p>\n<p>While the cost is higher than standard LASIK, the benefits in terms of customization and visual quality make it a preferred choice for many patients.</p>\n<p><strong>Consult a qualified eye surgeon to get a personalized cost estimate and check your eligibility.</strong></p>\n<p><em>Disclaimer: Costs are indicative and may vary by city, hospital, and patient condition. Please consult a certified ophthalmologist for exact pricing.</em></p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Discover the cost of Wavelight Plus InnovEyes LASIK in India for 2026, including pricing breakdowns, factors affecting cost, and tips for choosing the right clinic for this advanced laser vision correction procedure.</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-wavelight-plus-innoveyes-better-than-contoura-vision-a-detailed-comparison","date":"2026-02-24","title":"Is Wavelight Plus InnovEyes Better Than Contoura Vision? A Detailed Comparison","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2026/02/24/is-wavelight-plus-innoveyes-better-than-contoura-vision-a-detailed-comparison","contentHtml":"<p>When it comes to advanced laser eye surgery, two of the most talked-about technologies are <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> and <strong>Contoura Vision</strong>. Both are highly advanced LASIK techniques using Alcon’s WaveLight laser platform, but they differ in how they plan and deliver treatment.</p>\n<p>This guide explains the differences in a simple and medically accurate way to help you understand which option may be better for your eyes.</p>\n<h4>What Is Contoura Vision?</h4>\n<p><strong>Contoura Vision</strong> is a <strong>topography-guided LASIK</strong> procedure. It focuses on the <strong>corneal surface</strong> and uses detailed mapping to correct irregularities along with refractive error.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Based on corneal topography (surface mapping)</li>\n<li>Highly effective for irregular corneas</li>\n<li>Uses WaveLight excimer laser</li>\n<li>Well-established with strong clinical results</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>What Is WaveLight Plus InnovEyes?</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> is an advanced <strong>AI-based LASIK technology</strong> that uses <strong>3D eye modeling</strong>. Instead of focusing only on the cornea, it analyzes how light travels through the <strong>entire eye</strong>.</p>\n<p>This allows for a more <strong>personalized treatment plan</strong>, aimed at improving overall visual quality.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Based on full eye optical system</li>\n<li>AI-driven personalized treatment</li>\n<li>Performed using Femto LASIK approach</li>\n<li>Focus on visual quality (not just number correction)</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Key Differences</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Treatment Approach:</strong><br />\nContoura – Cornea-focused<br />\nInnovEyes – Whole eye (optical system)</li>\n<li><strong>Customization:</strong><br />\nContoura – Surface-level customization<br />\nInnovEyes – Deeper, more personalized correction</li>\n<li><strong>Visual Quality:</strong><br />\nContoura – Excellent clarity<br />\nInnovEyes – Enhanced contrast, night vision, and visual comfort</li>\n<li><strong>Technology Type:</strong><br />\nBoth use advanced excimer lasers, but InnovEyes adds AI-based planning</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Which One Gives Better Results?</h4>\n<p>Both technologies provide excellent results, but the difference lies in the goal of treatment:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Contoura Vision:</strong> Best for correcting corneal irregularities and achieving sharp vision</li>\n<li><strong>InnovEyes:</strong> Designed for improved <strong>quality of vision</strong>, especially in low-light and night conditions</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For many patients, both options can achieve 6/6 vision or better.</p>\n<h4>Who Should Choose What?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Choose Contoura Vision if:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>You have corneal surface irregularities</li>\n<li>You want a proven and widely used advanced LASIK</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Choose InnovEyes if:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>You want the latest personalized LASIK technology</li>\n<li>You are focused on better night vision and visual quality</li>\n<li>You are suitable for premium customized treatment</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Important Note</h4>\n<p>The choice between InnovEyes and Contoura Vision depends on your <strong>eye condition, corneal structure, and surgeon’s recommendation</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Technology is important, but correct patient selection and surgeon expertise are more important for successful outcomes.</strong></p>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes and Contoura Vision are both advanced and safe LASIK options.</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Contoura Vision focuses on <strong>corneal precision</strong></li>\n<li>InnovEyes focuses on <strong>overall visual quality and personalization</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>The best option is the one best suited to your eyes — not just the latest technology.</strong></p>\n<p>Consult an experienced refractive surgeon to determine the right treatment for you.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Comparing Wavelight Plus InnovEyes and Contoura Vision to help you understand the key differences in technology, diagnostic integration, and clinical outcomes between these two advanced laser eye surgery platforms.</p>\n"},{"slug":"wavelight-plus-innoveyes-lasik-benefits-risks-results-you-need-to-know","date":"2026-02-24","title":"Wavelight Plus InnovEyes LASIK: Benefits, Risks & Results You Need to Know","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2026/02/24/wavelight-plus-innoveyes-lasik-benefits-risks-results-you-need-to-know","contentHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery has advanced significantly in recent years, and <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> represents one of the latest developments in vision correction. This technology combines a high-precision excimer laser with <strong>AI-based 3D eye modeling</strong> to deliver more personalized treatment and improved visual quality.</p>\n<p>If you are considering LASIK, understanding the benefits, risks, and expected results is essential before making a decision.</p>\n<h4>What Is WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK?</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus</strong> is an advanced excimer laser system by Alcon, known for its speed and accuracy in LASIK procedures.</p>\n<p><strong>InnovEyes</strong> enhances this by creating a <strong>3D model of the eye</strong>, analyzing how light travels through the entire optical system. This allows surgeons to plan a highly customized laser treatment.</p>\n<p>The procedure is typically performed using <strong>Femto LASIK (bladeless LASIK)</strong>, where a thin corneal flap is created and the underlying cornea is reshaped to correct vision.</p>\n<h4>Key Benefits of InnovEyes LASIK</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Personalized treatment:</strong> Customized correction based on your unique eye structure</li>\n<li><strong>Improved visual quality:</strong> Better contrast sensitivity and night vision</li>\n<li><strong>High precision:</strong> Advanced excimer laser with accurate eye tracking</li>\n<li><strong>Fast procedure:</strong> Laser treatment takes only a few seconds</li>\n<li><strong>Quick recovery:</strong> Most patients see clearly within 24 hours</li>\n<li><strong>Reduced glare and halos:</strong> Compared to older LASIK techniques</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Possible Risks and Side Effects</h4>\n<p>Like any surgical procedure, LASIK has some potential side effects. Most are temporary and manageable:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Dry eyes:</strong> Common in early recovery, usually improves over time</li>\n<li><strong>Glare or halos:</strong> Especially noticeable at night initially</li>\n<li><strong>Fluctuating vision:</strong> During the healing period</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Rare risks include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Under-correction or over-correction</li>\n<li>Flap-related issues (specific to LASIK)</li>\n<li>Infection or inflammation (very rare)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Proper screening and experienced surgeons significantly reduce these risks.</p>\n<h4>Expected Results</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>More than <strong>95% of patients achieve 6/6 (20/20) vision or better</strong></li>\n<li>Vision improves within <strong>24 hours</strong> in most cases</li>\n<li>Stabilization occurs over a few weeks</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Many patients report improved comfort in daily activities such as night driving and screen use.</p>\n<h4>Who Is a Good Candidate?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Age above 18 years with stable vision</li>\n<li>Suitable corneal thickness</li>\n<li>No major eye diseases</li>\n<li>Realistic expectations from surgery</li>\n</ul>\n<p>A detailed eye examination is required to confirm eligibility.</p>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK is a safe and advanced option for vision correction</strong>, offering personalized treatment and high-quality visual outcomes.</p>\n<p>While results are excellent for most patients, the final outcome depends on proper evaluation, surgeon expertise, and post-operative care.</p>\n<p><strong>Consult an experienced refractive surgeon to determine if InnovEyes LASIK is right for you.</strong></p>\n<p><em>Disclaimer: This content is for educational purposes only and does not replace medical advice. Please consult a qualified ophthalmologist before making a decision.</em></p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK combines ultra-fast excimer laser technology with advanced diagnostics for highly personalized vision correction. Learn about its benefits, potential risks, and the impressive visual outcomes patients can expect.</p>\n"},{"slug":"who-is-eligible-for-wavelight-plus-innoveyes-lasik-a-complete-guide-to-candidacy","date":"2026-02-24","title":"Who Is Eligible for WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK? A Complete Guide to Candidacy","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2026/02/24/who-is-eligible-for-wavelight-plus-innoveyes-lasik-a-complete-guide-to-candidacy","contentHtml":"<p>With advancements in laser vision correction, <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> has become one of the most advanced options available today. However, not everyone is suitable for this procedure. Understanding eligibility is essential before planning your LASIK surgery.</p>\n<p>This guide explains who can undergo InnovEyes LASIK and the key factors doctors evaluate before recommending it.</p>\n<h4>What Is WaveLight Plus InnovEyes?</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> is an advanced <strong>AI-based LASIK technology by Alcon</strong> that uses <strong>3D eye modeling</strong> to create a highly personalized treatment plan.</p>\n<p>The procedure is performed using a <strong>Femto LASIK (bladeless LASIK)</strong> approach, where the cornea is reshaped using an excimer laser to improve vision quality and clarity.</p>\n<h4>Basic Eligibility Criteria</h4>\n<p>To be considered for InnovEyes LASIK, you should generally meet the following conditions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Age:</strong> 18 years or older (preferably 21+ with stable vision)</li>\n<li><strong>Stable Number:</strong> No significant change in power for at least 1 year</li>\n<li><strong>Refractive Error:</strong> Myopia, hyperopia, or astigmatism within treatable range</li>\n<li><strong>Corneal Thickness:</strong> Adequate thickness for safe laser correction</li>\n<li><strong>Healthy Eyes:</strong> No active eye diseases or infections</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Eye Conditions That May Disqualify You</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Keratoconus or weak cornea</li>\n<li>Severe dry eye syndrome</li>\n<li>Uncontrolled glaucoma</li>\n<li>Active eye infection or inflammation</li>\n<li>Advanced cataract affecting vision</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>General Health Considerations</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Uncontrolled diabetes</li>\n<li>Autoimmune disorders</li>\n<li>Conditions affecting wound healing</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These may affect healing and overall outcomes.</p>\n<h4>Additional Factors Doctors Evaluate</h4>\n<h4>Pupil Size</h4>\n<p>Large pupils may increase the risk of night glare or halos. Advanced treatment planning helps manage this, but evaluation is necessary.</p>\n<h4>Dry Eye Status</h4>\n<p>Mild dryness is common and manageable, but severe dry eye needs treatment before considering LASIK.</p>\n<h4>Contact Lens Use</h4>\n<p>Contact lenses must be stopped before evaluation (usually 1–2 weeks for soft lenses) to allow accurate measurements.</p>\n<h4>Pregnancy &#038; Nursing</h4>\n<p>Laser surgery is usually postponed during pregnancy or breastfeeding due to hormonal changes affecting vision.</p>\n<h4>Who Gets the Best Results?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Patients with stable vision</li>\n<li>Healthy corneas</li>\n<li>No underlying eye disease</li>\n<li>Realistic expectations</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Alternative Options If Not Eligible</h4>\n<p>If you are not suitable for InnovEyes LASIK, other options may include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>PRK (surface laser treatment)</li>\n<li>SMILE (flapless procedure)</li>\n<li>ICL (implantable lens surgery)</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Importance of a Detailed Eye Check-Up</h4>\n<p>A complete eye examination is the most important step. Doctors perform detailed tests to evaluate:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Corneal shape and thickness</li>\n<li>Tear film and dryness</li>\n<li>Overall eye health</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This ensures safety and helps select the most suitable procedure.</p>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK is suitable for many patients, but not everyone.</strong> Eligibility depends on multiple factors including your eye condition, corneal health, and medical history.</p>\n<p><strong>The best way to know if you are eligible is to undergo a detailed evaluation by an experienced refractive surgeon.</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Book your eye check-up today and take the first step toward clear, glasses-free vision.</strong></p>\n<p><em>Disclaimer: This content is for patient awareness and educational purposes only. Please consult a qualified ophthalmologist for medical advice.</em></p>\n<p>&#8220;`</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Wondering if you qualify for WaveLight Plus InnovEyes LASIK? This guide covers all the key eligibility factors, from prescription requirements and corneal thickness to overall health considerations, so you can determine if this advanced laser vision correction system is right for you.</p>\n"},{"slug":"wavelight-plus-innoveyes-vs-smile-vs-lasik-which-laser-eye-surgery-is-best-in-2026","date":"2026-02-24","title":"Wavelight Plus InnovEyes vs SMILE vs LASIK ‚Äì Which Laser Eye Surgery Is Best in 2026?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2026/02/24/wavelight-plus-innoveyes-vs-smile-vs-lasik-which-laser-eye-surgery-is-best-in-2026","contentHtml":"","excerptHtml":""},{"slug":"wavelight-plus-innoveyes-success-rate-patient-outcomes-a-comprehensive-guide","date":"2026-02-24","title":"Wavelight Plus InnovEyes Success Rate & Patient Outcomes: A Comprehensive Guide","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2026/02/24/wavelight-plus-innoveyes-success-rate-patient-outcomes-a-comprehensive-guide","contentHtml":"<p>With advancements in laser vision correction, <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> has emerged as a next-generation approach designed to improve precision and visual quality. Patients often want to know one key thing: <strong>What is the success rate and what results can I expect?</strong></p>\n<p>This guide explains success rates, clinical outcomes, and real patient benefits in a simple and medically accurate way.</p>\n<h4>Understanding WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus</strong> is an advanced excimer laser system by Alcon, widely used for LASIK and PRK procedures due to its speed and accuracy.</p>\n<p><strong>InnovEyes</strong> enhances this by using <strong>AI-based 3D eye modeling</strong>, which analyzes how light travels through the entire eye. This allows surgeons to create a <strong>highly personalized treatment plan</strong> aimed at improving overall visual quality.</p>\n<h4>Success Rate – What to Expect</h4>\n<p>Modern LASIK procedures using WaveLight platforms have consistently shown high success rates when performed on suitable candidates.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Visual Acuity:</strong> More than <strong>95% of patients achieve 6/6 (20/20) vision or better</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Accuracy:</strong> Most patients achieve results close to their intended correction</li>\n<li><strong>Stability:</strong> Vision remains stable in the long term in the majority of cases</li>\n</ul>\n<p>InnovEyes aims to further enhance these outcomes by improving treatment customization and visual quality.</p>\n<h4>Visual Quality and Patient Outcomes</h4>\n<p>Beyond just achieving clear vision, InnovEyes focuses on improving how well you see in different conditions.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Better night vision</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Improved contrast sensitivity</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Reduced glare and halos</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Sharper and more natural vision</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Many patients report high satisfaction due to improved visual comfort in daily activities such as night driving and screen use.</p>\n<h4>Recovery and Healing</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Vision improves within <strong>24 hours</strong> in most cases</li>\n<li>Functional vision is achieved quickly</li>\n<li>Stabilization typically occurs within a few weeks</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Recovery timelines may vary depending on individual healing and procedure type.</p>\n<h4>Safety and Complication Rates</h4>\n<p>Laser vision correction using WaveLight technology has a strong safety profile:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Serious complications are <strong>rare</strong></li>\n<li>Most side effects (dryness, glare) are <strong>temporary</strong></li>\n<li>Enhancement (repeat correction) may be required in a small number of cases</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Who Gets the Best Results?</h4>\n<p>The best outcomes are seen in patients who:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Have stable vision numbers</li>\n<li>Have healthy corneas with adequate thickness</li>\n<li>Do not have underlying eye diseases</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Proper patient selection and detailed pre-operative evaluation are critical for success.</p>\n<h4>Important Factors That Influence Outcomes</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Surgeon experience</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Quality of diagnostic evaluation</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Correct procedure selection</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Post-operative care and follow-up</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Technology improves outcomes, but overall success depends on the complete treatment process.</p>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes offers high success rates comparable to modern LASIK, with added benefits of personalized treatment and improved visual quality.</strong></p>\n<p>While most patients achieve excellent results, the final outcome depends on individual eye condition and proper surgical planning.</p>\n<p><strong>Consult an experienced refractive surgeon to understand your expected results and suitability.</strong></p>\n<p><em>Disclaimer: This content is for educational and patient awareness purposes only. Please consult a qualified ophthalmologist for personalized medical advice.</em></p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Discover the impressive success rates and patient outcomes associated with the Wavelight Plus InnovEyes laser vision correction platform, including clinical data on visual acuity, safety, and patient satisfaction.</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-wavelight-plus-innoveyes-safe-a-doctor-backed-guide-to-this-laser-eye-technology","date":"2026-02-24","title":"Is Wavelight Plus InnovEyes Safe? A Doctor-Backed Guide to This Laser Eye Technology","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2026/02/24/is-wavelight-plus-innoveyes-safe-a-doctor-backed-guide-to-this-laser-eye-technology","contentHtml":"<p>If you are considering laser eye surgery, you may have come across <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong>, one of the latest advancements in vision correction. A common and important question patients ask is: <strong>Is it safe?</strong></p>\n<p>This guide explains the safety of InnovEyes technology in a simple and medically accurate way, helping you make an informed decision.</p>\n<h4>What Is WaveLight Plus InnovEyes?</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus</strong> is an advanced excimer laser system by Alcon, widely used in LASIK and PRK procedures.</p>\n<p><strong>InnovEyes</strong> enhances this by using <strong>AI-based 3D eye modeling</strong> to analyze how light travels through the entire eye. This allows for a more <strong>personalized and precise treatment plan</strong>, focused on improving overall visual quality.</p>\n<h4>Is WaveLight Plus InnovEyes Safe?</h4>\n<p><strong>Yes — when performed on suitable candidates by an experienced surgeon, InnovEyes-based LASIK is considered safe and effective.</strong></p>\n<p>The safety comes from a combination of:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Proven excimer laser technology used globally for many years</li>\n<li>Advanced eye-tracking systems that ensure precise laser delivery</li>\n<li>Personalized treatment planning to reduce visual side effects</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Clinical Safety and Track Record</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Modern LASIK procedures using WaveLight platforms have high safety standards</li>\n<li>More than <strong>95% of patients achieve 6/6 vision or better</strong> in suitable cases</li>\n<li>Serious complications are rare when proper screening is done</li>\n</ul>\n<p>InnovEyes builds on this safety by improving treatment customization and visual quality.</p>\n<h4>What Do Doctors Say?</h4>\n<p>Refractive surgeons consider InnovEyes an advancement in LASIK because it focuses on <strong>quality of vision</strong>, not just number correction. However, doctors also emphasize that:</p>\n<p><strong>“The outcome depends more on proper patient selection and surgical expertise than technology alone.”</strong></p>\n<h4>Possible Side Effects</h4>\n<p>Like any laser eye surgery, some temporary side effects can occur:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Dry eyes:</strong> Common in the first few weeks, usually temporary</li>\n<li><strong>Glare or halos:</strong> Especially at night during early recovery</li>\n<li><strong>Fluctuating vision:</strong> During the healing phase</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Rare risks include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Under-correction or over-correction</li>\n<li>Infection or inflammation (very rare)</li>\n<li>Flap-related issues (in LASIK procedures)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Most side effects are temporary and manageable with proper care.</p>\n<h4>Who Is a Suitable Candidate?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Age above 18 years with stable number</li>\n<li>Adequate corneal thickness</li>\n<li>No active eye diseases</li>\n<li>No uncontrolled systemic conditions</li>\n</ul>\n<p>A detailed pre-LASIK evaluation is essential to ensure safety.</p>\n<h4>Important Factors That Affect Safety</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Surgeon experience</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Quality of pre-operative screening</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Following post-operative instructions</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Technology alone does not guarantee results — the overall treatment process matters.</p>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes is a safe and advanced option for laser vision correction</strong> when performed under the right conditions.</p>\n<p>It combines proven LASIK technology with modern customization to improve visual quality and patient satisfaction.</p>\n<p><strong>The safest approach is to consult an experienced refractive surgeon, undergo proper evaluation, and choose the procedure best suited to your eyes.</strong></p>\n<p><em>Disclaimer: This content is for patient awareness and educational purposes only. It should not replace medical consultation. Please consult a qualified ophthalmologist before making any decision.</em></p>\n<p>&#8220;`</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Wondering if the Wavelight Plus InnovEyes laser system is safe for vision correction? This doctor-backed guide covers clinical evidence, FDA approval data, potential risks, and expert opinions to help you make an informed decision.</p>\n"},{"slug":"innoveyes-vs-smile-pro-which-one-gives-better-vision","date":"2026-02-24","title":"InnovEyes vs SMILE Pro – Which One Gives Better Vision?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2026/02/24/innoveyes-vs-smile-pro-which-one-gives-better-vision","contentHtml":"<p>If you are exploring advanced laser eye surgery options, you may have come across <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> and <strong>SMILE Pro</strong>. Both are among the latest technologies in vision correction, offering high precision and fast recovery. However, they work very differently and are suited for different types of patients.</p>\n<p>This guide explains both procedures in a simple and medically accurate way to help you understand which option may be better for your eyes.</p>\n<h4>Understanding the Technology</h4>\n<h4>What Is WaveLight Plus InnovEyes?</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> is an advanced <strong>AI-based LASIK technology</strong> developed by Alcon. It uses <strong>3D eye modeling</strong> to analyze how light travels through your entire eye — not just the cornea.</p>\n<p>Based on this, a highly personalized laser treatment is performed using a <strong>Femto LASIK approach</strong> (bladeless LASIK), where the cornea is reshaped with an excimer laser.</p>\n<p>This technology focuses on improving overall <strong>quality of vision</strong>, including night vision, contrast, and clarity.</p>\n<h4>What Is SMILE Pro?</h4>\n<p><strong>SMILE Pro</strong> (Small Incision Lenticule Extraction) is a <strong>minimally invasive, flapless laser procedure</strong> developed by ZEISS.</p>\n<p>In this technique, a femtosecond laser creates a small lenticule (thin layer of tissue) inside the cornea, which is removed through a tiny incision (2–4 mm). No flap is created.</p>\n<p>SMILE Pro is mainly used for <strong>myopia (minus power) and myopic astigmatism</strong>.</p>\n<h4>Key Differences Between InnovEyes and SMILE Pro</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Procedure Type:</strong><br />\nInnovEyes is a flap-based Femto LASIK procedure, while SMILE Pro is flapless.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong><br />\nInnovEyes uses AI-based 3D eye modeling for customized treatment, whereas SMILE Pro uses a lenticule extraction technique.</li>\n<li><strong>Customization:</strong><br />\nInnovEyes offers higher customization for overall visual quality. SMILE Pro is less customizable but highly effective for standard myopia.</li>\n<li><strong>Conditions Treated:</strong><br />\nInnovEyes can treat myopia, hyperopia, and astigmatism. SMILE Pro mainly treats myopia and myopic astigmatism.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Procedure Experience &#038; Recovery</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Procedure Time:</strong> Both procedures are quick (10–15 minutes for both eyes)</li>\n<li><strong>Discomfort:</strong> Minimal in both procedures</li>\n<li><strong>Recovery:</strong><br />\nSMILE Pro – Functional vision in 24–48 hours<br />\nInnovEyes – Clear vision often within 24 hours</li>\n<li><strong>Dry Eye Risk:</strong><br />\nSMILE Pro has slightly lower dry eye risk due to no flap<br />\nInnovEyes may have mild temporary dryness, which is manageable</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Visual Outcomes – Which Is Better?</h4>\n<p>Both procedures provide excellent results, but the difference lies in <strong>quality vs approach</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>SMILE Pro:</strong> Excellent for standard number correction with stable outcomes</li>\n<li><strong>InnovEyes:</strong> Better for enhanced visual quality, especially night vision and contrast</li>\n</ul>\n<p>InnovEyes may be preferred in patients who want <strong>premium, highly customized vision correction</strong>.</p>\n<h4>Who Should Choose What?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Choose SMILE Pro if:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>You have myopia (minus power)</li>\n<li>You prefer a flapless procedure</li>\n<li>You are concerned about dry eyes</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Choose InnovEyes if:</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>You want the most advanced, customized LASIK</li>\n<li>You have complex vision requirements</li>\n<li>You want better night vision and visual quality</li>\n<li>You have hyperopia or mixed errors</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Important Note</h4>\n<p>The best procedure depends on your <strong>eye condition, corneal thickness, and lifestyle</strong>. Not everyone is suitable for both options.</p>\n<p>A detailed eye check-up with an experienced refractive surgeon is essential before deciding.</p>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p><strong>Both InnovEyes and SMILE Pro are advanced and safe technologies</strong>, but they serve different needs. SMILE Pro is ideal for minimally invasive correction of myopia, while InnovEyes offers a more personalized approach with enhanced visual quality.</p>\n<p><strong>The right choice is the one best suited to your eyes — not just the latest technology.</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Book a detailed eye evaluation to find out which procedure is best for you.</strong></p>\n<p>&#8220;`</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Comparing InnovEyes and SMILE Pro for laser vision correction — explore the technology, recovery, visual outcomes, and ideal candidates for each procedure to determine which one delivers better vision for your eyes.</p>\n"},{"slug":"innoveyes-vs-traditional-lasik-a-complete-side-by-side-comparison-for-2024","date":"2026-02-24","title":"InnovEyes vs Traditional LASIK: A Complete Side-by-Side Comparison for 2024","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2026/02/24/innoveyes-vs-traditional-lasik-a-complete-side-by-side-comparison-for-2024","contentHtml":"<p>If you are considering laser eye surgery, you may have come across both <strong>traditional LASIK</strong> and the newer <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> technology. With advancements in laser vision correction, choosing the right option can feel confusing.</p>\n<p>This guide explains the key differences between InnovEyes and traditional LASIK in a simple, medically accurate way — covering technology, procedure, recovery, and outcomes.</p>\n<h4>What Is Traditional LASIK?</h4>\n<p><strong>LASIK (Laser-Assisted In Situ Keratomileusis)</strong> is a well-established procedure used for over 20 years to correct:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Myopia (minus power)</li>\n<li>Hyperopia (plus power)</li>\n<li>Astigmatism</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The procedure involves creating a thin corneal flap (using a microkeratome or femtosecond laser) and reshaping the cornea with an excimer laser to correct vision.</p>\n<h4>What Is WaveLight Plus InnovEyes?</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> is an advanced <strong>next-generation LASIK technology by Alcon</strong> that uses <strong>AI-based 3D eye modeling</strong>.</p>\n<p>Unlike traditional LASIK, which mainly focuses on correcting glasses power, InnovEyes analyzes how light travels through the entire eye and creates a <strong>highly personalized treatment plan</strong>.</p>\n<p>This results in improved overall visual quality, especially in low-light conditions.</p>\n<h4>Key Differences Between InnovEyes and Traditional LASIK</h4>\n<h4>1. Treatment Approach</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Traditional LASIK:</strong> Based on glasses number and basic measurements</li>\n<li><strong>InnovEyes:</strong> Based on full eye optical system using 3D modeling</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>2. Level of Customization</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Traditional LASIK offers standard or wavefront-optimized treatment</li>\n<li>InnovEyes provides <strong>highly personalized correction</strong> tailored to your eye</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>3. Visual Quality</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Traditional LASIK:</strong> Focus on achieving 6/6 vision</li>\n<li><strong>InnovEyes:</strong> Focus on better <strong>quality of vision</strong> (contrast, night vision, clarity)</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>4. Technology Used</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Both use excimer laser for corneal reshaping</li>\n<li>InnovEyes combines advanced diagnostics with precision laser treatment</li>\n<li>Both can use bladeless Femto LASIK for flap creation</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Procedure and Recovery</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Procedure Time:</strong> 10–15 minutes for both eyes in both techniques</li>\n<li><strong>Pain:</strong> Minimal in both</li>\n<li><strong>Vision Recovery:</strong> Most patients see clearly within 24 hours</li>\n<li><strong>Stabilization:</strong> 2–4 weeks (may vary)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Recovery experience is similar, though InnovEyes may provide slightly better visual comfort in some patients.</p>\n<h4>Who Is It Suitable For?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Traditional LASIK:</strong> Suitable for most standard vision correction cases</li>\n<li><strong>InnovEyes:</strong> Suitable for patients seeking premium, customized correction or better visual quality</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Final eligibility depends on corneal thickness, eye health, and detailed screening.</p>\n<h4>Cost Difference (India)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Traditional LASIK:</strong> ₹25,000 – ₹60,000 per eye</li>\n<li><strong>InnovEyes:</strong> ₹60,000 – ₹90,000 per eye (approx.)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>InnovEyes is a premium procedure due to advanced technology and customization.</p>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p><strong>Both InnovEyes and traditional LASIK are safe and effective</strong>, but they serve slightly different goals.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Choose <strong>traditional LASIK</strong> for a proven, cost-effective solution</li>\n<li>Choose <strong>InnovEyes</strong> for advanced, personalized vision correction with improved visual quality</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>The best choice depends on your eyes — not just the technology.</strong></p>\n<p>Consult an experienced refractive surgeon to determine the most suitable option for you.</p>\n<p>&#8220;`</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Considering laser eye surgery? This in-depth comparison of InnovEyes and traditional LASIK covers technology, recovery, cost, and outcomes to help you choose the right vision correction procedure.</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-is-ray-tracing-technology-in-lasik-innoveyes-explained","date":"2026-02-24","title":"What is Ray Tracing Technology in LASIK? InnovEyes Explained","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2026/02/24/what-is-ray-tracing-technology-in-lasik-innoveyes-explained","contentHtml":"<p>If you&#8217;ve been researching the latest advancements in LASIK eye surgery, you may have come across the term <strong>ray tracing technology</strong> — specifically in connection with the <strong>InnovEyes platform</strong>. This cutting-edge approach is transforming how surgeons plan and perform laser vision correction, delivering unprecedented levels of precision and personalized treatment. But what exactly is ray tracing, and how does it improve LASIK outcomes? Let&#8217;s break it down.</p>\n<h2>Understanding Ray Tracing: From Computer Graphics to Eye Surgery</h2>\n<p>Ray tracing is a concept that originated in the world of computer graphics and optical engineering. At its core, ray tracing is a computational method that simulates the path of light rays as they travel through a complex optical system — in this case, the human eye.</p>\n<p>Unlike traditional measurement techniques that rely on simplified models of how light passes through the cornea and lens, ray tracing tracks <strong>thousands of individual light rays</strong> as they enter the eye, refract through the cornea, pass through the pupil and lens, and ultimately reach the retina. This allows for an extraordinarily detailed map of the eye&#8217;s optical imperfections, including:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Lower-order aberrations</strong> — such as nearsightedness, farsightedness, and astigmatism</li>\n<li><strong>Higher-order aberrations</strong> — subtle irregularities like coma, trefoil, and spherical aberration that standard glasses and contacts cannot correct</li>\n<li><strong>Pupil-dependent variations</strong> — changes in visual quality that occur as the pupil dilates or constricts under different lighting conditions</li>\n</ul>\n<p>By capturing these nuances, ray tracing provides a far more complete picture of a patient&#8217;s unique visual system than conventional wavefront or topography measurements alone.</p>\n<h2>What is InnovEyes? The Platform Behind the Precision</h2>\n<p>The <strong>InnovEyes platform</strong> is an advanced diagnostic and treatment planning system that integrates ray tracing technology directly into the LASIK workflow. Developed to push the boundaries of personalized refractive surgery, InnovEyes uses proprietary algorithms and sophisticated optical modeling to create a highly individualized treatment plan for each patient.</p>\n<p>Here&#8217;s how the InnovEyes process typically works:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Comprehensive eye measurement:</strong> The platform captures detailed data about the cornea&#8217;s shape, thickness, curvature, and the eye&#8217;s internal optics using advanced diagnostic instruments.</li>\n<li><strong>Ray tracing analysis:</strong> Instead of relying on a single averaged measurement, InnovEyes traces the path of numerous light rays through the patient&#8217;s entire optical system. This produces a true, physics-based model of how light behaves in that specific eye.</li>\n<li><strong>Personalized ablation profile:</strong> Based on the ray tracing data, InnovEyes generates a custom laser treatment profile that addresses not only standard refractive errors but also the unique higher-order aberrations present in the patient&#8217;s eye.</li>\n<li><strong>Optimized outcomes:</strong> The treatment plan is designed to maximize visual quality, reduce the risk of post-operative side effects like glare and halos, and deliver sharper vision across all lighting conditions.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This level of personalization represents a significant leap beyond traditional LASIK approaches, which often use more generalized treatment profiles based on a patient&#8217;s prescription alone.</p>\n<h2>Why Ray Tracing Matters: Benefits for LASIK Patients</h2>\n<p>The integration of ray tracing technology into LASIK offers several meaningful advantages for patients seeking laser vision correction:</p>\n<h3>1. Superior Visual Acuity</h3>\n<p>By addressing higher-order aberrations that conventional LASIK ignores, ray tracing-guided treatments can help patients achieve <strong>sharper, crisper vision</strong> — sometimes even better than what glasses or contacts could provide before surgery.</p>\n<h3>2. Reduced Night Vision Issues</h3>\n<p>One of the most common complaints after traditional LASIK is difficulty with night vision, including glare, halos, and starbursts around lights. Because ray tracing accounts for how the eye performs under low-light conditions when the pupil is dilated, treatments designed with this data tend to <strong>minimize these side effects significantly</strong>.</p>\n<h3>3. Truly Personalized Treatment</h3>\n<p>No two eyes are identical. Ray tracing acknowledges this by creating a treatment that is as unique as the patient&#8217;s fingerprint. This <strong>individualized approach</strong> leads to more predictable results and higher patient satisfaction rates.</p>\n<h3>4. Enhanced Safety and Precision</h3>\n<p>With a more accurate understanding of the eye&#8217;s optics, surgeons can plan treatments with greater confidence, potentially <strong>reducing the need for enhancement procedures</strong> and improving first-time success rates.</p>\n<h2>The Future of Laser Vision Correction</h2>\n<p>Ray tracing technology, as implemented in platforms like InnovEyes, represents a broader trend in refractive surgery: the move toward <strong>fully personalized, data-driven treatments</strong>. As diagnostic tools become more sophisticated and computational power continues to increase, the ability to model the eye&#8217;s optical system with extreme accuracy will only improve.</p>\n<p>For patients considering LASIK, the availability of ray tracing-guided procedures means that better visual outcomes with fewer compromises are now within reach. If you&#8217;re exploring your options, ask your ophthalmologist whether they use ray tracing technology or the InnovEyes platform — it could make a meaningful difference in the quality of your results.</p>\n<p>As laser technology continues to evolve, innovations like ray tracing remind us that the future of vision correction is not just about seeing clearly — it&#8217;s about seeing <em>optimally</em>.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Ray tracing technology in LASIK, as used in the InnovEyes platform, traces thousands of light rays through the eye to create highly personalized treatment plans that deliver sharper vision and fewer side effects than traditional approaches.</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-makes-wavelight-plus-innoveyes-different-from-other-lasik-a-complete-breakdown","date":"2026-02-24","title":"What Makes WaveLight Plus InnovEyes Different from Other LASIK? A Complete Breakdown","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2026/02/24/what-makes-wavelight-plus-innoveyes-different-from-other-lasik-a-complete-breakdown","contentHtml":"<p>LASIK eye surgery has evolved significantly over the years, but not all LASIK technologies deliver the same level of precision and visual quality. One of the latest advancements is <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes by Alcon</strong> — a next-generation laser vision correction approach designed for highly personalized and optimized outcomes.</p>\n<p>In this guide, we break down what makes InnovEyes different from traditional LASIK and other modern technologies like Contoura Vision and SMILE.</p>\n<h4>Understanding WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus</strong> is an advanced excimer laser platform known for its speed, precision, and safety in LASIK procedures.</p>\n<p><strong>InnovEyes</strong> enhances this by introducing <strong>AI-based 3D eye modeling</strong>, which analyzes how light travels through the entire eye — not just the corneal surface.</p>\n<p>This allows surgeons to create a highly customized treatment plan focused on improving overall visual quality, not just correcting the glasses number.</p>\n<h4>Key Differences from Traditional LASIK</h4>\n<h4>1. Whole Eye Treatment vs Cornea-Only Treatment</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Traditional LASIK:</strong> Based on glasses power</li>\n<li><strong>Contoura Vision:</strong> Based on corneal surface mapping</li>\n<li><strong>InnovEyes:</strong> Based on full eye optical system using AI modeling</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This makes InnovEyes more comprehensive and precise in delivering visual outcomes.</p>\n<h4>2. Advanced Personalization with AI</h4>\n<p>InnovEyes creates a <strong>3D digital model of your eye</strong>, allowing treatment to be customized based on how light behaves inside your eye. This leads to better clarity, improved contrast, and more natural vision.</p>\n<h4>3. Improved Visual Quality (Not Just 6/6 Vision)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Better night vision</li>\n<li>Reduced glare and halos</li>\n<li>Enhanced contrast sensitivity</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Unlike standard LASIK, which focuses on achieving 6/6 vision, InnovEyes aims to improve overall visual performance.</p>\n<h4>4. High-Speed Laser with Precision Tracking</h4>\n<p>The WaveLight Plus laser offers:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>High-speed excimer laser delivery</li>\n<li>Advanced eye-tracking technology</li>\n<li>Precise corneal reshaping with minimal tissue impact</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This ensures safety, accuracy, and consistent outcomes.</p>\n<h4>5. Better Suitability for Complex Cases</h4>\n<p>InnovEyes is particularly beneficial for patients with:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Higher refractive errors</li>\n<li>Subtle optical irregularities</li>\n<li>Night vision concerns</li>\n<li>Demand for premium visual quality</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>InnovEyes vs Other Modern Technologies</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>SMILE:</strong> Minimally invasive but less customizable</li>\n<li><strong>Contoura Vision:</strong> Cornea-focused customization</li>\n<li><strong>InnovEyes:</strong> Full optical system customization with AI</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Important Consideration</h4>\n<p>While technology is important, <strong>surgeon expertise remains the most critical factor</strong>. A well-executed procedure by an experienced refractive surgeon ensures the best results.</p>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> represents a major advancement in laser vision correction by combining high-speed laser precision with AI-driven personalization. It addresses many limitations of traditional LASIK and offers superior visual quality, especially in challenging conditions like night driving.</p>\n<p>If you are considering LASIK, consult an experienced eye surgeon to determine whether InnovEyes is the right option for your eyes.</p>\n<p><strong>Experience next-generation vision correction with advanced, personalized laser technology.</strong></p>\n<p>&#8220;`</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The WaveLight Plus InnovEyes platform sets itself apart from other LASIK systems through integrated diagnostics, ultra-fast 500 Hz laser speeds, topography-guided treatments, and advanced eye tracking — delivering more precise and personalized vision correction outcomes.</p>\n"},{"slug":"innoveyes-eye-surgery-in-hyderabad-complete-guide-to-advanced-laser-vision-correction","date":"2026-02-24","title":"InnovEyes Eye Surgery in Hyderabad – Complete Guide to Advanced Laser Vision Correction","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2026/02/24/innoveyes-eye-surgery-in-hyderabad-complete-guide-to-advanced-laser-vision-correction","contentHtml":"<h3>InnovEyes Eye Surgery in Hyderabad – Complete Guide to Advanced Laser Vision Correction</h3>\n<p>Hyderabad has become one of India’s leading hubs for advanced eye care, offering world-class infrastructure and highly experienced refractive surgeons. Among the latest innovations in vision correction, <strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> stands out as a next-generation, AI-powered laser eye surgery designed for superior precision and personalized outcomes.</p>\n<p>If you are looking to eliminate glasses or contact lenses, InnovEyes offers one of the most advanced and customized laser vision correction solutions available today in Hyderabad.</p>\n<h4>What Is InnovEyes Eye Surgery?</h4>\n<p><strong>WaveLight Plus InnovEyes</strong> is an advanced laser vision correction technology developed by Alcon that uses <strong>artificial intelligence and 3D eye modeling</strong> to deliver highly personalized treatment.</p>\n<p>Unlike conventional LASIK, which primarily focuses on correcting the glasses number, InnovEyes analyzes how light travels through your entire eye. It creates a detailed 3D model of the eye’s optical system and designs a treatment plan tailored specifically to your visual profile.</p>\n<p>This results in improved visual quality, especially in challenging conditions like night driving, low light, and screen usage.</p>\n<h4>Conditions Treated with InnovEyes</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Myopia (near-sightedness)</li>\n<li>Hyperopia (far-sightedness)</li>\n<li>Astigmatism</li>\n<li>Select cases of presbyopia (based on suitability)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Eligibility depends on factors such as corneal thickness, eye health, and detailed diagnostic evaluation.</p>\n<h4>InnovEyes vs Traditional LASIK</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Standard LASIK:</strong> Corrects vision based on glasses power</li>\n<li><strong>Contoura Vision:</strong> Corrects corneal surface irregularities</li>\n<li><strong>InnovEyes:</strong> Uses AI-driven 3D eye modeling for complete optical system correction</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This makes InnovEyes one of the most advanced forms of customized laser eye surgery available globally.</p>\n<h4>Procedure Overview</h4>\n<p>InnovEyes treatment is typically performed using a <strong>bladeless Femto LASIK approach</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Step 1: A precise corneal flap is created using a femtosecond laser</li>\n<li>Step 2: AI-guided excimer laser reshapes the cornea based on your 3D eye model</li>\n<li>Step 3: The flap is repositioned naturally without stitches</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The procedure is painless and usually completed within <strong>10–15 minutes for both eyes</strong>.</p>\n<h4>Key Benefits of InnovEyes Surgery</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>AI-based <strong>highly personalized treatment</strong></li>\n<li>Enhanced <strong>night vision and contrast sensitivity</strong></li>\n<li>Reduced glare and halos</li>\n<li>Greater precision compared to standard LASIK</li>\n<li>Fast recovery with minimal discomfort</li>\n<li>Improved overall visual quality, not just clarity</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Cost of InnovEyes Surgery in Hyderabad</h4>\n<p>The cost of InnovEyes eye surgery in Hyderabad typically ranges between:</p>\n<p><strong>₹1,20,000 to ₹1,80,000 for both eyes</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Cost may vary depending on the hospital, surgeon expertise, and technology platform</li>\n<li>This is a premium procedure and may not be covered under standard insurance plans</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Recovery and Post-Operative Care</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Day 1:</strong> Noticeable vision improvement within 24 hours</li>\n<li><strong>Week 1:</strong> Avoid eye rubbing, water exposure, and heavy physical activity</li>\n<li><strong>1 Month:</strong> Vision stabilizes significantly</li>\n<li><strong>3 Months:</strong> Final visual outcomes are achieved</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Regular follow-up visits are important to monitor healing and ensure optimal results.</p>\n<h4>Why Choose InnovEyes in Hyderabad?</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Access to advanced <strong>AI-driven laser technology</strong></li>\n<li>Experienced refractive surgeons with high surgical volumes</li>\n<li>Availability at select premium eye hospitals</li>\n<li>Competitive pricing compared to other metro cities</li>\n<li>Comprehensive pre-operative diagnostics for better safety</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Important Considerations</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Not all patients are suitable for InnovEyes — proper screening is essential</li>\n<li>Dry eye assessment is crucial before surgery</li>\n<li>Choosing an experienced surgeon significantly impacts outcomes</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\n<p><strong>InnovEyes Eye Surgery</strong> represents the future of laser vision correction, combining artificial intelligence, advanced optics, and precision laser technology. For patients in Hyderabad seeking a premium and highly customized alternative to traditional LASIK, InnovEyes offers excellent safety, accuracy, and visual outcomes.</p>\n<p>If you are planning to permanently remove your glasses, consult a qualified refractive surgeon in Hyderabad and undergo a detailed evaluation to determine your eligibility for InnovEyes treatment.</p>\n<p><strong>Book your InnovEyes consultation today and take the first step toward clearer, sharper vision.</strong></p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Discover everything about InnovEyes Eye Surgery in Hyderabad, including laser procedures like LASIK, SMILE, and PRK, advanced technology, experienced surgeons, costs, and recovery expectations in this complete guide.</p>\n"},{"slug":"faq-on-lasik-eligibility-for-railway-recruitment-board-rrb-jobs-alp-a1-a2-a3-b1-b2-c1-c2-and-group-d","date":"2025-10-02","title":"FAQ on LASIK Eligibility for Railway Recruitment Board (RRB) Jobs 2025  – ALP A1, A2, A3, B1, B2, C1, C2, and Group D","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2025/10/02/faq-on-lasik-eligibility-for-railway-recruitment-board-rrb-jobs-alp-a1-a2-a3-b1-b2-c1-c2-and-group-d","contentHtml":"<p data-start=\"133\" data-end=\"219\">For more information, speak directly with a laser vision specialist at <strong data-start=\"204\" data-end=\"218\">9667770453</strong>.</p>\n<p data-start=\"256\" data-end=\"329\">अधिक जानकारी के लिए laser vision doctor से सीधे बात करें: <strong data-start=\"314\" data-end=\"328\">9667770453</strong>.</p>\n<p><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"Railway ALP A1 Medical Vision Test – Must to Know &amp; Get 6/6 Clear Vision | Helpline 9667770453\" width=\"900\" height=\"506\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/PFB6Oyy2O7M?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>\n<h3 data-start=\"284\" data-end=\"369\">Q1. Is LASIK allowed in <strong data-start=\"312\" data-end=\"366\">Railway ALP (Assistant Loco Pilot) A1 Medical Test</strong>?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"370\" data-end=\"462\"><strong data-start=\"370\" data-end=\"381\">Answer:</strong> ❌ No. LASIK is <strong data-start=\"397\" data-end=\"412\">not allowed</strong> in A1 category jobs like ALP and Train Drivers.</p>\n<ul data-start=\"463\" data-end=\"578\">\n<li data-start=\"463\" data-end=\"518\">\n<p data-start=\"465\" data-end=\"518\">A1 requires <strong data-start=\"477\" data-end=\"515\">6/6 natural vision without glasses</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"519\" data-end=\"578\">\n<p data-start=\"521\" data-end=\"578\">Even after LASIK, candidates are considered ineligible.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"580\" data-end=\"583\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"585\" data-end=\"643\">Q2. Can I apply for <strong data-start=\"609\" data-end=\"628\">Railway A2 jobs</strong> after LASIK?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"644\" data-end=\"767\"><strong data-start=\"644\" data-end=\"655\">Answer:</strong> ❌ No. LASIK is <strong data-start=\"671\" data-end=\"688\">not permitted</strong> in A2 category jobs (e.g., Station Master, Traffic Apprentice, Goods Guard).</p>\n<ul data-start=\"768\" data-end=\"906\">\n<li data-start=\"768\" data-end=\"851\">\n<p data-start=\"770\" data-end=\"851\">Vision requirement: <strong data-start=\"790\" data-end=\"849\">6/6 in one eye and 6/9 in the other without correction.</strong></p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"852\" data-end=\"906\">\n<p data-start=\"854\" data-end=\"906\">LASIK automatically disqualifies candidates in A2.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"908\" data-end=\"911\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"913\" data-end=\"954\">Q3. What about <strong data-start=\"932\" data-end=\"951\">Railway A3 jobs</strong>?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"955\" data-end=\"1069\"><strong data-start=\"955\" data-end=\"966\">Answer:</strong> ❌ LASIK is <strong data-start=\"978\" data-end=\"993\">not allowed</strong> for A3 category (e.g., Traffic Assistant, Senior Clerks in control room).</p>\n<ul data-start=\"1070\" data-end=\"1199\">\n<li data-start=\"1070\" data-end=\"1132\">\n<p data-start=\"1072\" data-end=\"1132\">Vision requirement: <strong data-start=\"1092\" data-end=\"1130\">6/9 in one eye, 6/12 in the other.</strong></p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1133\" data-end=\"1199\">\n<p data-start=\"1135\" data-end=\"1199\">Natural eyesight is mandatory, no refractive surgery accepted.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"1201\" data-end=\"1204\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1206\" data-end=\"1258\">Q4. Is LASIK accepted for <strong data-start=\"1236\" data-end=\"1255\">Railway B1 jobs</strong>?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"1259\" data-end=\"1311\"><strong data-start=\"1259\" data-end=\"1270\">Answer:</strong> ✅ Yes, but with <strong data-start=\"1287\" data-end=\"1308\">strict conditions</strong>:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"1312\" data-end=\"1585\">\n<li data-start=\"1312\" data-end=\"1350\">\n<p data-start=\"1314\" data-end=\"1350\">Surgery must be <strong data-start=\"1330\" data-end=\"1347\">uncomplicated</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1351\" data-end=\"1391\">\n<p data-start=\"1353\" data-end=\"1391\"><strong data-start=\"1353\" data-end=\"1389\">Corneal thickness &gt; 425 microns.</strong></p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1392\" data-end=\"1431\">\n<p data-start=\"1394\" data-end=\"1431\"><strong data-start=\"1394\" data-end=\"1429\">Retina (fundus) must be normal.</strong></p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1432\" data-end=\"1491\">\n<p data-start=\"1434\" data-end=\"1491\"><strong data-start=\"1434\" data-end=\"1457\">At least 1 year gap</strong> between LASIK and medical test.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1492\" data-end=\"1540\">\n<p data-start=\"1494\" data-end=\"1540\">No progressive eye disease like keratoconus.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1541\" data-end=\"1585\">\n<p data-start=\"1543\" data-end=\"1585\">Vision up to <strong data-start=\"1556\" data-end=\"1583\">6/9 or 6/12 acceptable.</strong></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"1587\" data-end=\"1590\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1592\" data-end=\"1645\">Q5. Can I join <strong data-start=\"1611\" data-end=\"1630\">Railway B2 jobs</strong> after LASIK?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"1646\" data-end=\"1702\"><strong data-start=\"1646\" data-end=\"1657\">Answer:</strong> ✅ Yes, with the <strong data-start=\"1674\" data-end=\"1699\">same conditions as B1</strong>.</p>\n<ul data-start=\"1703\" data-end=\"1840\">\n<li data-start=\"1703\" data-end=\"1758\">\n<p data-start=\"1705\" data-end=\"1758\">Safe LASIK, healthy retina, thickness &gt;425 microns.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1759\" data-end=\"1802\">\n<p data-start=\"1761\" data-end=\"1802\">1 year gap between surgery and medical.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1803\" data-end=\"1840\">\n<p data-start=\"1805\" data-end=\"1840\">Vision up to <strong data-start=\"1818\" data-end=\"1838\">6/12 acceptable.</strong></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"1842\" data-end=\"1845\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1847\" data-end=\"1901\">Q6. Is LASIK allowed in <strong data-start=\"1875\" data-end=\"1898\">Railway C1 category</strong>?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"1902\" data-end=\"1922\"><strong data-start=\"1902\" data-end=\"1913\">Answer:</strong> ✅ Yes.</p>\n<ul data-start=\"1923\" data-end=\"2033\">\n<li data-start=\"1923\" data-end=\"1945\">\n<p data-start=\"1925\" data-end=\"1945\">LASIK is accepted.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1946\" data-end=\"1992\">\n<p data-start=\"1948\" data-end=\"1992\">Candidate must carry post-surgery reports.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1993\" data-end=\"2033\">\n<p data-start=\"1995\" data-end=\"2033\">Vision up to <strong data-start=\"2008\" data-end=\"2016\">6/12</strong> is acceptable.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"2035\" data-end=\"2038\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"2040\" data-end=\"2085\">Q7. What about <strong data-start=\"2059\" data-end=\"2082\">Railway C2 category</strong>?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"2086\" data-end=\"2106\"><strong data-start=\"2086\" data-end=\"2097\">Answer:</strong> ✅ Yes.</p>\n<ul data-start=\"2107\" data-end=\"2239\">\n<li data-start=\"2107\" data-end=\"2156\">\n<p data-start=\"2109\" data-end=\"2156\">LASIK is allowed without strict restrictions.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2157\" data-end=\"2198\">\n<p data-start=\"2159\" data-end=\"2198\">Reports should be carried for safety.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2199\" data-end=\"2239\">\n<p data-start=\"2201\" data-end=\"2239\">Vision up to <strong data-start=\"2214\" data-end=\"2222\">6/12</strong> is acceptable.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"2241\" data-end=\"2244\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"2246\" data-end=\"2301\">Q8. Is LASIK allowed in <strong data-start=\"2274\" data-end=\"2298\">Railway Group D jobs</strong>?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"2302\" data-end=\"2363\"><strong data-start=\"2302\" data-end=\"2313\">Answer:</strong> ✅ Yes, LASIK is <strong data-start=\"2330\" data-end=\"2360\">allowed without conditions</strong>.</p>\n<ul data-start=\"2364\" data-end=\"2487\">\n<li data-start=\"2364\" data-end=\"2444\">\n<p data-start=\"2366\" data-end=\"2444\">Vision requirement is relaxed – <strong data-start=\"2398\" data-end=\"2419\">6/12 or even 6/18</strong> depending on the role.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2445\" data-end=\"2487\">\n<p data-start=\"2447\" data-end=\"2487\">LASIK will not disqualify a candidate.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"2489\" data-end=\"2492\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"2494\" data-end=\"2559\">Q9. Which Railway categories <strong data-start=\"2527\" data-end=\"2556\">do not allow LASIK at all</strong>?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"2560\" data-end=\"2635\"><strong data-start=\"2560\" data-end=\"2571\">Answer:</strong> LASIK is <strong data-start=\"2581\" data-end=\"2596\">not allowed</strong> in <strong data-start=\"2600\" data-end=\"2614\">A1, A2, A3</strong> medical standards.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"2637\" data-end=\"2640\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"2642\" data-end=\"2694\">Q10. Which Railway categories <strong data-start=\"2676\" data-end=\"2691\">allow LASIK</strong>?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"2695\" data-end=\"2809\"><strong data-start=\"2695\" data-end=\"2706\">Answer:</strong> LASIK is <strong data-start=\"2716\" data-end=\"2727\">allowed</strong> in <strong data-start=\"2731\" data-end=\"2762\">B1, B2, C1, C2, and Group D</strong>, but B1 &amp; B2 have strict medical conditions.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"2811\" data-end=\"2814\" />\n<h2 data-start=\"2816\" data-end=\"2834\">📌 Final Note</h2>\n<ul data-start=\"2835\" data-end=\"3088\">\n<li data-start=\"2835\" data-end=\"2883\">\n<p data-start=\"2837\" data-end=\"2883\"><strong data-start=\"2837\" data-end=\"2881\">A1, A2, A3 → LASIK strictly not allowed.</strong></p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2884\" data-end=\"3015\">\n<p data-start=\"2886\" data-end=\"3015\"><strong data-start=\"2886\" data-end=\"2928\">B1, B2 → LASIK allowed with conditions</strong> (uncomplicated surgery, &gt;425 microns corneal thickness, healthy retina, 1-year gap).</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"3016\" data-end=\"3088\">\n<p data-start=\"3018\" data-end=\"3088\"><strong data-start=\"3018\" data-end=\"3086\">C1, C2, Group D → LASIK allowed with minimal or no restrictions.</strong></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"3090\" data-end=\"3130\">👉 If you plan LASIK for Railway jobs:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"3131\" data-end=\"3331\">\n<li data-start=\"3131\" data-end=\"3182\">\n<p data-start=\"3133\" data-end=\"3182\">Always confirm your job’s <strong data-start=\"3159\" data-end=\"3179\">medical category</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"3183\" data-end=\"3236\">\n<p data-start=\"3185\" data-end=\"3236\">Plan surgery <strong data-start=\"3198\" data-end=\"3233\">at least 1 year before medicals</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"3237\" data-end=\"3331\">\n<p data-start=\"3239\" data-end=\"3331\">Carry all <strong data-start=\"3249\" data-end=\"3311\">reports (corneal thickness, retina status, surgical notes)</strong> for verification.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"3333\" data-end=\"3470\">With the right treatment like <strong data-start=\"3363\" data-end=\"3397\">Contoura or Epi Contoura LASIK</strong>, plus proper documentation, you can safely pursue your Railway career.</p>\n<p data-start=\"133\" data-end=\"219\">For more information, speak directly with a laser vision specialist at <strong data-start=\"204\" data-end=\"218\">9667770453</strong>.</p>\n<p data-start=\"256\" data-end=\"329\">अधिक जानकारी के लिए laser vision doctor से सीधे बात करें: <strong data-start=\"314\" data-end=\"328\">9667770453</strong>.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>For more information, speak directly with a laser vision specialist at 9667770453. अधिक जानकारी के लिए laser vision doctor से सीधे बात करें: 9667770453. Q1. Is LASIK allowed in Railway ALP (Assistant Loco Pilot) A1 Medical Test? Answer: ❌ No. LASIK is not allowed in A1 category jobs like ALP and Train Drivers. A1 requires [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"faq-on-lasik-eligibility-for-indian-army-forces-2025","date":"2025-10-02","title":"FAQ on LASIK Eligibility for Indian Army Forces 2025","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2025/10/02/faq-on-lasik-eligibility-for-indian-army-forces-2025","contentHtml":"<h3 data-start=\"258\" data-end=\"319\">Q1. Is LASIK surgery allowed for Indian Army selection?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"320\" data-end=\"515\"><strong data-start=\"320\" data-end=\"331\">Answer:</strong> ✅ Yes, LASIK is allowed in the Indian Army with specific conditions. Candidates who have undergone LASIK are not automatically disqualified, provided they meet the medical criteria.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"517\" data-end=\"520\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"522\" data-end=\"583\">Q2. At what age can LASIK be done for Army eligibility?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"584\" data-end=\"716\"><strong data-start=\"584\" data-end=\"595\">Answer:</strong> LASIK is considered valid only if performed <strong data-start=\"640\" data-end=\"665\">after 20 years of age</strong>. Any surgery done before that is not acceptable.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"718\" data-end=\"721\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"723\" data-end=\"796\">Q3. What should be the visual acuity after LASIK for Army medicals?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"797\" data-end=\"913\"><strong data-start=\"797\" data-end=\"808\">Answer:</strong> Candidates must achieve a corrected vision of <strong data-start=\"855\" data-end=\"869\">6/6 or 6/9</strong> in both eyes. Stable vision is mandatory.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"915\" data-end=\"918\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"920\" data-end=\"985\">Q4. How long should the eyesight remain stable after LASIK?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"986\" data-end=\"1124\"><strong data-start=\"986\" data-end=\"997\">Answer:</strong> The refractive error must remain <strong data-start=\"1031\" data-end=\"1063\">stable for at least 6 months</strong> post-surgery before appearing for the medical examination.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"1126\" data-end=\"1129\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1131\" data-end=\"1199\">Q5. Are complications after LASIK acceptable in Army medicals?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"1200\" data-end=\"1356\"><strong data-start=\"1200\" data-end=\"1211\">Answer:</strong> ❌ No. Surgery must be <strong data-start=\"1234\" data-end=\"1251\">uncomplicated</strong>. Any post-LASIK complications such as corneal haze, scarring, or ectasia can lead to disqualification.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"1358\" data-end=\"1361\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1363\" data-end=\"1437\">Q6. Is there a required corneal thickness for Army LASIK candidates?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"1438\" data-end=\"1668\"><strong data-start=\"1438\" data-end=\"1449\">Answer:</strong> While the Army does not specify an exact microns value (unlike Air Force), the cornea must be clinically healthy and thick enough to ensure long-term stability. Detailed corneal topography reports should be provided.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"1670\" data-end=\"1673\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1675\" data-end=\"1747\">Q7. What tests are done to confirm LASIK history in Army medicals?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"1748\" data-end=\"1960\"><strong data-start=\"1748\" data-end=\"1759\">Answer:</strong> Army ophthalmologists may use <strong data-start=\"1790\" data-end=\"1815\">slit lamp examination</strong> and <strong data-start=\"1820\" data-end=\"1841\">retina evaluation</strong> to check for signs of LASIK. Torchlight examination usually does not detect LASIK, but slit lamp can reveal changes.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"1962\" data-end=\"1965\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1967\" data-end=\"2041\">Q8. Does Army accept all types of LASIK or only specific procedures?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"2042\" data-end=\"2240\"><strong data-start=\"2042\" data-end=\"2053\">Answer:</strong> Both <strong data-start=\"2059\" data-end=\"2139\">LASIK and advanced surface ablation techniques (like Contoura, Epi-Contoura)</strong> are acceptable, as long as they are complication-free and vision stability criteria are fulfilled.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"2242\" data-end=\"2245\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"2247\" data-end=\"2319\">Q9. Will candidates be required to submit LASIK surgery documents?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"2320\" data-end=\"2410\"><strong data-start=\"2320\" data-end=\"2331\">Answer:</strong> ✅ Yes. Candidates should carry <strong data-start=\"2363\" data-end=\"2396\">complete post-surgery reports</strong>, including:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"2411\" data-end=\"2547\">\n<li data-start=\"2411\" data-end=\"2432\">\n<p data-start=\"2413\" data-end=\"2432\">Corneal thickness</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2433\" data-end=\"2466\">\n<p data-start=\"2435\" data-end=\"2466\">Retina status (fundus report)</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2467\" data-end=\"2505\">\n<p data-start=\"2469\" data-end=\"2505\">Pre- and post-operative refraction</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2506\" data-end=\"2547\">\n<p data-start=\"2508\" data-end=\"2547\">Surgery details and discharge summary</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"2549\" data-end=\"2552\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"2554\" data-end=\"2611\">Q10. What are the key Army LASIK criteria in short?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"2612\" data-end=\"2625\"><strong data-start=\"2612\" data-end=\"2623\">Answer:</strong></p>\n<ul data-start=\"2626\" data-end=\"2894\">\n<li data-start=\"2626\" data-end=\"2667\">\n<p data-start=\"2628\" data-end=\"2667\">LASIK only <strong data-start=\"2639\" data-end=\"2664\">after 20 years of age</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2668\" data-end=\"2702\">\n<p data-start=\"2670\" data-end=\"2702\"><strong data-start=\"2670\" data-end=\"2699\">No surgical complications</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2703\" data-end=\"2746\">\n<p data-start=\"2705\" data-end=\"2746\"><strong data-start=\"2705\" data-end=\"2735\">Stable vision for 6 months</strong> minimum.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2747\" data-end=\"2784\">\n<p data-start=\"2749\" data-end=\"2784\"><strong data-start=\"2749\" data-end=\"2770\">6/6 or 6/9 vision</strong> acceptable.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2785\" data-end=\"2828\">\n<p data-start=\"2787\" data-end=\"2828\">Retina and cornea <strong data-start=\"2805\" data-end=\"2825\">healthy &amp; normal</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2829\" data-end=\"2894\">\n<p data-start=\"2831\" data-end=\"2894\">All supporting <strong data-start=\"2846\" data-end=\"2875\">reports and documentation</strong> must be carried.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"2896\" data-end=\"2899\" />\n<h2 data-start=\"2901\" data-end=\"2919\">📌 Final Note</h2>\n<p data-start=\"2920\" data-end=\"3139\">LASIK does not disqualify you from Indian Army recruitment if the surgery is <strong data-start=\"2997\" data-end=\"3034\">safe, stable, and well-documented</strong>. With the right procedure and timely planning, candidates can meet Army medical standards confidently.</p>\n<p data-start=\"3141\" data-end=\"3293\">👉 For more information, speak directly to a <strong data-start=\"3186\" data-end=\"3223\">laser vision doctor at 9667770453</strong> and book a <strong data-start=\"3235\" data-end=\"3256\">free eye check-up</strong> before planning your Army medical.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Q1. Is LASIK surgery allowed for Indian Army selection? Answer: ✅ Yes, LASIK is allowed in the Indian Army with specific conditions. Candidates who have undergone LASIK are not automatically disqualified, provided they meet the medical criteria. Q2. At what age can LASIK be done for Army eligibility? Answer: LASIK is considered valid only if [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"faq-on-lasik-eligibility-for-indian-air-force-recruitment","date":"2025-10-02","title":"FAQ on LASIK Eligibility for Indian Air Force Recruitment","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2025/10/02/faq-on-lasik-eligibility-for-indian-air-force-recruitment","contentHtml":"<h3 data-start=\"245\" data-end=\"311\">Q1. Is LASIK surgery allowed for Indian Air Force selection?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"312\" data-end=\"502\"><strong data-start=\"312\" data-end=\"323\">Answer:</strong> ✅ Yes, LASIK is allowed in the Indian Air Force with strict medical guidelines. Candidates who undergo LASIK are considered eligible only if they meet all specified conditions.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"504\" data-end=\"507\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"509\" data-end=\"587\">Q2. What is the minimum age for LASIK to be valid in Air Force medicals?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"588\" data-end=\"688\"><strong data-start=\"588\" data-end=\"599\">Answer:</strong> LASIK must be done <strong data-start=\"619\" data-end=\"644\">after 20 years of age</strong>. Any surgery before 20 is not acceptable.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"690\" data-end=\"693\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"695\" data-end=\"777\">Q3. What is the required waiting period between LASIK and Air Force medical?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"778\" data-end=\"894\"><strong data-start=\"778\" data-end=\"789\">Answer:</strong> There must be a <strong data-start=\"806\" data-end=\"831\">minimum gap of 1 year</strong> between LASIK surgery and the Air Force medical examination.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"896\" data-end=\"899\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"901\" data-end=\"986\">Q4. What should be the corneal thickness after LASIK for Air Force eligibility?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"987\" data-end=\"1114\"><strong data-start=\"987\" data-end=\"998\">Answer:</strong> Post-surgery <strong data-start=\"1012\" data-end=\"1055\">corneal thickness must be ≥ 450 microns</strong>. Candidates with thinner corneas are not considered fit.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"1116\" data-end=\"1119\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1121\" data-end=\"1195\">Q5. Is there a limit for axial length in Air Force LASIK candidates?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"1196\" data-end=\"1348\"><strong data-start=\"1196\" data-end=\"1207\">Answer:</strong> ✅ Yes. The <strong data-start=\"1219\" data-end=\"1253\">axial length must be ≤ 25.5 mm</strong>, and it should be measured specifically using an <strong data-start=\"1303\" data-end=\"1325\">IOL Master machine</strong> (not other devices).</p>\n<hr data-start=\"1350\" data-end=\"1353\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1355\" data-end=\"1452\">Q6. What should be the pre-operative refractive error limit for Air Force LASIK candidates?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"1453\" data-end=\"1622\"><strong data-start=\"1453\" data-end=\"1464\">Answer:</strong> The refractive error (spectacle number) should not exceed <strong data-start=\"1523\" data-end=\"1540\">±6.0 diopters</strong> before LASIK. Any correction beyond this limit will result in disqualification.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"1624\" data-end=\"1627\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1629\" data-end=\"1702\">Q7. Are complications after LASIK acceptable in Air Force medicals?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"1703\" data-end=\"1862\"><strong data-start=\"1703\" data-end=\"1714\">Answer:</strong> ❌ No. The LASIK surgery must be <strong data-start=\"1747\" data-end=\"1764\">uncomplicated</strong>. Any post-operative complication such as corneal haze, scarring, or ectasia leads to rejection.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"1864\" data-end=\"1867\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1869\" data-end=\"1946\">Q8. What visual acuity is required after LASIK for Air Force selection?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"1947\" data-end=\"2093\"><strong data-start=\"1947\" data-end=\"1958\">Answer:</strong> Candidates should achieve <strong data-start=\"1985\" data-end=\"2012\">6/6 vision in both eyes</strong>. Minor allowances are not accepted in the Air Force (stricter than Army/Navy).</p>\n<hr data-start=\"2095\" data-end=\"2098\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"2100\" data-end=\"2162\">Q9. Will LASIK be detectable in Air Force medical tests?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"2163\" data-end=\"2336\"><strong data-start=\"2163\" data-end=\"2174\">Answer:</strong> LASIK can usually be detected under <strong data-start=\"2211\" data-end=\"2236\">slit lamp examination</strong> but not in simple torchlight. Hence, transparency and proper medical documentation are essential.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"2338\" data-end=\"2341\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"2343\" data-end=\"2427\">Q10. What documents should candidates carry for Air Force medical after LASIK?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"2428\" data-end=\"2498\"><strong data-start=\"2428\" data-end=\"2439\">Answer:</strong> Candidates must carry complete LASIK reports, including:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"2499\" data-end=\"2737\">\n<li data-start=\"2499\" data-end=\"2541\">\n<p data-start=\"2501\" data-end=\"2541\">Pre-operative refractive error details</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2542\" data-end=\"2589\">\n<p data-start=\"2544\" data-end=\"2589\">Post-operative refraction and visual acuity</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2590\" data-end=\"2619\">\n<p data-start=\"2592\" data-end=\"2619\">Corneal thickness reports</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2620\" data-end=\"2656\">\n<p data-start=\"2622\" data-end=\"2656\">Axial length (IOL Master) report</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2657\" data-end=\"2683\">\n<p data-start=\"2659\" data-end=\"2683\">Fundus (retina) report</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2684\" data-end=\"2737\">\n<p data-start=\"2686\" data-end=\"2737\">Surgery details from the performing doctor/clinic</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"2739\" data-end=\"2742\" />\n<h2 data-start=\"2744\" data-end=\"2788\">📌 Key Air Force LASIK Criteria Summary</h2>\n<ul data-start=\"2789\" data-end=\"3138\">\n<li data-start=\"2789\" data-end=\"2832\">\n<p data-start=\"2791\" data-end=\"2832\">Surgery only <strong data-start=\"2804\" data-end=\"2829\">after 20 years of age</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2833\" data-end=\"2886\">\n<p data-start=\"2835\" data-end=\"2886\"><strong data-start=\"2835\" data-end=\"2857\">1-year minimum gap</strong> between LASIK and medical.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2887\" data-end=\"2927\">\n<p data-start=\"2889\" data-end=\"2927\"><strong data-start=\"2889\" data-end=\"2924\">Corneal thickness ≥ 450 microns</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2928\" data-end=\"2981\">\n<p data-start=\"2930\" data-end=\"2981\"><strong data-start=\"2930\" data-end=\"2978\">Axial length ≤ 25.5 mm (IOL Master measured)</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2982\" data-end=\"3022\">\n<p data-start=\"2984\" data-end=\"3022\"><strong data-start=\"2984\" data-end=\"3019\">Pre-op refractive error ≤ ±6.0D</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"3023\" data-end=\"3051\">\n<p data-start=\"3025\" data-end=\"3051\"><strong data-start=\"3025\" data-end=\"3039\">6/6 vision</strong> required.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"3052\" data-end=\"3085\">\n<p data-start=\"3054\" data-end=\"3085\"><strong data-start=\"3054\" data-end=\"3074\">No complications</strong> allowed.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"3086\" data-end=\"3138\">\n<p data-start=\"3088\" data-end=\"3138\"><strong data-start=\"3088\" data-end=\"3122\">Detailed medical documentation</strong> is mandatory.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"3140\" data-end=\"3143\" />\n<h2 data-start=\"3145\" data-end=\"3160\">Final Note</h2>\n<p data-start=\"3161\" data-end=\"3408\">The Indian Air Force has <strong data-start=\"3186\" data-end=\"3227\">one of the strictest medical policies</strong> regarding LASIK. However, with <strong data-start=\"3259\" data-end=\"3305\">safe surgery like Contoura or Epi-Contoura</strong>, stable vision, and the right medical records, candidates can successfully clear Air Force medicals.</p>\n<p data-start=\"3410\" data-end=\"3585\">👉 For more clarity on your eligibility, speak directly to a <strong data-start=\"3471\" data-end=\"3508\">laser vision doctor at 9667770453</strong> and book a <strong data-start=\"3520\" data-end=\"3541\">free eye check-up</strong> before scheduling your Air Force medical.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Q1. Is LASIK surgery allowed for Indian Air Force selection? Answer: ✅ Yes, LASIK is allowed in the Indian Air Force with strict medical guidelines. Candidates who undergo LASIK are considered eligible only if they meet all specified conditions. Q2. What is the minimum age for LASIK to be valid in Air Force medicals? Answer: [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"faq-on-lasik-eligibility-for-ssc-gd-staff-selection-commission-general-duty-recruitment","date":"2025-10-02","title":"FAQ on LASIK Eligibility for SSC GD (Staff Selection Commission – General Duty) Recruitment","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2025/10/02/faq-on-lasik-eligibility-for-ssc-gd-staff-selection-commission-general-duty-recruitment","contentHtml":"<h3 data-start=\"334\" data-end=\"402\">Q1. Is LASIK surgery allowed for SSC GD Constable recruitment?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"403\" data-end=\"624\"><strong data-start=\"403\" data-end=\"414\">Answer:</strong> ✅ Yes, LASIK is generally allowed for SSC GD recruitment, provided the surgery is safe, stable, and the candidate meets vision standards prescribed for CAPFs (BSF, CRPF, CISF, ITBP, SSB, Assam Rifles, etc.).</p>\n<hr data-start=\"626\" data-end=\"629\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"631\" data-end=\"707\">Q2. What is the required age for LASIK to be valid in SSC GD medicals?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"708\" data-end=\"880\"><strong data-start=\"708\" data-end=\"719\">Answer:</strong> LASIK should ideally be done <strong data-start=\"749\" data-end=\"774\">after 18 years of age</strong> (since refractive error stabilizes after this age). Surgery done earlier may not be accepted as stable.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"882\" data-end=\"885\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"887\" data-end=\"951\">Q3. What visual acuity is required for SSC GD after LASIK?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"952\" data-end=\"1068\"><strong data-start=\"952\" data-end=\"963\">Answer:</strong> Candidates should have <strong data-start=\"987\" data-end=\"1037\">6/6 vision in one eye and 6/9 in the other eye</strong>, with or without correction.</p>\n<ul data-start=\"1069\" data-end=\"1200\">\n<li data-start=\"1069\" data-end=\"1200\">\n<p data-start=\"1071\" data-end=\"1200\">Spectacle correction is permitted in SSC GD, but LASIK is considered acceptable as long as final vision falls within standards.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"1202\" data-end=\"1205\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1207\" data-end=\"1277\">Q4. Are complications after LASIK acceptable in SSC GD medicals?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"1278\" data-end=\"1436\"><strong data-start=\"1278\" data-end=\"1289\">Answer:</strong> ❌ No. LASIK must be <strong data-start=\"1310\" data-end=\"1327\">uncomplicated</strong>, without corneal haze, scarring, or retinal issues. Any post-operative complication may lead to rejection.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"1438\" data-end=\"1441\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1443\" data-end=\"1535\">Q5. Do candidates need to maintain a gap between LASIK and SSC GD medical examination?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"1536\" data-end=\"1724\"><strong data-start=\"1536\" data-end=\"1547\">Answer:</strong> While SSC does not specify a fixed timeline, experts recommend keeping at least a <strong data-start=\"1630\" data-end=\"1648\">6–12 month gap</strong> between LASIK and medicals to ensure vision stability and proper healing.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"1726\" data-end=\"1729\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1731\" data-end=\"1811\">Q6. Are there limits on refractive error correction for SSC GD candidates?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"1812\" data-end=\"1985\"><strong data-start=\"1812\" data-end=\"1823\">Answer:</strong> Unlike Defence forces, SSC GD has <strong data-start=\"1858\" data-end=\"1890\">no strict upper limit of ±6D</strong>. However, candidates must meet the prescribed <strong data-start=\"1937\" data-end=\"1965\">6/6, 6/9 vision standard</strong> after correction.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"1987\" data-end=\"1990\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"1992\" data-end=\"2048\">Q7. Can LASIK be detected in SSC GD medical tests?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"2049\" data-end=\"2263\"><strong data-start=\"2049\" data-end=\"2060\">Answer:</strong> Under <strong data-start=\"2067\" data-end=\"2093\">torchlight examination</strong>, LASIK is usually not detected. But if <strong data-start=\"2133\" data-end=\"2158\">slit lamp examination</strong> is performed, signs may be visible. This is why it’s important to carry medical reports transparently.</p>\n<hr data-start=\"2265\" data-end=\"2268\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"2270\" data-end=\"2350\">Q8. What documents should candidates carry for SSC GD medical after LASIK?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"2351\" data-end=\"2397\"><strong data-start=\"2351\" data-end=\"2362\">Answer:</strong> It is strongly advised to carry:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"2398\" data-end=\"2568\">\n<li data-start=\"2398\" data-end=\"2440\">\n<p data-start=\"2400\" data-end=\"2440\">Pre- and post-operative vision reports</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2441\" data-end=\"2469\">\n<p data-start=\"2443\" data-end=\"2469\">Corneal thickness report</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2470\" data-end=\"2500\">\n<p data-start=\"2472\" data-end=\"2500\">Retina (fundus) evaluation</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2501\" data-end=\"2568\">\n<p data-start=\"2503\" data-end=\"2568\">Surgery discharge summary and certificate from operating doctor</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"2570\" data-end=\"2573\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"2575\" data-end=\"2629\">Q9. Will LASIK disqualify me in SSC GD medicals?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"2630\" data-end=\"2696\"><strong data-start=\"2630\" data-end=\"2641\">Answer:</strong> ❌ No. LASIK alone will not disqualify you, provided:</p>\n<ul data-start=\"2697\" data-end=\"2830\">\n<li data-start=\"2697\" data-end=\"2739\">\n<p data-start=\"2699\" data-end=\"2739\">Surgery was safe and complication-free</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2740\" data-end=\"2782\">\n<p data-start=\"2742\" data-end=\"2782\">Vision is within the required standard</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2783\" data-end=\"2830\">\n<p data-start=\"2785\" data-end=\"2830\">Documentation is available for verification</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"2832\" data-end=\"2835\" />\n<h3 data-start=\"2837\" data-end=\"2909\">Q10. What are the key LASIK eligibility rules for SSC GD in short?</h3>\n<p data-start=\"2910\" data-end=\"2923\"><strong data-start=\"2910\" data-end=\"2921\">Answer:</strong></p>\n<ul data-start=\"2924\" data-end=\"3180\">\n<li data-start=\"2924\" data-end=\"2960\">\n<p data-start=\"2926\" data-end=\"2960\">LASIK after <strong data-start=\"2938\" data-end=\"2957\">18 years of age</strong>.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"2961\" data-end=\"3009\">\n<p data-start=\"2963\" data-end=\"3009\"><strong data-start=\"2963\" data-end=\"2994\">6/6 and 6/9 vision standard</strong> must be met.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"3010\" data-end=\"3071\">\n<p data-start=\"3012\" data-end=\"3071\"><strong data-start=\"3012\" data-end=\"3037\">Uncomplicated surgery</strong> with healthy retina and cornea.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"3072\" data-end=\"3135\">\n<p data-start=\"3074\" data-end=\"3135\">Preferably <strong data-start=\"3085\" data-end=\"3104\">6–12 months gap</strong> between surgery and medical.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"3136\" data-end=\"3180\">\n<p data-start=\"3138\" data-end=\"3180\">Carry complete reports for verification.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr data-start=\"3182\" data-end=\"3185\" />\n<h2 data-start=\"3187\" data-end=\"3205\">📌 Final Note</h2>\n<p data-start=\"3206\" data-end=\"3491\">For SSC GD Constable recruitment, LASIK is <strong data-start=\"3249\" data-end=\"3266\">not a barrier</strong> as long as your vision meets prescribed standards and surgery is complication-free. Unlike Army and Air Force, SSC rules are <strong data-start=\"3392\" data-end=\"3408\">more relaxed</strong>, but medical examiners still prioritize <strong data-start=\"3449\" data-end=\"3488\">stability, safety, and transparency</strong>.</p>\n<p data-start=\"3493\" data-end=\"3648\">👉 To confirm your LASIK suitability for SSC GD medicals, speak directly to a <strong data-start=\"3571\" data-end=\"3608\">laser vision doctor at 9667770453</strong> and schedule a <strong data-start=\"3624\" data-end=\"3645\">free eye check-up</strong>.</p>\n<p><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"SSC GD Medical 2025 🚨 Don’t Fail Eye Test! Clear Without Glasses | www.laser.fyi | Call 9667770453\" width=\"563\" height=\"1000\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/cXDrwsbD-jI?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Q1. Is LASIK surgery allowed for SSC GD Constable recruitment? Answer: ✅ Yes, LASIK is generally allowed for SSC GD recruitment, provided the surgery is safe, stable, and the candidate meets vision standards prescribed for CAPFs (BSF, CRPF, CISF, ITBP, SSB, Assam Rifles, etc.). Q2. What is the required age for LASIK to be valid [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"do-you-need-reading-glasses-after-lasik-3","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Do you need reading glasses after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/do-you-need-reading-glasses-after-lasik-3","contentHtml":"<p>The basic cause people incline to go for the Lasik surgery is to get rid of the reading glasses and contact lens, which disturb the regular lifestyle or hinder the day to day activities. So, after Lasik, most of the patients do not need reading glasses. However, it may not be the case for all 100% of the patients, who undergo Lasik, because of various reasons.</p>\n<p><strong>Reading Glasses After Lasik</strong></p>\n<p>Usually after Lasik surgery, reading glasses are not required, because the existing refractive error gets corrected during the procedure. by then, no refractive error can be existing. Reading glasses would be needed only in rare cases, where the prescription of the refractive error is much more. More than 95% of the Lasik patients do not need any kind of reading glasses, even for reading the books or newspaper.</p>\n<p>However, there would be need for the reading glasses, after 40s. The cause for the need for the glasses is not Lasik surgery, but something different. There are other factors that influence the overall vision of the eyes. For instance, after 40s, the basic capability of focusing lens would be deteriorated. This cause has no way related with the refractive error, which is corrected through correction over the cornea surface. This condition is called persbyopia and it cannot be prevented or influenced by Lasik surgery procedure, because it is age-related issue with the eye. Other example is cataract problem, which is again caused because of the age of the human being.</p>\n<p><strong>Special Conditions</strong></p>\n<p>Hyperopia or farsightedness is one common refractive error that can be corrected through Lasik surgery. The cornea would be of either too short or too flat and cause reflection of light to occur behind the retina. So, the patients with farsightedness have problems to see the objects nearby. After Lasik surgery performed for hyperopia, the need for reading glasses would be very far, for many years or decade(s).</p>\n<p>Myopia or nearsightedness is a condition, where one can see nearby objects, not farer objects. Usually, this condition can be corrected with the Lasik surgery, by reshaping the cornea, by removing the excess tissue on its surface. Usually, after the Lasik surgery to correct myopia condition, there would be no need for glasses for reading and other activities for many years and even decades.</p>\n<p>Hence, Lasik laser eye surgery can correct the surface disturbances and so the refractive errors accordingly. Hence, this procedure can correct hyperopia, myopia or astigmatism problems and other eye problems can have no effect. Reading glasses would not be required after Lasik surgery, but may be because of other eye related issues, like presbyopia, cataract and other problems.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The basic cause people incline to go for the Lasik surgery is to get rid of the reading glasses and contact lens, which disturb the regular lifestyle or hinder the day to day activities. So, after Lasik, most of the patients do not need reading glasses. However, it may not be the case for all [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-laser-eye-surgery-dangerous","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Is Laser eye surgery dangerous?","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/is-laser-eye-surgery-dangerous","contentHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery for correcting refractive errors of the eye can be performed with different techniques and procedures and no procedure is dangerous if performed with the standard protocols and by qualified surgeon. Three basic kinds of laser surgery for eye refractive error correction are Lasik, Lasek and PRK. These are absolutely safe, as they have excellent safety profiles with higher rates of success. All these three are designed and developed to get rid of the hassle-some contact lens or eye glasses, by treating hyperopia, astigmatism or myopia problems. So far the patient safety record has been excellent.</p>\n<p><strong>Is the Surgery Dangerous?</strong></p>\n<p>Laser related surgery is never dangerous, when done with the standard protocols, because laser does not harm the skin like incision made with the blade or knife. So, technically there are no dangerous outcomes possible, unless done accidentally.</p>\n<p><strong>So, Any Complications?</strong></p>\n<p>Yes, there can be complications, which can be caused from various factors and reasons. These complications sometimes can be threatening slightly, like deterioration of vision or even significant loss of vision. There are also certain side effects possible. Complications and side effects are different. Almost all kinds of complications and side effects can be resolved, with medical treatments and also through surgical procedures.</p>\n<p>There are millions of patients, who have undergone laser eye surgery after commencement of the surgery, during these 20 years. The possible complications and side effects post laser surgery can be the following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Flap Complications</li>\n<li>Temporary discomfort and disturbances of vision</li>\n<li>Dry eyes</li>\n<li>Remarkable regression, overcorrection or under-correction</li>\n<li>Eye infection</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Factors for Complication and Risks</strong></p>\n<p>Laser surgeries are performed with different procedures and different techniques and each of the procedures require certain eligibility criteria. And not everyone is suitable to undergo these surgical procedures. And certain anatomical factors and certain conditions would limit optimal results of the surgery or increase the undesirable outcome risks. These factors are the following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Irregular corneas or too thin corneas can leave the correction of refraction error incomplete and so the outcome also incomplete, out of expected. Usually, pre-examination and assessment of the eye condition can help to determine the best suitable procedure to resolve the refractive error problems.</li>\n<li>High refractive error is also another important one and this condition sometimes do not get resolved or corrected with a single laser eye surgery and sometimes enhancement procedure also may be required.</li>\n<li>Unstable vision is yet another factor that may not be resolved completely or may create new complications.</li>\n<li>Dry eyes may worsen the outcomes and this problem can be more severe after the laser eye surgery.</li>\n<li>Large pupils may not allow to get the best outcomes without risks and complications.</li>\n<li>Age is another important factor and risks and complications can be more prominent if the age is not in between 20 to 40 years.</li>\n<li>Active autoimmune or certain degenerative disorders may increase the risks and complications.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These complications can be reduced by conducting pre-surgery assessment and determining the best suitable laser eye surgery, by the eye surgeons.</p>\n<p><strong>How To Minimize the Complications?</strong></p>\n<p>Since laser eye surgery is also a surgery, limitations, unforeseen side effects and potential risks cannot be ruled out. These limitations, risks and complications can be minimized significantly, by choosing qualified and experienced laser eye surgeon and relying on the medical center that follows standard protocols for procedures.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery for correcting refractive errors of the eye can be performed with different techniques and procedures and no procedure is dangerous if performed with the standard protocols and by qualified surgeon. Three basic kinds of laser surgery for eye refractive error correction are Lasik, Lasek and PRK. These are absolutely safe, as they [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-get-laser-eye-surgery-twice-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can you get laser eye surgery twice?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-you-get-laser-eye-surgery-twice-2","contentHtml":"<p>In most of the cases, the outcomes and results of Lasik are permanent, however, it may not be the same case for 100% Lasik patients, because of various factors. Hence, sometimes there may be a need arising to undergo the Lasik laser eye surgery again.</p>\n<p><strong>Why Lasik Second Time?</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik surgery is meant for correcting refractive error that cause hyperopedia (farsightedness), myopia (nearsightedness) or astigmatism. After the surgery, these problems can be corrected by correcting the existing error. However, there are also chances that the same problem may occur again, because of various factors, such as age, poor lifestyle, no special care for the eyes, etc. No matter what the cause is, there may be a need arising to undergo the same surgery again. Though it is a rare condition, yet it is possible, because of various causes. Lesser than 5% of Lasik patients have the probability of going back for the Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>What is Second Time Lasik Surgery Called?</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik eye surgery, when required to perform for the second time, it is called as touch-ups or enhancement surgery. Usually, the need for this surgery is identified during the period of recovery, while the follow-up visits are made by the Lasik patients. On the other hand, Lasik eye surgery may be needed after decades of the first Lasik also, as the vision becomes deteriorated with the age and other factors.</p>\n<p><strong>How To Find the Need For Second Lasik Surgery?</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik is definitely a procedure that is long-lasting, but does not fix all kinds of errors associated with the vision, because other vision problems, like cataract, presbyopia are not caused from cornea, etc.</p>\n<p>Usually changes in vision get started after 40s. Refractive errors may get developed, apart from the presbyopia or cataract. In such cases, Lasik surgery will be needed, though it is second time. When the second procedure is required, it requires another flap creation. And most of the eye surgeons prefer to perform second Lasik procedure only after 5 to 10 years of previous Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p>If the first Lasik surgery is incomplete or any complications occur or the cornea surface correction is underdone or overdone, the second surgery performed is usually enhancement procedure, right after the first Lasik surgery. In case the refractive error is developed after a few years, a full-fledged Lasik surgery would be required after a couple of years or decades.</p>\n<p><strong>Who Decides the Need for Second Lasik?</strong></p>\n<p>Usually, the problem of vision starts after 40s and eventually, the patient prefers to go to the same medical center, where one had Lasik surgery before. There, basic eye examination is performed, considering overall vision related problems. Most commonly the problem of vision is caused from presbyopia or cataract. When these two causes are ruled out, the other possible cause for the vision problem would be usually, refractive error, in most of the cases. If any one of the two above are the causes, eventually, the respective treatment would be required, as Lasik cannot treat those conditions. On the other hand, if the refractive error causes the vision problem, there will be need for Lasik surgery for the second time.</p>\n<p>All these assessments and determination of the respective treatment, Lasik or no Lasik is done by the medical center and the eye doctor only. Eventually, one is qualified for the Lasik. So, technically, yes, Lasik surgery can be performed twice.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>In most of the cases, the outcomes and results of Lasik are permanent, however, it may not be the same case for 100% Lasik patients, because of various factors. Hence, sometimes there may be a need arising to undergo the Lasik laser eye surgery again. Why Lasik Second Time? Lasik surgery is meant for correcting [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"does-laser-eye-surgery-last-forever-3","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Does laser eye surgery last forever?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/does-laser-eye-surgery-last-forever-3","contentHtml":"<p>The results and outcomes of the Lasik eye surgery continue to improve, right from the approval of the surgery, 1996. The surgery renders several benefits and improves the overall lifestyle and quality of life, significantly. Today more than 10 million Americans have become independent of the eyeglasses and contact lenses, because of the latest Lasik technology and skill and experience of the surgeon.</p>\n<p><strong>After Lasik Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>Most of the Lasik patients can achieve vision of 20/20 after the Lasik surgery, however, the outcomes do vary from one patient to another. Some of them may achieve the vision of 20/40 or sometimes lesser than that. Though hardly, in some cases, some of the Lasik patients may have the need to use contact lenses or glasses, after Lasik, but visual acuity level and the prescription after surgery would be lesser to a great extent compared to the one, prior to Lasik.</p>\n<p>Lasik surgery has got the safety record, to an excellent level, however, similar to any kind of surgery, complications are possible after the procedure. A very few Lasik patients may need to undergo the additional procedure called touch up or enhancement procedure for improvement of vision to the level desired.</p>\n<p><strong>Vision Problems After Lasik</strong></p>\n<p>Some of the Lasik patients may need eyeglasses for reading, after crossing age of 40s, because of presbyopia, because of loss of near vision, which are normal with age progressing. Other possible causes are also existing, such as cataract problems.</p>\n<p><strong>Life of Lasik</strong></p>\n<p>The most important thing and a million dollar concern is the life of Lasik. Every potential Lasik patient and old Lasik patient has the concern of the life of Lasik. The direct answer for life of Lasik is both permanent and temporary. It is permanent because the probability of returning the refractive error, which is corrected during Lasik procedure is almost nil. Hence, it is permanent. On the other hand, it is temporary, because the recurrence of vision problems is possible, as the vision problem can be caused from other vision related problems also, such as cataract, presbyopia problems, etc. Hence, Lasik patient can be assured of the success of the Lasik, provided the surgery procedure is performed according to the standard protocols and by the qualified and experienced eye surgeon.</p>\n<p>If you want to be assured about this fact, the best reference is the review and study reports by the standard medical authorities. Almost all the reports have assured and reassured that the success rate of the Lasik eye laser surgery is more than 96%.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The results and outcomes of the Lasik eye surgery continue to improve, right from the approval of the surgery, 1996. The surgery renders several benefits and improves the overall lifestyle and quality of life, significantly. Today more than 10 million Americans have become independent of the eyeglasses and contact lenses, because of the latest Lasik [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-have-lasik-after-prk","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can you have Lasik after PRK?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-you-have-lasik-after-prk","contentHtml":"<p>Yes, if one had undergone PRK procedure, he or she can go through Lasik after it. There is a technical requirement however, for the same to get done. PRK and Lasik are usually for same purpose, like correction of refraction error.</p>\n<p><strong>PRK and Lasik </strong></p>\n<p>PRK and Lasik are proven to be safe, effective and proven. The procedures correct the vision by applying a non-thermal or cool light beam, which is controlled by computer. The movement and focus of the laser beam has been clearly programmed according to the prescription of the patient. The laser is turned on and off at any moment by the surgeon, during the procedure. Risk of errors can be reduced to be a great extent, because several safeguards are in place.</p>\n<p><strong>Why Lasik After PRK?</strong></p>\n<p>Usually PRK should resolve the problem of vision, caused from refractive errors. However, sometimes, reading may not be clear as expected without glasses. Hence, to get better the vision, Lasik may be required. Both the PRK and Lasik are painless and if one has to go deeper, Lasik is less painful compared to the Lasik surgery, as this procedure needs exposing of the deeper cornea layers. After PRK, usually enough time is required to decide to go to the Lasik, as patient has to wait for long enough time till the protective surface cells grow back over the surgical area treated. Usually it takes at least a few weeks to know the complete results after the PRK procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Technical Requirement </strong></p>\n<p>There is one technical requirement to undergo Lasik after PRK. The potential patient should have adequate thickness of cornea available. Most commonly, however, enough thickness of cornea may not be available to perform Lasik, since significant amount of tissue above the cornea surface might have been removed with the original PRK procedure. technically, in such cases, PRK may not be feasible, since no adjustments can be done. In such cases, PRK may be repeated. In case the PRK procedure performed prior to Lasik hasn’t removed much of the tissue, Lasik procedure can be followed. When this is the basic requirement, other factors and requirements are assessed during the pre-operative evaluation.</p>\n<p>Another requirement is that there must be a gap of three to four years in between these procedures. When the Lasik is performed, followed by the PRK procedure, the surface tissue over the cornea has to be dealt very carefully, since usually less amount of tissue is left. And when the laser is used instead of blade, the risk of complication would be lesser. So, there would be hardly any problems associated with the similar procedure repeated.</p>\n<p>When the Lasik procedure is performed after PRK, usually vision recovery would be slow and still restoring vision would be great. The overall result and recovery of vision can be much better after performing the second procedure, Lasik, after PRK.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Yes, if one had undergone PRK procedure, he or she can go through Lasik after it. There is a technical requirement however, for the same to get done. PRK and Lasik are usually for same purpose, like correction of refraction error. PRK and Lasik PRK and Lasik are proven to be safe, effective and proven. [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-lasik-surgery-detectable","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Is Lasik surgery detectable?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/is-lasik-surgery-detectable","contentHtml":"<p>Yes, technically Lasik surgery can be detectable. Lasik surgery is possible to detect and it cannot be done very easily. Just by seeing the eyes, one cannot detect, whether the surgery is done or not.</p>\n<p><strong>Lasik Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik surgery is easy to detect for the eye surgeons. It needs a special procedure to explore and discover the same thing. To explore it, first one has to understand why and how the Lasik surgery is performed. Lasik laser eye surgery is a refractive surgery, often performed to correct astigmatism, hypermetropia, myopia.</p>\n<p><strong>Detecting Lasik </strong></p>\n<p>So, in simple terms Lasik surgery over the eyes can be detected by examining the cornea surface. Lasik surgery is performed in two steps. During the first step, flap is created through cutting the Bowman’s layer or corneal epithelium layer. This process makes use of either blade or laser. As the corneal flap is created on the top of cornea, the edges of this cornea flap can give the indication that the Lasik surgery is performed. This can easily be identified by eye doctor under slit lamp or microscope examination post lasik surgery, even after several years of lasik procedure.</p>\n<p>With advanced diagnostic system, such as Pentacam, eye specialist can easily detect whether lasik is operated in eyes or not. Post lasik overall corneal thickness get reduced and curvature of eyes gets altered. Such changes any be easily identified with advanced diagnostic system examination.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Yes, technically Lasik surgery can be detectable. Lasik surgery is possible to detect and it cannot be done very easily. Just by seeing the eyes, one cannot detect, whether the surgery is done or not. Lasik Procedure Lasik surgery is easy to detect for the eye surgeons. It needs a special procedure to explore and [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-lasik-reverse","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can Lasik reverse?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-lasik-reverse","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik procedure is performed to correct refractive error of the eye and sometimes it is not unusual to think, whether this procedure can be reversed or not. The procedure is usually performed to get rid of the eyeglasses and contact lens, by resolving hyperopia, myopia or astigmatism eye related problems.</p>\n<p><strong>Why Reversal?</strong></p>\n<p>In most of the cases, more than 96% of them have positive outcomes after the Lasik surgery. However, there are certain instances, where the outcomes are not as expected. So, the outcomes may not be pleasant and the problems of reduced vision, halos, glare and night driving vision. It may be because of the treatment decentration. In rare cases, it is also possible that Lasik is performed to correct multiple vision problems and a single vision refractive error can be reversed, while the other one is retained. And some of the Lasik procedures but not all the Lasik procedures have the ability to get them reversed.</p>\n<p><strong>Reversal of Lasik Procedure </strong></p>\n<p>The process involved in the Lasik is removing the extra tissue over the surface of the cornea and reshaping the cornea to the expected shape. Removing the tissue is a permanent change made over the cornea and hence the results are also permanent. Eventually, the vision can never be gone back to the previous position.</p>\n<p>But, any relative changes made within the eye may make the result to be modified in a certain period of time. Basically, aging of eyes’ lens can affect the near vision. Here, aging of the lens refers to the presbyopia, which is a pre-cataract change that begins usually, in the beginning of 50s. And in cases of corrections of large myopic or nearsighted refractive error, the epithelium over the area of laser is expected to be thicken, slightly more than the normal quantity and it eventually result in changes in refraction in smaller amounts. However, it cannot be back to the position, the shape or quantity it was, prior to Lasik. So, on an overall Lasik never gets reversed.</p>\n<p><strong>Another Dimension</strong></p>\n<p>On the other hand, there have been certain attempts made to reverse Lasik, especially, when the outcomes are lesser than ideal. These attempts were made with better outcomes and good results.</p>\n<p><strong>Studies and Reports</strong></p>\n<p>Supracor procedure, which is a procedure of intracorneal femtosecond laser has been attempted to reverse the procedure and so the unpleasant outcomes too. The initial procedure was attempted to resolve the vision related problems, called presbyopia and hyperopia. Reversal of Lasik procedure has been attempted to reverse the correction of presbyopia, however, the effects and outcomes of hyperopia are retained well. This experimental Lasik procedure has been proven to be successful in reversing the effects of presbyopia, while retaining the positive results of the hyperopia.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik procedure is performed to correct refractive error of the eye and sometimes it is not unusual to think, whether this procedure can be reversed or not. The procedure is usually performed to get rid of the eyeglasses and contact lens, by resolving hyperopia, myopia or astigmatism eye related problems. Why Reversal? In most of [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-prk-better-than-lasik","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Is PRK better than Lasik?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/is-prk-better-than-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>Both PRK and Lasik are laser eye surgeries and sometimes PRK is considered and known as cousin of Lasik, in the medical industry. Since these two are laser eye surgery procedures, there are some similarities and of course there are some differences also. Let us explore both the similarities and differences between them.</p>\n<p><strong>Differences Between PRK and Lasik</strong></p>\n<p>The basic difference in between these procedures is the way they are performed. And in detail, during the procedure, the way the cornea is accessed by the LVC surgeon is the key difference. When the procedure starts, the excimer laser sculpts the surface of the cornea and overall shape of the cornea. So, before that the cornea’s epithelium tissue, which covers it, has to be moved out temporarily or removed out from the way. In the procedure of PRK, the tissue is removed and it is moved out temporarily out of the way, in the procedure of Lasik.</p>\n<p><strong>Which Is Better, PRK or Lasik?</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>PRK is preferred over Lasik, as it is medically approved in cases of sports and other employment related aspects, where as Lasik is not.</li>\n<li>PRK offers permanent solution to the refractive error, though it takes long time for healing and recovery.</li>\n<li>The fundamental difference between PRK and Lasik is flap. PRK is considered to be better for having no flap touched in the surgery procedure. Hence, there are no complications associated with the flap. For the same reason, some of the patients and eye surgeons prefer PRK to some of the patients, who are suitable. So, PRK is better than Lasik and preferred by some of the professionals or sport persons, who accept higher risk of direct trauma.</li>\n<li>One more advantage of the PRK over Lasik is that the corneal thickness does not need to be more as needed for Lasik. So, eye patients, who have more refractive error with nearsightedness or naturally thinner corneas or even both these conditions, prefer PRK as the suitable procedure, rather than Lasik.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>While the above are fundamental differences and benefits of PRK compared to Lasik, there are also certain downsides related to PRK. First of healing period is a bit longer and the patient has to wear the bandage of contact lens for about 4 days to 5 days during initial healing phase of epithelial tissue. Hence, the patient has to be limited to stay at home before resuming the day to day and normal activities.</p>\n<p>Most often, suitability of the laser eye procedure, whether it is PRK or Lasik is determined by the eye surgeons, rather than the patient oneself.</p>\n<p>On an overall, each of the laser eye surgery procedure has its own pros and cons and selection of the procedure purely depends on the condition of the eye and refractive error. This selection is done by the eye doctor, only after examining the eyes and considering the prescription from one year before. PRK is definitely a beneficial one compared to Lasik, for the high contact sports and relative professionals and also the patients, who have very thin cornea.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Both PRK and Lasik are laser eye surgeries and sometimes PRK is considered and known as cousin of Lasik, in the medical industry. Since these two are laser eye surgery procedures, there are some similarities and of course there are some differences also. Let us explore both the similarities and differences between them. Differences Between [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-prk-surgery-painful-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Is PRK surgery painful?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/is-prk-surgery-painful-2","contentHtml":"<p>PRK is a laser eye surgery procedure and so there is no considerable pain resulted during and after the surgery. However, the intensity of pain is a bit more compared to the Lasik eye surgery procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Understanding the PRK Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>To understand the level of pain during and after PRK, the procedure of PRK must be explored and understood. Unlike Lasik, no flap is created during the PRK procedure. Instead, the cornea’s epithelial tissue layer is removed gently. Later eximer laser is applied to the cornea exposed for the purpose of reshaping. Once the process of cornea reshaping is done, a bandage with contact lens, which do not have any prescription power would then be placed over the cornea, allowing to grow back the skin, underneath.</p>\n<p><strong>Pain During and After PRK</strong></p>\n<p>Since the cornea tissue layer is removed and alter laser beam light is applied, there is a mild pain experienced by the patient. It should be mild pain, not more, because numbing drops are applied, just before starting the procedure.</p>\n<p>After the PRK procedure, healing is taken place in three stages, initial healing, removal of bandage contact lens and total healing. During these three phases, pain is a bit more in the first stage and it should be decreasing, later in the following stages. On an overall, it takes about 30 days of duration for total recovery to complete these three stages. Pain is expected during the phase, where contact lens bandage is present. However, pain relieving medicine is prescribed by the surgeon to feel relaxed and get rid of the pain. So, after the PRK procedure, though pain is there, it would be relieved because of this medicine and mild discomfort is anyways expected and experienced by the patient. Recovery period consists of many follow-up visits to the surgery medical center and the surgeon monitors the healing process and adjusts the overall medicated drop dosage for controlling the epithelial tissue healing and ensure natural and complete healing. Usually complete healing takes about 30 days, since the cornea’s epithelial tissue is regenerated by itself naturally, for every 30 days.</p>\n<p>Both during and after the PRK surgery, pain is considerably less, though it exists. However, in case of serious pain, which does not decrease even with the over-the-counter pain medications, the patient has to report to the surgeon immediately, as it can be a sign of possible complications. Special protection shield must be worn continuously after a few days of the surgery to prevent any flavours of shampoo, soap, hairspray, lotion, makeup etc. In all the stages, the pain can be easily managed with the pain relieving medication and so there is nothing to worry about the pain.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>PRK is a laser eye surgery procedure and so there is no considerable pain resulted during and after the surgery. However, the intensity of pain is a bit more compared to the Lasik eye surgery procedure. Understanding the PRK Procedure To understand the level of pain during and after PRK, the procedure of PRK must [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-is-the-success-rate-of-prk-surgery-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"What is the success rate of PRK surgery?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/what-is-the-success-rate-of-prk-surgery-2","contentHtml":"<p>PRK or PhotoRefractive Keratectomy is one of the first laser eye surgery procedures developed and also approved by the Food and Drug Administration, in the US, compared to Lasik and SMILE, which are the other two famous procedures.</p>\n<p><strong>Why PRK?</strong></p>\n<p>PRK is preferred by the surgeons for correcting myopia from mild to moderate level. The correction is attempted by reshaping the cornea. PRK procedure is performed by scrapping off the cornea’s outermost layer or epithelium, for exposing the cornea. Microscopic amounts or tiny amounts of tissue are removed out from the cornea surface. The corneal changes required makes use of the computer program to map the surface of the cornea and remove the targeted tissue to obtain the shape expected.</p>\n<p><strong>PRK – Success Rate</strong></p>\n<p>PRK has the success rate of 95%, according to the Food and Drug Administration medical authority in the US. The success rate is definitely high for the patients, who undergo the PRK eye surgery, when they are qualified technically.</p>\n<p><strong>Qualifying Criteria for Better Success Rate</strong></p>\n<p>Success rate is basically dependent on the standard protocols followed in every instant of the procedure and also qualification and skill of the eye surgeon. Apart from these two factors, success rate can be better anticipated, when the PRK patient is qualified to undergo the same procedure.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The refractive error of myopia or nearsightedness must be mild, not severe.</li>\n<li>The potential PRK patient must at least be 21 years of age, in case the treatment is expected to be held with Summit laser, or 18 years old, in case VISX laser is used for treatments, which are excimer laser brands.</li>\n<li>All the side effects and risks must be well known by the candidates, along with the benefits of the surgery.</li>\n<li>The potential candidate has to be free from any problems associated with the retina, eye diseases or even cornea scarring.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>The success rate of PRK can be better, when the above criteria are fulfilled.</strong></p>\n<p>PRK is one of the laser eye surgeries, like Lasik, Lasek, SMILE and the complications after the surgery are quite often possible, like others. However, the symptoms appear with each of the procedures is different from each other. The best part of the PRK is that the dry condition, which is more prominent symptom after the Lasik procedure, would have less probability.</p>\n<p>Another important part of the PRK is that it is the best suitable laser eye procedure preferred for professionals, who have more probability of eye straining activities and eye risky activities. It is because total problem can be resolved, without retaining any source of the problem.</p>\n<p>So, like the other laser eye surgery procedures, PRK is also one of the best procedures, with more than 95% of success rate and hence stands as one of the best procedures preferred by the eye surgeons and patients to correct the refractive error issues, in the medical industry.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>PRK or PhotoRefractive Keratectomy is one of the first laser eye surgery procedures developed and also approved by the Food and Drug Administration, in the US, compared to Lasik and SMILE, which are the other two famous procedures. Why PRK? PRK is preferred by the surgeons for correcting myopia from mild to moderate level. The [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-soon-after-prk-can-i-drive","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How soon after PRK can I drive?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-soon-after-prk-can-i-drive","contentHtml":"<p>Healing time for PRK is a bit longer compared to the Lasik procedure. So, PRK patients have to wait a bit longer to drive. And the patient has to come to for the surgery along with a family member or a friend to get back home, as they cannot drive, right after the surgery of PRK.</p>\n<p><strong>PRK Procedure and Drive</strong></p>\n<p>PRK procedure is performed as an outpatient surgery and needs at least 5 to 15 minutes for each eye. Anaesthetic drops are given to the eyes for numbing and feel no pain, before the procedure starts. The surface layer of the cornea will then be removed and cornea is reshaped using excimer layer that is guided and operated through computer-controlled light energy pulses.</p>\n<p>Once the cornea reshaping is completed, a bandage contact lens will then inserted by the surgeon for protecting the cornea and retained until epithelial layer is grown back. With this bandage, it is not usually possible to drive, as patient can see only with one eye. So, the patient has to arrange somebody to drive the car and take the patient back home. Hence, immediately after the surgery, the patient cannot drive to get back home.</p>\n<p><strong>Drive During Recovery</strong></p>\n<p>The bandage is retained at least 3 to 5 days after the surgery. During these days, driving is not possible with one eye. After the bandage is removed during the follow-up visit, the patient will be able to drive, in ideal conditions. However, the patient has to judge oneself and take the decision of going for drive or not, on the basis of how fast and how well the image can be captured and interpreted, while driving.</p>\n<p>Ideally, it is always good to take 10 days of rest after the PRK procedure. optimally, one can resume driving and get back to the work after 4 to 5 days after the surgery. When enough rest is taken, without straining the eyes, recovery can be faster and the epithelium layer can grow back and restart functioning as it is supposed to be. Any how, you are the best person to judge how well you are comfortable driving after removing the bandage.</p>\n<p>You should never forget to take the opinion from the surgeon regarding resuming driving during the follow-up visits. If you continue to experience any serious inconvenience, even after removing the bandage, talk to your doctor and take the guidelines and instructions accordingly. Follow each and every guideline of the doctor seriously and use the medicine without fail, regularly.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Healing time for PRK is a bit longer compared to the Lasik procedure. So, PRK patients have to wait a bit longer to drive. And the patient has to come to for the surgery along with a family member or a friend to get back home, as they cannot drive, right after the surgery of [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-does-prk-recovery-take-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How long does PRK recovery take?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-long-does-prk-recovery-take-2","contentHtml":"<p>PRK takes considerably more time for recovery, compared to the other laser eye surgery, Lasik. So, the patient has to be prepared to take enough time rest after the surgery, before resuming the day to day activities.</p>\n<p><strong>Why Longer Recovery Time After PRK?</strong></p>\n<p>Compared to Lasik, PRK takes more time for recovery. The reason is simple and technical. During the procedure, the outer layer of the cornea, which is also called as epithelium layer is removed from the surface of the cornea. Eventually, the patient has to wait to get back to the day to day normal activities until this layer is grown back to a considerable level. Cornea is started healing from the edges and continues to heal towards the center and epithelium ridge is formed across the pupil, where meeting of the healing tissues is performed. This ridge takes 4 to 5 days to form, usually and it gives green signal and safety signal to remove the contact lens bandage.</p>\n<p>By the formation of ridge, the vision gets improved to a range of 20/30 to 20/50, according to the corrective treatment done. This epithelium ridge gets smoothen out in 4 to 6 weeks and vision gets improved gradually.</p>\n<p>Usually, it takes 30 days for regeneration of this layer. Hence, the vision will be completely clear and the best outcomes can be started experiencing after one month to six weeks of duration.</p>\n<p><strong>Experience During Recovery</strong></p>\n<p>Contact lens bandage covering the eye can decrease the discomfort level during the first 4 to 5 days after the surgery. And the patient experiences mild to moderate discomfort and feels the sensation of a foreign body, staying in the eye.</p>\n<p>During the recovery, it is common to experience blurred vision, sensitivity to light and tearing. These symptoms can be relieved after the surface of cornea is started healing. And medically, relieving is possible, as chilled medicated lubricating drops are prescribed to apply in the eyes for faster cornea healing. The same drops also help to decrease any possible risk of infection and scar formation.</p>\n<p><strong>Best Results After PRK</strong></p>\n<p>For the best results, visual clarity and crispy and crystal clear vision can be experienced by the patient after a couple of months. The vision keeps bettered from one month to couple of months and then clear vision gets stabilized. On an overall, it takes 3 months to 6 months to start enjoying the better vision fruits by the patient. Better care and following every guideline and recommendation of the eye surgeon can fasten this period of recovery.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>PRK takes considerably more time for recovery, compared to the other laser eye surgery, Lasik. So, the patient has to be prepared to take enough time rest after the surgery, before resuming the day to day activities. Why Longer Recovery Time After PRK? Compared to Lasik, PRK takes more time for recovery. The reason is [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-much-does-prk-eye-surgery-cost","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How much does PRK eye surgery cost?","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-much-does-prk-eye-surgery-cost","contentHtml":"<p>PRK procedure is usually preferred to correct mild myopia. The cost of the PRK procedure is different from the Lasik, as there is a variation in the technology and procedure. in addition to that the cost of the procedure varies according to the geographical location. There are various factors that determine the cost of the surgery, such as the rural and urban areas.</p>\n<p><strong>PRK </strong></p>\n<p>PRK, which is one of the laser eye surgeries, costs more, when compared to the eye glasses and contact lens. However, it can be a better choice as the outcomes are long lasting and clarity of vision is better, and more than everything, it is hassle free, unlike maintenance of the glasses and lens.</p>\n<p>As mentioned above the cost of the PRK varies from one place to another and on average it costs around $1800, when generalized PRK procedure is considered. When the patient prefers to go for the custom PRK procedure, it costs more and may reach up to $4000. And these procedures can eliminate the dependency over the contact lens and glasses permanently.</p>\n<p><strong>Custom PRK </strong></p>\n<p>The cost of the PRK is more compared to the generalized and traditional PRK, because it demands advanced technology. The basic and technical difference between traditional PRK and Custom PRK is that the Custom PRK designs the PRK procedure as a computer program, exclusively for one customer. The computer program is developed according to the prescription made from the pre-assessment. So, the procedure is performed exclusively for one customer, unlike the generalized or traditional PRK procedure. The major benefit for the Custom PRK procedure is that it offers much accurate procedure, leaving no human error and minimized complications.</p>\n<p><strong>PRK Financing</strong></p>\n<p>Since the cost of the PRK procedure is more compared to the regular glasses and contact lens, some of the medical centers do offer financing options. These medical centers offers allow their patients to pay the charges for the procedure in more than one instalment. Some of the insurance companies offer partial or full financial assistance to undergo this procedure. The percentage of financial assistance varies from one insurance company to another and also from one place to another place. So, it is always a better idea to contact your insurance personnel, before undergoing this procedure and also contact medical centers as they may provide some inputs of how to get financial assistance from any sources like insurance companies, etc.</p>\n<p>The initial cost and overall cost of the PRK may seem to be more, but it is worth, because the positive outcomes and longer fruits of better vision.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>PRK procedure is usually preferred to correct mild myopia. The cost of the PRK procedure is different from the Lasik, as there is a variation in the technology and procedure. in addition to that the cost of the procedure varies according to the geographical location. There are various factors that determine the cost of the [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-after-prk-does-vision-clear-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How long after PRK does vision clear ?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-long-after-prk-does-vision-clear-2","contentHtml":"<p>Some medical experts believe and say that well-informed patient is one of the keys for the best possible outcomes after any surgery. In the same way, when the patient is informed more about the PRK procedure, recovery and outcomes, the results can be better and optimal.</p>\n<p><strong>Recovery &amp; Clear Vision After PRK Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>After the PRK procedure, healing is happened in two phases. First phase is the period where epithelium healing is happened. It takes about 3 to 5 days immediately after the surgery and these days, the patient experiences blurry vision and feels uncomfortable with the contact lens bandage. And the phase two starts, after epithelium healing begins. Vision still looks blurry and discomfort gets minimized during this phase.</p>\n<p>Second phase is the period, where clear and good vision start experiencing by the patient, though vision is a bit blurry. The vision clears up gradually, while this recovery phases progresses.</p>\n<p>After a month of the surgery, a gradual improvement will be noticed, while fluctuations in the vision are common, during the first 2 to 3 weeks. These fluctuations are more prominent with higher corrections. The eyesight keeps improving and finally reaches a state of stable vision. The total time to reach this stability of vision varies from one patient to another. When the patient reacts well for the surgery, the stability of vision can be achieved in just a few weeks and it may take 3 to 6 months for others.</p>\n<p>As the healing is progressing, discomfort is gradually disappeared and slowly one feels better and more comfortable to look at near and farer distances. Sometimes a thin pair of glasses can be useful, for driving during nights and other critical distance vision activities. Unless correction procedure for monovision gets done, PRK patients above 45 years of age may need reading glasses for reading activity.</p>\n<p><strong>Minimizing Discomfort</strong></p>\n<p>Epithelium is like a clear skin in the eye and when this is removed from the cornea, discomfort is common. Mild to moderate discomfort is possible, while the epithelium keeps healing. Usually, patients report that they feel like there is small grain of sand within the eyes. Fortunately, contact lens can increase comfort levels, as it would be like a bandage over the eye. Mild pain and discomfort can be well managed with the prescribed non-steroidal anti-inflammatory agent consisting eye drops. Including the eye drops, pain relievers are also prescribed and are used by the patients, only when needed.</p>\n<p>So, PRK vision takes considerably longer time to achieve clearer vision. However, the results are much better after the complete recovery period. Though it takes more time to recovery completely, the patient can resume to the normal activities by maximum of one week after the surgery.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Some medical experts believe and say that well-informed patient is one of the keys for the best possible outcomes after any surgery. In the same way, when the patient is informed more about the PRK procedure, recovery and outcomes, the results can be better and optimal. Recovery &amp; Clear Vision After PRK Procedure After the [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-prk-covered-by-insurance","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Is PRK covered by insurance?","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/is-prk-covered-by-insurance","contentHtml":"<p>After deciding to undergo PRK or even any other laser eye surgery, the first financial concern arises is whether the PRK is covered by insurance or not. It is a first good thought and worth exploring the solution for the same.</p>\n<p><strong>Insurance for PRK</strong></p>\n<p>Most of the health insurance companies do not offer insurance for PRK and even other laser eye surgery procedures also, as these surgeries in the medical industry are considered to be elective. So, they consider this procedure as a cosmetic procedure, but not necessary one medically. However, because of increased competition among the insurance companies, some of them have started thinking of offering insurance for these surgical procedures to grab more customers and retain existing customers.</p>\n<p>Hence some of the insurance companies offer apparent partial coverage or discounted price for PRK and other laser eye surgeries, though vision plan.</p>\n<p>Vision Plans Considered By Insurance Companies</p>\n<p>Some of the companies try to find the severity of the refractive error and if the PRK or other surgery is found to be essential, then they prefer to offer insurance. The conditions, under which the medical plans for insurance cover laser eye surgery to correct refractive error, in rare circumstances cover the PRK procedure, like the following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Laser eye surgery becomes mandatory for refractive errors, which become as a result of another surgery.</li>\n<li>Eye surgery is needed to perform to correct the refractive errors, because of eye injuries.</li>\n<li>Eye surgery is necessary, in case the patient is unable to wear contact lens or eye glasses, because of certain physical limitations, like lens intolerance or deformity or allergy with eye glasses.</li>\n<li>Eye surgery is necessary, when the refractive errors become severe. But, no standard impairment level is there, at which the correction is covered by insurance. Coverage of insurance, in such cases is very inconsistent, generally and each patient has to check with the health insurance personnel.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The above are a few cases, where the insurance can be offered with probability. So, each of the individual has to check with their insurance providers, by submitting pre-assessment report and based on the reports and requirement of the procedure, coverage of insurance is decided and offered by the insurance providers.</p>\n<p>There are other alternative ways to check out with the employer. As part of your employment benefits, one may be eligible for Flexible Benefit Accounts, Flexible Spending Arrangements or FLEX. As a final alternative, check with the medical center, where you wish to undergo the PRK procedure about credit programs to start the procedure immediately and pay the charges on monthly basis that can fit into your budget affordable to pay monthly.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>After deciding to undergo PRK or even any other laser eye surgery, the first financial concern arises is whether the PRK is covered by insurance or not. It is a first good thought and worth exploring the solution for the same. Insurance for PRK Most of the health insurance companies do not offer insurance for [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-lasik-or-prk-more-expensive-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Is Lasik or PRK more expensive?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/is-lasik-or-prk-more-expensive-2","contentHtml":"<p>LASIK and PRK, both are laser eye surgeries and there should no much difference in terms of cost, though there are differences in terms of procedure and other aspects. PRK is a laser assisted surgical procedure that has been developed to correct majorly myopia or nearsightedness. This procedure is developed as a pioneer laser eye corrective surgery and so LASIK, LASEK, SMILE and all other procedures and respected technologies are developed later.</p>\n<p><strong>Cost Difference Between LASIK and PRK</strong></p>\n<p>Just like any other surgery cost, the cost of LASIK and PRK also vary from one place to another place. The cost of LASIK and PRK are also varied from one place to another place. Another factor that influences the cost of the procedure is the technology. As the technology progresses, the cost of the respective surgery also increases. When geographical area and technology are considered to be the same, PRK procedure is less expensive than LASIK as it consists of lesser process. So, LASIK is more expensive than PRK. The difference is just in hundreds of dollars. If the cost of LASIK is around $2500 per eye, the cost of PRK is in between $1700 to $2000. The difference is less in cost but more in terms of procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Procedural Difference Between LASIK and PRK</strong></p>\n<p>Thought the difference is not much in between Lasik and PRK, there is fundamental and basic difference, in terms of procedure. PRK does not involve the process of creation of corneal flap, but the LASIK procedure does. LASIK creates flap and then reshapes the cornea. The total procedure of PRK is comparatively smaller than LASIK and so the cost of it also.</p>\n<p>Procedure of PRK removes cornea surface cells mechanically using excimer laser and then removes small amount of tissue, till the lens are reached. When LASIK is considered, a flap is created and then it is placed back right in its place and finally it is left like that for healing.</p>\n<p>So, if the cost is a concern, PRK can be the first choice compared to LASIK. In terms of insurance, both of them are considered to be elective procedures and so in most of the cases, insurance is not offered by the insurance companies.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>LASIK and PRK, both are laser eye surgeries and there should no much difference in terms of cost, though there are differences in terms of procedure and other aspects. PRK is a laser assisted surgical procedure that has been developed to correct majorly myopia or nearsightedness. This procedure is developed as a pioneer laser eye [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"does-insurance-cover-lasik-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Does insurance cover lasik eye surgery?","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/does-insurance-cover-lasik-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>LASIK eye surgery is a laser eye surgery and so it is considered as an elective procedure, in the medical industry. Usually LASIK and other laser eye surgeries are preferred and performed to reduce dependency over contact lens and eye glasses. Insurance companies usually do not offer insurance for these elective procedures, as these are more of cosmetic procedures. However, there is another dimension to look at this surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Insurance Offers By Some Insurance Companies</strong></p>\n<p>Insurance providers offer vision insurance plans, but LASIK, which is a refractive surgery is not qualified to be part of an approved vision insurance plan, as it is not medically necessary procedure. There are certain insurance companies, which prefer to grab more customers and retain existing customers, offer some discounts for these elective laser eye surgeries.</p>\n<p><strong>Certain insurance companies offer insurance for the Lasik and other laser eye surgeries in following conditions.</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Laser eyes surgery is required as a result of another surgery.</li>\n<li>Laser eye surgery is mandatory, as a result an injury.</li>\n<li>The patient cannot use either contact lens or eye glasses, because of physical limitations and Lasik or other laser eye surgery becomes mandatory to perform.</li>\n<li>Severe refractive errors made the laser eye surgery as mandate.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Insurance Support From Employers</strong></p>\n<p>Some of the employers negotiate with the Lasik medical centers or refractive surgery centers and make arrangements and offer some special discounts for Lasik eye surgery to their employees. In case you work for a big company, there is more likely that you can get certain discounts for the refractive surgeries, like Lasik.</p>\n<p>And some employers offer some discounts for Lasik surgery through subsidized health plan offers.</p>\n<p><strong>Other Financial Supports</strong></p>\n<p>FSA or Flexible Spending Accounts can help to pay partially for the Lasik laser eye surgeries. These provisions allow pre-tax income to be diverted to health care expenses from the job expenses. There is also another option called HSA (Health Savings Account) to get discount for Lasik surgery. This provision is available for the people, who are covered by HDHP (High Deductible Health Plan) at the workplace. This way, you can start saving money and contribute it for your HSA for a couple of years to cover even entire cost of the Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p>Hence, insurance is not a very feasible option for many Lasik patients, however, it is better to contact the respective health insurance providers to see how far they can be eligible to get the discount.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>LASIK eye surgery is a laser eye surgery and so it is considered as an elective procedure, in the medical industry. Usually LASIK and other laser eye surgeries are preferred and performed to reduce dependency over contact lens and eye glasses. Insurance companies usually do not offer insurance for these elective procedures, as these are [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"do-any-insurance-companies-cover-lasik","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Do any insurance companies cover lasik?","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/do-any-insurance-companies-cover-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>The direct answer for this question is no. No insurance company offers insurance completely for Lasik eye surgery, because it is not medically necessary procedure, as it is an elective or cosmetic procedure. However, some of the Lasik patients can be benefited from the insurance companies in some ways or partially.</p>\n<p><strong>Insurance Company Offers</strong></p>\n<p>Some major insurance providers offer various discounts in the form of ‘courtesy discounts’ to pay for Lasik laser eye surgery, partially. Some insurance companies have clear standards set and pay partially accordingly. So far no insurance company makes it clear that it offers insurance for LASIK surgery directly. The companies may pay, but the specifications are too confined.</p>\n<p>Though specifications are too confined, the following are the conditions, where the insurance providers provide financial support either completely or partially.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>In case the Lasik patient serves in military, along with meeting the pre-determined requirements of the vision, then insurance coverage is assured for them.</li>\n<li>One more professionals qualified for the insurance support are law enforcement professionals and first responders. However, it depends on the severity of the cases.</li>\n<li>Though the patient is not from the above specified careers, still there is a possibility to get qualified, if one is from the sports, entertaining and acting professionals and convince the need for Lasik for the profession, to the insurance provides.</li>\n<li>Other possibility to get qualified for insurance for Lasik is certain medical conditions, such as contact lens intolerance, allergies or severe dry eye conditions are the cases.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>So far no insurance company announced that it can offer financial support for Lasik patients. However, based on the severity and Lasik being last alternative, the patient can convince the provider.</p>\n<p><strong>Financial Support By Other Than Insurance</strong></p>\n<p>Don’t worry, if insurance is not possible to get the support financially, as there are other financial supporting provisions. There are tax-saving tools, like Flexible Spendign Account and Health Savings Accounts can allow to save necessary financial resources for Lasik needs on the basis of pre-tax.</p>\n<p>On the other hand, some of the Lasik centers also offer options for financial support, so that the pay is not spent on one go, but paid in multiple terms. So, after you plan for Lasik, the best way is to meet your financial advisor and take go for the best financial support option.</p>\n<p>So, one thing is very clear that getting the insurance financial support is very hard, except for the people, who are in specific professions. And so far no insurance company has clearly mentioned that it can compensate the expenses of Lasik completely for any insurance seeker.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The direct answer for this question is no. No insurance company offers insurance completely for Lasik eye surgery, because it is not medically necessary procedure, as it is an elective or cosmetic procedure. However, some of the Lasik patients can be benefited from the insurance companies in some ways or partially. Insurance Company Offers Some [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"do-i-qualify-lasik-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Do i qualify lasik?","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/do-i-qualify-lasik-2","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik eye surgery is not technically possible to conduct for all the eye patients. There is a criteria followed by the Lasik medical centers and surgeons to qualify the patients accordingly. Though most of the Lasik patients prefer to go for this surgery, it may not be the case that everyone can undergo this process.</p>\n<p><strong>Criteria to Qualify for Lasik Eye Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>There are a certain criteria, which have to be followed by every Lasik medical center. Then only the success rate of the Lasik surgery can be optimal.</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>The operating eye must be enough healthy.</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>It is important that the eye has to be healthier without any severe problems, except refractive error problem, so that the eye can respond to the Lasik eye surgery and then heals properly after the procedure. in case any problems are associated with the surgery, the potential patient has to wait, until that condition or problem is resolved.</p>\n<p>In addition to that in case of any dry eye condition, where enough tears are not produced naturally to lubricate the eyes, the surgery may aggravate the dry eye problem. Dry eyes include the problems of stinging and burning of eye, reduced wind tolerance and intermittent blurry vision.</p>\n<p>During the pre-assessment, this condition can be detected and so usually, surgeon would identify the problem and takes the decision accordingly.</p>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n<li><strong>The cornea’s thickness must be sufficient</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Most of the laser refractive corrective procedures are performed to improve visual acuity through cornea reshaping. Thin cornea or irregular surface of the cornea may compromise the results and vision impairment may be a negative outcome.</p>\n<p>However, there are certain exceptions that femtosecond laser, in place of microkeratome can manage the procedure with thinner cornea, to a certain a level, because of recent advances. It can also preserve enough tissue over the cornea after the laser treatment.</p>\n<ol start=\"3\">\n<li><strong>The prescription of the patient has to be within certain limits.</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>In case the prescription is too high, because of astigmatism, farsightedness or nearsightedness, Lasik procedure may be advised by the surgeon. Based on the degree of the prescription, eye doctor prescribes the surgery accordingly.</p>\n<ol start=\"4\">\n<li><strong>The age of the eye patients should be certain limits.</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>The patient must be within 21 to 40s. though there is no upper age limit, 40 is usually considered as so, because after 40, though refractive errors are corrected, there can be other eye related vision problems that still leave the vision poor. So, in most of the cases laser eye surgery is conducted for the patients, in between 20 to 40 years. Usually, presbopia, which is prominent vision problem for people above 40 years, can also be operated by monovision Lasik. So, for above 40 years of age, other Lasik procedure is selected recommended.</p>\n<ol start=\"5\">\n<li><strong>The vision has to be enough stable.</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Young adults and teenagers usually experience continuous changes in the prescription of their eyeglasses and contact lens prescription, from one year to the next year. To get the laser refractive error correction procedure performed, the vision has to be stable for minimum of 12 months, before the patient goes through the laser refractive eye surgery. So, younger people have wait until the eye vision gets settled down. Stability of vision can be discovered by observing the prescription for one year before.</p>\n<ol start=\"6\">\n<li><strong>Overall health of the patient has to be good enough.</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>There are certain contraindications to the laser eye surgery, such as uncontrolled autoimmune diseases, like rheumatoid arthritis, AIDS, type 1 diabetes, Sjogren’s syndrome and other uncontrolled degenerative conditions. These people have trough in terms of healing and the risk of unsatisfactory laser eye surgergy outcome is higher.</p>\n<p>Apart from the above, certain medications, like immunosuppressant also could interfere healing after the surgery and some of them may increase dry eye syndrome to next degree.</p>\n<ol start=\"7\">\n<li><strong>The patient has to wait for sometime, if she is pregnant.</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Pregnant women and nursing mothers need to wait for some time, until they cross that period, to undergo the Lasik procedure. It is because the shape of the cornea can be altered because of hormonal changes and may lead to changes in the vision temporarily. Pregnant women may suffer from dry eye syndrome and so needs to wait.</p>\n<p>So, eye doctor recommends the procedure, only after the vision and hormones returned to normal state.</p>\n<ol start=\"8\">\n<li><strong>Patient has to have expectations realistically.</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Lasik surgery has higher success rate and outcomes are excellent and still every potential patient has to be aware of the risks, complications and side effects associated with the Lasik eye surgery, before undergoing the surgery.</p>\n<p>When all these conditions are satisfied, eye doctors recommend Lasik or other laser refractive error correction surgery.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik eye surgery is not technically possible to conduct for all the eye patients. There is a criteria followed by the Lasik medical centers and surgeons to qualify the patients accordingly. Though most of the Lasik patients prefer to go for this surgery, it may not be the case that everyone can undergo this process. [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-much-does-laser-eye-surgery-cost-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How much does laser eye surgery cost?","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-much-does-laser-eye-surgery-cost-2","contentHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery is performed to correct any refractive errors for the eyes. Laser eye surgery is performed through different procedures and each of the procedure is varied technically and so the requirements. Eventually, cost of each of the surgery varies from one another.</p>\n<p><strong>Laser Eye Surgeries and Costs</strong></p>\n<p>Though there are various procedures performed using laser for refractive error correction, the most prominent surgery is Lasik surgery and the cost of this surgery varies from place to another place. So, when the cost of the laser surgery is referred, it is usually the cost of the Lasik laser eye surgery.</p>\n<p>The cost of any surgery varies according to the geographical area and so the cost of the Lasik surgery. However, on an average the cost of Lasik is set to around $2200 for each eye. This is the price in the US.</p>\n<p><strong>Factors of Cost</strong></p>\n<p>The price of the Lasik or other laser eye surgery depends on various factors, such as the following and the total cost is accumulation of all these cost factors.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The first and foremost factor is the kind of procedure performed. Even in one kind of procedure, there are variant technologies implemented. The more the technology is advanced, the more the cost of the procedure. The cost of the procedure with femtolaser costs more than the procedure with microkeratome or blade. And most importantly, the cost varies about 18.6% on the basis of technology. Custom Lasik with the wavefront technology costs more than any other procedures.</li>\n<li>Another important factor is the surgeon and experience. When the surgeon is more skilled and experienced, the Lasik center would increase the cost of the procedure, as anyways every eye surgeon, who performs the procedure has to be qualified anyways.</li>\n<li>One more important aspect is the degree of refractive error. If the refractive error is more, the cost is more likely to increase.</li>\n<li>Inclusive and exclusive price also matters. Some of the Lasik centers cost and offer only for specific Lasik procedure, either including or excluding the other service charges and it influence the overall cost of the Lasik surgery. This way also the total cost of the Lasik may be changed, either much less or much more than the average cost of the Lasik.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>It is always good to look for standard Lasik medical centers rather than going according to cost of the surgery. If any medical center is offering very low Lasik surgery, look for the standards and protocols followed in the procedure. otherwise, just ignore such offers.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery is performed to correct any refractive errors for the eyes. Laser eye surgery is performed through different procedures and each of the procedure is varied technically and so the requirements. Eventually, cost of each of the surgery varies from one another. Laser Eye Surgeries and Costs Though there are various procedures performed [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-go-blind-from-laser-eye-surgery-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can you go blind from laser eye surgery?","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-you-go-blind-from-laser-eye-surgery-2","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik is a laser eye surgery considered as highly successful and fairly low-risk elective surgery. Complications are often possible, but blindness is not. Success and failure of the surgery have many factors involved and enough care should taken in each and every step, before, during and even after the Lasik surgery. Millions of Lasik patients undergo this surgery and there are no cases of going blind recorded.</p>\n<p><strong>Technical Factors to Go Blind</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik laser eye surgery is like any other surgery and so complications are also more likely. However, these complications are very less compared to other surgeries because this surgery can be conducted with laser, by eliminating the need for microkeratome or blade. So, going blind is hardly possible after this surgery.</p>\n<p>Technically, there is a possibility of going blind, though it is extremely rare and no reports are found to be recorded. According to the medical eye expertise, the only possible cause to go blind after Lasik surgery is highly intense and tremendous infection. This infection is usually developed in a period of time and it is important to identify at the earlier stages to get it treated earliest.</p>\n<p><strong>Reports About Going Blind and Success Rate After Lasik </strong></p>\n<p>There are many reports published about the success of Lasik surgery, in multiple dimensions, like customer satisfaction, achieving perfect vision, recovering from refractive errors, avoiding dependency on eyeglasses and contact lens. Not even a single report has reported that a Lasik patient has gone blind after the surgery.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>According to the reports of the American Refractive Surgery Council, no cases of blindness have been reported from Lasik surgery and success rate of the surgery is more than 96%. The same council has reported that the more than 90% of Lasik patients have been satisfied with the vision rate of 20/20.</li>\n<li>The American Foundation for the Blind has reported that blindness occurs when the vision becomes 20/200 or worse, legally. And most of the Lasik patients achieve better vision than 20/20.</li>\n<li>According to the reports of the US Food and Drug Administration, blindness can be occurred and possible after Lasik surgery and in case occurred, it cannot be reversed or corrected with glasses, contact lens or additional surgery. The same reports that despite small level risks possible, Lasik has very higher success rate and rare complication are possible.</li>\n<li>The American Journal of Cataract and Refractive Surgery provided reports from its studies that Lasik laser eye surgery stands as one most successful procedures of surgery. It reports that Lasik does not cause legal blindness, though with rare complications, a few lines of vision can be lost on the vision chart.</li>\n<li>Consumer Reports report that vision loss disabling is a very rare occurrence after Lasik that can even occur even lesser than 1%. However, temporary visual disturbances are possible, because of many factors, like incomplete surgery procedure performed or inconsistent post operative care.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>So, there is nothing to worry about going blind after Lasik as enough care is obviously taken by the medical professionals during the surgery and enough post surgery care by the patient, because, after all, eyes are the most sensitive organs of the human body and demands utmost care.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik is a laser eye surgery considered as highly successful and fairly low-risk elective surgery. Complications are often possible, but blindness is not. Success and failure of the surgery have many factors involved and enough care should taken in each and every step, before, during and even after the Lasik surgery. Millions of Lasik patients [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"when-should-i-get-lasik-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"When should i get lasik?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/when-should-i-get-lasik-2","contentHtml":"<p>If your concern is to know when to undergo the Lasik laser eye surgery, it is more associated with the age. Appropriate age for Lasik is very specific and usually, patients in the same range of age are only recommended by the eye surgeons.</p>\n<p><strong>Lasik and Qualification </strong></p>\n<p>Like any other surgery, Lasik surgery also can have more success rate, when it is performed on the qualified and right patient and less for others. The basic qualification for the patient is the age and the rest of the qualification factors follow.</p>\n<p><strong>Age Factor</strong></p>\n<p>The right age to undergo Lasik surgery is from 21 years to 40 years. Though surgery can also be performed above 40 years, the success rate is more for the patients, who are below 40 years. Some of the Lasik centers are more flexible in terms of age and allow the patients with ages from 18 to 45 years, provided other criteria is met.</p>\n<p>When the patient undergoes Lasik at 18 years, the surgery can be performed form both distance vision and near vision for longest period in one’s life. And they have the capability to heal amazingly well. On the other hand, if one is operated after 40 and before 45, it is the earliest age that the same surgery can give better blended vision and it stands permanent, until the older age gets affected with cataracts. So, according to them, surgery with this age group gives better and blended vision both with distance and near vision, for longest period in their lives.</p>\n<p><strong>Other Factors </strong></p>\n<p>The patient is recommended to undergo Lasik surgery by the Lasik surgery surgeons, when the following conditions are fulfilled by the patient.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Eye health is an important factor. If the eye to be operated is suffering from any kind of other eye related problem, then the complications will be more and so one has to wait until those problems are solved.</li>\n<li>Overall or general body health of the patient has to be good enough to receive the surgery and any kind of sensitivity in the body like blood pressure, blood sugar can create various problems to the general health and overall healing of the Lasik surgery and affects the outcomes.</li>\n<li>One more important technically and medically important factor is that the cornea should have sufficient thickness to undergo Lasik surgery, otherwise, surgeons do not recommend this surgery.</li>\n<li>The size of the pupil should not be very large.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>All these factors are examined in detail, in screening test or pre-assessment of prescription of the potential and based on the personalized assessment report, the eye surgeon determines and recommends the procedure suitable and apt for the prescription.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>If your concern is to know when to undergo the Lasik laser eye surgery, it is more associated with the age. Appropriate age for Lasik is very specific and usually, patients in the same range of age are only recommended by the eye surgeons. Lasik and Qualification Like any other surgery, Lasik surgery also can [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-laser-eye-surgery-safe-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Is laser eye surgery safe?","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/is-laser-eye-surgery-safe-2","contentHtml":"<p>It is the first and foremost question or doubt arises after considering to go for Lasik surgery is whether this surgery is safe enough or not. This doubt and concern is important, since eyes are the most sensitive and important organ of the human body. Laser eye surgery is safe and effective and the same has been proved many times in many clinical studies and reports revealed by many medical authorities.</p>\n<p>The patient can be reassured that today’s laser refractive eye surgery is a safe procedure. There are various surgery procedures and techniques developed and implemented for nearly 30 years and these procedures have been established very well. These procedures, like Lasik, PRK, SMILE and other procedures are proved to be safe and effective, when operated on the patients, who are qualified. So, including other important factors, qualification of the patient stands as important factor for safety and success of the surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Studies and Reports</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>NICE (National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence) of the British National Health Service has researched and considered evidence of potential risks and effectiveness of the laser surgery. It stated that photorefractive or laser surgery for refractive error correction is effective and safe for use, when the patients are selected appropriately, according to the current evidences.</li>\n<li>FDA has reported that the laser refractive surgery procedures’ safely and effectiveness is not determined in the patients, who had been suffering from some kind of diseases.</li>\n<li>There are some experimental techniques performed for Lasik eye surgeries. For instance Lasik has been performed with IntraLase femtosecond laser. Even the newer and experimental techniques, there is no difference found in terms of efficacy and safety, compared to the Lasik surgery performed using blade or microkeratomes performed for myopia correction. But, using femtosecond laser has some potential advantages in terms of predictability.</li>\n<li>Some other studies have been conducted for the laser eye surgeries and the results are analyzed and reported as the following.\n<ul>\n<li>More than 98% of the laser eye surgery patients are happy with the final surgery outcomes.</li>\n<li>More than 90% of the laser eye surgery patients have achieved the results perfectly, like 20/20 or more than that and almost all of the patients have achieved the vision that satisfies and meets the requirements of Australian legal driving.</li>\n<li>More than 98% of the patients haven’t lost vision clarity of less than 3 lines, in terms of corrected distance visual acuity.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>When the surgery is performed the right person, in right way, followed by good post-operative care would ensure the surgery to be safe and effective.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>It is the first and foremost question or doubt arises after considering to go for Lasik surgery is whether this surgery is safe enough or not. This doubt and concern is important, since eyes are the most sensitive and important organ of the human body. Laser eye surgery is safe and effective and the same [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-percent-of-lasik-surgeries-go-wrong-4","date":"2019-09-15","title":"What percent of lasik surgeries go wrong?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/what-percent-of-lasik-surgeries-go-wrong-4","contentHtml":"<p>Technically, any surgery can go wrong, no matter the surgery is performed with blade or without the blade and Lasik surgery is no exception. Any surgery can be successful and the surgery of going wrong can be nullified, only when the surgery is technically successful, followed by apt post surgery care.</p>\n<p>According to many clinical studies and their respective reports, the success rate of Lasik surgery is more than 96% and hence the percent of Lasik surgeries that go wrong is lesser than 4%. When the unsuccessful rate of Lasik can be lesser than 4%, it does not mean that the surgery is failure. There is a considerable area between white and black, which can be grey. So, between success and failure, there can be complications and risky percentage. Every potential Lasik patient has to be aware of these possible risks and complications.</p>\n<p><strong>Complications </strong></p>\n<p>Complications are usually technical factors, where the technical aspects are not fulfilled, while performing the surgery. Another factor for complications is Lasik surgery performed for inappropriate patient. One more factor to consider is inappropriate or inconsistent post-operative care.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Eye Infections</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The first and foremost possible complication after Lasik surgery can be eye infection and it potential threat to the eyes. Hence, it is mandatory for every patient to ensure that there is no infection attacked to the eyes.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Detached Retinas</li>\n</ul>\n<p>It is technically possible, but not usually done with any patients, because eye surgery is performed with an utmost care and care after surgery is also considered as a serious aspect.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Vision Loss</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Loss of vision is subjective and it may start from 1% and it may increase to beyond 90%. The reasons can be inappropriate surgery for the prescription.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Night Vision Problem</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Night vision can be a problem and unclear vision during night, especially during night drive. Night vision in turn declines the quality of life during nights to some extent.</p>\n<p><strong>Complications Rate</strong></p>\n<p>Complications rate after Lasik is extremely low and it is lesser than 1% of the cases. These complications can be easily avoidable, when pre assessment is done in appropriate ways and right surgery and right procedure is provided to the right Lasik patient. On the other hand, appropriate post surgery care also ensures better outcome and decrease complication rate.</p>\n<p><strong>Risks and Side Effects</strong></p>\n<p>Risks and side effects are common usually after every kind of surgery and so Lasik surgery. The possible risks and side effects of Lasik surgery are the following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Dry eyes</li>\n<li>Halos</li>\n<li>Chronic pain</li>\n<li>Glare</li>\n<li>starbursts</li>\n</ul>\n<p>There have been millions of patients, who have gone through the Lasik surgery, every year and the appreciable success rate encourage millions of the potential Lasik patients to undergo the Lasik surgery.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Technically, any surgery can go wrong, no matter the surgery is performed with blade or without the blade and Lasik surgery is no exception. Any surgery can be successful and the surgery of going wrong can be nullified, only when the surgery is technically successful, followed by apt post surgery care. According to many clinical [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-is-your-vision-blurry-after-lasik-4","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How long is your vision blurry after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-long-is-your-vision-blurry-after-lasik-4","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik is preferred by the patients to leave the contact lens or glasses behind and tackle the routine risks, like gardening, reading and many others. The patient may expect clear and crispy vision after the surgery, immediately.</p>\n<p>One needs to understand and remember that the Lasik is a laser eye surgery and it obviously involves an incision and it takes some time to heal after the surgery. The process of healing of the body involves inflammation and it may impact clear vision. It is quite common for the vision to get blurred and continue for several weeks sometimes even months after the Lasik surgery, according to the American Academy of Ophthalmology.</p>\n<p><strong>The Symptom of Blur Vision</strong></p>\n<p>The blurred vision stands as part of the healing process of the body and so, mostly, you need to do nothing or just a little to treat and avoid this issue. In most of the cases, the problem of blurring will be faded with time, though total time to relieve from this system varies from patient to another.</p>\n<p><strong>Causes of Blur</strong></p>\n<p>However, in some cases, according to the journal, Ocular Surgery News, it points out that some of the patients react to the Lasik surgery unusually and blur vision of them. Laser, during laser treatment stimulate tiny particles of the cornea and these particles get swollen and eventually, block light that should natural enter the eye. It results in vision blurring and images would look indistinct. This problem can be medicated easily by doctors, however, this symptom is healed by itself, as the inflammation gets reduced and site also gets healed.</p>\n<p>Other cause of blurred vision is infection, especially, when the infections are caused from bacterial colonies that grow on the eye’s surface. This issue can also be addressed by medication, by the surgeon. The symptom can be treated again medically, by the doctor.</p>\n<p><strong>Return of Blurring</strong></p>\n<p>Blurring may also be returned after a few years after Lasik surgery. It is because the eyes do have transformations with age, since the eye lens get stiffen and lens controlling muscles may become weaker. This is an age related and natural process and it impacts of the eye portions, which are untouched during Lasik surgery. Hence, this blurring caused from age and not from Lasik and so cannot be corrected by corrective procedures of Lasik. The only solution can be contracting an eye doctor, preferably the eye surgeon, who performed Lasik surgery, who is well aware about the conditions and complications related to the eyes.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik is preferred by the patients to leave the contact lens or glasses behind and tackle the routine risks, like gardening, reading and many others. The patient may expect clear and crispy vision after the surgery, immediately. One needs to understand and remember that the Lasik is a laser eye surgery and it obviously involves [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-watch-tv-after-laser-eye-surgery-3","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can i watch TV after laser eye surgery?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-i-watch-tv-after-laser-eye-surgery-3","contentHtml":"<p>One day after Lasik laser eye surgery is very important for the process of healing. No strain of eyes is entertained during this one day time and eye condition must be maintained very easy. Hence, it is important to stay away from using any screens, including phone, tablet, watching television, reading or video games. These activities can be resumed after one day of the laser surgery. However, according to the FDA, you need to wait for a few days to get back to these activities and take off to work. However, the time to get back to the normal vision with no temporary visual disturbances and subside any other discomforts.</p>\n<p><strong>Why Screen Sensitive?</strong></p>\n<p>Compared to many other activities, watching television or viewing any screen that includes smartphones, tablet and other screens exhaust eyes more and faster. It is because computers, television, smartphones and tablets emit different light wavelengths, like LED, white light wavelengths and blue wavelengths and these are harmful to the yes. The more the eyes look at these, the more they get strained and damaging. After the eye surgery, like Lasik or other laser surgeries, the surgical site within the eye becomes very sensitive and needs better protection, compared to the normal conditions of the eyes. And more than anything, even a normal eye can get affected, while watching the screen, since the rate of blinking the eyes naturally gets decreased and this risk is more with the surgery eyes.</p>\n<p><strong>Factors Determine Screen Off Time</strong></p>\n<p>The patient has to minimize the screen time, for a few days ideally, after the Lasik surgery procedure. Otherwise, the eyes experience drying and become easily strained. Not only that screen time before proper primary healing. The time to stay away from television or any screen is not the same for all the Lasik patients and it varies according to several factors, like the following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The kind of laser eye surgery the patient has gone through</li>\n<li>The prescription of the eye or eye condition, prior to the surgery</li>\n<li>The kind of technology or technique used for the laser eye surgery, especially with microkeratome or purely laser</li>\n<li>How far the television is watched and the brightness of the TV screen</li>\n<li>Size of the TV screen</li>\n<li>The general health condition of the patient, which decides healing time of any surgical site</li>\n<li>The rate of blinking the eyes to prevent or minimize the eyes to get dried</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Having understood these factors, it is always better to stay away from the screen for considerably longer time.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>One day after Lasik laser eye surgery is very important for the process of healing. No strain of eyes is entertained during this one day time and eye condition must be maintained very easy. Hence, it is important to stay away from using any screens, including phone, tablet, watching television, reading or video games. These [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-do-you-have-to-wear-sunglasses-after-lasik-3","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How long do you have to wear sunglasses after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-long-do-you-have-to-wear-sunglasses-after-lasik-3","contentHtml":"<p>Taking additional care for the eyes after Lasik surgery is vital, since eyes are most important and sensitive organs of the human body. After the Lasik surgery, the eyes will be intensely sensitive, when they are exposed to light. This sensitivity continues for at least one monthpost surgery and one needs to wear sunglasses or protective goggles.</p>\n<p><strong>Why Sunglasses?</strong></p>\n<p>On the day of surgery of Lasik, the eyes must be kept in dark, for the whole day. Right after the surgery, dark goggles are given by Lasik center to wear at home and it must be continued continuously for a few days of healing process. These goggles not only protect your eyes from the light that is harmful, but also from protecting the eyes against rubbing during sleep. Not disturbing the eyes must be the most important thing for healing, because Lasik flap can be damaged easily with even smaller disturbance.</p>\n<p><strong>How Long?</strong></p>\n<p>Now the question is how long the Lasik patient has to wear after the Lasik surgery. It is not the same for all the patients, though usually, one week of time is ideal to ensure that the eyes are enough protected during the healing process and recovery. This duration varies from one patient to another patient, because of various factors that determine the healing and recovery process.</p>\n<p>However, in most cases, practically, Lasik patients wear the sunglasses, for the first day and wear only when they go out during day, for a week or more. It depends on the comfort levels of the Lasik patient, who feels comfortable with and without sun glasses. However, it is important to note that do not know, how harsh the external environment would be and how adverse situations may arise to the eyes. So, ideally, feel free and take enough care by wearing the sunglasses after the Lasik surgery and wear the sunglasses at least one month after the Lasik surgery, whenever you go out, during day time.</p>\n<p>Eyes are the most precious parts of the human body and quality of life and life experiences are strongly related to the vision, every fraction of second we live. So, take enough care.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Taking additional care for the eyes after Lasik surgery is vital, since eyes are most important and sensitive organs of the human body. After the Lasik surgery, the eyes will be intensely sensitive, when they are exposed to light. This sensitivity continues for at least one monthpost surgery and one needs to wear sunglasses or [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-many-days-rest-is-required-after-lasik-surgery","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How many days rest is required after lasik surgery?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-many-days-rest-is-required-after-lasik-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Compared to the other laser eye surgeries, Lasik eye patients are happier about the time need to spend for recovery, with majority of the patients reporting and sharing that they started experiencing normal vision fairly, after one day of the Lasik surgery. Improved vision is even experienced by many of Lasik patients, immediately after the Lasik. It is more likely that the patients having higher prescriptions would tend to get improvement of vision quicker, compared to the patients with lower prescription.</p>\n<p><strong>Recovery Time After Lasik</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Immediately After the Surgery\n<ul>\n<li>Each Lasik surgeon establishes own protocols for Lasik recovery, according to the best results they are looking for. Most likely, the surgeon provides eye shields or protective sunglasses for the eyes protection and you need to wear them most of the time at home, especially during the nights, for at least one week after the surgery. Though some surgeons release the patient right after the procedure, some of the surgeons prefer you to take rest for at least 10 to 15 minutes of time, before you head home. The patient has to arrange family member or friend to drive home, as one cannot drive immediately after the surgery.</li>\n<li>The numbing drops applied for numbing the eye nerves, during the procedure will wear off, usually in 20 to 30 minutes, right after the surgery. After that, a mild itching or burning sensation would be felt by the patient, and still the eyes should not be touched or rubbed. The eyes may become watery considerably and bloodshot may be appeared or red spots may be developed. However, these are temporary and quite normal symptoms.</li>\n<li>This is very crucial recovery period, as the patient has to be very careful with the eyes and should be very conscious about the eye, not to touch or disturb it.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>First Day &amp; First Week After the Procedure\n<ul>\n<li>First follow-up visit would be scheduled usually, within 24 to 48 hours after the procedure and the surgeon checks that the healing procedure is going correctly. Most of the Lasik patients prefer to go to work, after a day or two after the surgery. However, if possible, it is better to stay at home at least two days after the surgery, to give enough time good healing. During this period, the recommended lubricating eye drops, antibiotic eye drops or steroid eye drops must be given to the eyes, as prescribed by the doctor.</li>\n<li>During the first one week, a slight discomfort is quite possible and this condition is called as ‘eye lash, within the eye. It is not an alarming situation, as it is quite normal.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>First Few Weeks After the Procedure\n<ul>\n<li>Eyes must be continued to be lubricated for a few weeks after the surgery, until the surgeon recommends doing so, at least 3 to 4 times a day to prevent the symptom of dry eye condition. Sensitivity to light is common during this period and this condition can be alleviated with the help of sunglasses, while outdoors.</li>\n<li>During this period, your surgeon may limit certain activities, like wearing eye makeup, exercise, swimming, etc. These can be started after a few weeks after taking assurance from the doctor. If any issues or pain or accidental events occur with the eyes, they should be taken into notice immediately to the doctor to prevent any kind of infections or other complications in the future.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>First 2 to 3 Months After the Procedure\n<ul>\n<li>Usually, complete healing takes total 3 months after the procedure and vision continues to be improved. In case of severe prescription, this period may increase to even 6 months. Since everybody’s condition is unique, healing period is also unique and rarely, about 3 to 5% of cases may need enhancement procedure, in case the vision is not improved to the expected levels.</li>\n<li>During this period, contact sports, whirlpools and hot tubs must be avoided and resumed only after confirmation from the surgeon.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Hence, the total recovery is not the same for all, however, taking special care to the eyes and resuming the activities must be followed in the same way as specified above.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Compared to the other laser eye surgeries, Lasik eye patients are happier about the time need to spend for recovery, with majority of the patients reporting and sharing that they started experiencing normal vision fairly, after one day of the Lasik surgery. Improved vision is even experienced by many of Lasik patients, immediately after the [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-sleep-after-lasik-4","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can you sleep after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-you-sleep-after-lasik-4","contentHtml":"<p>Usually, many of the Lasik patients tend to take a nap after going home. Sleep after surgery is no harm, according to many people and a very few people would rethink before doing the same. So, let us see, whether sleeping is encouraged by eye surgeons or not and how it is treated as good and not good by some others.</p>\n<p><strong>Sleep Right After the Surgery Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>Millions of Lasik patients prefer to go to sleep after the surgery and the success rate of the surgery is extremely high. So, there is no harm in sleeping right after the surgery. However, there is a small time gap is required after the surgery for technical reasons.</p>\n<p>The final step in the procedure of Lasik involves top layer of cornea replaced. It is supposed to be done perfect. The layer has to be ideally, aligned so well that the edge should not found even, when looked with a microscope, even immediately after 10 minutes of the surgery. the topcoat of epithelium has to be sealed on the edge of that specific layer and this process needs at least six hours. After it occurs, there can be change to change. Any changes done as part of this may not be healthier and healing may be delayed and the changed would be hard to occur.</p>\n<p>When sleeping, the eye lids are closed and movement of eye is also common. It does not allow the layer to get dried and completely sticking to the surface. Eventually, sleeping immediately after the surgery does not allow the layer to heal completely, as it should be by that time.</p>\n<p><strong>So, How Much Gap Is Needed?</strong></p>\n<p>According to the eye surgeons, the patient needs to wait for 4 to 6 hours of time, before sleeping. After this period, sleeping can be advantageous and gives the surgical site the opportunity to heal in a better ways. Before going to take nap or sleep, it is quite important to wear the protective shield to ensure that eyes are not at all disturbed, even accidentally and no pressure is applied during sleep.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Usually, many of the Lasik patients tend to take a nap after going home. Sleep after surgery is no harm, according to many people and a very few people would rethink before doing the same. So, let us see, whether sleeping is encouraged by eye surgeons or not and how it is treated as good [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-cook-after-lasik-surgery-3","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can i cook after laser surgery?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-i-cook-after-lasik-surgery-3","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik is one of the laser eye surgeries, preferred by most of the people, compared to the other surgeries, like PRK, LASEK, SMILE, etc. The reason for preferring this procedure is earlier recovery.</p>\n<p><strong>Activities After Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>Since Lasik is preferred for quicker recovery, most of the activities performed day to day in our lives can be resumed, much earlier than the other procedures. Regarding the normal activities, most of the day to day regular activities can be resumed after two days of the surgery. Most of the patients do get the doubt, cooking is part of the regular activities and is it fine, if cooking can also be resumed after the day of Lasik surgery. Yes, the concern is good and one needs to know why the patient can go and why the patient cannot go for cooking after the procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Cooking After the Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>As normal activities can be resumed after one day of the surgery procedure, cooking can be resumed after at least two days after the surgery. It is because, the process of cooking demands closer contact with the vessels on the stove and eyes have to go closer to the vessel. Since, cooking vessel emits heat, in most of the cases, eventually, the eyes, which get closer to the vessel tend to absorb more heat and it may not be healthier for the eye corneal surface and flap, which are in the course of healing. So, it may not be very good for the eyes operated with Lasik.</p>\n<p>However, compared to the other laser eye surgeries, recovery is a bit faster with the Lasik procedure, rather than the other procedures. So, you need not wait for weeks together before cooking. Small and easier cooking tasks and for a few minutes can be resumed in two to three days after the surgery.</p>\n<p>If you are very much interested for cooking, it is important that you consult your surgeon and address your interests and concerns. Based on your unique prescription, the surgeon will be the right person to suggest you when exactly you can resume cooking two days or one week after your surgery.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik is one of the laser eye surgeries, preferred by most of the people, compared to the other surgeries, like PRK, LASEK, SMILE, etc. The reason for preferring this procedure is earlier recovery. Activities After Surgery Since Lasik is preferred for quicker recovery, most of the activities performed day to day in our lives can [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-use-phone-after-lasik-3","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can i use phone after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-i-use-phone-after-lasik-3","contentHtml":"<p>Usually, while recovery from any health issues, it is quite common for people to stay at home and keep watching television, working with computer, watching videos in mobile. However, it is not an encouraging practice after the Lasik surgery. After the Lasik surgery, the patient has to be away from almost any kind of screens.</p>\n<p><strong>Phone Usage After Lasik Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>Usage of mobile phone has been increased, after smartphones have been launched into the market and internet is started to be accessible from the mobile phones. So, we tend to start using the mobile phone to just to reply for a Watsapp message and we tend to forget time, hours together, in chatting over Watsapp. This is a dangerous circumstance for the patients, who have just undergone Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p>Lasik surgery is a special laser eye surgery, which has faster recovery time than the other laser eye surgeries. So, you can get back to the normal activities almost in a day or two. During this time, the patient has to keep the screen away from the eye sight. In case one keeps looking the screen of the mobile or computer or television, the eyes get more strained and vision becomes uncomfortable. It may also lead to dry eyes, as the natural blinking rate would be reduced to a greater extent.</p>\n<p><strong>Changing Phone Settings Accordingly</strong></p>\n<p>Though the Lasik patient avoids the mobile screen for two days after the surgery, he or she cannot stay away for weeks together, realistically. So, while minimizing the screen time can be of great help for healing process, small changes in phone settings can reduce the risks of dry eye and discomfort to the eyes to a much better extent.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Sending messages, setting reminders, setting alarms, performing searches and many other tasks can be performed using voice controls. So, switch to voice control operation, in order to make use of the mobiles, without affecting the day to day communication with the world and workplace. Android mobile users can also make use of Google Assistant, which can perform the tasks you wish, by responding to your voice. iPhone users can get the same help from Siri, similarly.</li>\n<li>Set the backlight options, according to the comfort levels. Go to your smartphone display settings and decrease the brightness to the level, it does not disturb your eyes. Lasik is a light sensitivity eye surgery and hence it would be a good idea to invert the mobile phone colors and it changes the backlight color to be black and the text looks in white color.</li>\n<li>Screen readers can help you to listen the text displayed on the screen, without any need of reading, by looking at the screen. For instance, text messages can also be read using screen readers.</li>\n<li>You got to increase the text size to the level of comfort to look by eyes to read. The default text size must be increased to at least 5 points more.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>So, including the general post surgery care, such as applying the eye drops to the eyes and taking long rest, you can do these small changes in the mobile phone, so that your essential phone associated tasks would not be disturbed.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Usually, while recovery from any health issues, it is quite common for people to stay at home and keep watching television, working with computer, watching videos in mobile. However, it is not an encouraging practice after the Lasik surgery. After the Lasik surgery, the patient has to be away from almost any kind of screens. [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-crying-affect-lasik-3","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can crying affect lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-crying-affect-lasik-3","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik surgery, being popularly operated throughout the world, it has got many hopes and myths as well. Lasik surgery is one of the safest laser eyes surgeries in the world, with lesser side effects and faster recovery. Crying is one different condition with respect to the surgery and so let us see how it may influence the overall recovery.</p>\n<p><strong>Action of Crying</strong></p>\n<p>First we need to understand what is crying and how this action is associated with the eyes. When we cry, we tend to produce the tears naturally and these tears are developed within the eye and come out from it. This is a natural lubrication process for the eye and this is no way problem, as the eyes would be more lubricant and the condition of dry eye would be reduced. So far it is safe enough in one dimension, however, there is one more dimension to consider and think of it.</p>\n<p>Another dimension of crying is rubbing the eyes with the eyes, usually with the intension of wiping off the tears. When the eyes are rubbed with pressure, using the hands, it would impose risks to the eyes. When the eyes are rubbed, the risk is imposed to the flap within the eye. The risks can be of different forms and different levels and it may start from creation of small folds or wrinkles within the eye or in severe cases, the flap even can be displaced.</p>\n<p><strong>What Are the Affects?</strong></p>\n<p>In case there are any folds or wrinkles are created, the symptoms can be blurred or unclear hazy vision. On the other hand, if the flap is reduced, it may create some complications and symptom possible can be pain experienced within the eye.</p>\n<p><strong>What To Do When Symptoms Arise?</strong></p>\n<p>When you feel any different experience after crying, especially, after rubbing the eyes, the first action that should be taken is to consult your eye surgeon, who operated the eye. In case any issue or disturbance occurs with the eye, the doctor would discover it, when the eyes are checked under the slit lamp.</p>\n<p>When any wrinkles, displacement or any other kind of disturbances occur, the eye surgeon has to treat it, by performing certain corrections. With the advancement of technology, the severity of these issues is less and correction would be easier. So, don’t worry about crying, but the most important thing is that you should not rub the eyes or create any kind of pressure, not only while crying, but also with any other kind of activity.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik surgery, being popularly operated throughout the world, it has got many hopes and myths as well. Lasik surgery is one of the safest laser eyes surgeries in the world, with lesser side effects and faster recovery. Crying is one different condition with respect to the surgery and so let us see how it may [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-read-the-day-after-lasik-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can you read the day after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-you-read-the-day-after-lasik-2","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik surgery is special among other laser eye surgeries, because of the faster recovery. There are many day to day activities, which can be resumed much earlier than the other laser eye surgeries.</p>\n<p><strong>Reading After Lasik</strong></p>\n<p>There are certain activities, which can be resumed after a day or two of the Lasik eye surgery. Usually, the most commonly activities that are allowed and considered as safer activities after one day of surgery include reading the books also. However, intensive reading is not recommended, right after the surgery. Technically, a Lasik patient can resume reading the book after 24 hours.</p>\n<p><strong>Special Care While Reading</strong></p>\n<p>Though reading is not restricted after the surgery, if the patient prefers to read intensively, he or she needs to take special care, while attempting to read.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The first and foremost thing to consider while reading is lubrication of the eye. The eye drops prescribed by the eye must be used regularly, without skipping anytime. It is important because, while reading, people tend to blink the eyes less frequently and eventually, eye surface gets dried up very soon. To prevent this condition, eye drops must be frequently used.</li>\n<li>Another important aspect is to consciously keep blinking more, while reading. Though one is completely immersed in reading, blinking should not be forgotten, as it may also increase the risk of dry eye condition.</li>\n<li>If the patient keeps reading intensely every day, it takes about 2 months to recover from fluctuating vision. It may result in starbursts and glare, especially, during the nights. Special care is required in such situations that the patient has to take longer breaks between reading. It should be done, while giving conscious breaks even while reading.</li>\n<li>Based on the eye prescription of the patient, which is unique for every patient, reading concern has to be addressed to the eye surgeon, who operated the eye. If the patient likes to go for longer reading, special additional precautions must be taken, according to the prescription.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Ideally, biological system is the best alarm to say when to read and when to stop reading to take a break. So, follow the same and go for happy reading.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik surgery is special among other laser eye surgeries, because of the faster recovery. There are many day to day activities, which can be resumed much earlier than the other laser eye surgeries. Reading After Lasik There are certain activities, which can be resumed after a day or two of the Lasik eye surgery. Usually, [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-drive-after-lasik-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can i drive after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-i-drive-after-lasik-2","contentHtml":"<p>No, immediately, after Lasik surgery, the patient should not attempt to drive. Lasik eye surgery is quite safe and is have quick recovery. However, the precautions must be safely followed, after the surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Immediately After the Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>Though the vision seems to be clear enough, immediately after the Lasik surgery, blurriness is quite possible for several hours, post Lasik. The numbing eye drops, which are used by the surgeon, during the surgery, wear off after a few hours of the surgery. Then eyes become more sensitive to the light. The eyes will start watering and it affects the vision of the eyes.</p>\n<p>In addition to that the vision affected, mild sedatives, which are given prior to the surgery also become an important factor. This sedative is given to help the patient to relax and it sometimes give a slight drowsiness and it affects the overall reaction time after the procedure of Lasik.</p>\n<p>So, during this course of reaction and recovery, immediately after the surgery, your friend or family member has to accompany you to drive you home. During this course, it is important that the patient keeps relaxing and take rest. Driving may give additional stress to the mind, apart from the physical strain to the eyes. Protective shields are given to wear after the surgery and he or she must wear them, while getting back home. So, it is always a good idea to take your friend or family member to drive you back home.</p>\n<p><strong>Legal Driving Aspects After the Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>Once the surgery is over, it is not the end of medication or hospital visit, as one has to keep visiting the hospital, for follow-ups. When the patient returns to the Lasik medical center, for the first post-operative exam, the eyes are checked up for the eyesight, by the doctor. This check is also done to ensure legal aspects for driving, without any need for corrective lenses. In this visit, some paperwork may be given by the doctor to forward to the local Motor Vehicles department office. When everything goes well and after natural cure of the refractive error problem, legal driving license will be given without need of the corrective lenses. Eventually, motor and vehicles department office can remove the restriction of ‘requires corrective lenses’, from the driving license.</p>\n<p>After the confirmation of the visual acuity meeting the requirements of the legal requirement, which is 20/40 or better, in many of the geographical areas, the patient is safe to drive legally after the Lasik surgery procedure.</p>\n<p>So, be very cautious to take the decision about driving and decide to drive only after getting legal safe driving license.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>No, immediately, after Lasik surgery, the patient should not attempt to drive. Lasik eye surgery is quite safe and is have quick recovery. However, the precautions must be safely followed, after the surgery. Immediately After the Surgery Though the vision seems to be clear enough, immediately after the Lasik surgery, blurriness is quite possible for [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-swim-after-lasik-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can i swim after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-i-swim-after-lasik-2","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik eye surgery improves the eye vision and reduces dependence over the contact lens or eye glasses. Lasik is the laser eye surgery procedure, preferred by many eye patients, as it has faster recovery time and normal and regular activities can be resumed quickly, compared to the other laser eye surgeries.</p>\n<p><strong>Swimming After Lasik</strong></p>\n<p>After Lasik eye surgery, the patient has to wait at least for two weeks, before going for swimming, otherwise serious recovery issues and eye health issues may arise. No matter you wish to head down the shore or swim in a small pool, two week recovery period must be completed to wait.</p>\n<p><strong>Risks and Complications With Swimming</strong></p>\n<p>When the Lasik surgery is performed, small flap is created in the cornea and customized treatment is given with the help of advanced lasers. Though it is a shorter procedure, the eyes become sensitive during recovery for better healing.</p>\n<p>When these eyes are exposed to the water, while swimming, the eyes easily get irritated and dried so easily. In addition to that bacteria and chemicals present in the swimming water can cause any serious eye problems or infections in the eyes.</p>\n<p><strong>Precautions Before and During Swimming</strong></p>\n<p>Though swimming is started after two weeks of recovery period, still, additional care needs to be taken, to protect the eyes from unclean and unclear swimming water. Follow certain suggestions and guidelines, before and during swimming.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Before going for swimming take the opinion of your doctor, as the recovery time may vary according to your eye prescription. You need to get to know the exact condition of your eye and its healing state and it gives the clues about what activity to resume and what not.</li>\n<li>Wear goggles, though eyes are recovered to some extent, while swimming. Continue to wear these goggles, for at least a month, after resuming swimming activity. These goggles prevent the eyes from direct contact with irritating chemicals or debris, present in water.</li>\n<li>Initially, when you go for swimming, prefer to swim in chlorinated swimming pool, instead of other pools. After this phase, go for swimming in natural water bodies, like oceans, lakes, etc.</li>\n<li>Going for swimming is almost going for outing. So, you need to protect your eyes against the ultraviolet rays also by wearing sun glasses.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>So, swimming aspirants need not worry for anything, as they can go for swimming and resume most of the low impact and medium impact water activities, after one month of recovery and gradually, high impact water activities also can be resumed later.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik eye surgery improves the eye vision and reduces dependence over the contact lens or eye glasses. Lasik is the laser eye surgery procedure, preferred by many eye patients, as it has faster recovery time and normal and regular activities can be resumed quickly, compared to the other laser eye surgeries. Swimming After Lasik After [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-after-lasik-can-i-work-out-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How long after lasik can i work out?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-long-after-lasik-can-i-work-out-2","contentHtml":"<p>With the increasing health consciousness by the people, daily workout activities have become part of day to day activities in their lives. There is no wonder that many of the Lasik patients enquire about how soon they can get back to these daily workouts.</p>\n<p><strong>Lasik Procedure, Recovery and Workouts</strong></p>\n<p>The procedure of Lasik involves creating a flap. So, if any harder activities like daily workouts or sports are started, before this flap is recovered, it would be inviting the complications related to flap. Even wiping sweat over the eyes, by applying small pressure over the eyes can also result in complications of the flap. Full length of recovery has to be completed, before resuming regular daily workout activities.</p>\n<p><strong>Resuming Workouts</strong></p>\n<p>A Lasik patient can return to simple workouts like walking, running and other small stressful activities after three days of the surgery, provided the eyes are untouched consciously. You need to be very mindful about any stress or discomfort experienced to your eyes and ensure that these workouts are performed slower enough.</p>\n<p>If you are a serious workout passionate lover and prefer to go for sports, martial arts, boxing and other high-intensity workouts, you need to wait for at least one month after the surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Special Care During Workouts </strong></p>\n<p>You need to be very careful about the eyes during workouts and make sure that the following special care instructions are followed.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Before resuming the daily workouts and also sports, you need to discuss with your doctor and get confirmation to resume these activities.</li>\n<li>After the workouts are started, sweat is possible and it should not be flowing into the eyes as it may create irritation. So, do not let the sweat to fall into the eyes. In case sweat flows into eyes, don’t attempt to rub the eyes by applying pressure, as it may displace flap created during Lasik. So, wipe off sweat on the forehead itself, without falling down to prevent any discomfort and blurred vision.</li>\n<li>Make use of protective eyewear, while working out so that the process of healing is not disturbed. This protective eyewear can help the eyes to stay away from debris and dirt to prevent irritation of the eyes, while doing exercises. The same can protect you from trauma and high impact, while performing hard workout activities.</li>\n<li>If your workout is extended to playing sports, like tennis, basketball, prefer to wear sport goggles, made especially with polycarbonate lenses. The material polycarbonate is durable and is famous for its property of resistance, which could help shielding the eyes against fast moving objects.</li>\n<li>Give at least one month of recovery time, before resuming high impact and intense exercises and follow all the standard practices and precautions more consciously.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Remember, simple exercises, like walking and running can be resumed in lesser than a week time. But being conscious and taking extra care about the eyes are more important.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>With the increasing health consciousness by the people, daily workout activities have become part of day to day activities in their lives. There is no wonder that many of the Lasik patients enquire about how soon they can get back to these daily workouts. Lasik Procedure, Recovery and Workouts The procedure of Lasik involves creating [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-exercise-after-laser-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can you exercise after laser eye surgery?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-you-exercise-after-laser-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery is the most preferred eye refractive error surgery in the medical industry. The primary cause to prefer this surgery is faster recovery and less invasive process. Faster recovery indicates less time needed to resume the day to day activities and so exercises and sports.</p>\n<p><strong>Resuming Exercises</strong></p>\n<p>When can a laser eye surgery patient resume day to day exercises and workouts after the surgery? Recovery time varies from one person to one person, as every patient has unique refractive error and eye prescription. And hence, there is no single answer for this question. Another reason for varied answers is because exercises and workouts range from lower impact to higher impact and wider range of the same.</p>\n<p><strong>Factors Influencing Recovery </strong></p>\n<p>There are multiple factors that influence the total recovery period after the surgery and so the waiting period before resuming the exercises.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The first factor is the kind of laser eye surgery the patient has gone through. For instance, if the patient has gone through the Lasik surgery, the overall recovery time before resuming the exercises is only two to four weeks. On the other hand, if the surgery is PRK, then the recovery time is more compared to Lasik surgery. Hence, the patient has to wait for more than a month, as a minimum waiting period. Other surgeries like SMILE, LASEK have comparatively lesser recovery time and so lesser waiting period.</li>\n<li>Another important factor is from the patient side. Every eye condition is unique and so every patient’s eye prescription. Based on this prescription, the refractive error correction surgery varies and eventually, the recovery time of the same.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Resuming Exercises </strong></p>\n<p>Today, people have been becoming more health consciousness and so yoga has become part of their morning routine. Yoga can be resumed after one week of the laser eye surgery. Slight jogging can also be resumed after this period. Remember that hard workouts and intensive yoga exercises must be avoided, at the time of resuming and it is fine to do the same after a month’s period.</p>\n<p>Based on the surgery the patient has gone through, one can return to gym after two to four weeks of duration. Here also, lower impact exercises are fine and going forward, higher impact exercises can be resumed. Higher impact sports need much longer time, it is even good to wait for at least six months of duration.</p>\n<p>No matter what kind of exercises you have resumed, make sure that the sweat does not fall into your eyes as it may cause certain complications and risks. So, make sure that the sweat is wiped off very carefully, without even touching eyes or even slight pressure on the eyelids.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery is the most preferred eye refractive error surgery in the medical industry. The primary cause to prefer this surgery is faster recovery and less invasive process. Faster recovery indicates less time needed to resume the day to day activities and so exercises and sports. Resuming Exercises When can a laser eye surgery [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-after-prk-can-i-swim","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How long after PRK can i swim?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-long-after-prk-can-i-swim","contentHtml":"<p>PRK procedure is comparatively more invasive procedure and so the recovery time is more than the other laser eye surgeries. So, during this recovery period, physical activities must be avoided and good rest must be taken to ensure that the process of healing is not disturbed and better vision is ensured.</p>\n<p><strong>Waiting Period for Swimming</strong></p>\n<p>After PRK laser eye surgery, the patient can resume to swimming, only after one week period and this is the minimum time. If all the other conditions are well and at optimum level, this period is acceptable. This waiting period time must be more, in cases of higher risks and complications. Still, there are certain conditions to resume this swimming.</p>\n<p><strong>After Two Weeks</strong></p>\n<p>After a week, swimming activity can be resumed, but there are certain limitations. Swimming is allowed in only swimming pools that are clean enough and filled with clean water. The patient should avoid swimming in lakes, rivers and oceans. Even before resuming this activity, you need to get the confirmation from your eye surgeon, who has best known about your eye condition and associated risks and complications.</p>\n<p><strong>After Four Weeks</strong></p>\n<p>Swimming in outdoors and outdoor water bodies is allowed only after a period of two weeks.</p>\n<p><strong>Care During Swimming</strong></p>\n<p>Special care is mandatory, when the patient goes for swimming. Since, most of the swimming pools are at outdoors, the patient has to wear sunglasses, while going to the outdoors. On the other hand, goggles are mandatory to wear, while swimming. It is important because when the eyes are opened underwater, any debris or dust particles should not disturb the surface of the eye.</p>\n<p><strong>Disturbances During Swimming</strong></p>\n<p>Before going for swimming, make sure that the guidelines and recommendations provided by the PRK medical center are clearly followed. If the patient experiences any kind of disturbances or accidental events during swimming, immediate first aid and necessary medications must be taken. Even it is a smaller issue, it must be addressed to the respective eye surgeon, either in the following follow-up visit or immediately, in cases of any severe or serious issues.</p>\n<p>Usually, during the recovery time, certain risks and symptoms are common after PRK and even any other laser eye surgery. These symptoms should not be intensified with the process of swimming. So, make sure all the precautions are followed and no disturbances are occurred, when resuming swimming.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>PRK procedure is comparatively more invasive procedure and so the recovery time is more than the other laser eye surgeries. So, during this recovery period, physical activities must be avoided and good rest must be taken to ensure that the process of healing is not disturbed and better vision is ensured. Waiting Period for Swimming [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-after-prk-can-i-drive-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How long after PRK can i drive?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-long-after-prk-can-i-drive-2","contentHtml":"<p>The patient cannot drive immediately after the surgery to go home from the PRK medical center. There are two reasons for the same, firstly sedative given during the surgery makes the patient feel drowsy and secondly, the vision becomes blurry immediately after the surgery. It continues for several hours and after that also a slight discomfort is common to continue. So, you need to arrange someone to drive and take you home from the medical center.</p>\n<p><strong>Driving After PRK</strong></p>\n<p>PRK surgery is comparatively more invasive procedure compared to the other laser eye surgeries and so it needs more recovery time. Most of the PRK patients can experience better vision with decreased blur by the next morning of the surgery, however, it is not easy and safe for them to drive at that instance. Fairly good vision takes at least a week time.</p>\n<p>The patient experiences discomfort for a couple of days after the PRK surgery and it is usually mild to moderate. Visual recovery takes several days. Driving activity needs more time after the surgery. So, it takes 5 days to one week to resume driving by the PRK patient.</p>\n<p><strong>Special Care During Driving</strong></p>\n<p>Based on special and unique prescription of the patient, the surgery and recovery time also depend accordingly.</p>\n<p>Night vision is problematic after the surgery and it continues for several days. Hence, night driving must be avoided for many days. During day driving also special care is required. Eye glasses are very important to wear to make sure that there are no debris particles and dust entered the eyes. Most importantly don’t let sweat to enter the eyes even during the summer driving days.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The patient cannot drive immediately after the surgery to go home from the PRK medical center. There are two reasons for the same, firstly sedative given during the surgery makes the patient feel drowsy and secondly, the vision becomes blurry immediately after the surgery. It continues for several hours and after that also a slight [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-wear-contact-lenses-after-prk","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can i wear contact lenses after PRK?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-i-wear-contact-lenses-after-prk","contentHtml":"<p>The objective of undergoing refractive error corrective laser eye surgery, such as PRK, LASIK, LASEK etc., is to reduce or eliminate dependency on the contact lens or eye glasses. However, though in minority cases, wearing contact lens attain better still visual acuity, improving quality of life.</p>\n<p><strong>Cornea Surface After PRK</strong></p>\n<p>Technically, the answer is yes. The patient can wear contact lens after PRK or any other refractive error surgery. Fitting contact lens to the eyes of PRK patients is straight forward, typically. The reliving part is that the eye, after PRK tolerates wearing the contact lens as the cornea stands lesser sensitive to it, in fact in a better way an eye can without the surgery.</p>\n<p>PRK surgery operates the cornea central part to 6mm. The zone of 6mm is smaller compared to the average contact lenses’ optic zone. Hence, you need to realize that the readings of the central keratometry have to be clear and should be flatter than expected, before fitting contact lenses, post the surgery. These corneal readings along with the transition zones and smoothness of the treatment can be determined with the help of topography. Usually, very central cornea flatter looks with regular pattern than the normal, when seen with topography. The technical reason behind this is that the PRK does not make changes to the shape of the cornea, outer treatment zone.</p>\n<p><strong>Challenges of Wearing Contact Lens Post Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>Fitting contact lenses in normal condition is easier compared to the cases of post refractive error corrective laser surgeries. It is because any laser refractive surgery, including PRK changes the natural shape of the cornea.</p>\n<p>Usage of soft contact lens does not interfere with the modified cornea surface. PRK patients who wore soft lenses can wear them after the surgery also. Technically, the PRK patient can also wear rigid contact lenses, however, there is a challenge of fitment. At the same time, rigid contact lens cannot be used by some of the PRK patients and other refractive vision correction patient and it is dependent on the prescription of the patient.</p>\n<p>Usually, the PRK patients, who are interested to wear contact lens after this surgery, under-correction is sought by them and eventually, for the activities like sports and other harder activities, contact lens are needed. And the PRK patients, who are interested to undergo mono-vision refractive surgery, may need to wear contact lens occasionally, towards distance acuity improvement on the near eye, over near eye.  Usually, contact lens designed and made especially for such context and circumstances are preferred and recommended by the laser eye surgeons.</p>\n<p><strong>Wearing Lens After PRK</strong></p>\n<p>Certain studies report that wearing lenses after PRK surgery procedure improve visual acuity to better levels, however, the same may be associated with the decentralization and instability of lens from mild to moderate levels. However, when soft lenses are fit, lens stability and centration are improved while satisfying better visual acuity requirement. There are different kinds of lens, which affect the visual acuity and fitting in different levels.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The objective of undergoing refractive error corrective laser eye surgery, such as PRK, LASIK, LASEK etc., is to reduce or eliminate dependency on the contact lens or eye glasses. However, though in minority cases, wearing contact lens attain better still visual acuity, improving quality of life. Cornea Surface After PRK Technically, the answer is yes. [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-wear-contacts-if-you-have-had-lasik-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can you wear contacts if you had lasik eye surgery?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-you-wear-contacts-if-you-have-had-lasik-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Refractive laser eye surgery, LASIK corrects the refractive error of the eye and there are cases, where eye glasses or contact lenses may be needed after the surgery, based on certain conditions.</p>\n<p><strong>Need For Contacts After LASIK</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Usually, after Lasik or other refractive error correction surgery, if the results are unacceptable, hybrid contact lens or custom gas permeable are preferred to improve the eye vision. These options are preferred, when the enhancement procedures or follow-up surgical procedures are not possible.</li>\n<li>Another possibility can be a LASIK patient has had vision corrected fully, but one experience presbyopia, in one’s older age. Such patients may need contact lens on one eye for mono-vision and prefer lenses rather than depending over glasses for reading.</li>\n<li>One more opted LASIK patients are the ones, who are interested to wear color contact lenses towards their eye color enhancement or have perfect vision, either on specific occasions or on regular or daily basis.</li>\n<li>Another important cause to go for lenses can be presbyopia, which attacks you in your older age.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In all these cases LASIK patients can wear contact lenses safely. If you would like to wear the contact lenses for both the eyes, after LASIK, in most of the cases, hybrid contact lenses or gas permeable contact lenses can provide sharper vision, rather than going for the soft contact lenses.</p>\n<p><strong>Challenges in Wearing Lens After LASIK </strong></p>\n<p>The basic challenge in wearing contact lenses after LASIK is in fitting the lenses. It is because the front eye curvature surface is altered slightly, after LASIK. Hence, it is important to contact an eye doctor with specialization in contact lenses fitting for the cases of hard to fit eyes.</p>\n<p>According to the LASIK surgeons, you need to wait for at least two to three months post the surgery, before going for contacts. It is always good to communicate the wish of wearing contact lens, if you have the desire, with the eye surgeon for some specific guidelines and recommendations, according to prescription.</p>\n<p><strong>Better Options</strong></p>\n<p>In case your LASIK outcomes have not reached to the expected or satisfactory levels, unlike in majority cases, and if the vision is blurry slightly, because of possible mild retained retfractive error, the best solution can be wearing eyeglasses and for only part time, rather than going for the contact lenses.</p>\n<p>If you prefer contact lenses, then get going with the lenses having anti-reflective coating, for distracted reflections elimination to prevent any night vision problems and glare. You can also go for photochromic lenses, which can darken the lenses, when you are under sunlight, automatically. In cases of presbyopia attacked usually after 40s, eyeglasses with progressive lens can be the better option, even you need to wear them only part time.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Refractive laser eye surgery, LASIK corrects the refractive error of the eye and there are cases, where eye glasses or contact lenses may be needed after the surgery, based on certain conditions. Need For Contacts After LASIK Usually, after Lasik or other refractive error correction surgery, if the results are unacceptable, hybrid contact lens or [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-after-prk-does-vision-clear-3","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How long after PRK does vision clear?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-long-after-prk-does-vision-clear-3","contentHtml":"<p>PRK stands as the best alternative to LASIK surgery, especially when the thickness of the cornea is not at sufficient amount. Another incline to go for PRK is that it is recommended and considered as a recommended procedure for the certain professionals from certain industries, to undergo. Both the refractive eye surgeries have good outcomes with very higher success rates and the only different is the recovery period for PRK is more, comparative to LASIK.</p>\n<p><strong>Complete Recovery Period</strong></p>\n<p>The complete recovery period is usually, not the same for all the patients as it depends on various factors. Though complete recovery takes a few months duration, recovery of vision is achieved in different phases. After each of the recovery phase, you can gradually resume to more and more regular day to day activities.</p>\n<p><strong>Phases of Recovery After PRK Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>Right After Surgery – The vision becomes blurry, right after the vision and so it is important that someone accompany you for the surgery to the medical centre and take you back home after completing the surgery. After arriving home, since the vision is not clear enough to do the regular, you should plan to take a nap on the day of the surgery. Do not spend your time watching television or reading books or playing game in your smartphone. Apply the medicated drops, as they can allow you to relax and relieve from any discomfort or pain that is natural after any surgery. The eye gets covered with contact lens bandage.</p>\n<p>After Day 1 – After 24 hours of the PRK surgery, some blurry vision continues, though self caring activities can be resumed to a better extent. The bandage is retained and the activities are to be continued, with the bandage itself.</p>\n<p>After a Week – This is the time bandage contact lens is removed, by your surgeon. After removal of it, a great improvement is experienced for the vision and this improvement is felt according to the prescription or refractive error the patient had before the surgery. Correction may range from 20/30 to 20/50, usually and so the vision is continued to improve in the following weeks. In a couple of weeks, you would achieve much improved visual acuity.</p>\n<p>After a Month – The vision continues to improve during this period and by this time, you may resume most of the personal activities you perform day to day. After first month, corneal tissue is almost healed and eventually, the vision becomes clearer. Most of the daily activities can be resumed by this time. Though, eyes are felt dry, visual distortions and sensitivity to light get reduced.</p>\n<p>After 3 Months – The vision gets completely improved by this time and it reaches to 20/40 or even better. In between 3 months to 6 months, the vision reaches to 20/40, for most of the PRK patients.</p>\n<p>So, after six months period, the PRK patient feels complete healing and vision is much improved and harder activities can be resumed totally. However, during these phases of recovery, resuming activities must be done after consulting of one’s eye surgeon, such as going for swimming, playing sports, high contact activities etc. Only your surgeon can tell you the best time to resume these activities, as your unique eye condition is known by that doctor only.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>PRK stands as the best alternative to LASIK surgery, especially when the thickness of the cornea is not at sufficient amount. Another incline to go for PRK is that it is recommended and considered as a recommended procedure for the certain professionals from certain industries, to undergo. Both the refractive eye surgeries have good outcomes [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-your-eyesight-get-worse-after-laser-eye-surgery-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can your eyesight get worse after laser eye surgery?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-your-eyesight-get-worse-after-laser-eye-surgery-2","contentHtml":"<p>Once the laser eye surgery is completed successfully, the changes made over the cornea become completely stable and permanent. The new vision will be quickly adapted by the eyes. This improved vision continues for very long period and after you get older, this vision may get influenced because of the aging process.</p>\n<p><strong>Eyesight After Laser Eye Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>Technically, yes, it is possible that the eye sight may become worsen, either after shorter period of time or longer period of time, post the surgery. It is purely because of the aging process of the human body, not at all because of the laser eye surgery. In case the laser eye surgery is not successful, improper vision may result, but is immediate, rather than after a couple of months or years. Though smaller vision problems occur, immediately after the surgery, these discomforts are quite temporary and never last long, unless in cases of intense complications or infections. So, it is worth noting by you that the worsening of the eye sight is not at all because of the laser surgery, but because of the aging process.</p>\n<p><strong>Aging Process and Vision Problems</strong></p>\n<p>Aging process is continuous and it starts right after the birth. However, the degradation of the function of each of the body parts start usually after 40s. Eventually, hard parts become softer and soft parts become harder with aging. The same happens with the eyes and the changes in the eye and eyesight and this condition is called Presbyopia, which starts at 40s and continue for the rest of the life.</p>\n<p><strong>Eyesight Assurance After Laser Eye Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>No eye doctor or no laser medical centre assures you of removing the need for the glasses for life long, not because of the unsuccessful predicted outcomes, but because of the natural changes of the eye which may need eye glasses in the future, even after getting older.</p>\n<p>Most of the laser medical centres give assurance that the laser eye surgery can be successful and the outcomes can reduce or remove dependency over the eye glasses or contact lens. They assure for better eye vision, because of the trust they have on the advanced laser technology. In case the outcomes are not at the optimum level, they can easily make further corrections through enhancement procedure.</p>\n<p>So, technically, there are pure chances that the patient can get rid of hassle-some eye glasses or contact lens after the laser eye surgery or may need them after a period of time, after you grow older, as the eyesight may get worse with your age.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Once the laser eye surgery is completed successfully, the changes made over the cornea become completely stable and permanent. The new vision will be quickly adapted by the eyes. This improved vision continues for very long period and after you get older, this vision may get influenced because of the aging process. Eyesight After Laser [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"do-you-still-need-reading-glasses-after-lasik-surgery","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Do you still need reading glasses after lasik surgery?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/do-you-still-need-reading-glasses-after-lasik-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>The objective of the LASIK eye surgery is to correct the refractive errors and distance vision. So, it can reduce or remove the need for the glasses, when the glasses are prescribed because of the refractive vision and distance vision problems. On the other hand, eye glasses may also be needed towards correction of other eye vision related problems and in such cases LASIK surgery cannot influence the problems associated with the same.</p>\n<p><strong>Need for Reading Glasses After LASIK </strong></p>\n<p>The chances are 50 and 50. There may be a need for the reading glasses after LASIK surgery, in the following circumstances or conditions.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>LASIK laser eye surgery has not been successful and the outcomes are not up to the expected levels.</li>\n<li>You might have undergone the wrong laser eye procedure, unmatched to the prescription, because of the wrongly recommended procedure after pre-LASIK assessment.</li>\n<li>Inappropriate post operation care or medication not followed after the LASIK surgery.</li>\n<li>Condition of Presbyopia, which attacks almost every human being after 40s and eyesight gets worsen.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Here the discussion is about the reading glasses, which need to wear only during the activity of reading and the rest of all kinds of activities can be performed normally, without need for glasses.</p>\n<p><strong>What is Presbyopia?</strong></p>\n<p>As a human grows older, the ciliary muscles of the eye become loose and its property of elasticity gets deteriorated. Eventually, the natural ability of focus gets deteriorated and the focus gets limited to the objects closer only. This is the Presbyopia condition. Almost every human gets attacked by Presbyopia, unless special care is taken for eyes.</p>\n<p>So, no matter you have undergone LASIK eye surgery or not, it is quite possible that you need reading glasses after your 40s or at least 50s. Basic LASIK works on correction of refractive errors, rather than on focusing capability of the eyes and hence it has no control over the development of Presbyopia condition. However, the technology has brought a viable solution, again with the same laser eye surgery procedure, LASIK.</p>\n<p><strong>Modern LASIK for Presbyopia</strong></p>\n<p>A great news for older people, after they get attacked by Presbyopia is that they can get this problem treated with the modern LASIK treatment. The new technique developed in this context is called monovision.</p>\n<p><strong>How Modern LASIK Works?</strong></p>\n<p>The logic is simple, but has potential benefits and render solution to the Presbyopia condition. In the monovision procedure, the surgeon corrects the refractive errors completely in one eye and leaves the other eye intentionally to stay as nearsighted. Eventually, the eye, which is fully corrected can view the objects in distant places clearly and the other eye, which is nearsighted can provide clear vision for the objects nearby. So, the need for the reading glasses can be eliminated completely.</p>\n<p><strong>Other Presbyopia Procedures </strong></p>\n<p>There are also some other procedures developed to treat the Presbyopia condition. One of such surgeries is corneal inlay surgery, performed as Presbyopia correction surgery. And one more surgery is multifocal LASIK surgery.</p>\n<p>Hence, after basic LASIK surgery, there may or may not be a need for the reading glasses. In case Presbyopia happens to attack and cannot read without reading glasses, this condition can still be corrected with the modern LASIK procedures.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The objective of the LASIK eye surgery is to correct the refractive errors and distance vision. So, it can reduce or remove the need for the glasses, when the glasses are prescribed because of the refractive vision and distance vision problems. On the other hand, eye glasses may also be needed towards correction of other [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-are-the-side-effects-of-lasik","date":"2019-09-15","title":"What are the side effects of lasik?","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/what-are-the-side-effects-of-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik is highly successful laser eye surgery, with very higher percentage of success. However, just like any other surgery, it also undergoes operation at certain site over the human body. Eventually, side effects, complications and risks are quite common, though are very less, compared to the regular surgeries. And LASIK eye surgery leaves much reduced side effects or complications, when operated with bladeless technology, compared to the surgery with blade.</p>\n<p><strong>Basic LASIK Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>During the eye surgery of LASIK, a flap is created in the cornea. Cornea is a dome-shaped transparent surface over the eye and it accounts for larger part of the refracting or bending power of eye. Reshaping is performed with a laser towards correction of the problems associated with the refraction in the eye.</p>\n<p><strong>Side Effects After LASIK</strong></p>\n<p>Though, the side effects are much reduced because of usage of laser rather than sharp blade during the procedure, after the procedure. the possible side effects and risks are the following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Dry Eyes</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The basic procedure of LASIK causes reduction in the production of tears, temporarily. This unusual dryness condition is continued at least for six months post the surgery. It may reduce quality of vision and to prevent this problem, medical eye drops are recommended by your surgeon. In case the patient has dry eye problem, even before the surgery, usually, other procedures are preferred, which includes special plugs to use in the tear ducts that helps the tears to prevent from draining away from the eye surface.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Halos, Glare and Double Vision</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>After the surgery is finished, there may be difficult to see during the nights. Quite often, you may notice double vision or halos, glare around brighter lights. This condition may continue for a few weeks. Your vision may deteriorate in dim light, like in fog or dusk, post the surgery than prior to before the surgery, though good visual results are measured and found under standard conditions of testing.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Flap Problems</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>During the surgery, either removing or folding back the flap from the front part of the eye may cause certain complications technically and risks may include excess tears and infection. Epithelium or outermost tissue layer of cornea may grow underneath the flap, abnormally, during the process of healing.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Overcorrections</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Laser is supposed to remove the tissue from the eye and it is possible that the same is removed with an excess amount. Technically, complications and risks become more prominent with overcorrections compared to the undercorrections.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Undercorrections</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Laser removes lesser amount of tissue than needed according to the prescription, in cases of undercorrections. Eventually, the vision results are not clearer as expected and this risk is more for the nearsighted patients. The solution can be removing more tissue in further LASIK procedure and should be performed in just one year.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Astigmatism </strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>When the tissue is removed unevenly or not according to the requirements, additional surgery may be required. Alternatively, contact lens or glasses may be required.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Changes or Loss of Vision</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Though it is rare change of vision or even loss of vision is possible, technically, because of complications during the surgery. When the surgery is not successful, vision may not be clearer or sharper as expected.</p>\n<p>All these complications and risks are quite possible technically. However, when the right procedure is selected and performed successfully, following apt post surgery care all these can be minimized or nullified.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik is highly successful laser eye surgery, with very higher percentage of success. However, just like any other surgery, it also undergoes operation at certain site over the human body. Eventually, side effects, complications and risks are quite common, though are very less, compared to the regular surgeries. And LASIK eye surgery leaves much reduced [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"does-lasik-last-forever-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Does lasik last forever?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/does-lasik-last-forever-2","contentHtml":"<p>An immediate next question arises in the minds of the potential LASIK patients, usually, after deciding to go for the LASIK eye surgery, is whether the results of LASIK is forever or not. For your information, the results of LASIK eye surgery last forever for the problems related to vision, such as astigmatism, farsightedness and nearsightedness.</p>\n<p><strong>LASIK Procedure and Results</strong></p>\n<p>LASIK procedure is performed with the cornea, by reshaping it according to the requirement, with respect to the prescription. The changes made on the cornea are permanent and eventually, the results of LASIK are also permanent.</p>\n<p><strong>After LASIK</strong></p>\n<p>Once the LASIK surgery is completed, the result is either completely successful and the expected outcome is achieved or the surgery is not completely successful and expected results are not achieved. If the surgery outcomes meet the expectation levels, there is nothing to worry. On the other hand, if the outcomes are not to the expected levels, there is a further procedure, called enhancement procedure, recommended by the surgery. The enhancement procedure is intended to correct the undercorrections resulted from the LASIK procedure.</p>\n<p>In both these conditions, the refractive error of the eyes would be corrected by the LASIK and or enhancement procedure and eventually, LASIK enable the patient to achieve the expected results and these results are permanent.</p>\n<p><strong>Vision Problems In Future Irrespective of Eye Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>Right after LASIK, the outcome is good, if the surgery is successful and appropriate post surgery care is taken. After a long period of time, there may be chances that the vision may deteriorate. The primary cause for these vision problems is not in fact LASIK surgery, but the age itself. Like other parts of the body, the eyes also keep changing over the time. The most probable cause for deterioration of vision is Presbyopia, which means ‘aging of eyes’ in Greek.</p>\n<p><strong>Causes For Presbyopia</strong></p>\n<p>The primary cause for Presbyopia, aging related vision problem is the problem associated with the lens. The focusing capability of these lenses gets deteriorated because they get hardened with the progressing age of the eye of the human. The result is the problem reading and other vision demanding tasks. Eventually, the demand for eye glasses or contact lens keep increasing after 40s, though one has born with perfect eye vision and never used eye glasses for the life before.</p>\n<p>In all other conditions, the refractive error related problems till then are resolved with successful LASIK surgery, unless new problems get developed.</p>\n<p>So, technically, the results and outcomes of the LASIK surgery are permanent and in case any future vision related problems are developed, these are caused from only because of the age or other sub-organs of the eye, but because of the failure or incomplete LASIK surgery.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>An immediate next question arises in the minds of the potential LASIK patients, usually, after deciding to go for the LASIK eye surgery, is whether the results of LASIK is forever or not. For your information, the results of LASIK eye surgery last forever for the problems related to vision, such as astigmatism, farsightedness and [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-age-is-recommended-for-laser-eye-surgery-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"What age is recommended for laser eye surgery?","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/what-age-is-recommended-for-laser-eye-surgery-2","contentHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery is one of the refractive error correction surgeries. LASIK or Laser-Assisted in Situ Keratomileusis surgery is a refractive eye surgery, which is very popular globally. The surgery is allowed to be performed for a wide range of patients with refractive errors and it stands cost-effective, efficient and safe.</p>\n<p><strong>Age Limit For Laser Eye Surgery.</strong></p>\n<p>The age limit has been expanding for the laser surgery, because of the advancement of the technology according to the FDA in the US, the age approved to undergo any laser eye surgery is minimum 18 years. However, some of the eye surgeons expect you to wait for at least two more years after 18 years, since the vision has to become stable, through stable refraction. Most often, the refraction error prescription does not change post the age of 18 years, however, every human eye condition is not the same and it demands some waiting period for the surgeon. And for any laser eye surgery, the technical requirement is that the prescription has to be stable before one year of the surgery. In such conditions, after 18 years, this technical condition is only evaluated and decision is taken to undergo the surgery, provided other technical requirements are met.</p>\n<p><strong>40 to 60 Years </strong></p>\n<p>While the lower limit is 18 years, the upper limit is 40 years. Patients, who want to get rid of the eye glasses after 40s are not eligible for the surgery, usually because, the cause for the eye glasses at that age group usually is Presbyopia or cataract. This condition called Presbyopia cannot be corrected with the regular LASIK surgery, though modern surgeries have become potential to control and provide solution for this condition. Hence, the treatment for Presbyopia is sought out in other dimensions and procedures, rather than going for the regular laser eye surgery procedures. Technically Presbyopia condition is treated through monovision LASIK. With the modern technology, the upper age limit to undergo the laser eye surgery keeps is stretching and even going to 60s for the refractive error correction or Presbyopia eye condtiions.</p>\n<p><strong>Above 60 Years</strong></p>\n<p>Diseases related to eye keep increasing after 60 and are developed from various causes. Usual causes are cataract, AMD (Age-Related Degeneration), glaucoma and many others. Though all these cannot be corrected with the regular laser eye surgeries, pre-surgery evaluation is done more carefully, for these senior citizens to find the matching procedure to obtain optimum outcomes.</p>\n<p>For other eye related problems, such as cataract, the laser eye surgery does not offer any treatment procedures. Hence, the patients, who have not been experiencing development of cataract stand eligible and good candidates for laser eye surgery.  However, 18 to 40 stands as the ideal age limit to undergo regular LASIK surgery.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery is one of the refractive error correction surgeries. LASIK or Laser-Assisted in Situ Keratomileusis surgery is a refractive eye surgery, which is very popular globally. The surgery is allowed to be performed for a wide range of patients with refractive errors and it stands cost-effective, efficient and safe. Age Limit For Laser [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-get-laser-eye-surgery-twice-3","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can you get laser eye surgery twice?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-you-get-laser-eye-surgery-twice-3","contentHtml":"<p>The success rate of laser eye surgery is more than 95% on an overall, considering most of these surgeries. In rest of the 5% cases, enhancement procedures can attempt further corrections. The enhancement surgery is not second laser surgery, since it is considered as a touch up procedure, to make necessary corrections, after basic LASIK surgery. However, though in very rare cases, there may be need to undergo laser eye surgery, second time. The answer for such query is yes, technically.</p>\n<p>However, getting laser eye surgery twice is not as simple as it sounds. Since each of the eye condition and patient’s case is unique, maximum care has to be taken to determine, whether second procedure is required, possible and safe or not.</p>\n<p><strong>Possibility For Second Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>There are various factors that demand second surgery. Each of the patients has to be judged exclusively, based on these factors and so expert opinion is needed in each of these cases. The key technical factor to consider here is the total amount of tissue required left in the eye and the amount removed previously, in the previous laser eye surgery.</p>\n<p>Theoretically, a detailed assessment is conducted by the surgeon, based on specific conditions, before recommending the procedure for second time. More detailed assessment is mandatory as there are certain risks associated, when the same laser surgery is conducted for the second time. Detailed assessment is mandatory here, because there are more vision related problems experienced by any human being as he or she grows older. The root cause for the new vision problem after the laser eye surgery may not be only from refractive error, but also from Presbyopia, cataract, glaucoma and many more sources. In such instances, the same procedure is not recommended by the surgeons. The root cause has to be found and the appropriate procedure is recommended. In results of these pre-assessments usually, rule out the need for the same laser eye surgery to undergo again.</p>\n<p>When Presbyopia is developed, treatment for this problem is different from the regular laser procedure, though modern procedures offer healing of this condition. And in cases of cataract, this condition cannot be treated through laser eye surgery and other treatment procedures have to be explored accordingly.</p>\n<p>Hence, lesser than 5% of the laser eye surgery patients do experience smaller to bigger problems related to vision and most of these can further be corrected through enhancement procedure and very minimal percentage of patients may have the other problems. And most of these vision problems in older age have different causes, other than refractive errors, which can be corrected through the laser eye surgeries.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The success rate of laser eye surgery is more than 95% on an overall, considering most of these surgeries. In rest of the 5% cases, enhancement procedures can attempt further corrections. The enhancement surgery is not second laser surgery, since it is considered as a touch up procedure, to make necessary corrections, after basic LASIK [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-go-blind-from-lasik-2","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Can you go blind from lasik?","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/can-you-go-blind-from-lasik-2","contentHtml":"<p>LASIK is widely performed throughout the world, because of the trust built on it, because of its success rate, which is more than 95%. Safety and effectiveness are the key factors for choosing this laser surgery procedure. So, it is unusual extremely for any of LASIK patient to result in blindness from LASIK surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Risks After LASIK</strong></p>\n<p>Since LASIK is a surgery procedure, complications are quite common, just like other surgery procedures. However, the number of risks and complications are less and less intensive compared to the other surgeries, since the procedure is performed by using laser.</p>\n<p>The most frequently occurred risks and complications can be glare, halos, dry eyes and other disturbances of vision. Though they occur frequently, these are purely temporary and last in just a few days or weeks. Going blind or vision loss is technically possible with severe complications, however, these are very uncommon.</p>\n<p><strong>Legal Blindness</strong></p>\n<p>According to the AFB (American Foundation for the Blind), legal blindness is considered when the vision becomes 20/200 or worse. The problem of vision, such as blur, dry eye is common, but is temporary and after recovery, it becomes completely normal and after recovery, vision gets much improved. The Food and Drug Administration from the US has reported that vision loss is possible, technically, after the LASIK surgery and these outcomes cannot be corrected, even after additional surgery, contact lenses or eye glasses. However, these severe and intense complications are very rare as LASIK has very high success rate and even small corrections can be done with an enhancement procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Possible Complications</strong></p>\n<p>The possible complication that may result in vision loss or blindness is basically is infection. Causes for this infection are many.</p>\n<p><strong>Preventing Complications</strong></p>\n<p>Severe complications, such as infections must be prevented on higher priority, at any point after the surgery. The following precautions can prevent or reduce the possibilities of these infections.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Quite important factor, even before undergoing the LASIK surgery is pre-LASIK assessment. Accurate prescription can only determine the suitable and appropriate procedure. Qualification and expertise of the surgeon proposing the suitable surgery play a key role in this context.</li>\n<li>Success of the LASIK surgery is the primary key factor that influence the overall outcome of the procedure. when appropriate procedure is selected and surgery is performed successfully, the success rate reaches more than 90%.</li>\n<li>Last, but most important factor is the post operative care. As long as enough care is taken all possible complications can be ruled out. In case of any accidental issues happen to the eyes, those should be addressed immediately, without delay, to the respective eye surgeon, so that further complications can be completely eliminated.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>So, don’t worry about going blindness, as so far no such conditions are reported by the medical authorities and no studies and reports have indicated such information.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>LASIK is widely performed throughout the world, because of the trust built on it, because of its success rate, which is more than 95%. Safety and effectiveness are the key factors for choosing this laser surgery procedure. So, it is unusual extremely for any of LASIK patient to result in blindness from LASIK surgery. Risks [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-there-an-age-limit-for-laser-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Is there any age limit for laser eye surgery?","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/is-there-an-age-limit-for-laser-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Yes, there is an age limit for laser eye surgery. Though the realistic and generalized age period to undergo the LASIK surgery is from 20 to 40 years, this criteria of age has been relaxed more today than before. Eventually, this age period has been expanding, as never before.</p>\n<p><strong>Age Range</strong></p>\n<p>The ideal range of age to undergo the LASIK surgery is from 20 to 40 and this upper limit has been increasing with the advancement of the technology. Though 18 years is the minimum age for LASIK recommended by the FDA, doctors usually wait until 20 years of age, since the eye prescription has to become stable.</p>\n<p><strong>Stretching Upper Age Limit</strong></p>\n<p>In fact, there is no upper limit for the LASIK laser eye surgery, as it can be performed for even aged people, only in the cases that the eyesight problem is caused exclusively because of the refraction error, but no other causes. Hence, the regular LASIK medical centres also attempt to perform the surgery, even for the people, who have more than 40 years of age.</p>\n<p>One more important factor that the LASIK surgery can be opted by the older patients, above 40 years of age also, is Presbyopia condition. Today’s technology allows the patients to get this eyesight problem treated, as it enables the surgeons to treat Presbyopia through monovision LASIK eye surgery.</p>\n<p>Eventually, the upper age limit is not just 40 years, but may extend to 50, 60, 70 years or even more.</p>\n<p><strong>Age Consideration For the Patient</strong></p>\n<p>Though the general age period is specified with certain limits, the upper age limit has been extended. It is worth mentioning here is that the eligibility of the LASIK surgery is not only age of the patient, but also many other factors. So, when the age is more than 40 years for a patient, it means, he or she has to undergo more specific and rigorous pre-LASIK assessment, compared to the other patients. More and in-depth analysis is mandatory to explore and discover the root cause for the respective and specific eyesight problem. Then only the laser eye surgeons determine, whether they are eligible for the LASIK eye surgery or not.</p>\n<p>Hence, the overall suitable age is in between 20 to 40 years. And patients, who are older than 40 years are also eligible, however, only after more and in-depth pre-LASIK determination.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Yes, there is an age limit for laser eye surgery. Though the realistic and generalized age period to undergo the LASIK surgery is from 20 to 40 years, this criteria of age has been relaxed more today than before. Eventually, this age period has been expanding, as never before. Age Range The ideal range of [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-lasik-surgery-painful-5","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Is lasik surgery painful?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/is-lasik-surgery-painful-5","contentHtml":"<p>When the sound of the word surgery hits the ear, it visualizes poking the body surface with the needles, splitting the blood. But don’t worry the truth with the LASIK surgery is very far from such usual surgery procedures. There are no needles involved in the LASIK surgery procedure.</p>\n<p>Most of the patients do worry about the possible pain and discomfort, since the site of surgery is over the eye surface, which is the most sensitive organ and surface of the human body. One important factor to remember is that the laser eye surgery does not involve any needles or sharp blades to perform the procedure. Hence, there is no question of poking into the eyes with the needles and no pain over the eyes. Just like other surgery procedure, the site of the surgery is numbed.</p>\n<p>Let us see how the procedure is run and the possibilities of pain before, during and after the LASIK surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Before the Surgery </strong></p>\n<p>There is no pain experienced by the patient before the surgery, during the first step, giving anaesthetic drops to numb the eye. The surgeon then clamps the eyelids of the patients to keep the eye open. You won’t experience any pain, though clipping the clamps may make a bit uncomfortable. In case you are very conscious and anxious about the pain, giving a mild sedative may be preferred by your surgeon.</p>\n<p><strong>During the Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>During the surgery procedure, the entire process is pain-free for the patient, as anaesthetic drops are applied to the eyes to ensure that the eyes are numb, completely. Some of the older LASIK patients have reported that they have felt a slight pressure, while the laser is kept focused on the eye. The total treatment time applying the laser beam is not more than 50 seconds and hence the overall feel of discomfort may last in lesser than a minute.</p>\n<p><strong>After the Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>There are mixed experiences felt and experienced by the old LASIK patients some of them felt a mild sensation of stinging and some of them experienced pain at moderate levels.</p>\n<p>The overall healing process is short with LASIK, comparative to the other procedures. So, the total post operative pain is very minimal and short lived. In addition to that the eye surgeon recommends the medication and medication drops to relieve the possible pain after the surgery. When the prescribed medicine and eye drops are followed with enough care, provided enough rest is given to the eyes for a day or two, you almost feel no pain after the surgery.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>When the sound of the word surgery hits the ear, it visualizes poking the body surface with the needles, splitting the blood. But don’t worry the truth with the LASIK surgery is very far from such usual surgery procedures. There are no needles involved in the LASIK surgery procedure. Most of the patients do worry [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-age-is-good-for-lasik","date":"2019-09-15","title":"What age is good for lasik?","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/what-age-is-good-for-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>Age is very important factor for any human being as it marks plenty of milestones, such as working, voting, retiring, driving and many more. However, there is no specific age restriction, especially upper age limit for the LASIK eye surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Generalized Age Limit</strong></p>\n<p>Generalized age limit to undergo the LASIK surgery is in between 20 years to 40 years and it is not hard border, but the eye surgeons are flexible enough to explore and discover the unique eye conditions of the people and consider other eligibility factors, before deciding and recommending the LASIK procedure to the patient. So, the age of the patient definitely influences the candidacy of LASIK, however, it does not draw an absolute boundary, by no means.</p>\n<p><strong>Lower Age Limit</strong></p>\n<p>Usually, 18 years is the specific lower age limit, however, most commonly surgeons wait for two more years to ensure that the eyesight has been reached to its stable state. On the other hand, there are also instances, where younger than 18 years also got eligible for the LASIK surgery, in very rare cases, like extreme nearsightedness.</p>\n<p><strong>Upper Age Limit</strong></p>\n<p>The upper age limit, though not restricted to it, is 40 years. The advancement of technology allows the patients to be eligible for the LASIK surgery, even after forties. It is because the candidacy for LASIK is just not limited to a single factor, age, but many other factors, such as the general health and eye health on an overall. The profession of the patient also stands as an important factor to influence the candidacy for the LASIK surgery.</p>\n<p>LASIK patients can be even after 40s. In such cases, the concern is not the age, but the actual source of the problems associated with the eyesight of the patients. As long as the source of the eyesight is the refractive error, there is quite more probability that the candidate is eligible for the surgery, but if it is other than the refractive error, the treatment proposed would be different.</p>\n<p>So, age stands as only one of the factors that influences the overall candidacy to undergo the LASIK surgery, but not the whole and sole deciding factor to determine the candidacy.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Age is very important factor for any human being as it marks plenty of milestones, such as working, voting, retiring, driving and many more. However, there is no specific age restriction, especially upper age limit for the LASIK eye surgery. Generalized Age Limit Generalized age limit to undergo the LASIK surgery is in between 20 [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-is-the-maximum-eye-power-for-lasik","date":"2019-09-15","title":"What is the maximum eye power for lasik?","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/what-is-the-maximum-eye-power-for-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>LASIK laser eye surgery can be performed on most of the eye patients suffering from refractive error, however, there are certain specific criteria, which need to be fulfilled to undergo. This will be determined by your eye doctor, during a comprehensive eye exam. Your eligibility for LASIK eye surgery is determined according to various factors and the maximum eye power for LASIK is one of the important and deciding factors.</p>\n<p><strong>Comprehensive Eye Exam</strong></p>\n<p>The eye doctor determines the refractive error of your eyes, by examining your astigmatism, nearsightedness or farsightedness, with which you have been suffering from. The eye glass prescription is noted down during this exam. The maximum power required for each of these refractive error problems is varied to undergo the LASIK surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Refractive Error</strong></p>\n<p>Refractive errors are caused from the cornea or lenses misshape. The result is the problems of vision and the severity of the problem is measured in dioptres (D). Positive number, here indicates hyperopia or farsightedness and negative number indicates myopia or nearsightedness. When the objects at both near and farer are seen blurred, the condition is considered as astigmatism.</p>\n<p><strong>Refractive Error Limits for LASIK Surgery </strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Nearsightedness refractive error prescription should not be more than -11.00 D</li>\n<li>Farsightedness prescription should not cross +5.00 D</li>\n<li>Astigmatism should not cross 5.00</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The above technical specifications are specific to the LASIK surgery, when performed by using excimer lasers. When astigmatism problem is combined with myopia or hyperopia problems, the range of power is varied. In the same way, when astigmatism is occurred with mixed conditions then also it is considered as a special condition by the eye surgeons. These limits are maximum limits. The more the refractive error, the more there will be the risk after the surgery. Additional care is required by both the surgeon during the surgery and by the patient after the surgery, if the prescription falls in last 20% of the upper limits. This maximum power limit for the refractive error should not be crossed to undergo the LASIK eye surgery. In case the surgery is performed for the ineligible patients, the results and outcomes can be risky with the symptoms of halos and glare, more intense during night.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>LASIK laser eye surgery can be performed on most of the eye patients suffering from refractive error, however, there are certain specific criteria, which need to be fulfilled to undergo. This will be determined by your eye doctor, during a comprehensive eye exam. Your eligibility for LASIK eye surgery is determined according to various factors [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-lasik-safe-long-term-5","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Is lasik safe long term?","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/is-lasik-safe-long-term-5","contentHtml":"<p>Yes, LASIK is safe in long term and it depends on the total success of the surgery. The overall success of the surgery is influenced by multiple factors. When all these factors are satisfied, it is quite easy to commit for promising and long lasting results by the LASIK medical centres.</p>\n<p><strong>Safety and Success Rate</strong></p>\n<p>Safety is an important factor for any surgery and so for LASIK surgery also. LASIK has been approved and proved in the medical industry with the success rate of more than 95% and it is a clear indication that complications are almost nil. The rest of the 5% of LASIK patients may undergo certain risks and complications and the degree of complications vary according to various factors. The surgery is approved by the FDA, since it has acceptable success rate and minimal rate of complications, all because of the usage of the laser eye beams, instead of microkeratome or blade.</p>\n<p><strong>Alternatives For Better and Long Term Safety</strong></p>\n<p>The success rate of the LASIK surgery is more than 95% and so the below 5% of LASIK patients still have an opportunity to improve the success rate. In case the outcome of the surgery is not up to the expected levels, there is still an opportunity to obtain expected outcomes, through a procedure, followed by the LASIK surgery, called enhancement procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>LASIK Life</strong></p>\n<p>The life of LASIK is very long, in fact, lifelong. LASIK surgery gives long lasting results. However, the problems associated with the vision cannot be terminated completely with the LASIK surgery. It is because the sources of vision problems are multiple and refractive error is one of them and LASIK can resolve only this problem. Other sources, such as natural eye lens, cataract, Presbopia may also cause the problems with the vision. So, the root causes that can be resolved with the LASIK cannot be possibly recurred, however, other vision problems cannot be controlled or influenced by the LASIK surgery.</p>\n<p>On an overall, LASIK is approved to be effective and safe and the patients can enjoy the benefit of improved vision.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Yes, LASIK is safe in long term and it depends on the total success of the surgery. The overall success of the surgery is influenced by multiple factors. When all these factors are satisfied, it is quite easy to commit for promising and long lasting results by the LASIK medical centres. Safety and Success Rate [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-does-it-take-to-recover-from-laser-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How long does it take to recover from laser eye surgery?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-long-does-it-take-to-recover-from-laser-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>The recovery time varies from one laser eye surgery to another eye surgery. In fact, among all the laser eye surgeries, LASIK is the most common and familiar to the people. Other laser eye surgery procedures are PRK, LASEK, SMILE and others.</p>\n<p><strong>Recovery Period After LASIK</strong></p>\n<p>Significant improvements are found in just a day or two after the LASIK surgery, by the patients. On an overall, it takes 2 days to 7 days for basic recovery and get back to the regular day to day activities. The total recovery period is dependent on various factors, such as the expertise of the eye surgeon, refractive surgery procedure performed and the intensity of problem or refractive error. Complete recovery takes on an overall takes 6 months duration after the LASIK surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Short Term Recovery</strong></p>\n<p>Immediately after LASIK surgery, your vision becomes blurred and one needs to be relaxed. So, you should not drive, right after the surgery and you need somebody to accompany to the LASIK medical centre to drive the car and take you home. Strict instructions are given by your doctor and the same must be followed for the first few hours after the surgery.</p>\n<p>Some eye pain and irritation are possible during the short recovery period. It may make you feel to have a small piece of sand in the eyes. Wearing a eye shield or patch may be necessary, as instructed by your doctor, to prevent rubbing the eyes. Wearing it is important, especially during the nights to prevent rubbing the eyes accidentally, while sleeping. For the first few days, the eyes will be blurry and may become very sensitive to the light.</p>\n<p>Depending on the kind of LASIK procedure performed, subconjunctival haemorrhage is possible because of the usage of the suction device placed over the eye, while the procedure is performed. This condition is possible to continue for a few weeks and usually fade away in a few days.</p>\n<p>Check-up appointment is scheduled usually within  a day or two after the surgery. The vision is tested by examining the eyes by your doctor. Medicated eye drops are prescribed to prevent inflammation and infection. Wearing contact lenses is not suggested during this period, though the vision is blurry.</p>\n<p><strong>Long-Term Recovery</strong></p>\n<p>For LASIK surgery, the complete healing time is usually around 6 months. Vision fluctuations are possible to experience during this long recovery period. Several follow-ups are scheduled to check and monitor the progress and recovery. Most of the patients can recover decent vision in four weeks.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The recovery time varies from one laser eye surgery to another eye surgery. In fact, among all the laser eye surgeries, LASIK is the most common and familiar to the people. Other laser eye surgery procedures are PRK, LASEK, SMILE and others. Recovery Period After LASIK Significant improvements are found in just a day or [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-expensive-is-laser-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-15","title":"How expensive is laser eye surgery?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/how-expensive-is-laser-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Cost of the laser eye surgery varies as the overall cost is dependent on various factors. However, the average cost of the laser surgery can be predictable in each of the geographical area. Laser eye surgery is of various types and each of them is made available to the patients with varied costs.</p>\n<p><strong>LASIK Surgery Cost</strong></p>\n<p>By 2017, the cost of the LASIK laser eye surgery is about $2100. And the cost of this surgery varies from one geographical area to another and many important factors.</p>\n<p><strong>Factors Influencing Overall Cost of Surgery</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The laser medical centre you have approached is the first factor. The world class medical centres obviously charge more for each and every service they provide with higher price tags.</li>\n<li>Skill and expertise of the eye surgeon also an important factor and the cost of the surgery would be more with more expertise and skill of the surgeon.</li>\n<li>And most important factor is the technology with which the procedure is performed. The more the advanced and recent technology, the more the cost of the surgery.</li>\n<li>Prescription or refractive error of the eye stands as the primary factor. The more the refractive error, the more and intense procedure needed and so cost of the surgery is increased accordingly.</li>\n<li>Services included in the laser eye surgery treatment influence the overall cost. Some medical centres offer the laser eye surgery, while including all the services and some others charge only for the surgery exclusively. Each of the service is charged separately.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Realistic Cost of Laser Eye Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>The cost of the laser eye surgery is usually fixed and bargaining the cost is not a good idea. Instead, the laser eye surgery patient should inquire all the details and breakdown of the surgery costs. Though the overall cost of the surgery is more, it should include all the services, right from the beginning of the surgery till the patient is relieved. If the surgery is offered for very low cost, one should double check whether all the services associated with the laser surgery procedure or not.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Cost of the laser eye surgery varies as the overall cost is dependent on various factors. However, the average cost of the laser surgery can be predictable in each of the geographical area. Laser eye surgery is of various types and each of them is made available to the patients with varied costs. LASIK Surgery [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-lasik-surgery-permanent","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Is lasik surgery permanent?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/is-lasik-surgery-permanent","contentHtml":"<p>LASIK laser eye surgery improves vision and the improved vision outcomes are permanent in most of the cases, as it has very high success rate. That is why LASIK surgery is preferred by most of the patients, who suffer from refractive error problems, like nearsightedness, farsightedness and astigmatism.</p>\n<p><strong>Life of LASIK</strong></p>\n<p>To determine the lifetime of the benefits of LASIK, visual acuity is measured by the researchers, right after the surgery procedure. In some cases, additional acuity measurements are also considered as the time passes. The values measured right after the surgery are retained and compared with the visual acuity values taken after years of the procedure. If these values do not match, the benefits and results of the surgery are considered to be fading out.</p>\n<p>When LASIK surgery was totally unfamiliar to the people, many studies were taken place, like the above, in all over the country. After numerous researches and studies and the respective reports, LASIK is started considering as a standard laser eye surgery to correct refractive error permanently. The modern studies show how well the outcomes are achieved.</p>\n<p><strong>Research Studies and Reports</strong></p>\n<p>The Middle East African Journal of Ophthalmology had researched the life of LASIK results and it followed the LASIK patients for 10 years. The studies have reported that 98.5% of the LASIK patients have continued to be satisfied with surgery results after 10 years. This research had not measured visual acuity of these patients, but distributed questionnaire and collected the patients’ opinions in the aspects of LASIK results and quality of life.</p>\n<p><strong>Probable Vision Problems Long After LASIK</strong></p>\n<p>LASIK can resolve the problems associated with the refractive errors, however, vision problems can be stemmed from many other sources also, which cannot be controlled by LASIK laser surgery. So, the following can be the other sources of vision problems for human eye.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Changes With Age</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Presbyopia is possible at the older age, especially after 40 years. The cause of this problem is hardening of the eye’s lens, which are controlled through weakened muscles. Eventually, the closer objects may seem indistinct and blurry. That is the reason, why many older people can read only through the reading glasses.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Change of Prescription</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Change of the prescription of the eye is possible in minor cases of LASIK surgery, where the outcomes are not to the expected levels. Another cause of change of the prescription can be growing eye health issue, which is not considered as the failure of LASIK.</p>\n<p>So, after LASIK surgery, the results are permanent for more than 95% of cases and the rest of the percentile of patients still can undergo enhancement procedure to achieve the expected outcomes. Definitely, the results are long lasting and permanent almost.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>LASIK laser eye surgery improves vision and the improved vision outcomes are permanent in most of the cases, as it has very high success rate. That is why LASIK surgery is preferred by most of the patients, who suffer from refractive error problems, like nearsightedness, farsightedness and astigmatism. Life of LASIK To determine the lifetime [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-is-the-success-rate-of-laser-eye-surgery-4","date":"2019-09-15","title":"What is the success rate of laser eye surgery?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/what-is-the-success-rate-of-laser-eye-surgery-4","contentHtml":"<p>The success rate of LASIK laser eye surgery is influenced by various factors and it varies from one geographical area to another one. In fact the success rate also varies from one medical centre to another medical centre, in the same geographical area.</p>\n<p><strong>Approval and Success</strong></p>\n<p>LASIK laser eye surgery has been approved by the Food and Drug Administration, in the US, in the year 1999. There were 1.4 million LASIK surgeries performed in the year 2000 and each year 700,000 surgeries are performed. LASIK stands today as one of the most familiar, popular elective surgeries in various countries in the world and the rate of satisfaction is high remarkably.</p>\n<p><strong>Success Rate of Vision</strong></p>\n<p>LASIK has grabbed exceptionally high success rate, especially, when the patient goes for an elective surgery. Here, success is defined as a combination of patient satisfaction and quality of vision. According to the Journal of Cataract and Refractive Surgery, LASIK gains more than 96% of success rate and satisfaction by the patients.</p>\n<p>According to the medical eye surgery experts, about 96% to 98% of LASIK patients end up with the vision of 20/20 and 40 to 50% of the patients achieved better than 20/20 vision.</p>\n<p><strong>Compliments For Success</strong></p>\n<p>Many experts consider LASIK surgery as the best solution to correct refractive errors. Some of the experts consider this surgery as the ‘second-best 24 hour medical miracle’.</p>\n<p><strong>Factors Of Higher Success Rates</strong></p>\n<p>The rate of success is directly proportional and well influenced by various factors, both internal and external. Each and every factor can make or break the success of the LASIK surgery. So, every factor is equally important and equally useful.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Prescription of refractive error of the patient is an internal and most important factor of all. The kind of prescription and intensity of the vision problem is the key to choose the appropriate procedure, with which only the vision problem can be resolved.</li>\n<li>Another internal factor is the condition of the eye and general health of the patient. It is another key factor that determines, in fact the limits the choices from the available procedure.</li>\n<li>One important external factor is the LASIK medical centre, which offers you expertise of the better or best eye surgeon, while enabling the standard protocols during the procedure.</li>\n<li>Another significant external factor is the technology with which the LASIK surgery procedure is performed. The more the advanced technology, the more the success rate.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>So, most of the factors are in the hands of the patients. Though internal factors, like the eye refractive error and eye health are not in the hands of the patients, going to a standard and accountable medical LASIK centre can increase the success rate of the LASIK eye surgery.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The success rate of LASIK laser eye surgery is influenced by various factors and it varies from one geographical area to another one. In fact the success rate also varies from one medical centre to another medical centre, in the same geographical area. Approval and Success LASIK laser eye surgery has been approved by the [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-insurance-covers-lasik","date":"2019-09-15","title":"What insurance covers lasik?","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/what-insurance-covers-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>Almost all the health plan holders concern about the LASIK surgery, whether it comes under insurance coverage or not, so that they can grab the benefits of this surgery, without spending much budget over it. Let us see, how insurance can help them out to enjoy the results of the LASIK, while spending less.</p>\n<p><strong>Insurance For LASIK</strong></p>\n<p>There is good news for health insure seekers, as there are certain policies fulfilling the wish of covering LASIK, though partially. So far it is not considered as a medically necessity, covering the entire cost of the LASIK is still very rare. Health insurance providers often come up with their point of long that the contacts and glasses are adequate to attain fair to good eye vision.</p>\n<p><strong>How Insurance Can Cover LASIK?</strong></p>\n<p>In the context of LASIK, vision insurance can be of a bit help. But, the benefits of vision insurance are different slightly compared to the health or medical insurance. Plans for vision insurance are usually designed and planned to reduce the cost associated with the preventive eye care for the patients. At the same time, most of the benefits associated with the examination of eye and prescription of eye wear, additional savings are offered by certain plans.</p>\n<p>Certain vision insurance carriers offer certain benefits for specific laser vision correction surgery procedures, which include the following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Discounts associated with the procedures of laser vision correction and it includes LASIK, which is one of the laser vision corrections.</li>\n<li>For the procedures, which are performed by the in-network surgeons, are offered with 50% discount.</li>\n<li>Frame benefits for post vision correction surgery non-prescription sunglasses.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Exploring and understanding the way the LASIK is covered with the insurance can ease and make a difference for the potential LASIK seeking patients. Some of the cost is supposed to be paid for the procedure, apart regardless of the plan of insurance. LASIK can be paid in many ways and so for the LASIK laser eye surgery too.</p>\n<p>So, at this point of time, the patient cannot expect full pay coverage for LASIK eye surgery. At the same time, insurance companies still want to increase their customer base and eventually, keep offering at least part of the full LASIK charges. May be in the near future, all LASIK patients will keep getting the full health insurance coverage after the surgery. After all, patients with health insurance wish to get full coverage and health insurance providers like to accumulate customer base to become huge, and the only way is to fulfil the wishes of the customers.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Almost all the health plan holders concern about the LASIK surgery, whether it comes under insurance coverage or not, so that they can grab the benefits of this surgery, without spending much budget over it. Let us see, how insurance can help them out to enjoy the results of the LASIK, while spending less. Insurance [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"are-you-awake-during-lasik-7","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Are you awake during lasik?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/are-you-awake-during-lasik-7","contentHtml":"<p>LASIK laser eye surgery needs only 10 to 15 minutes to complete. No general anesthesia is given during the surgery and yes, the patient has to be awake, while the procedure is being performed. Many patients are squeamish regarding keeping the eyes open, while laser is pointed and being focused direct to the eye. Some of them go a bit further and worry about the risk of moving the eye or head accidentally and danger of damaging the eye. All these thoughts eventually increase anxiety levels of the patients. But don’t worry, there is no damage possible to your eye and the surgeons are aware of the responses of the patients and adequate care is taken during the procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Why No General Anaesthesia?</strong></p>\n<p>General anaesthesia is not preferred by the eye surgeons, because of various reasons. The primary reason is that the patient needs to be awake and keep the eye open so that the laser beam can be focussed. And secondary reason is that there is no pain or harm to the eye, when the laser beam is focused and hence, there is no need for the patient to fall asleep. Moreover, there are certain ill-affects to the body, when general anaesthesia is given to the body, unnecessarily, when not needed. It affects the body parts like lungs, heart, brain with the same drugs. It increases the cost of the surgery, as anaesthesia specialist need additionally to be present during the procedure. General anaesthesia also may result in confusion, nausea and agitation after awakening from sleep.</p>\n<p><strong>Any Sedatives?</strong></p>\n<p>Yes, there are certain sedatives, like Valium is given to the patient so that the patient stays calm and relaxed. These sedatives make the eye to be numbed and it allows no pain to be felt by the patient, even laser beams are focused sharply over the eye. Most of the patients express their opinion of feeling relaxed with no pain, by awaking during the surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>What About Moving Accidentally?</strong></p>\n<p>The threat of moving the head accidentally is another reason, why most of the patients get scared to be awake during the procedure. The laser used does not make the eyes dry or painful, as the eyes are kept hydrated consistently. So, the threat of moving the eyes is automatically ruled out. And additional good news is that modern devices used for LASIK has been equipped with the feature of safety shutoff. In case the eyes or head is moved accidentally, the machine gets shut off automatically, leaving the procedure unaffected or disturbed because of the movement. The device reacts well before the surgeon reacts and the necessary action is taken instantly.</p>\n<p>So, never worry about being awake or even accidental movement of the eyes or head, while the procedure is performed. Your eyes are operated with enough safety.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>LASIK laser eye surgery needs only 10 to 15 minutes to complete. No general anesthesia is given during the surgery and yes, the patient has to be awake, while the procedure is being performed. Many patients are squeamish regarding keeping the eyes open, while laser is pointed and being focused direct to the eye. Some [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"which-insurance-covers-lasik","date":"2019-09-15","title":"Which insurance covers lasik?","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2019/09/15/which-insurance-covers-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>Every health or medical insurer wants to get insurance coverage for the laser eye surgery and also for the LASIK eye surgery. According to the insurance provider, the object of offering insurance is to cover any loss, when any uncertain risk happens. They argue that any problem associated with the vision is not considered as the risk.</p>\n<p><strong>Why Most Insurance Companies Don’t Cover LASIK?</strong></p>\n<p>Insurance companies do not prefer to cover for the surgeries, such as refractive error corrective surgeries, for various reasons. First and foremost thing is that these are very expensive surgeries and if all the surgeries are paid by these companies, the financial burden increases hugely. They show the reason for not offering insurance for these procedures saying that these are cosmetic surgeries and so are purely elective. They mean that the procedures can only increase the quality of life, but without these surgeries, survival is not a problem at all. So, these procedures are not considered to be necessary surgeries.</p>\n<p><strong>Insurance Provider For LASIK</strong></p>\n<p>Insurance is provided by certain insurance providers. However, they offer only with some conditions. They are very specific about the refractive error shown in the prescription. For instance, some insurance companies offer insurance for LASIK surgery, if the existing power is more than -6D. There is no surprise that some companies offer full insurance coverage, if all their long list of conditions is satisfied. Some companies set this border line to even +/- 7.5. Each of the insurance providers has its own set of policies defined and set to offer possible insurance coverage its customers. Competition among the insurance companies is one benefit for the laser surgery patients, as they tend to offer more than the competitor.</p>\n<p><strong>So, Which Insurance Companies Offer?</strong></p>\n<p>There are very few insurance companies, which offer insurance paid for LASIK surgery and among them, the most important ones to mention are Blue Cross Blue Shield, Davis Vision, VSP and so on. They negotiate with the providers of LASIK often for offering a courtesy discount to their customers and help to offset the huge cost of the procedure, the customer wants to undergo. Most importantly they want their preset conditions to be fulfilled to offer this benefit.</p>\n<p><strong>Conditions To Fulfil</strong></p>\n<p>The first potential situation is the profession. If you are from military profession, LASIK, this medical bill can be covered under health insurance policy. Some specific occupations and some special forces in the military need specific requirements of vision without contact lenses or eye glasses. Hence, the soldiers need to undergo LASIK as the glasses and lens can hinder the operations in their profession. However, this surgery needs to be done only under the facility of military and some waiting period is also associated.</p>\n<p>Another profession that can be covered under health insurance policy is acting, sports or entertaining. If you are from any of these professions and if the job demands the need for laser eye surgery, then you can make a case and demand the insurance providers to cover at least part of the charges.</p>\n<p>Apart from the profession, if the LASIK potential patient has any genuine health concerns for wearing the contact lenses or eye glasses, such as severe allergies or dry eyes or especially, serious intolerance for wearing. A strong claim with a serious and genuine health concern can become key elements to claim for health insurance.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Every health or medical insurer wants to get insurance coverage for the laser eye surgery and also for the LASIK eye surgery. According to the insurance provider, the object of offering insurance is to cover any loss, when any uncertain risk happens. They argue that any problem associated with the vision is not considered as [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-feel-lasik-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can you feel Lasik eye surgery?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-you-feel-lasik-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Surgery sounds very big and risky in medical terms. However, it is no longer so, with the advancement of technology today. Still, the human brain seeks confirmation. It is important to explore the level of comfort and possibilities of hurt and pain. The fact is you can feel the surgical procedure very slightly and there is no question of hurting, since no needles and no poking are required.</p>\n<p><strong>Does It Hurt?</strong></p>\n<p>Almost no surgery is conducted without anesthesia and so Lasik eye surgery too. So, before the surgery process is initiated, local anaesthesia is applied into your eyes in the form of eye drops to create numbness of the eyes. Don’t worry, this affect continue only for 20 to 30 minutes and the treatment is completed by then. There is no question of burning also, since the laser beak is usually cold.</p>\n<p>Later, there may be some itchy feeling in your eyes, however, you need to resist yourself to not to rub your eyes. This discomfort will slowly fade away as the eyes get healed, as you will be medicated with the eye drops to lessen the discomfort.</p>\n<p><strong>What Happens During The Procedure?</strong></p>\n<p>Knowing what exactly happens during the procedure can help you to ensure that it is not a complicated procedure and does not hurt.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Initially, local anaesthetic eye drops are applied to the eyes to ensure that the patient does not feel pain, while the surgery is performed.</li>\n<li>Then femtosecond laser is used for creating flap.</li>\n<li>Later, this flap is lifted above gently, which is the only time, the patient feels slight discomfort.</li>\n<li>Then the Excimer laser is used for reshaping the tissue of cornea, for correction of the refractive error.</li>\n<li>The flap would then be replaced gently and aligned into its original position back.</li>\n<li>This flap will be healed naturally and it does not need any kind of stitches.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In the entire procedure, there is hardly any process that hurts or feel of burn of the eyes. After the procedure, it is important to be patient enough for a few weeks, until the discomfort gets faded away completely. Later, it is only enjoyment of the better vision, thanking Lasik eye surgery.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Surgery sounds very big and risky in medical terms. However, it is no longer so, with the advancement of technology today. Still, the human brain seeks confirmation. It is important to explore the level of comfort and possibilities of hurt and pain. The fact is you can feel the surgical procedure very slightly and there [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-use-phone-after-lasik","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can I use phone after Lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-i-use-phone-after-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>Mobile phones and tablets have become not only part of our lives, but also because some external organs of the body that stays touching the hand and ears. It is always advisable to be far away from the mobile phones right after the Lasik surgery for sometime, though for not longer time.</p>\n<p><strong>When Can Revert To Phone?</strong></p>\n<p>Technically, the natural healing process starts after 24 hours, post the Lasik eye surgery. It is a known fact that the radiation heat waves keep flowing around certain radius of the operating mobile phone. These waves are harmful for the sensitive organs, like eyes, which are close to the ears.</p>\n<p><strong>Any Precautions</strong></p>\n<p>Yes, there are certain precautions to follow, while attending important calls, right after one day of the surgery.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Consider taking frequent breaks, if you must attend the phone calls</li>\n<li>Use the time of these breaks to lubricate the eyes with antibiotic drops</li>\n<li>Consider the usage of the hands-free to attend the calls that are long</li>\n<li>Consciously keep blinking the eyes for many times than usual, while speaking over the phone, as it helps moisturising the eyes for long time</li>\n<li>Reduce the usage of social networks over your smartphones, to minimize the gazing at the small screen</li>\n<li>Enable minute reminder to keep reminding you with the beeps, after every minute of your conversation over your phone</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Lasik eye surgery is not a complex surgery, as it sounds. It is because the surgery is conducted with no devices or needles coming direct in contact with the eye, physically, instead of the laser beam focus. More care is considered to stay far from the digital screens and talking over the phones, not because of the surgery, but because of the sensitiveness factor of the eyes.</p>\n<p>Hence, after the Lasik eye surgery, you are allowed to use the mobile phones and allowed to watch the television, but with certain limit until the eyes are completely recovered back to normal stage. Then you will have complete freedom to enjoy the better vision. Wish you a comfort and clear vision.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Mobile phones and tablets have become not only part of our lives, but also because some external organs of the body that stays touching the hand and ears. It is always advisable to be far away from the mobile phones right after the Lasik surgery for sometime, though for not longer time. When Can Revert [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-cook-after-lasik-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can I cook after Lasik surgery?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-i-cook-after-lasik-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>As a part of post-operative preparation and advice sought after Lasik treatment, it is quite usual to get the doubt whether cooking would affect the eyes, which are operated. Cooking is the process, where one has to work with the steams, fire and smoke. It is quite possible that the smoke and steam could touch the eye ball. And the question is, whether the eye ball will have affects during the process of cooking.</p>\n<p>Most of the doctors suggest and recommend the people, who have undergone the Lasik procedures to stay in very clean environment, where dust and dust particles are minimum. It is quite important because the patient is advised to use lubricants for the eyes to avoid dryness of the eyes. So, when the dust particles or any kind of unusual environment is experienced, and the eye lubricant gets mixed with the unwanted or harmful dust particles, the results may not pleasant.</p>\n<p>Hence, it is important to understand and realize that the process of cooking in kitchen is more of dealing with different food ingredients, such as flours, etc. and cutting vegetables, like onions and using spices. All these ingredients may not be safe for the very sensitive eyes after the Lasik procedures.</p>\n<p>However the sensitiveness of the eyes is not carried longer. After a few days, eyes become to a normal state, where regular and day to day activities can be performed with no hesitation. It is for a couple of days that one is recommended to avoid cooking, which is more like dealing with higher temperatures. The patient has to be very careful, even with heating water, dealing with very hot food.</p>\n<p>After one week of time, most of the people will come to a state that they forget they have undergone the Lasik procedure because of their newly gained comfort to perform day to day activities. Hence, it is quite fine to cook after duration of a week. And it has to be remembered that if the patient feels any kind of discomfort with the eyes and performing any kind of day to day activities, including cooking in the kitchen, one has to avoid doing so and should take an appointment with the respective doctor.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>As a part of post-operative preparation and advice sought after Lasik treatment, it is quite usual to get the doubt whether cooking would affect the eyes, which are operated. Cooking is the process, where one has to work with the steams, fire and smoke. It is quite possible that the smoke and steam could touch [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-crying-affect-lasik","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can crying affect Lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-crying-affect-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik surgery, being an advanced surgery in the medical industry, there are various myths developed by the people. However, one would prefer and go for the Lasik surgery because it is one of the safest surgical procedure, as it does not include blades and incision for the surgery. So, technically it is an advanced and one of the fastest procedures and very safe too. Complications and side effects after the surgery are uncommon. However, the myths such as effect of crying to the eyes, post the surgery are worth addressing, since eyes are the most sensitive organs in the body.</p>\n<p>Addressing technically, crying after Lasik surgery is not harmful and so safe. However, the threat can be with the rubbing the eyes with pressure, during or after crying. Though it is not a big threat, it is recommended by the doctors, because the eye and internal micro organs in the eye become very sensitive after the surgery and the natural structure should not be disturbed by rubbing the eyes.</p>\n<p>So, what happens if the eyes are rubbed, while crying? If the eyes are rubbed immediately after the procedure of Lasik, it can result in risking the flap that has been taken. Rubbing possibly creates displacement, wrinkles of folds of flap. In case of flap wrinkles or flap fold occur, the vision can be blurred that may result in unclear and hazy vision.</p>\n<p>Then what to do? Ideally, rubbing should not be done, though crying is absolutely fine after the surgery. In case rubbing is done and discomfort is felt by the patient after rubbing, the treating doctor has to be consulted. Then the treating doctor would examine and check the eye under the slit lamp. In case any folds and wrinkles are found, further medication and treatment would be followed. So, not only while crying, but in any other situations or conditions, you shall not rub your eyes that hinder the natural healing process and recovery process of your eyes.</p>\n<p>One can prevent any kind of these side effects by considering and following the post-operative suggestions. When all these instructions are followed, much improved and clear vision can be enjoyed by the patient, improving the quality of life to a greater extent.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik surgery, being an advanced surgery in the medical industry, there are various myths developed by the people. However, one would prefer and go for the Lasik surgery because it is one of the safest surgical procedure, as it does not include blades and incision for the surgery. So, technically it is an advanced and [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"when-can-i-apply-kajal-after-lasik","date":"2019-09-14","title":"When can i apply kajal after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/when-can-i-apply-kajal-after-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>After the Lasik surgery, it is important to consider the condition of recovery before applying the eye makeup, like Kajal, eye liner, mascara, etc. As the eyes become very sensitive during the process of healing, the eyes must be protected against the irritants, so that recovery can be impeded. Eye makeup, especially, kajal makes direct contact with the eyes and so it is important to avoid kajal, before and after a few days of the Lasik eye surgery. If any substances cause irritation to the skin on and out of the eye, it may lead to infection. So, the face has to be cleansed thoroughly after removing the kajal, eye liner, etc., the night before the surgical procedure.</p>\n<p>After the Lasik surgery, the first six hours at least, the eye surface is smoothed over to a level, where there is hardly any sensation of any foreign body. The eye is so sensitive that even the slightest abrasion of a foreign body is felt by the eye and makes you conscious. The natural system of the eye produces tears to flush away the foreign body. So, in case any tiny foreign particles from the eye makeup is stuck on or near the surface of the scratch, the bacteria, which is adherent invariably to that tiny particle also can be grown, resulting in infection. The process of applying and removing the eye makeup also increase the pressure over the eye and it becomes an unnecessary poke into the eyes and poking the eyes may lead to the dislodging of the Lasik flap. This condition is possible during the recovery period after the surgery, not later.</p>\n<p>The concern is that though most of the eye makeup is promoted as safe and hypoallergenic, these products still have the risk of irritation and infection post-surgery. For instance, tiny and small particles get trapped near or in the surgical site and result in inflammation and discomfort. So, ‘better safe than sorry’ saying is applied in this instance, as avoiding the makeup to the eyes can prevent the complications further. The process of applying the eye makeup is also sometimes harmful and irritates the eyes. For instance more pressure than adequate level on the eyelid may also hinder the underlying corneal flap healing. It may have negative impact over the outcome of the vision, as it causes discomfort.</p>\n<p>It is recommended by the medical professionals not to wear the eye makeup, like mascara, eye shadow, eyeliner or kajal for at least four weeks of duration. And it is crucial to not apply for some more time, if you feel any discomfort for your eyes. To stay safe from any possible irritation, doctors advise to purchase new set of eye makeup and use after the Lasik surgical procedure. Follow it as a rule of thumb so that potential infections and complications can be avoided.</p>\n<p>After a week, you can resume kajal and other eye makeup and never forget to apply it gently.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>After the Lasik surgery, it is important to consider the condition of recovery before applying the eye makeup, like Kajal, eye liner, mascara, etc. As the eyes become very sensitive during the process of healing, the eyes must be protected against the irritants, so that recovery can be impeded. Eye makeup, especially, kajal makes direct [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-drink-after-lasik","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can I drink after Lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-i-drink-after-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>There might be some social events coming up after or before Lasik eye surgery. However, it is important to know that drinking is not advisable after Lasik eye surgery. One of the important reasons is simple and direct that one becomes dehydrate after having drink and it is directly connected to the fact that the initial healing period leaves one uncomfortable. During the procedure and after the procedure, the patient is given with the medications and eye drops and the same can be interfered with the alcohol. And after the surgery, it is important to have as much as of the liquid as you want, along with taking enough rest. It makes the process of recovery to be smooth.</p>\n<p><strong>So, How Long?</strong></p>\n<p>According the advises of optometrists, the patient should avoid the alcohol completely for one week after the Lasik surgery, to ensure that the body will have full effect of healing process to prevent any dehydration possible to the eyes.</p>\n<p><strong>How Body Is Affected from Surgery?</strong></p>\n<p>The alcohol affects the eyes, if consumed during the first week of recovery period in three ways. The important affect is the dryness of the eyes, since the alcohol makes the body and so eyes dehydrate, as it has mild diuretic effect. Another affect is the swelling of the eyes and it again hinders the process of healing from the surgery naturally. And another important affect is that you may miss out lubricating the eyes, when your body gives less control, when one consumes more alcohol. So, having excessive alcohol makes the recovery process to hinder badly.</p>\n<p><strong>What if I Can’t Miss the Event?</strong></p>\n<p>It is still not a good idea to attend any social events and engagements, right after the Lasik surgery or even during the first week of recovery period. However, if there is any social event of your family members or closer friends, you may not afford to miss. In such cases, you can prefer to attend the meeting, but it is quite needed to stick to the soft drinks and ensure that you are back home, before it is late night, having considering the fact that your body needs enough rest. Ideally, your recovery of eyes has more priority compared to any social events, during the recovery period post to the surgery.</p>\n<p>So, no worries, the waiting period is one week and later you can have alcohol, but remember to take moderate for the overall general health of your body.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>There might be some social events coming up after or before Lasik eye surgery. However, it is important to know that drinking is not advisable after Lasik eye surgery. One of the important reasons is simple and direct that one becomes dehydrate after having drink and it is directly connected to the fact that the [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-after-lasik-can-i-work-out","date":"2019-09-14","title":"How long after lasik can i work out?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/how-long-after-lasik-can-i-work-out","contentHtml":"<p>If you are a fitness freak and play sports like cricket very often, the concern of workout is natural after the Lasik surgery. However, there is nothing to worry as the waiting period is not very long. Since eyes are the most sensitive organs of the body and incredibly precious, the patient should ensure enough time is given for healing and recovery, after the Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>How Workouts Affect?</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik surgery involves creation of the flap and flap has to be maintained with no physical stress or pressure above. During the workouts or sports, simple pressure, even wiping sweat over the eyes can result in complications of the flap. And think of rubbing the eyes for correction of eyesight that is usually done, while looking at the farer object, how much it can damage the flap. Though workouts and sports are healthy for the body, any pressure over the eyes is possible, done either knowingly or unknowingly.</p>\n<p><strong>So, How Long?</strong></p>\n<p>As the list and types of workouts and sports is very long and huge and diversity of them is more, in terms of movement and flexibility of the body, there is no one single and fixed period of time for recovery to wait before resuming. And one more important deciding factor for the waiting time is the type of Laser surgery one has gone through. So, let us see what kind of exercises and workouts need how much time for recovery, when Lasik surgery is considered to be gone through.</p>\n<p>For lighter and gentle workouts, like jogging, Pilates or yoga, one week period is enough after the surgery. If any weightlifting is part of your workout, you need to wait for two weeks, if youworkout with lighter weights and four weeks for heavier weights. Other workout activities, such as swimming and steam room need one month of period before resuming. If you are a regular player of tennis, football or cricket, the waiting period would be 6 weeks minimum. Other sports like basketball, badminton and squash also need 6 months. Based on the complexity of each of the workout and sports, one can understand how much time it is important to leave for recovery. Your workout activity most probably would be covered within this complexity.</p>\n<p>So, the total period of waiting to resume to regular workouts and exercises would be in between one week to six months of duration, covering in between the specified complexity levels.</p>\n<p><strong>Good to Know While Workout</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>After the specified period of recovery, you can resume your workout or exercise, however it should be started slower with smaller. Initially, go for a walk in your garden, rather than in the parks or jogging tracks.</li>\n<li>Ensure to use elliptical machines while resuming the workout</li>\n<li>Then slowly go for higher intensity workouts that sweat you more, like heavy weight lifting or even hot yoga.</li>\n<li>If you sweat more often, wear a sweatband over the head so that sweat can be prevented from dripping into your eyes and keep a small towel always handy to give touch up to the face, without touching the eyes.</li>\n<li>Never rub the swipe the sweat on the eyes with towel or fingers.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>So, when you resume your workout be conscious about your eyes and never allow any physical pressure over the eyes.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>If you are a fitness freak and play sports like cricket very often, the concern of workout is natural after the Lasik surgery. However, there is nothing to worry as the waiting period is not very long. Since eyes are the most sensitive organs of the body and incredibly precious, the patient should ensure enough [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-do-you-have-to-use-artificial-tears-after-lasik","date":"2019-09-14","title":"How long do you have to use artificial tears after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/how-long-do-you-have-to-use-artificial-tears-after-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>While the Lasik surgery goes on, the patient is given the anaesthetic drop, an anti-inflammatory steroid drop and an antibiotic drop. After the surgery, the anti-inflammatory drops and antibiotic drops need to be continued for first week, four times a day. In case intralase laser flap creation is performed during the procedure, every hour, anti-inflammatory steroid drop should be taken on the first day after surgery, while awake. A preservative-free artificial tear drops also have to be taken every half hour, on the surgical procedure day and evening.</p>\n<p><strong>Why Artificial Tears?</strong></p>\n<p>The reason is simple and clear. After the Lasik surgery recovery needs continuous lubrication of the eyes and this purpose can be served with the artificial tears. Artificial tears are considered for the recovery after the Lasik procedure, as they help treating the dryness and also irritation, in relation with the deficient production of tears. They function as supplements with other kinds of treatments in dry eyes in varied forms, from moderate to severe. There is a small difference between the natural tears and artificial tears. Artificial tears contain polymers, salts mixed in water and natural tears contain proteins also in addition. If the artificial tears have to be used regularly below three hours of gap, they should contain no preservatives and even it contains the preservatives, the preservative must be non-irritating. These tears may blur the vision temporarily, if thick or denser.</p>\n<p>In certain unusual circumstances, such as a particle of dust or eyelash getting in the eye, after a first few weeks of the Lasik procedure, artificial tears can flush the dust particles from the eyes. It prevents from rubbing the eyes.</p>\n<p>Apart from the artificial tears, antibiotic eye drops are also advised to use to prevent any further possible infection.</p>\n<p><strong>How Long?</strong></p>\n<p>During the follow-up visits you will be advised about how many more days you have to take continue the drops to lubricate the eyes, based on the condition of recovery, by your Lasik surgeon. Most often, the artificial tears are advised to take four times in one day and it should continue for three months after the surgery. Based on different kinds of Lasik surgeries, sometimes the patient even has to apply 8 times a day with the gap of 2 hours.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>While the Lasik surgery goes on, the patient is given the anaesthetic drop, an anti-inflammatory steroid drop and an antibiotic drop. After the surgery, the anti-inflammatory drops and antibiotic drops need to be continued for first week, four times a day. In case intralase laser flap creation is performed during the procedure, every hour, anti-inflammatory [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-can-i-take-care-of-my-eyes-after-lasik","date":"2019-09-14","title":"How can i take care of my eyes after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/how-can-i-take-care-of-my-eyes-after-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik surgery is required to conduct reshaping of the corneas, towards correction of the refractive errors. And during this procedure, the flaps are lifted slightly and reshaping is done through laser. After the correction is attempted, flap is sealed. Hence, proper care has to be taken to protect the eyes to heal properly and prevent any possible infection and damage. It would not be difficult when the patient knows and considers the following post-operative guidelines.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Don’t read more. Reading can dry your eyes, since the rate of blinking gets reduced in this process. Instead your can prefer audio book, such as Amazon kindle.</li>\n<li>Never forget to wear sunglasses to protect the eyes both from the sun as well as the dust and debris in the environment</li>\n<li>Avoid any of risky activities. Not only simple activities like working in the garden, but also any of outdoor or indoor activities that may cause nasty complications to the eye must be avoided. In a nutshell, it is important to stay indoors and stay calm, listening to music or sleep.</li>\n<li>Avoid any eye makeup. Makeup should be avoided during the healing or recovery period after the Lasik surgery for three reasons. The first reason is the dust or any makeup particles disturbing the structure of the flap and cornea and the second reason is unwanted pressure over the eyes and eyelids. The third reason is that eyes are more susceptible to the bacteria and infection, from the makeup products. Even after the recovery period, ensure that new makeup kit is used for the eye makeup.</li>\n<li>Avoid hot tubs and swimming. The reason is both are veritable parties of bacteria. To prevent any contact of bacteria and development of infection, avoid both swimming and hot tubs.</li>\n<li>Avoid Smoking and Boozing. Smoke should be refrained for longer period even after the recovery, since the smoke comes from it can easily and quickly irritate the eyes. Alcohol consumption must be avoided for majorly preventing dehydration of the body and so dehydration of the eyes.</li>\n<li>Don’t wash your hair till day after the surgery.</li>\n<li>Don’t drive immediately. Though ideally and technically, one would get the capability of eyesight for legal driving, it is not advisable to drive on the same day of the surgery. So, wait for 24 hours, before you steer your car.</li>\n<li>Protect your eyes consciously, without rubbing or pressurizing the eyes. It is advisable to wear eye shied, when you go to bed, to prevent rubbing eyes, while sleeping.</li>\n<li>Avoid saunas, whirlpools, lakes or lakes for 3 weeks after the surgery.</li>\n<li>For any kind of regular activities, wait for four days to one week at least, until you confirm yourself that you are comfortable performing any day to day task.</li>\n<li>Be in a tidy environment for at least two weeks after the procedure.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>So, no matter it is a regular intake of food or liquids or daily activities done, make sure that you do them consciously after ensuring that the food, drink or activity does not harm the eyes after Lasik eye surgery.</p>\n<p>9491828711</p>\n<p>9491070174</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik surgery is required to conduct reshaping of the corneas, towards correction of the refractive errors. And during this procedure, the flaps are lifted slightly and reshaping is done through laser. After the correction is attempted, flap is sealed. Hence, proper care has to be taken to protect the eyes to heal properly and prevent [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-your-eyesight-get-worse-after-laser-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can your eyesight get worse after laser eye surgery?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-your-eyesight-get-worse-after-laser-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Theoretically and technically Laser eye surgery improves the vision of the eyes, instead of getting worse. Usually, there would be no negative effects or side effects experienced after the surgery.</p>\n<p>The overall success of the surgery is dependent on several factors. The first factor is the precession and accuracy of the surgical procedure is conducted, which again depends on the experience of the Lasik surgeon and standards followed during the procedure, reliable infrastructure. And the secondary factor is how well the eyes are protected against any odds or disturbances post surgery. Though there are many other factors that influence the success of the surgery and so the correction of the vision, the above two specified factors play major roles.</p>\n<p>In case the above two factors got to influence negatively, like if the surgery is not successful or done with the industry standards or if no enough protection or care is taken post surgery, the following negative effects may be experienced by the patient.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>In any possible case, where changes are occurred in the lens, internal to the eye after the Lasik surgery, any of the conditions like farsightedness, nearsightedness and/or astigmatism will possibly be returned after the surgery.</li>\n<li>The possible side effects are…\n<ul>\n<li>Difficulty to drive during nights</li>\n<li>Dry eyes</li>\n<li>Glare</li>\n<li>Fluctuating vision</li>\n<li>Halos seen around images</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Even the patient experiences any one or more than one symptoms after the surgery and recovery period, there is nothing to worry, because there are also some corrective procedures possible. If the patient experiences any farsightedness, nearsightedness or astigmatism, and feels bothersome, it is possible to restore better and clear vision with the Lasik enhancement, which is a follow-up procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Rate of Failure or Side Effects</strong></p>\n<p>Most of the patients, who have gone through the Lasik eye surgery find almost no complaints with the vision. The success rate of the Lasik procedure is more than 96% for this 25 year old technology. The rate of success is further increased with the enhancement procedure. The further changes of the vision and eyesight changing with the age can be even corrected by far after Lasik. There is hardly any requirement of the contact lens or eyeglasses after the Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p>Considering the statistics, the need for Lasik enhancement is close to 6%, when considering 10 years of duration after the surgery. The cost of the enhancement surgery is minimum or zero immediately after the Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p>Having considering all these facts, it is easy to analyse that the Lasik procedure is almost completely safe, when performed with the standards of the industry and post operative care is good enough.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Theoretically and technically Laser eye surgery improves the vision of the eyes, instead of getting worse. Usually, there would be no negative effects or side effects experienced after the surgery. The overall success of the surgery is dependent on several factors. The first factor is the precession and accuracy of the surgical procedure is conducted, [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-is-the-average-cost-of-lasik-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"What is the average cost of lasik surgery?","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/what-is-the-average-cost-of-lasik-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>When you consider the Lasik surgery, overall cost of the surgery becomes a significant concern, after its safety features. Finding the exact cost of the Lasik surgery exactly is a bit complex, because of the variation in different locations and based on different factors.</p>\n<p><strong>Factors of Surgery Cost</strong></p>\n<p>So, before exploring the exact cost of the surgery, it is important to explore the factors that influence the overall cost.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Vision Correction Required</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The cost of the Laser surgery is proportional to the severity of the vision condition of the patient. If the patient has very poor vision, the surgery becomes very expensive as it needs deeper correction. And in case the correction needed is small, the surgery is less expensive.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Surgeon Skill</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The overall experience and expertise of the surgeon, who is going to conduct the Lasik surgery influence. The more the surgeon is experienced, the more expensive the surgery will be and vice versa. And eventually, the outcomes and results also will be optimistic, when the surgery done by the experienced surgeon.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Laser Technology</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The kind of technology to focus the laser on the eye is another important factor contributing the overall cost of the surgery. As the technology gets advanced, such as custom Lasik, the cost of the surgery becomes more. With the advanced technology, the cost of the Laser devices adds some more cost of the surgery. The individual preferences of the patient add or decrease the overall cost. The kind of technology and associated costs become the major cost factor of the surgery.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Pre and Post Operative Care</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The necessary standard procedure and care before and after the surgery cost the patient, on the basis of the standards followed by the patient.</p>\n<p>The Laser surgery vision hospital should inform about each and every cost factor, including major and minor cost factor. The services also must include the follow-up procedure after the surgery. When the three above significant contributors of the Laser surgery cost are considered, the overall cost of the surgery may vary in between $1000 to $3000.</p>\n<p><strong>What to Know?</strong></p>\n<p>After receiving the estimated cost of the surgery, the following questions have to be posed to the Laser surgeon or hospital administration.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>What is the type of technology of Lasik used?</li>\n<li>What gets included and what not included in the list of final cost of the surgery?</li>\n<li>Is the quotation proposed for one eye or both the eyes?</li>\n<li>What will be the cost, in case contact lenses or temporary eye glasses are required or recommended temporarily?</li>\n<li>Whether the cost of the medications prescribed is going to be additional or included in the overall cost.</li>\n<li>Whether the quoted cost includes the post-operative visits and number of visits are specified or not.</li>\n<li>Whether the itemized and written quote is given or not.</li>\n<li>Whether the administration is willing to provide the references or testimonials of the patients or not?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The best time for inquiring the overall cost of the Lasik surgery is initial Lasik consultation for vision correction with the Lasik technology. You need to ensure that even smaller cost item is included in the quoted cost of the surgery. Not even a single dollar should be charged additionally, by the medical center, when the mentioned or specified Lasik surgery is performed.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>When you consider the Lasik surgery, overall cost of the surgery becomes a significant concern, after its safety features. Finding the exact cost of the Lasik surgery exactly is a bit complex, because of the variation in different locations and based on different factors. Factors of Surgery Cost So, before exploring the exact cost of [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-is-the-cost-of-lasik-in-india","date":"2019-09-14","title":"What is the cost of lasik in India?","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/what-is-the-cost-of-lasik-in-india","contentHtml":"<p>The cost of the Lasik surgery is decided basically on the basis of the Lasik technology and procedure that will be performed. The technology is primarily of three kinds called blade procedure, blade-less procedure and contoura vision. Among them, contoura vision is the most expensive one and may range around 1 Lakh INR in India. And blade-less procedure is eventually more expensive with 90,000 INR compared to the blade procedure that cost within the range of 30,000 INR to 60,000 INR. The costs are specified for both the eyes.</p>\n<p>Lasik techniques vary as 100% blade-free technique, surface ablation or blade techniques. And each of the technique varies in terms of cost because of the variations in terms of complexity. Each of the medical center has its own list of the cost of each item and even then the difference of the cost of the surgery for the same technique varies just from 5000 INR to 1,00,000 INR for one eye. When two medical centers offer the same Lasik technology for the surgery, the two other important factors to consider before choosing the right place are the quality control and medical safety protocols and standards.</p>\n<p>Anyhow, on an overall, the average cost of the Lasik surgery in India varies from 25,000 INR to 45,000 INR. You need to ensure that the medical center offers the services with the industry standards, without bad practices, like re-use of disposables, poorly maintained lasers and have no expertise to deal when the conditions become complex during or after the surgery.</p>\n<p>Ideally, the overall cost for each of the patient may vary, as each patient has unique condition. The overall condition of the patient can be investigated and interpreted after conducting certain tests.</p>\n<p><strong>Evaluation Tests</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Dry eye test</li>\n<li>Size of pupil in dim light</li>\n<li>Pachymetry</li>\n<li>Wavefront analysis, performed using aberrometer to check the pupil size for the analysis of the issues related to the night vision</li>\n<li>Cycloplegic refraction</li>\n<li>Topography</li>\n</ul>\n<p>All the above tests are done to explore and interpret two things, qualitative part and quantitative part of the procedure to be performed. Qualitative part is important and it helps to determine whether this procedure is good and safe enough, especially post procedure. Quantitative part helps to determine, in case you could achieve 6/6 or 20/20 vision or not. Some of the advanced Lasik lasers are VisuMax laser, Concerto 500 Hz, so on. Some of the Lasik procedures are topo link PRK, bladeless Lasik, custom Lasik, wavefront guided Lasik, surface ablations, epiLasik, ReLExSmILE, etc.</p>\n<p>In a nutshell, the overall price no matter in India or out of India, it is determined on the basis of various factors that include patient’s unique condition of vision, the technology adapted for the procedure and the standards followed by the Lasik center.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The cost of the Lasik surgery is decided basically on the basis of the Lasik technology and procedure that will be performed. The technology is primarily of three kinds called blade procedure, blade-less procedure and contoura vision. Among them, contoura vision is the most expensive one and may range around 1 Lakh INR in India. [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-much-does-smile-laser-eye-surgery-cost","date":"2019-09-14","title":"How much does smile laser eye surgery cost?","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/how-much-does-smile-laser-eye-surgery-cost","contentHtml":"<p><strong>What is SMILE?</strong></p>\n<p>SMILE is a new laser procedure, which is conducted sometimes in addition to the Lasik procedure and most often as an individual SMILE procedure. This procedure is a standard laser procedure as it is approved by the FDA and is regularly performed in the US.</p>\n<p><strong>How is it Different from LASIK?</strong></p>\n<p>SMILE is a short form of SMall Incision Lenticule Extraction. The procedure of SMILE is similar to that of the LASIK with a small variation. Both of them perform the procedure to reshape the cornea, but the SMILE needs very small incision, which is approximately 4mm for removing the lenticule, as compared to more than 10mm, in terms of LASIK. This small incision is made possible by employing efmotsecond laser. Then on the surface of the cornea, a small incision in the shape of an arc is made by the same laser. Then lenticule is extracted gently and discarded. Shaper vision is ensured fundamentally, by correcting nearsightedness. And very fewer corneal nerges get affected because of smaller incision. Since the incision is smaller, it is healed quickly.</p>\n<p><strong>Who Prefers SMILE?</strong></p>\n<p>SMILE is preferred for the patients, who need correction of -10.00 diopters of nearsightedness, by the surgeon. According to Carl Zeiss Meditec, so far 1.5 million SMILE procedures are conducted.</p>\n<p><strong>Dry Eye Affect after SMILE</strong></p>\n<p>According to the research report, the risk of dry eye is lesser with the SMILE procedure compared to the Lasik procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Cost of SMILE</strong></p>\n<p>In most of the cases the cost of the SMILE is same as that of the Lasik and any other laser procedures. It costs around $2000 to $3000 per an eye. This is an average price and the total price usually depends on various cost factors, such as the standards followed in the medical center and the unique condition of the patient. The cost of the procedure gets varied on the basis of the experience of the surgeon, the location of practice, including or excluding the follow-up exams and many other patient specific and medical center specific expenses. On an overall the total cost of the SMILE procedure does not exceed maximum of $3500.</p>\n<p>On an overall SMILE procedure has the advantages of no pain, no flap and quick recovery and when a fair level of expertise and technology are considered, the entire surgery can possibly completed within the budget of $3000.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>What is SMILE? SMILE is a new laser procedure, which is conducted sometimes in addition to the Lasik procedure and most often as an individual SMILE procedure. This procedure is a standard laser procedure as it is approved by the FDA and is regularly performed in the US. How is it Different from LASIK? SMILE [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-prk-surgery-painful","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Is PRK surgery painful?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/is-prk-surgery-painful","contentHtml":"<p>In simple and short, no laser surgery is painful. No matter it is a PRK surgery or Lasik surgery, one does not experience any pain during the surgical procedure. It is because of the fact that anesthetic eye drops are placed in the eye, before the procedure starts. There may be a small discomfort or small fear, as the procedure deals with the eyes, the most sensitive organs in the body.</p>\n<p><strong>After the Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>Once the procedure is performed the affect of anesthetic medication will be gone and the effect of the surgery remains. There can be a fear of pain after the surgery, however, according to the reports of the patients, who have gone through the surgery indicate that there is no or mild discomfort felt. The discomfort or mild pain is only for the next day of the surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Pain During Recovery</strong></p>\n<p>Recovery time for the PRK is a bit longer and during this period, some kind of discomfort or soreness is possible and it is quite tolerable. The discomfort can be easily managed with the pain relievers prescribed to use post surgery. The soreness is visible and noticeable only during the first one two weeks and abates with time.</p>\n<p><strong>Pain Reduction</strong></p>\n<p>Oral pain agents can be used to reduce the pain. Antiseizure medication is preferred by many ophthalmologists apart fromt eh regular topical approaches, like cold saline, soft contacts, anesthetics, ice and NSAIDs. Pain management is well managed with pregabalin and gabapentin. Both these medications give similar results. According to the study and reports by American Journal of Ophthalmology, both these medications work the same way, as per the reports collected from the patients. These medications have to be used only upon recommendation of the surgeon, since the jury still has to ensure the effectiveness of this medication.</p>\n<p>There is nothing to worry about the pain or discomfort after the PRK procedure as it is quite temporary and can be managed easily with enough medication. Apart from that small changes in the lifestyle, like listening to music spending good time with the family and friends can make the pain to be unnoticeable.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>In simple and short, no laser surgery is painful. No matter it is a PRK surgery or Lasik surgery, one does not experience any pain during the surgical procedure. It is because of the fact that anesthetic eye drops are placed in the eye, before the procedure starts. There may be a small discomfort or [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-is-the-success-rate-of-prk-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"What is the success rate of PRK surgery?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/what-is-the-success-rate-of-prk-surgery","contentHtml":"<p><strong>Success Rate of PRK</strong></p>\n<p>Technically speaking, having no failure is a big success. Though there are certain risks associated with the PRK surgery like any other surgery, the risks can be prevented with careful choosing of the surgeon and careful lifestyle during the recovery period. There is one closed ended or objective question to be made to ensure whether this laser surgery can be successful or not. The governmental authority gives the green signal to only medical procedures, which are harmless and successful. The first and foremost thing to ensure that the PRK procedure is safe and secured or not, is to double check whether the PRK procedure is approved by the local government medical and drug authority or not. Since PRK is approved procedure all over the world, it is the first indication the procedure has the potential success rate.</p>\n<p>The success rates of PRK are quite exceptional. The reports say that around 95% of patients undergone the PRK surgery achieves the vision of at least 20/40. The statistics give the indication that at least 95% of the patients do not need to wear the glasses or contact lenses for clear vision.</p>\n<p>The success rates of PRK are quite comparable to the success rates of the Lasik surgery. These both procedures are very close to each other with small variation in intensity.</p>\n<p><strong>How to Improve Success Rate For Me?</strong></p>\n<p>The success rate of the PRK procedure or in fact any other laser procedure can be made in our control, after choosing government approved surgical procedure like PRK.</p>\n<p>There are two factors to consider. First one is to choose an experienced surgeon in an experienced medical center with proven records. The previous and average success rate of the surgeon and hospital define the success rate of our PRK surgery. The second important factor is the care taken in each and every task and step of the surgery, both prior, during and post to the surgery. It includes understanding the general health condition and eye’s vision condition. Getting physically and mentally willing to undergo the PRK procedure with complete trust to achieve and enjoy the pure vision after the surgery is quite important and it plays major role in reducing or preventing the complications after the surgery.</p>\n<p>So, medically and technically PRK procedure is successful and the rest of the external factors in choosing the right surgeon and right hospital and internal factors of giving enough care to the eyes and general health enable 100% positive results.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Success Rate of PRK Technically speaking, having no failure is a big success. Though there are certain risks associated with the PRK surgery like any other surgery, the risks can be prevented with careful choosing of the surgeon and careful lifestyle during the recovery period. There is one closed ended or objective question to be [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-lasik-better-than-prk","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Is lasik better than PRK?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/is-lasik-better-than-prk","contentHtml":"<p>Technically both Lasik and PRK eye care surgical procedures are safe and standard as they are approved by the governments all over the world. The two methods are similar in terms of achieving healthy vision for eyes, avoiding the need for contacts and glasses. And the methods of applying the procedures are slightly varied in between them.</p>\n<p>Technically the difference between Lasik and PRK is the way the cornea is accessed for reshaping the same by the surgeon, using the excimer laser. The tissue called epithelium tissue or skin covering the cornea has to be either permanent removed or temporarily moved away, before sculpting the cornea with the excimer laser. The Lasik procedure moves the tissue out of the way temporarily and the tissue is removed using the PRK. Then the Lasik procedure involves fashioning the Lasik cap or flap, using a special surgical instrument.</p>\n<p><strong>Lasik is Better than PRK in Terms of…</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Lasik procedure allows the patient to recover faster compared to the PRK procedure, because the epithelium is moved out temporarily and it will be replaced, instead of removing it completely. So, the tissue is back in very few days over the area treated. Lasik is so popular primarily for this reason, as the people in the busy world want to get back to their normal and work life soon after the procedure.</li>\n<li>Compared to PRK, Lasik procedures leave the patient with less discomfort to no discomfort at all.</li>\n<li>PRK is suitable for very a few candidates, who has thin flap, but Lasik is suitable for any patient.</li>\n<li>Lasik procedure needs care not PRK demands comparatively more care, post surgery. It makes the patient to be get back to the normal day to day life quickly except keeping the eye lubricated or ensuring to not to rub the eyes. For PRK one is not preferred to go in bright sun for at least one to one and half months.</li>\n<li>Though Lasik procedure is deeper and complex, it is considered as a complete and effective procedure, according to the surgeon, because of enough depth of treatment though without blade but using laser.</li>\n<li>Lasik has lesser chances of haziness of vision or infection of the eye during the recovery period, comparatively PRK.</li>\n<li>Lasik is well recognized than the PRK.</li>\n<li>Both the patient and surgeon prefer Lasik procedure most of the time, as it solves the problem of regular wearing of glasses or contact lenses.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Lasik has many advantages compared to the PRK procedure and it is a kind of complete procedure that permanently cures the problem, though it is complex. Though there are certain advantages of PRK also, Lasik is preferred by both the patients and surgeons for quick recovery and kind of completion of the procedure to get rid of the vision related problem completely.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Technically both Lasik and PRK eye care surgical procedures are safe and standard as they are approved by the governments all over the world. The two methods are similar in terms of achieving healthy vision for eyes, avoiding the need for contacts and glasses. And the methods of applying the procedures are slightly varied in [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-lasik-or-prk-more-expensive","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Is lasik or PRK more expensive?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/is-lasik-or-prk-more-expensive","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik and PRK both the surgeries are performed using laser and can treat the problems of vision with refractive errors. The complexity and degree of depth of the procedure varies in between these two and so the cost too. The results and recovery duration also differ in between these two procedures according to the procedures.</p>\n<p><strong>Which is Expensive?</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik surgery is expensive, since it is a complex procedure compared to the PRK procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>How Much Variation?</strong></p>\n<p>The difference between Lasik and PRK procedures vary in hundreds of dollars.</p>\n<p><strong>Why Lasik is Expensive?</strong></p>\n<p>To understand the difference in the cost of the procedures, the actual processes involved in them must be explored. Let us consider the Lasik procedure first. Initially a flap in the cornea is cut, either with a laser or microkeratome. Flap is an outer skin layer that protects the internal parts of the eye. The laser will then be focused on the eye lenses. The area and depth of the focus is determined by the pre-program, coded according to the refractive prescription of the patient, taken during primary check up of the eyes. Then the cornea is reshaped accordingly and easily.</p>\n<p>When PRK is considered, initially a small corneal epithelium area will be removed, with the help of a blade, laser, special brush or solution of alcohol. After cornea is made out of the way, the lens will be shaped according to the pre-program coded according to the unique prescription of the patient. After the reshaping process is done according the program, a special bandage contact lens will be given.</p>\n<p>Having understood the differences in the procedures, the cost is also varied according to the complexity of the procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Which is Preferred?</strong></p>\n<p>Though Lasik is expensive and complex procedure for correcting the refractive errors of the eye, still Lasik is preferred by both the patient and surgeon. The reason for preferring the Lasik procedure is quick recovery and ability to return to normal life in very short time, within a couple of days. It is preferred because of the fact that the post operation risks and infections can be lesser.</p>\n<p><strong>How Much Each Cost</strong></p>\n<p>The total cost of each procedure is dependent upon various factors, starting from the unique patient’s condition, surgeon’s experience and standards followed by the hospital. The cost of Lasik procedure is approximately $2,000 to $2500 per one eye. When the PRK is considered, the cost of the procedure is around $2000 per eye.</p>\n<p>After the treatment there are follow-up visits and these charges are added in the total charges of procedure most often. It is important to request the hospital administration to specify each and every expense and breakdown of the overall charges of the procedure selected.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik and PRK both the surgeries are performed using laser and can treat the problems of vision with refractive errors. The complexity and degree of depth of the procedure varies in between these two and so the cost too. The results and recovery duration also differ in between these two procedures according to the procedures. [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-after-prk-does-vision-clear","date":"2019-09-14","title":"How long after prk does vision clear?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/how-long-after-prk-does-vision-clear","contentHtml":"<p>PRK laser eye procedure is preferred by millions of people in the world in one year to become independent of the contact lenses and glasses. The fact has to be accepted that PRK does take longer time to completely heal the area of treatment and achieve clearer vision. It is a bit longer compared to the other laser based surgical eye treatments. The reason for longer recovery time is that the PRK procedure removes the outer corneal tissue layer totally.</p>\n<p><strong>Vision after PRK</strong></p>\n<p>The epithelium or the skin layer takes some time for basic healing. During the period of recovery, the patient feels a bit discomfort and blurry vision is possible. Then the vision becomes a bit clear to feel enough comfort. On an overall, it takes a few months to perform day to day activities with enough ease. The overall vision can be bettered and the actual betterment of the vision will be evident in three months to six months after the surgery.</p>\n<p>The timeline for recovery after PRK procedure is as shown as the following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>After 1 to 3 days – slight irritation and mild discomfort are common, because of the removed tissue layer. Night driving is not advised during this period, because of the sensitivity of the eyes to the night lights. The patient has to lubricate the eyes with the eye drops, on regular basis.</li>\n<li>After 4 days to 1 week – slightly discomfort will keep subsiding and the vision becomes a hazy or a bit blurry, however, the vision will be better then and slowly to 20/40. In this period, protective contact lenses are taken out.</li>\n<li>After 1 week to 3 months – During this period, a new tissue of cornea will be grown back and the tissue becomes smoother. Slowly the vision will be improved. Still some halos or starbursts exist around bright lights and night driving must be avoided for a few weeks after the surgery.</li>\n<li>After 3 months to 6 months – This is the period, where the vision and the positive results of the procedure will be evident and the patient can get back to normal lifestyle with independent regular activities as before the procedure.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Precautions for Better Vision During Recovery</strong></p>\n<p>PRK procedure is performed basically for treating the refractive error called nearsightedness. So, after the procedure, recovery and better vision will be possible in between 3 to 6 months of duration. During this period, following certain precautions can help the recovery to be quick and harmless.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Discuss with your doctor regarding how do you suffer with nearsightedness and dry eye condition if any, so that prescription will be complete and according to your unique eye vision condition with necessary comparable remedies along with the regular artificial tears.</li>\n<li>If you feel uncomfortable with the post-operative lenses, inform the same with the doctor, so that suitable lenses will be applied so that healing can be expedited. If the lenses are still uncomfortable, let the doctor know your discomfort.</li>\n<li>Inflammation may be there but it is mild. If it goes a bit more comfortable, inform the same thing with your doctor, during the follow-up visits. Don’t take the steroids as the solution to this problem, as the process of healing may further be delayed.</li>\n<li>Ensure to chill the cornea, in case of any pain is experienced</li>\n<li>Give enough rest and time for the eyes for a few days for much better and clearer vision for life long.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>All these precautions can help preventing any complications during the recovery and healing process becomes faster.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>PRK laser eye procedure is preferred by millions of people in the world in one year to become independent of the contact lenses and glasses. The fact has to be accepted that PRK does take longer time to completely heal the area of treatment and achieve clearer vision. It is a bit longer compared to [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-much-does-prk-lasik-cost","date":"2019-09-14","title":"How much does PRK Lasik cost?","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/how-much-does-prk-lasik-cost","contentHtml":"<p>The cost of Lasik and PRK do vary because of the variation of the procedure and degree of depth of procedure, in correction of the refractive error of the eye. And the cost of the Lasik procedure is more than that of the PRK procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Cost of PRK</strong></p>\n<p>PRK or Photorefractive Keratectomy is also a surgical procedure with laser assistance and performed for refractive error corrections, like astigmatism, farsightedness and nearsightedness. This procedure is developed before approval of the Lasik and is almost the similar procedure as Lasik. Compared to the Lasik, PRK is less expensive. The cost of PRK procedure is around $1700 for each eye, which includes the procedure fee of $500, facility fee of $900 and follow-up and preoperative fee of $300.</p>\n<p><strong>Cost of Lasik</strong></p>\n<p>The cost of Lasik eye surgery is $2000 for one eye, in the United States. The cost for both the eyes is double this cost. Usually hospitals advertise the cost applied for the mild nearsightedness and with the farsightedness and astigmatism or more nearsightedness, this cost keeps increasing far more than the advertised price.</p>\n<p><strong>Cost Variation</strong></p>\n<p>Though some costs of the surgeries are specified, it varies between two hospitals even within the same city. It is because of the fact there are different factors that cumulate the total cost of the surgery.</p>\n<p>These factors can be like the experience of the surgeon and the standards followed by the hospital to practise the surgical procedure. Other important factor is the technology adopted to conduct the surgery. Wavefront technology is more advanced technology employed to perform most precise corrosion of vision possible. Usually there are two different prices for excimer laser and femtosecond laser. Some of the hospitals charge the price of the laser procedure according to the refractive error found after primary examination.</p>\n<p>The price advertised does not also cover the all the associated fee for medical services. For example, it does not cover cost of the additional post-operative care. The price offered is only for limited visits of follow-up and further visits will be paid visits. Any further retreatment or enhancement surgeries are not included as they are not mandatorily performed.</p>\n<p>Some hospitals also offer the same surgery for around $500 also. But such procedures are usually do not include bladeless or laser procedures. So, it is quite important that after the first consultation in the hospital, one should get the breakdown of the cost of each medical service obtained, including the names of the technologies and equipment used. It is not surprising that there can be variation of 50% and it varies from hospital to another.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The cost of Lasik and PRK do vary because of the variation of the procedure and degree of depth of procedure, in correction of the refractive error of the eye. And the cost of the Lasik procedure is more than that of the PRK procedure. Cost of PRK PRK or Photorefractive Keratectomy is also a [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-are-the-disadvantages-of-laser-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"What are the disadvantages of laser eye surgery?","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/what-are-the-disadvantages-of-laser-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>When laser eye surgery is considered, the one that flashes in the mind is the Lasik surgery, because of the familiarity and the frequency of choice of the potential laser eye surgery patients. There are two other laser eye surgeries, named PRK and SMILE, which are preferred to perform only at customized or specific eye vision conditions. The success rate of the Lasik laser eye surgery is very high, however, there are also certain drawbacks or disadvantages associated with the Lasik laser eye surgery.</p>\n<p>Apart from various advantages associated with the Lasik eye surgeries, the following are some possible disadvantages of the same.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Technically, there is a possibility of loss of best vision and this condition is very rare. The best vision can still be achieved in addition with the contact lenses or eye glasses.</li>\n<li>In case any changes made to the cornea are done in wrong way, the changes will be permanent and so the respective bad results too.</li>\n<li>Lasik is a complex procedure technically. There may be certain rare cases possible, such as creation of flap, by the surgeon and in such cases vision gets affected permanently. So, selection of the experienced surgeon becomes a key to success of the surgery.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Despite the above disadvantages, there are certain symptoms that are common after the surgery during the recovery period. If these symptoms are persistent even after the recovery period, which is beyond 6 months, then these symptoms can be considered and interpreted as the side effects. So, the symptoms are the following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Dry eyes</li>\n<li>Difficulty for night driving</li>\n<li>Glare</li>\n<li>Fluctuating vision</li>\n<li>Seeing starbursts and halos around the bright lights and images</li>\n<li>Disturbances and discomfort of vision temporarily</li>\n<li>Complications related to the flaps</li>\n<li>Remarkable overcorrection, regression or undercorrection</li>\n<li>Eye infections</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The disadvantages mentioned in the above list are not regular list of negative results, but possible symptoms. In any instances, any deviating condition is considered as a symptom and it is considered as a side effect and severe, only if the same condition is continued even after the recovery period. In case of complications, these can be identified immediately, usually during the follow-up visits.</p>\n<p>On an overall though there are possible disadvantages technically, these are the common disadvantages associated with any surgeries. So, to increase the success rate, selection of the experienced surgeon and standard medical center play vital role along with the post surgery care.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>When laser eye surgery is considered, the one that flashes in the mind is the Lasik surgery, because of the familiarity and the frequency of choice of the potential laser eye surgery patients. There are two other laser eye surgeries, named PRK and SMILE, which are preferred to perform only at customized or specific eye [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"does-lasik-wear-off","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Does lasik wear off?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/does-lasik-wear-off","contentHtml":"<p>There are so many myths built around the Lasik eye surgery, firstly because it is a new technology and secondly it is related with the eye, which is the most sensitive organ of the body. There is nothing wrong having the concern as it helps to clear the concern to start trusting the medical technology.</p>\n<p><strong>So, Does Lasik Wear Off?</strong></p>\n<p>Coming to the facts, the Lasik effects are mostly permanent and in majority of the cases, it indefinitely lasts, in unfavourable circumstances. During the Lasik eye surgery for astigmatism, farsightedness or nearsightedness, the shape of the cornea is changed with the help of the excimer laser. Cornea is an outer eye structure. The changes made over the eye are physical and technically, the changes are permanent.</p>\n<p><strong>What About Exceptions?</strong></p>\n<p>Exceptions are always there like, with any surgical procedure. A minor percentage of the patients, approximately, about less than 3% of them have their natural healing system a bit lower compared to the rest of the patients. And the exception here does not mean failure, but not 100%. In such cases, there would be still scope of getting accurate and better results. They have the solution of going through the Lasik enhancement treatment. The need for the enhancement surgery is not determined immediately after the surgery, as the healing process that takes considerable time, for a few months determine the overall success rate of the Lasik surgery, for that person. So, the need for it can be determined within 12 months of duration after the surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Any Come Backs?</strong></p>\n<p>When the Lasik surgery is technically successfully, ideally, there should be no come back of vision or refractive errors. However, based on unique body conditions and lifestyles of the patients, it is possible that a small percentage of the patients have the probability of developing nearsightedness or myopia, in a small degree. Usually, this condition is possible for the students, who make intense study during small durations, in their 20s. The change is natural, because of the eyeball lengthening, but not because of the technical failure or problem associated with the Lasik surgery. Lasik makes the changes of cornea permanent and any other factors can contribute the need for enhancement procedure. So, natural wear off does not mean Lasik wear off.</p>\n<p><strong>Any Other Factors</strong></p>\n<p>There are other factors that determine the overall vision of the eye and the first factor to consider is the age of a person. As the age progresses, the condition of Presbyopia is quite common for the people, who go through lesser accuracy of vision. This condition has the syndrome called dysfunctional lens syndrome. The change usually starts at 40s of the people. The condition gets severe as the human reaches to 50s and 60s. The condition of Presbyopia is possible for any human being in the world, irrespective of undergoing or not undergoing the Lasik eye surgery.</p>\n<p>Hence, ideally, Lasik does not wear off if the positive effects are retained well, with healthy lifestyle, in terms of preserving the eye vision with necessary related nutrition.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>There are so many myths built around the Lasik eye surgery, firstly because it is a new technology and secondly it is related with the eye, which is the most sensitive organ of the body. There is nothing wrong having the concern as it helps to clear the concern to start trusting the medical technology. [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-age-is-recommended-for-laser-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"What age is recommended for laser eye surgery?","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/what-age-is-recommended-for-laser-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>There is no much as age concern with the Lasik surgery, anyone who is above the age of 18 would be qualified to go through the surgery. However, most often people and doctors prefer the age between 20 to 40 and consider this age as the ideal age to go through the Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Facts Relating to Age</strong></p>\n<p>Technically, any human with the age of 18 person can go through the Lasik surgery, without any complications. However, most of the doctors prefer to cross 20 years and reach at least mid of 20, since the eye vision prescription keeps changing for anyone till this age. If it is mandate to go for the procedure, another factor is taken into consideration that the person should have a stable prescription consistently for two previous years. This factor is important for anyone no matter old or young, to be a good candidate for the Lasik eye surgery.  Age after 18 does not limit the level of absolute boundary, though age impacts the candidacy. Other important factors are the stable health along with the stable prescription.</p>\n<p><strong>Between 18 to 24 Years</strong></p>\n<p>This is the age, where the eyesight keeps changing consistently. Hence, usually, Lasik surgery waits for this period, until the end of 24 and decision is taken only after careful vision history consideration. Still if the contact lens or eye glasses stand stable for more than two years, this concern would not be anymore.</p>\n<p>The other dimension to look at is the profession of the people. In addition to the stable prescription, if one is in or wants to get into the profession of sports, military or law enforcement, surgeons consider the Lasik procedure for them.</p>\n<p><strong>Between 25 to 40 Years</strong></p>\n<p>So, most of the surgeons consider this age group is the ideal candidacy eligibility for the Lasik procedure. It is because, by 25 years, the eye prescription becomes stable and in most of the cases it does not change.</p>\n<p><strong>Between 40 to 55 Years</strong></p>\n<p>The eye prescription keeps changing after 40 years again. So, after forties, people though enjoyed perfect eye vision, start experiencing tough time reading and driving and start thinking of the glasses. They can prefer this Lasik procedure, which enable them to spend the rest of the life without contact lens or eye glasses, mostly. People are still eligible for this procedure, if they have stable health.</p>\n<p>The other factor that influences the positive decision of the procedure is the family history that may be glaucoma, diabetes or any corneal disorders. Such diseases can decrease the likelihood of being eligible for the Lasik eye surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>After 55 Years</strong></p>\n<p>Though there is no limit for the age to undergo the Lasik surgery, there are many factors should be taken into consideration towards the success of the Lasik procedure and correction of the refractive errors.</p>\n<p>One important factor that influence the decision is the cataracts. In case the cataracts started developing after 60s, first and foremost action should be taken is to treat the cataracts surgically initially and then can go for the Lasik procedure. People with no cataracts and clear eyes can go still be eligible candidates for the Lasik procedure.</p>\n<p>Having understood the technical factors, now, one can easily decide who are and who are not the ideal candidates for the Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>There is no much as age concern with the Lasik surgery, anyone who is above the age of 18 would be qualified to go through the surgery. However, most often people and doctors prefer the age between 20 to 40 and consider this age as the ideal age to go through the Lasik surgery. Facts [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"does-lasik-last-forever","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Does lasik last forever?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/does-lasik-last-forever","contentHtml":"<p>Just before taking the decision to go through Lasik surgery, the last but least thought arise, which helps to explore the life of the Lasik surgery results. It is still a good question to pose and explore the answer.</p>\n<p>Technically, the answer for the question, does Lasik last forever is no. however, the changes after the Lasik procedure is not under control of the Lasik procedure. So, no medical center can assure that the effects and results of the Lasik are permanent for life long. The problem is not with the Lasik procedure, but with the age and lifestyle of the patient, who has undergone the surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Why Change In Vision In Future?</strong></p>\n<p>The changes possible with the eye vision prescription are because of the changes of the lens, which decide the refraction and form the image on the retina of the eye. The functions of cornea, which is involved in the Lasik procedure and lens are independent processes and not interdependent.</p>\n<p><strong>What Lasik Does?</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik surgery involves the procedure of reshaping the cornea of the eye. Lasik procedure is completely a safe procedure, with very few risks possible. However, the chances of regression of the eyes are undeniable after years of the surgery. Regression after Lasik is possible in cases where the condition of cornea returns to the shape it was, either fully or partially. Regression however is possible in the vision with time, because of natural changes in the eye.</p>\n<p><strong>Post Lasik Regression</strong></p>\n<p>The reasons for the resulting regression are not known. However, the condition can be bettered by performing the Lasik procedure one more time, to make the results permanent. These changes must be accepted and initiate further corrections. It is better to visit the doctor, whenever the changes are evident and can go for either Lasik enhancement procedure or prefer to wear contact lens or eye glasses.</p>\n<p><strong>Can Regression Be Avoided?</strong></p>\n<p>Though no one can guarantee that regression can be totally prevented, the outcome of the Lasik procedure can be optimized by following the guidelines.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Go to only experienced surgeon and undergo the Lasik procedure. It is important as each and every unique condition of the patient is considered by the doctor and each session is tailored according to the needs of the individuals.</li>\n<li>Honestly, reveal all the details of the condition of eye and vision and also make sure that you inform about the family health history carefully and accurately to the doctor. Answer each and every question very clearly.</li>\n<li>Follow the guidelines of the doctor post surgery, during the recovery period, because after all the eyes are the most sensitive organs of the body and demand utmost care.</li>\n<li>Ensure eye examination yearly and communicate even small changes in the eye vision.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>On an overall, the success rate of the Lasik procedure and length of the positive results are highly dependent on internal and external factors. Ensure to follow internal factors and choose external factors carefully.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Just before taking the decision to go through Lasik surgery, the last but least thought arise, which helps to explore the life of the Lasik surgery results. It is still a good question to pose and explore the answer. Technically, the answer for the question, does Lasik last forever is no. however, the changes after [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-does-lasik-procedure-last","date":"2019-09-14","title":"How long does lasik procedure last?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/how-long-does-lasik-procedure-last","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik is a laser eye surgery performed with the advanced technology and equipment. The key of the procedure is the laser. The procedure is very advanced but completed in very little time, because of the usage of advanced and sophisticated equipment.</p>\n<p><strong>Time Taken For Lasik </strong></p>\n<p>The total Lasik procedure needs less than 10 minutes for each of the eye. In these 10 minutes, the core process takes only 20 seconds to 50 seconds to perform the corrections for each of the eye. One needs to prepare to stay in the hospital for at least one and half hours totally.</p>\n<p><strong>Before the Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>One has to reach the hospital before 30 minutes to 1 hour, the procedure starts. Eye drops are initially applied to get the eye numb, so that any kind of pain would not be occurred. These drops help to reduce any impulse to blink the eye.</p>\n<p>Then in a couple of minutes, a small device called precision flap-making instrument is held to hold the eyelids enough open to perform the surgery. Then eye tracker is connected to the monitor. It helps to track the position of the eye. The same device compensates any possible eye movements done involuntarily, so that the laser is focused on the right site and spot. This arrangement is needed to ensure that the eyes are not blinked and any involuntary movements occur to the eye. the patient will be asked to focus over light, fixed specially for this purpose. Then the precision instrument is then activated and reveals the middle cornea layer, after folding the corneal flap. Setting all these arrangements would take about 5 minutes.</p>\n<p><strong>During the Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>During the procedure, the cornea is attempted to reshape. The procedure of reshaping is different for different refractive error procedure.</p>\n<p>For treating nearsightedness or myopia, flattening of cornea is attempted so that the eye converging power can be reduced. It involves removing the excess tissue from the central part of and around the cornea.</p>\n<p>For treating farsightedness or hyperopia, the eye converging power is enhanced, through steepening the central cornea. The same is achieved through removal of excess tissue, not from the center but the periphery area.</p>\n<p>For treating astigmatism, removal of tissue is performed usually in one direction, by making the cornea as uniformly curved or shape of spherical.</p>\n<p>After any one of the procedure is completed, corneal flap is positioned to back. The flap is held naturally in place, till the completion of surface healing</p>\n<p>Any one of this procedure takes total of 5 to 7 minutes for each of the eye.</p>\n<p><strong>After the Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>Once the procedure is over, the patient is held for a moment and is brought to the recovery area. The vision becomes blur and nothing to worry, as it is continued for only a few minutes. The patient has to be accompanied by another person to take home, without needing them to drive.</p>\n<p>So, on an overall, the procedure can be completed within 20 minutes and one can get back home in one hour.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik is a laser eye surgery performed with the advanced technology and equipment. The key of the procedure is the laser. The procedure is very advanced but completed in very little time, because of the usage of advanced and sophisticated equipment. Time Taken For Lasik The total Lasik procedure needs less than 10 minutes for [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"does-laser-eye-surgery-hurt","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Does laser eye surgery hurt?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/does-laser-eye-surgery-hurt","contentHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery helps to improve the quality of human life, by improving the eye vision. Despite the benefits of the surgery, the fear of pain worries many people and make them hesitate to go through the procedure.</p>\n<p>One has to realize and understand that laser eye surgery cannot be painful as the procedure does not make use of the blades or incision into the skin. The procedure gives a bit discomfort it is minimal, if no fear is added, it can be very easily ignored. The experience and discomfort are different for different kinds of procedures, Lasik, Lasek and SMILE.</p>\n<p><strong>Lasik Laser Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik is the most commonly performed surgical procedure and takes overall 15 minutes of time. Prior to the surgery, anaesthetic eye drops are given to the eyes and it prevents from causing any pain to the patient. Even after the surgery, there is no question of pain as there is no incision or usage of blade in this procedure. During the procedure, there may be slight discomfort and it is minimal that can even be ignored, if one is out of fear. Lasik is trust by majority of people and has faster recovery time.</p>\n<p>During the surgery, femtosecond laser is used to enable the microscopic pulses to be directed at the upper cornea layer. It creates bubbles and also flap forming the corneal tissue. This flap is lifted gently by the surgeon to expose the tissue’s deeper layers. Then cornea is reshaped by using excimer laser thereby correcting the eye’s refractive errors. Then the flap would be replaced and it gets healed by itself. Lasik can correct the refraction errors like astigmatism, hyperopia, myopia and also wave-front abnormalities. More than 90% of the Lasik patients enjoy the positive results of the surgery, consistently.</p>\n<p><strong>Lasek Surgery </strong></p>\n<p>Lasek is a good alternative for the patient, who cannot undergo Lasik procedure. People with too flat and too thin corneas are not suitable for Lasik procedure and have to look for alternative procedures like PRK or Lasek. The procedure is similar to the Lasik and so performed with the laser beam. Hence, there is no pain felt in this surgery too, since anaesthetic eye drops are used.</p>\n<p>During the Lasek treatment, gentle ethanol solution is used to soften the cornea’s outer layer and detaches the cornea from the underneath layers. Then the deeper corneal tissues are exposed, by moving the outer layer aside. The next step is to reshape the cornea with excimer laser. After correction of refractive error is done, outer corneal layer will be replaced by the surgeon. After the surgery, bandage contact lenses are worn to protect the eye from external environment and heal without any such disturbances.</p>\n<p><strong>SMILE Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>SMILE is one fo the latest laser eye surgery and corrects myopia of higher degrees combined with or without astigmatism. This procedure is also initiated after appling the anaesthetic eye drops. Among these three procedures, this procedure is less invasive and involves like a keyhole surgery. So, many people prefer this one for correction of myopia.</p>\n<p>The procedure is performed by using a laser that directs microscopic pulse series towards the cornea’s central part. The result of the pulses is tiny bubbles, indicating the tissue that has to be removed for cornea reshape. This non-invasive technique is quick and gives least discomfort among the three procedures.</p>\n<p>In a nutshell, none of these three procedures hurt the eye and are painless.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery helps to improve the quality of human life, by improving the eye vision. Despite the benefits of the surgery, the fear of pain worries many people and make them hesitate to go through the procedure. One has to realize and understand that laser eye surgery cannot be painful as the procedure does [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-much-does-lasik-cost-in-india","date":"2019-09-14","title":"How much does lasik cost in India?","category":"LASIK Cost","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/how-much-does-lasik-cost-in-india","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik laser eye surgery is a potential option of treatment for the patients, who wish to get rid of the lens and glasses and still enjoy better vision. The cost of the Lasik surgery is not the same in two medical eye centers. It varies not only in between two cities, but also two medical centers in the same city. The overall cost varies according to multiple factors.</p>\n<p><strong>Lasik in India</strong></p>\n<p>When Lasik is considered in India, it can be a viable and preferable place in terms of advancement of technology and expertise ophthalmologists. Lasik has been added into the list of commonly surgeries performed, related to the eye surgeries, after the surgeries for cataract.</p>\n<p><strong>Cost in India</strong></p>\n<p>The variation of the cost is basically, on the expertise and experience of the surgeon. The more experienced the surgeon, the charges would be more for the surgery. In another dimension, the services offered including personalized services by the hospital also add up the charges on an overall.  Some of the centers even charge as low as 5,000 INR and it may also reach 1,00,000 INR.On an overall, cost of the Lasik in India with decent services can be INR 15,000. However, it is the basic price. The cost can even be more than double and reach INR 50,000 if some of the personal care charges are included.</p>\n<p>The cost of the Lasik surgery is not shared on the websites of even the hospitals. It is because of the reason that the overall cost of the surgery varies on the basis of multiple factors. These factors can be the age of the person and unique prescription of the patient. On the other hand, there are also some personalized services offered differently by different hospitals and the costs of each of these services in each of the hospital are different.</p>\n<p><strong>How the Overall Cost is Determined?</strong></p>\n<p>After the patient consults the ophthalmologist in a hospital, each and every details of the patient’s condition is recorded after pre-surgery assessments. Then the basic price of the surgery is determined on the basis of the requirements to be performed in the surgery. In addition to them, some of the specialized services offered by the hospitals and the respective service charges are imposed. Most of these services are regular services and cannot be avoided. It is not a good idea to bargain for the overall cost of the surgery, because then only every service specified by them, would be demanded. In other words, bargaining the cost may affect the overall quality of the surgery.</p>\n<p>So, Lasik laser eye surgery is available in India starting from 5,000 INR to 1,00,000 INR.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik laser eye surgery is a potential option of treatment for the patients, who wish to get rid of the lens and glasses and still enjoy better vision. The cost of the Lasik surgery is not the same in two medical eye centers. It varies not only in between two cities, but also two medical [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-my-prescription-suitable-for-laser-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Is my prescription suitable for laser eye surgery?","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/is-my-prescription-suitable-for-laser-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Though laser eye surgery is suitable for almost anyone within certain age limitation, ophthalmologists consider some important factors of the potential laser eye surgery patients, in terms of no complications arising post the laser surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Technical Factors</strong></p>\n<p>Apart from the general prescriptions and recommendations, ophthalmologists also look for some technical factors to be satisfied in order to obtain better vision results and also to reduce the complications.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Sphere Reading – Both the right eye and left eye sphere power reading are important to consider.</li>\n<li>Cylinder Reading – Both the right eye and left eye cylinder power reading are considered.</li>\n<li>Reading Addition – Bothe right and left eyes are considered, apart from the sphere and cylinder readings.</li>\n<li>Age – Though adult age is the minimum pre-requisite for the laser eye surgery, based on the age of the patient, the ophthalmologists predict the results of the surgery.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>While sphere and cylindrical readings are considered, plus and minus signs show the indication or severity of the eye vision problem. Minus sign indicates short sight and so plus sign indicates long sighted. Apart from these two signs, CYL indicates the condition of astigmatism. The term axis in this context shows the angle of astigmatism, however, it is not any condition that indicates suitability of the patient to the surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Prescription Table</strong></p>\n<p>Most of the ophthalmologists go with the following readings of short sight, long sight and astigmatism.</p>\n<p><strong>Short-Sight</strong></p>\n<p>Short sight, when exist within the range of -1 to -10, the person is eligible for the laser eye surgery. On the other hand, if the reading is in between -3 to -23, then lens implants are preferred.</p>\n<p><strong>Long-Sight</strong></p>\n<p>When the long sight is concerned, the readings are a bit different from the short sight. For long sight the readings are preferred from +1 to +6, for laser eye surgery. And in case the reading is from +3 to +11, lens implants are preferred mostly.</p>\n<p><strong>Astigmatism </strong></p>\n<p>The condition of astigmatism with the readings in between 1 to 5, shows indication of the laser eye surgery suitability. On the other hand, the values in between 3 to 8 indicate lens implants preference.</p>\n<p>When the prescription indicates +1to +2, it is suitable for the monovision laser eye surgery.</p>\n<p>Apart from these conditions, ophthalmologists also consider the following conditions to cater special and peculiar precautions before, during and after the surgery.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Increased eye pressure internally that has to be maintained under control</li>\n<li>Blepharitis, one kind of eye infection that needs to be cleared for the surgery</li>\n<li>Diabetes, which needs to be under control during the surgery</li>\n<li>Epilepsy or dry eye condition to be taken care well from right after the surgery</li>\n<li>Pupils in larger size that need to be corrected</li>\n<li>Prescription to be lower, lesser than 0.75 with no astigmatism</li>\n<li>Pregnancy or breast feeding condition, which demand some more time to give before the surgery</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The above are the conditions, where one can check the suitability of the laser eye surgery, in most of the conditions. However, one’s ophthalmologist is the best person to decide finally, about whether one is suitable for the laser eye surgery or not.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Though laser eye surgery is suitable for almost anyone within certain age limitation, ophthalmologists consider some important factors of the potential laser eye surgery patients, in terms of no complications arising post the laser surgery. Technical Factors Apart from the general prescriptions and recommendations, ophthalmologists also look for some technical factors to be satisfied in [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"do-specsavers-do-laser-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Do specsavers do laser eye surgery?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/do-specsavers-do-laser-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery is an advanced laser based procedure and it needs expertise surgeon and advanced technical equipment to conduct the surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Who Are Specsavers?</strong></p>\n<p>Specsavers is a chain of opticians and are famous in the UK. It supplies about 30% of the spectacles in the UK. It is one of the first companies preferred by the people for the eye glasses.</p>\n<p><strong>Do Specsavers Perform the Surgery?</strong></p>\n<p>Though specsavers have the opticians, who have the capability and expertise to perform the laser eye surgery, most of these clinics do not offer to perform laser eye surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>So, How Do Specsavers Help in this Context?</strong></p>\n<p>Specsavers offer the services of eye examinations. Specsavers do not offer to perform the surgery directly, however, the eye test done by them is most of the times accurate and it helps the pre-surgery assessment to decide, whether one has to go through the laser procedure or not.</p>\n<p>They offer various tests in different procedures that include checking for glaucoma, by using non-contact tonometers. The focus of the eyes is tested by them with the accurate and advanced autorefractor and reading a test chart. Outer surface of the eye examination is offered by them and they make use of slit lamp to test and assess the same.</p>\n<p>These tests and assessments are accurate most of the time, since a detailed questionnaire is attached along with the technical tests. The questionnaire helps the ophthalmologists to analyze and understand the lifestyle of the patients. A detailed technical eye assessment combined with the lifestyle facts can make out the accurate decision, whether one is eligible for the laser eye surgery or not.</p>\n<p><strong>How It Helps Lasik Treatment?</strong></p>\n<p>Specsavers are specialists as they offer specialized and total eye examination, including the post Lasik laser eye surgery, in long term. The tests and results are totally unbiased and it helps not only the ophthalmologists, but also the patient to analyze the conditions of the eyes accurately for reassurance of the decision. So, if it is possible and Specsavers is nearby the patient, it is always a better idea to get the eye examination done once, as a benefit of doubt and for better second opinion to decide, whether one needs the laser eye surgery or not.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery is an advanced laser based procedure and it needs expertise surgeon and advanced technical equipment to conduct the surgery. Who Are Specsavers? Specsavers is a chain of opticians and are famous in the UK. It supplies about 30% of the spectacles in the UK. It is one of the first companies preferred [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-laser-eye-surgery-safe","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Is laser eye surgery safe?","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/is-laser-eye-surgery-safe","contentHtml":"<p>As the term surgery sounds as a big, dangerous and complicated term, it may sound unsafe or filled with complications to anyone. The term laser, which is a far more complicated, because of the new technology, added to this term surgery gives some more complication to the laser eye surgery. However, this is not the case and it is not unsafe, but less complicated compared to any other surgery in the medical industry. One fact that is worth reminding is that every surgery has its own pros and cons.</p>\n<p><strong>What Medical Industry &amp; Experts Say?</strong></p>\n<p>The medical industry and medical experts emphasize that the laser eye surgery is one of the safest and elective surgery existing in the contemporary world. Laser may sound a bit advanced technology, however this technology exists from 30 years and is well established in most of the countries. Several clinical studies conducted in many countries indicate and show that each of the procedure for correction of the vision using laser is completely safe, with evidences. It is absolutely safe and effective for the surgery qualified patients. One needs to ensure that the person is the right candidate to go through the laser eye surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Facts &amp; Figures</strong></p>\n<p>Thousands of studies conducted in analysing the safety and effectiveness of the laser eye surgeries in terms of correcting the refractive errors. So far more than 16 million people have got the Lasik eye surgery performed for better vision. Recently the best 97 studies out of these thousands of studies have been analyzed in terms of safety and efficacy of the laser eye surgery. The study considered 67,893 eyes treated with Lasik laser eye surgery. The results are as the following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Almost close to 100% of the Lasik eyes operated with the laser eye surgery have been satisfied the standards of legal driving.</li>\n<li>More than 90% of the patients have achieved the perfect vision, indicated with 20/20 vision.</li>\n<li>More than 99% of the patients have the clarity of vision and less than 1% has missed the clarity of vision of two line or more in terms of corrected distance visual acuity.</li>\n<li>Close to 99% of the Lasik patients are happier for the results obtained, in terms of better vision</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Apart from the Lasik eye surgery, which is the most commonly performed one, the other laser eye surgeries are ASLA, SMILE, LASEK and PRK. These surgeries are newer compared to Lasik surgery, except the PRK. Including Lasik, all these laser eye surgeries are approved by the respective medical governing bodies, of each of the country.</p>\n<p>In addition to the facts, the results also have indicated the possible risks and side-effects possible with inaccurate or unsuccessful surgery or with lesser post-surgery care. The possible risks are the following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Dry Eye condition, in which the eyes dry up faster and it needs frequent lubrication</li>\n<li>Loss of vision sharpness, initially immediately after the surgery, but the condition gets resolved within 6 months, in most of the cases</li>\n<li>Under or over refractive error correction during the surgery, which can be corrected with additional enhancement surgery, possible technically</li>\n<li>Flap problems triggered with rubbing the eyes accidentally</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The risks and complications are quite common with any surgery and the experts emphasize that risks and complications associated with the laser eye surgery are much lesser compared to any other surgery, where blade or incision is used.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>As the term surgery sounds as a big, dangerous and complicated term, it may sound unsafe or filled with complications to anyone. The term laser, which is a far more complicated, because of the new technology, added to this term surgery gives some more complication to the laser eye surgery. However, this is not the [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-much-is-laser-eye-treatment","date":"2019-09-14","title":"How much is laser eye treatment?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/how-much-is-laser-eye-treatment","contentHtml":"<p>The laser eye treatment with laser eye surgery costs different in different countries or even in neighbourhood hospitals within the same city. The reason for variation of the cost is the involvement of multiple factors.</p>\n<p><strong>Facts &amp; Figures </strong></p>\n<p>According to an analytics company, leading vision care industry and its report, all about vision, the cost of the Lasik laser eye surgery in the US is $2,100 approximately and it is a bit higher compared to the previous years. The cost specified above is per one eye and the Lasik laser eye surgery is one of the commonly performed one, compared to the other laser eye surgeries, like PRK, Lasek, SMILE, etc. The cost specified here is an average cost and it varies widely, among several hospitals within the same city.</p>\n<p><strong>What Are Cost Factors?</strong></p>\n<p>The overall and final cost of the laser eye surgery varies on the basis of multiple factors.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Reputation, expertise and experience of the surgeon stand as the major cost contributing factor.</li>\n<li>Technology is another important major factor. Most of the reputed and experienced surgeons charge the charges for the vision correction procedures that are based on the excimer laser based. Others also make use of the femtosecond laser for the laser procedure, which is bladeless</li>\n<li>Technology is another important factor.</li>\n<li>About one fifth of the surgeons charge varied price on the basis of the specific technology adapted for the surgery. For instance, the charges are more for all kinds of custom Lasik or laser Lasik, employing the new technology called wavefront technology, for accurate and precise possible vision correction.</li>\n<li>Refractive error is also an important factor. The cost of the overall surgery varies on the basis of the refractive error of the patient also, however, the percent of variation is less compared to the above factors.</li>\n<li>Additional charges or assurance charges may also be imposed in the overall cost of the surgery. Sometimes corrective procedures are also offered by the same medical center post laser eye surgery, such as enhancement eye surgery. Usually, these procedures are needed in case the patient feels unsatisfied with the betterment of the vision. It is important to address the corrective procedures, if become necessary and ideally, no additional charge must be imposed for this procedure, as it is the result from inaccurate laser eye surgical procedure. So, some medical centers impose these charges in the overall cost of the surgery and offer the enhancement procedures for free of cost, if needed in the future.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>After the pre-surgery eye test and assessment, the overall cost of the preferred laser eye surgery is given to the patient. And the patient should ask for the breakup of the overall cost, to check whether the post operative procedures and follow-up visit charges are included or not.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The laser eye treatment with laser eye surgery costs different in different countries or even in neighbourhood hospitals within the same city. The reason for variation of the cost is the involvement of multiple factors. Facts &amp; Figures According to an analytics company, leading vision care industry and its report, all about vision, the cost [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-get-free-laser-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can i get free laser eye surgery?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-i-get-free-laser-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik laser eye surgery, growing popular, more and more people started opting to go for this surgery towards correction of the refraction errors. This procedure is less risky and less painful, relatively with faster and better results and help to get rid of the contact lens or eye glasses. Refractive errors are quite common with the age and these eye vision problems have been growing with the increased usage of the digital screens in day to day lives. The surgery starts from $1,000 INR and it is much more in the sophisticated medical centers, but not everyone can afford this amount, so it is usual for the people to look for the free laser eye surgery services.</p>\n<p><strong>Can I Get Free Lasik?</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik laser eye surgery is a much advanced, yet less complicated surgery to perform. The surgery does not take much time and can be finished within 30 minutes for both the eyes. However, the technology is advanced and equipment is expensive. Hence, in most of the cases, so far none is offering the Lasik laser eye surgery for free of cost.</p>\n<p>Though Lasik is not available for free of cost, the overall cost can be reduced to a certain extent, because some of the medical centers can offer free Lasik consultancy. They charge nothing, until Lasik procedure takes place.</p>\n<p>On the other hand, some of the medical centers or hospitals offer this laser eye surgery for lesser cost, because of the competition. It is not the case everywhere and every hospital.</p>\n<p><strong>Any Alternatives?</strong></p>\n<p>Yes, there can be some alternatives, like finding some financial support from the insurance companies. Not all the insurance companies offer the Lasik laser eye surgery. One needs to check with the insurance companies and only after ensuring that it offers the Lasik surgery, it is good to go.</p>\n<p>Alternatively, there are some non government organizations, which offer free eye surgeries and treatments and Lasik may be offered as part of the same. Such opportunity is a bit rare, because Lasik is an expensive procedure and can be performed using only expensive and advanced technology equipment.</p>\n<p>So, for no medical center, offering free Lasik laser eye surgery is difficult. In certain cases they may offer, like as part of the promotional programs. In case you happen to see any of such offers, be very careful to ensure the standards of the medical center and expertise of the surgeon, because eyes are the most sensitive organs in the body and so not worth experiments.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik laser eye surgery, growing popular, more and more people started opting to go for this surgery towards correction of the refraction errors. This procedure is less risky and less painful, relatively with faster and better results and help to get rid of the contact lens or eye glasses. Refractive errors are quite common with [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-lasik-cure-astigmatism","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can lasik cure astigmatism?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-lasik-cure-astigmatism","contentHtml":"<p>The direct answer for the question can Lasik cure astigmatism, is yes. Lasik not only cures the vision refractive errors near-sightedness, far-sightedness, but also astigmatism.</p>\n<p><strong>What is Astigmatism?</strong></p>\n<p>Sometimes astigmatism is misunderstood as stigmatism, and there is no relation or similarities in between them. Astigmatism is quite common problem of vision, just like near-sightedness and far-sightedness. Usually, it is caused by the eye’s cornea’s front surface that is in asymmetrical shape. Visually, cornea looks like an American football shape, instead of the baseball shape. When the eye gets affected with astigmatism, it does not look like ping-pong ball, but looks like back of spoon or egg. The condition is technically a problem associated with the focusing of light of the eye.</p>\n<p>An astigmatic eye disturbs the clear vision, as the light fails to a single focus over the retina. Rather than focusing on the retina, there would be occurrence of multiple focus points either behind the retina or in front of it or both. The results are distorted or blurred vision at all distances, to certain degree.</p>\n<p><strong>Symptoms of Astigmatism</strong></p>\n<p>The most common symptoms are headaches and eye strain, especially after prolonged visual tasks or reading. Sometimes squinting symptoms also stands as a quite common one. Recent studies indicate that schoolchildren get affected with astigmatism.</p>\n<p><strong>Causes of Astigmatism</strong></p>\n<p>The definition of astigmatism is imprecise, through it is not developed genetically. This condition accompanies usually hyperopia or myopia. The combinations are three kinds.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Hyperopic astigmatism is a condition, where either one meridian or both of them would be farsighted.</li>\n<li>Myopic astigmatism is a condition, either one meridian or both of them would get nearsighted.</li>\n<li>Mixed astigmatism is a condition, where one meridian gets hyperopic and another one gets hyperopic.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>When an eye is affected with the astigmatism, mostly it does not exceed the magnitude of 3.0 D (dioptres). In such cases the problem can be corrected through one Lasik procedure. When astigmatism is in initial condition, it is not necessary to go for Lasik laser and can manage with the eye glasses or contact lens.</p>\n<p><strong>Lasik for Astigmatism</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik uses an ultra-precise laser, which can be programmed for reshaping the cornea to make the front eye surface to be more symmetrical. However, not all the astigmatism conditions can be cured with the Lasik surgery. For example, irregular astigmatism cannot be operated and corrected by Lasik. And for keratoconus condition, where the shape of cornea bulges to be a cone, resulting in astigmatism, Lasik is not the solution. So, for the candidacy for Lasik for astigmatism treatment should be decided by a qualified Lasik specialist.</p>\n<p>When the astigmatism is more prominent, usually, one Lasik surgery does not suffice and so further Lasik enhancement surgeries would be needed as part of follow-up, sometimes, towards fine-turning the correction.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The direct answer for the question can Lasik cure astigmatism, is yes. Lasik not only cures the vision refractive errors near-sightedness, far-sightedness, but also astigmatism. What is Astigmatism? Sometimes astigmatism is misunderstood as stigmatism, and there is no relation or similarities in between them. Astigmatism is quite common problem of vision, just like near-sightedness and [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-an-eye-astigmatism-get-worse","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can an eye astigmatism get worse?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-an-eye-astigmatism-get-worse","contentHtml":"<p>Astigmatism is one of the problems of vision, which does not get cured without the treatment. If it is left untreated, there are quite chances that quality of the vision keeps declining with the age. However, the decline or deterioration of vision happens very slowly, but sure to happen. When it reaches to a certain degree, it would be difficult for the patient to ignore its effects. Astigmatism is only condition of decline of vision, but not any disease associated with either eyes or overall body. The difference with the vision is that it becomes more blur than before.</p>\n<p><strong>Symptoms and Depth Perception</strong></p>\n<p>When astigmatism condition is started, one feels eyestrain or fatigue, initially. There is some disturbance one observes in terms of clear vision, not able to figure out the things exactly as before.</p>\n<p>Depth perception stands as an ability of an eye to look and observe the things in the world, in three dimensions. There are certain issues related to depth perception and include difficulty in determining distance between two objects or opposite object’s proximity.</p>\n<p>When astigmatism is affected to an eye, the lack of depth perception becomes a common and more likely symptom. Eventually, this condition creates a severe imbalance feeling. As a result, the outlines of the objects look blur. Blur is common and depth perception may or may not be added to this condition, however, the overall vision quality becomes poor.</p>\n<p><strong>Diagnosis</strong></p>\n<p>The condition of astigmatism is an indication that the eye is not round completely. Everyone has this problem, but it is within acceptable and tolerable degree. But when it increases to higher degree, the symptoms get started. This condition of eye is checked with a thorough eye exam. In most of the cases, the disturbance can be with the nearsightedness or farsightedness. So, after initial eye exam, the problem will be diagnosed and the treatment is prescribed.</p>\n<p><strong>Treatment</strong></p>\n<p>When the astigmatism is in initial condition, then eye glasses or contact lens can solve the problem and enable one to look without blur. And the condition may become worse over a period of time. Eventually, the overall vision gets affected. In such cases, advanced treatment may become necessary. Lasik is one of the potential treatments to cure the problem of astigmatism. This treatment corrects the shape of the cornea and resolve the issues related with depth perception and other blurring of images. And this treatment is recommended by the surgeons, only if astigmatism is in advanced stage and if it cannot be managed with wearing the eye glasses.</p>\n<p>Laser vision correction can resolve most of the problems associated with the astigmatism and the vision becomes clear in a month after the surgery. The recovery period for Lasik is less compared to the other ones. During the recovery period, eyes must be protected very well and should not impose any physical pressure on it.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Astigmatism is one of the problems of vision, which does not get cured without the treatment. If it is left untreated, there are quite chances that quality of the vision keeps declining with the age. However, the decline or deterioration of vision happens very slowly, but sure to happen. When it reaches to a certain [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-astigmatism-be-corrected-naturally","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can astigmatism be corrected naturally?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-astigmatism-be-corrected-naturally","contentHtml":"<p>Astigmatism is a condition, where the shape of cornea becomes irregular. It is different from other vision refractive errors, like nearsightedness and farsightedness. With astigmatism, when the light is focused, it gets distorted and refracted to various focal points differently within the eye. It results in the problems with the vision, both far and near.</p>\n<p>Like any other health related problem, astigmatism also can be cured, when it is in the initial stages. Recent studies have found that many of the school going children start getting this problem with the vision and it is important to identify at the earlier stages and control it against growing worse.</p>\n<p>Types of Astigmatism</p>\n<p>There are two different kinds of astigmatism, called</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Irregular astigmatism – It is a rare possible condition, where the eyeball neither becomes in the shape of symmetrical nor spherical.</li>\n<li>Regular astigmatism – It is a common possible condition, where the shape of the eyeball becomes symmetrical, rather than spherical.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Natural Control of Astigmatism</p>\n<p>When it is in the initial stages, if one identifies that this is the problem of astigmatism, then one has to feel it as a wakeup call to start controlling it. Regular astigmatism is a quite common possible condition and so let us see how this vision problem can be resolved. One should consult a doctor initially, to discover the degree of vision problem it is then. If needed eye glasses would be prescribed and glasses must be worn as an immediate management of the vision problem.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Today, stress is the most common experience, irrespective of the age and it is the cause for various ailments and plaque the health of the human being. So, stress is the primary enemy, one has to fight with, to get rid of the vision problems and many. Hence, choose stress relieving lifestyle to control not only vision, but any other problems associated with the human health.</li>\n<li>Diet is one important factor that can control not only astigmatism, but also any kind of health. So, for natural cure of astigmatism, diet that enables the complete functionality of health should be consumed.</li>\n<li>Eye exercises are potential methods to control any kind of issues with the vision. These eye related exercises are also called visual training. These exercises are very easy to do and take hardly ten minutes of time in a day. Quality 10 minute time for valuable vision and eye health is worth spending in a day and it can control the astigmatism, naturally. Visual training can help the eye muscles to relax, which usually tightened as result of habitual strain and tension and prevent further dysfunction.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The above are the natural ways of controlling astigmatism and stop getting worse. However, if the condition of astigmatism is discovered lately, before following the above natural treatment methods, one should go to Lasik methods to ensure that astigmatism does not trouble you.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Astigmatism is a condition, where the shape of cornea becomes irregular. It is different from other vision refractive errors, like nearsightedness and farsightedness. With astigmatism, when the light is focused, it gets distorted and refracted to various focal points differently within the eye. It results in the problems with the vision, both far and near. [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-does-it-take-to-recover-from-lasik-3","date":"2019-09-14","title":"How long does it take to recover from lasik?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/how-long-does-it-take-to-recover-from-lasik-3","contentHtml":"<p>The fact is that the total recovery time caries from surgery to surgery and patient to patient. Most commonly, patients will get recovered and experience significant improvements in just two days after the surgery. On the basis of the Lasik surgeon’s skills and kind of procedure of refraction performed normal to better acquiring of vision varies from two days to seven days of duration. And one has to note that the total recovery with total experience of the improved vision takes over 6 months.</p>\n<p><strong>Short-Term Recovery</strong></p>\n<p>Right after the surgery, the vision will be blurred for the patient and so the patient needs to arrange for transportation or get somebody to accompany and to drive home. The surgeon will instruct strict guidelines to follow and take rest with no other activity, right after the surgery, for a few hours.</p>\n<p>After the surgery, the patient may feel mild pain, tendency to tear and irritation. It may also feel like slight piece of sand moving in the eye. First few days, the patient has to wear a shield or patch, according to the instructions of the doctor, particularly, while sleeping as it prevents from rubbing the eyelid and eye, accidentally. The eyes may become more sensitive to the light and blurry vision is common during the first days.</p>\n<p>During the recovery time, the patient may get subjected to sub-conjunctiva haemorrhage, based on the Lasik surgery performed. This condition is possible, because of the device for suction placed over the eye, while the surgery is being performed. Patient may continue to experience the haemorrhage for a week or two and may fade away day by day.</p>\n<p>After the surgery, the patient needs to arrange to go for an appointment with doctor for checkup in between next 1 to 2 days. Any possibilities of inflammation or infection can be prevented with medicated eye drops. Contact lens should not worn, even the vision is blurry, during this short-term recovery period.</p>\n<p><strong>Long-Term Recovery from Lasik</strong></p>\n<p>The total time for complete healing is usually around 6 months. During this long recovery period, slight fluctuations may be possible to experience. The progress of recovery, hence has to be checked by making many follow-up visits, scheduling accordingly to the hospital. These appointments for follow-ups are critical for complete recovery and improved vision and so it should not be neglected. Improved vision is expected to be experienced in about four weeks post the surgery.</p>\n<p>The recovery period of six months may also include many restrictions to ensure complete and complication free healing and recovery. Activities that have high impact over body and eye must be avoided for safe and healthy healing. All the post-operative instructions must be followed very carefully then.</p>\n<p>Since every individual eye is unique and so the vision conditions are unique, about 3 to 5% of chances are there that need further procedure of enhancement. The procedure of enhancement is quite the same as the procedure of the full Lasik. The concerned eye surgeon is the right person to decide, whether the procedure of enahancmenet is needed or not.</p>\n<p>During the long term recovery period, one vision problem, which is worth noted and addressed is the presbyopia condition. This condition is occurred usually after 40 years of age and the ability to focus over the nearby objects is slowly declined. Presbyopia development should not be considered as a condition as either over-correction or under-correction, but as a natural process that every human eye goes through, as a human age grows. One has to note that the presbyopia condition can occur to anyone after 40s, irrespective of the Lasik surgery is undergone or not. A typical enhancement procedure of Lasik cannot fix this condition. For most of the conditions, certain modification can be made and reading glasses may be needed.</p>\n<p><strong>Points Worth Noting</strong></p>\n<p>Once the Lasik surgery is completed, the eyes must be protected from injuries. The precautions have to be followed to ensure safe eye vision, even after complete recovery of the eyes, since the eyes become more prone to any injuries. So, wearing safety goggles is highly recommended for eye protection, whenever you are move in harsh weather or engage in any activity that is risky, like playing sports or working with power tools.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The fact is that the total recovery time caries from surgery to surgery and patient to patient. Most commonly, patients will get recovered and experience significant improvements in just two days after the surgery. On the basis of the Lasik surgeon’s skills and kind of procedure of refraction performed normal to better acquiring of vision [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"do-they-put-you-to-sleep-for-cataract-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Do they put you to sleep for cataract surgery?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/do-they-put-you-to-sleep-for-cataract-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>No, during the surgery, you would be awake and they don’t put you to sleep for the cataract surgery. This facilitation is needed because it eliminates the associated risks with general anaesthesia. In addition to that the cataract surgeon needs to communicate and talk to you, while the procedure goes on.</p>\n<p>Though you may have concerns about the idea of no sleep but to be awake during the cataract surgery, there is no need to fear, because you feel no discomfort and fully relaxed, as oral medication is given, before initiating the procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Anaesthesia and Medication</strong></p>\n<p>Most commonly topical anaesthesia is given for the cataract surgery. It can be accomplished through instilling medication for long numbing, into the eye. You may also opt for the choice of receiving the medication of IntraVenous or IV, so that you can feel comfortable and remain calm, during the procedure. This medication, in the surgical suite helps you to remember your experience after a brief procedure of 10 to 15 minutes gets completed and they reach to the area of recovery by then. The IV is given usually along with the medication in your arm, intravenously, to feel more comfortable and relaxed. It stands as lesser form of risky anaesthesia and it is done well with most of the patients with topical anaesthesia along with certain intravenous sedation. In certain cases, eyes are numbed by medication injected around the socket of the eye and it also helps to paralyze the movement of eyelid and eye. However, these injections are offered with a few risks and hence are less frequently used.</p>\n<p><strong>General Anaesthesia</strong></p>\n<p>Sometimes general anaesthesis is required for some patients. As the cataract surgery is performed by giving topical anaesthesia demands cooperation and awareness of the patient, in some cases, general anaesthesia may be required for the patients with dementia and child patients having developmental delays. Patients should lay still and flat, during cataract surgery. Hence general anaesthesia is required for certain patients with restless leg syndrome, Parkinson’s Disease or with movement disorders.</p>\n<p>For the patients, who surfer from neck or back pain or disorders or breathing troubles, experience discomfort, while lying flat, for cataract surgery.</p>\n<p>Later, you can leave the surgery centre after a short period of surgery, however, after the surgery, you cannot drive. So, someone has to accompany you to drive and take you back home.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>No, during the surgery, you would be awake and they don’t put you to sleep for the cataract surgery. This facilitation is needed because it eliminates the associated risks with general anaesthesia. In addition to that the cataract surgeon needs to communicate and talk to you, while the procedure goes on. Though you may have [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-happens-during-lasik","date":"2019-09-14","title":"What happens during lasik?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/what-happens-during-lasik","contentHtml":"<p><strong>During Lasik Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>The overall procedure for the Lasik is completed within 30 minutes or less. The patient enters the examination room that has laser system and will lie down on the back, in a reclining chair. The laser system is a large machine, attaching a computer screen and microscope to it.</p>\n<p>The process is initiated by placing numbing drops in the eyes and the cleaning is done for the around eye area and a lid speculum instrument is attempted to hold the eyelids open. Then the surgeon initiates the procedure either a microkeratome, which is a mechanical device or a laser keratome, which is a laser device to cut corenal flap.</p>\n<p>In case the corneal flap is attempted to cut with the mechanical microkeratome device, a small ring would be placed over the eye and suction is created to the cornea, by applying very high pressures. When the suction ring is on, the vision gets dim and pressure may be felt by the patient, along with certain discomfort levels, during this part of the procedure. the cutting instrument, microkeratome will then be attached to the suction ring. Microkeratome blade will be used by the surgeon for cutting a flap in the cornea. these blades of microkeratome must be disposed after usage for once. Then the suction ring along with microkeratome will be removed.</p>\n<p>In case a laser device, laser keratome is used for cutting a flap in the cornea, in place of mechanical microkeratome device, the procedure is different. Here, a plastic plate is used to flatten the cornea, in this case. Some feel of pressure is common and along with some discomfort and the result is the dim of the vision, during this phase of procedure. Inside the cornea tissue, laser energy will be focused and it creates thousand small gas and water bubbles and it will get expanded and connected for tissue separation, underneath the surface of the cornea, and the flap will be created. Then the plate will be removed.</p>\n<p>During the remaining part of the procedure, the patient will be able to see, however, blurred vision is experienced with fluctuating degrees. Then the flap will be lifted and folded back over its hinge and exposed tissue will be dried.</p>\n<p>As the next part, the patient will be suggested to keep staring at the focused light and then the doctor positions the laser over the eyes. In this instance, laser is not the one used for tissue removal from the cornea. the purpose of this light is to keep the eye focused on a single spot after laser comes on. Here, in case the patient is not able to stare at one fixed object continuously for 60 seconds minimum, one is not considered to be a eligible candidate to undergo this surgery.</p>\n<p>After the patient can stare the eye in the appropriate and fixed position, the process of laser will be started by the surgeon. The patient may experience new smells and sounds, at this point. The laser pulse creates small ticking sounds. While the laser is removing the tissue of cornea, some patents reported to experience smell alike burning hair.  The amount of energy delivered with Lasik is controlled by a computer. It is because the doctor had programmed to vaporize a specified tissue among, according to the prescription, taken during initial evaluation, before the surgery is started. The flap would be put back its regular position, once the laser energy pulses vaporise the tissue of cornea.</p>\n<p>At the end of the procedure, a shield would be placed for protection, as there are no stitches made for firm holding the flap in its place. Since this shield can prevent you from putting pressure or rubbing the eyes, while you sleep and also help protecting the eye from poked or hit, accidentally, until the flap is healed, it is important to wear it.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>During Lasik Surgery The overall procedure for the Lasik is completed within 30 minutes or less. The patient enters the examination room that has laser system and will lie down on the back, in a reclining chair. The laser system is a large machine, attaching a computer screen and microscope to it. The process is [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-are-the-disadvantages-of-lasik-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"What are the disadvantages of lasik surgery?","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/what-are-the-disadvantages-of-lasik-surgery","contentHtml":"<p><strong>Disadvantages</strong></p>\n<p>There are certain disadvantages of Lasik surgery, despite the pulses, from the Lasik eye surgery.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Lasik surgery is complex technically. The problems are rare when the flap is created by the doctor and the if so, the affects to the vision are permanent. So, choosing the right and experienced surgeon is important to perform these complex surgeries.</li>\n<li>There can be loss of best vision by the Lasik surgery. Here, the best vision is meant the vision with highest degree achieved, while the eye glasses or contact lens are worn.</li>\n<li>In cases any changes are happened unexpectedly to the cornea, these changes can be permanent. So, such errors cannot be withdrawn or reversed.</li>\n<li>Lasik eye surgery is not for all patients with eye related problems.</li>\n<li>The surgery is useful and beneficial for the patients, who are in certain age group and cannot expect optimistic results for the patients, beyond this age group.</li>\n<li>There are certain risks associated with the Lasik surgery, like any other surgery. These risks can be halos, dry eyes, higher order aberrations, etc.</li>\n<li>With the standard Lasik procedure, usually the eye patients, who have thin cornea may not get benefited and so the benefits are fruitful only for thick enough cornea.</li>\n<li>Lasik surgery is not suitable for the patients, who have no enough good general body health.</li>\n<li>The patients, who have any eye diseases or have no stable vision reaching condition, are not eligible to go through the Lasik eye surgery.</li>\n<li>In some cases, further enhancement procedure may be needed after the Lasik surgery, for better results.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>On an overall, though the surgery of Lasik is technically complex, the complexity is well handled by mechanizing the procedure and accuracy is increased by automation of process through the programmable machine and computer. So, if the patient is eligible for the procedure, the success of the surgery is almost guaranteed. When the right surgery center, with the experienced and skilled surgeon is chosen for the surgery, along with good post-surgery care, the disadvantages of the Lasik procedure can best be minimized.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Disadvantages There are certain disadvantages of Lasik surgery, despite the pulses, from the Lasik eye surgery. Lasik surgery is complex technically. The problems are rare when the flap is created by the doctor and the if so, the affects to the vision are permanent. So, choosing the right and experienced surgeon is important to perform [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-watch-tv-after-laser-eye-surgery-2","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can i watch tv after laser eye surgery?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-i-watch-tv-after-laser-eye-surgery-2","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik eye surgery in terms of technology and for the patient it is not. However, the responsibility of the patient is to ensure that enough care is taken during the recovery period and the eyes are less strained for a period of recovery.</p>\n<p>Technically, doctors recommend taking rest for possible period of time, after the surgery, to heal properly and minimize the complications. However, following the precautions, it is fine to start watching the television after 24 hours of the surgery, because the first 24 hours are considered to be no-screen period. Every patient’s condition is unique and so the guidelines can be added, based on the eye and overall health of the patient.</p>\n<p>So, when one chooses to watch the television, timely care for the eyes should not be forgotten and it is important to note down all the guidelines given by the surgeon and follow them without fail.</p>\n<p>Watching television should be reduced to minimum time and the main problem associated with watching the television is drying up the eyes. While watching the television, the watcher tends to keep the eye open and forget blinking for longer time. It dries up the eyes and dry condition of the eye hinders the process of recovery and creates complications. So, while watching the television, it is important that one is very careful in terms of lubricating the eyes during regular periods. If the screen time makes the patient exhausted, it should be immediately reduced and small nap or closing the eyes for sometime, at least during the commercial breaks is advisable.</p>\n<p>Though it is technically fine to watch the screen after one day of the surgery, it is always recommended to delay resuming back to watching the television for couple of days, after you feel comfortable with the new vision and eye condition. It also helps the chances of speedy recovery, by allowing the cornea pass through the acute stages, smoothly. Not only television, it is also important to resume to the visually exhausting activities, like watching the television, operating the smartphone frequently and working on the computer for longer time. Take this time as the best time for a break, in the busy personal, professional and social lives. Enjoy the music, while anticipating the best possible vision after recovery from the Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p>After a couple of days or more optimally after 1 week, you can get back to your day to day activities, except visually exhausting habits and you will enjoy the best outcome from the Lasik surgery.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik eye surgery in terms of technology and for the patient it is not. However, the responsibility of the patient is to ensure that enough care is taken during the recovery period and the eyes are less strained for a period of recovery. Technically, doctors recommend taking rest for possible period of time, after the [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-cook-after-lasik-surgery-2","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can i cook after lasik surgery?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-i-cook-after-lasik-surgery-2","contentHtml":"<p>Most of the people go for the Lasik surgery for better and clear eye vision and importantly to get rid of the eyeglasses and contact lens. And there are very frequent doubts about how early and how slow the regular activities have to be started, after undergoing the Lasik surgery. And cooking is one of such doubts. It is important to know when to cook after the Lasik surgery, because cooking is like dealing with heat.</p>\n<p>Usually, after the Lasik surgery, sufficient time has to be given until the vision becomes clear. In most of the cases, it takes a day or two to reach this state. Since, cooking is dealing with the eyes and eyes absorb the heat faster, at least two days of time has to be given after the surgery. And to protect from the heat to come in contact with the eyes, it is important to protect the eyes by wearing the sun glasses or transparent glasses. This arrangement is needed only during the first few days after the Lasik surgery. After you feel comfortable with the vision, you can stop using the glasses, while cooking.</p>\n<p>Not only cooking, the other activities also have to be consciously performed. In case of cooking, going out and moving around the dusty areas, wearing the sun glasses or normal glasses is important, to protect the eyes from the heat and dust. No matter whether you go out or not, the eyes must be lubricated on regular basis, at least 4 times a day and till the number of times, specified by the Lasik surgeon. After the Lasik surgery dryness of the eye is the common symptom and to get rid of the same condition, one has to go through this process of lubricating the eyes is significant.</p>\n<p>So, continue to wear the glasses after couple of days after the Lasik surgery and keep lubricating the eyes frequently, as suggested by the Lasik surgeon. Apart from these two precautions, one has to consciously avoid some strenuous activities, such as swimming, playing outdoor games, etc.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Most of the people go for the Lasik surgery for better and clear eye vision and importantly to get rid of the eyeglasses and contact lens. And there are very frequent doubts about how early and how slow the regular activities have to be started, after undergoing the Lasik surgery. And cooking is one of [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-crying-affect-lasik-2","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can crying affect lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-crying-affect-lasik-2","contentHtml":"<p>Myths are many about the Lasik surgery and post-surgery care. In fact Lasik surgery is one of the advanced and safest surgeries for a human. There are very few side effects and post-surgery complications with this surgery, especially, with the advanced technologies associated developed recently. However, it is common and natural to feel and doubtful about the complications.</p>\n<p>One of such fears and doubts regarding the Lasik surgery is crying and the respective affects. It is absolutely not true. Crying is a natural with human emotions and it is a natural lubrication process to the eye. According to the American Board of Ophthalmology, human eye tends to tear, all the day, through one is not emotional. When a human cries for emotion, the eyes become tearful. And this process is a natural lubrication process and does not harm the eyes, even after the Lasik surgical procedure. in fact it is even helpful to the eyes, because of its natural lubricating process and helps to fasten the healing process.</p>\n<p>However, there is some danger associated with crying that there will be increased chance of rubbing the eyes. When the eyes are rubbed with hand, there will be more pressure applied to the eye that definitely harms the cornea and flap within the eye. Though the severity of this complication is less with the recent advanced Lasik surgery technologies, most of the Lasik surgeons advise you to not to rub the eyes for many days after the Lasik surgery. So, when the eye starts tearing out of the discomfort associated with the vision or dust, it is quite fine to tear, but be very conscious about the fact that rubbing the eyes can hinder the natural process of healing and that in turn bring more complications.</p>\n<p>After the Lasik surgery, one has to wait for a few days to resume to regular and day to day activities and no pressure either with the dust or physical pressure is allowed to ensure that after surgery effects are good and outcome is as expected. So, don’t worry, if crying happens naturally, don’t worry, let your eyes lubricate naturally.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Myths are many about the Lasik surgery and post-surgery care. In fact Lasik surgery is one of the advanced and safest surgeries for a human. There are very few side effects and post-surgery complications with this surgery, especially, with the advanced technologies associated developed recently. However, it is common and natural to feel and doubtful [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-sleep-after-lasik-3","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can you sleep after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-you-sleep-after-lasik-3","contentHtml":"<p>When you decided to go for the Lasik, it is clear that you want to get rid of boring eye glasses and become independent from hard maintenance of the contact lens. Since the eyes are the most sensitive organs of the human body, there is no surprise and absolutely nothing wrong in getting confirmed about every move and every action that one tends do in day to day life. As part of it, it is usual even to know, whether sleeping after the Lasik surgery, is fine or not.</p>\n<p><strong>Sleep After Lasik</strong></p>\n<p>In fact sleep stands as the best remedy to get clear from the initial post-operation discomfort. This discomfort is usually because of the numbing drops that are worn off, after 4 to 6 hours after the Lasik surgery. The reason for applying the numbing drops is to ensure that the eye does not receive any pain, during the surgery. So, immediately after the surgery, if one can sleep after a couple of hours, this discomfort can be minimized and some of the patients, who have slept after the surgery have experienced this discomfort at minimum levels. It is also possible that people feel no or little discomfort, when they sleep immediately after going home.</p>\n<p>Protection eye shields are usually given after the surgery and the patient has to wear during sleep. The shield helps the patient not to rub the eyes, unknowingly, while sleeping and prevents the eyes from great complications.</p>\n<p><strong>Why 6 Hours?</strong></p>\n<p>Six hours are needed immediately after the Lasik surgery as this time is the waiting time on epithelium topcoat that gets sealed over that layer’s edge. There should be no modifications or disturbances resulted during this period, as it will be very hard to change in the future. So, let the eyes be naturally functioning and the flap layer takes enough time to settle down to function back normally.</p>\n<p>Sleeping is also good as the eyes don’t get dry easily and natural lubrication process continues. So, take a few days of time from your busy professional life, so that you can, you can spend quality time for yourself, while the corneal flap is healing. Sleep as much as possible, no matter it is a day or night. If you don’t feel like sleeping, take the head phones and start listening to pleasant music that makes your body and soul feel better. After a few days of this quality time and rest, you will thank your surgeon for the successful surgery and thank you also for the potential care you gave for your eyes that will improve your quality of life.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>When you decided to go for the Lasik, it is clear that you want to get rid of boring eye glasses and become independent from hard maintenance of the contact lens. Since the eyes are the most sensitive organs of the human body, there is no surprise and absolutely nothing wrong in getting confirmed about [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-do-eyes-take-to-heal-after-lasik","date":"2019-09-14","title":"How long do eyes take to heal after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/how-long-do-eyes-take-to-heal-after-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>The period of healing after the Lasik or any kind of surgery is the recovery time. The advantage of the Lasik is less recovery time, as many Lasik patients report that they started feeling normal with the vision, right on the next day or the day after. Some of the patients also experienced improved vision, right after the Lasik. However, one has to understand that patients, who prefer to undergo the surgery, with higher prescriptions usually experience noticeable improvement faster compared to the patients, with lower levels of prescriptions. However, immediate improvement in the vision also takes minimum of 6 to 8 hours after the procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Short Term or Immediate Recovery</strong></p>\n<p>Each of the Lasik surgeon establishes and follows one’s own protocol for Lasik recovery on the basis of what works well and give best results. Most likely yoru surgeon gives protective eye shields or sunglasses for protection of the eyes. Youneed to wear them, during sleep and this must be habituated and followed for at least one week, after the surgery. Some of the surgeons leave you immediately after the surgery and some of them prefer you to stay for at least 15 to 20 minutes and then go. And the patient needs to make own arrangements of transportation or get family member or family to drive you home and stay helpful, during transportation. Do not prefer to drive yourself as it is not advisable.</p>\n<p>After the numbing drops are worn off in 20 to 30 minutes, mild itching or burning sensation may be felt. As a thumb rule, never attempt to rub the eyes in entire short term and long term recovery periods. The eyes can be watery during the first 8 to 12 hours after the surgery and sometimes red spots may be developed or bloodshot may be appeared. These symptoms are temporary and normal. Still don’t rub your eyes and don’t worry, unless these symptoms are severe.</p>\n<p><strong>Long Term Recovery</strong></p>\n<p>When the long term recovery is considered, it is about managing the day to day activities and work life, while taking special care of the eyes. Most commonly surgeons suggest you to resume to work after a day or two of the surgery, except in the cases of any complications or discomforts. During this period, your surgeon may set limitations to you to for swimming, workouts and wearing the eye makeup. For many months, contact sports, whirlpools, hot tubs must be avoided. All the post operative instructions must be followed to ensure proper healing and to enjoy total Lasik effects. In case of severe symptoms or unusual symptoms contact the doctor immediately without delay, so that there can be enough scope for reducing the complications.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The period of healing after the Lasik or any kind of surgery is the recovery time. The advantage of the Lasik is less recovery time, as many Lasik patients report that they started feeling normal with the vision, right on the next day or the day after. Some of the patients also experienced improved vision, [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-many-years-does-lasik-eye-surgery-last","date":"2019-09-14","title":"How many years does lasik eye surgery last?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/how-many-years-does-lasik-eye-surgery-last","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik surgery has become so popular in the world and millions of people go through the surgery for the long lasting results. And the natural question arises is, how long? It is worth questioning and discussing, as every patient spends good amount of money, time and efforts to undergo the Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Lasik and Long Lasting Results</strong></p>\n<p>The most often asked question during the consultation for Lasik laser eye surgery is how long the results of the Lasik last for? Usually, the medical centres answer this question saying years and even decades. Why one is not sure about the years or decades? It is because the lasting results after the surgery depends on several factors and the major factor is the age of the patient, whether he or she is in twenties or forties. And the list of the factors goes on like degree of prescription, intensity of the problem, other eye related problems and most importantly post operative care also to preserve the results.</p>\n<p>Considering the general outcomes, considering the general factors, there are only 5% of the patients, who usually develop small changes in their prescriptions. These changes are technically possible after 3 months or even after 20 years or even later. These patients are not without solutions.</p>\n<p><strong>Age As Primary Factor</strong></p>\n<p>As it was addressed before, age plays vital role in deciding the overall quality life of the Lasik results. As the age progresses for a human being is it is quite common to experience presbyopia that starts even in middle ages for some patients. It is progressive diminishing capability of the eye in focusing the objects nearby. Hence, many people tend to wear bifocals or reading glasses, after they cross middle age. And eventually, Lasik patients, before they reach the stage of presbyopic condition, will need to wear the reading glasses for clear vision. And the patient can prefer monovision or laser vision correction procedure as a good alternative to these reading glasses.</p>\n<p>Other possibility of eye issues is cataracts, especially in the elderly patients. It is no way related to the Lasik surgery and corneal flap. It is about developing cataracts, which is cloudiness to the eye’s lens, which hamper the ability of the vision.</p>\n<p>So, the age related issues have more impact on the long lasting results of the Lasik surgery and the remaining factors have less impact over the life of the Lasik results.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik surgery has become so popular in the world and millions of people go through the surgery for the long lasting results. And the natural question arises is, how long? It is worth questioning and discussing, as every patient spends good amount of money, time and efforts to undergo the Lasik surgery. Lasik and Long [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-go-blind-from-lasik-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can you go blind from lasik surgery?","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-you-go-blind-from-lasik-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik surgery has much higher success rate and lower-risk potential. According to American Refractive Surgery Council, more than 90% of the Lasik patients are satisfied extremely as they end up with the vision of 20/20. According to the same council, no actual cases are reported about the occurrence of blindness after the Lasik surgery. Complications are very rare, but possible technically, after the surgery. Certain potential side effects, types of laser correction procedures or certain factors may increase the negative complications and respective odds. The reports of the US Food and Drug Administration indicate that the Lasik may cause loss of vision, in certain patients and this condition cannot be corrected, with contact lenses, glasses or additional surgery. It did not reach the blindness, according to the reports.</p>\n<p><strong>COMPLICATIONS</strong></p>\n<p>Usually complications arise are more related to the secondary issues and not because or direct causes from the surgery. For instance, post operation care is utmost important and any disturbances can result in infections that may even end up with blindness. After the procedure, the patient has to take utmost care for the eyes and to be conscious about all possible complications, like dry eyes, potential blindness that are possible to occur, in cases of inadequate care. However, vision loss is a very rare complication of Lasik and may occur even lesser than 1% of the patients. The reports also show that the usual complications are decreased night vision, halos around lights or starbursts.</p>\n<p><strong>Corneal Estasia</strong></p>\n<p>Technically, there is a possibility of going corneal estasia and the chances are minor, lesser than 0.2% of the laser patients. The causes of this condition are thinning out of cornea after bulging, usually from too much removal of the tissue. It may also lead to blindness also. If the patient undergoes this condition after the surgery, the solution is prescribing rigid contact lenses. In case the condition is extreme, corneal transplantation may be recommended.</p>\n<p><strong>Over or Under Correction of Vision</strong></p>\n<p>The possibility of this condition is lesser in Lasik compared to Lasek or PRK patients. The results are, in most cases, reversed, like nearsighted patient turns to longsighted and vice versa. This condition is reversible by performing another surgery, in case the cornea has enough thickness to withstand.</p>\n<p><strong>Visual Aberrations</strong></p>\n<p>It is a possible risk after the Lasik surgery, though the percentage of occurrence is lesser than 1%. The visual aberrations can be starbursts, halos or double vision, which are predominant during dim or night light and possible when the pupil is larger.</p>\n<p><strong>How to Prevent Major Complications?</strong></p>\n<p>It is always important to consult the ophthalmologist, prior to choosing the right Lasik procedure for you. Initial assessment is performed to determine the appropriate and suitable Lasik procedure for the patient. The success rates of the Lasik surgery keep improving and so the preference of the same procedures. Choosing an experienced and skilled surgeon is also an important factor. The Lasik outcomes do have great outcomes, while appropriate treatment protocol is followed with appropriate infrastructure and technology.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik surgery has much higher success rate and lower-risk potential. According to American Refractive Surgery Council, more than 90% of the Lasik patients are satisfied extremely as they end up with the vision of 20/20. According to the same council, no actual cases are reported about the occurrence of blindness after the Lasik surgery. Complications [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-percent-of-lasik-surgeries-go-wrong-2","date":"2019-09-14","title":"What percent of lasik surgeries go wrong?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/what-percent-of-lasik-surgeries-go-wrong-2","contentHtml":"<p>Complications post Lasik surgery is natural fears and there is nothing wrong with the same, as the eyes are the most sensitive organs of human body. These fears become dominating as the data from different sources contract with each other. Even a small complication alerts us, as after all eye vision is essential for every microsecond of the life, except sleeping. Eventually, the percentage of success rate and failure rate bother and influence the decision of going to Lasik.</p>\n<p><strong>Percentage of Side Effects and Complications</strong></p>\n<p>Side effects and complications are different, though both contribute the percentage of Lasik surgery going wrong. The probabilities of different side effects, which are possible during the period of recovery, after the Lasik surgery are the following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>There is lesser than 5% of probability of returning to the need for the contact lenses, glasses. The same is the probability to have the need for another Lasik surgery to achieve the expected smoothness out any of astigmatism, nearsightedness, farsightedness or any aberrations of higher order over the cornea, contributing the symptoms of the vision.</li>\n<li>There is up to 30% of probability that the patient experiences the symptoms of dry eye, especially, during the first three months, post surgery.</li>\n<li>Some of the patients may experience symptoms like night vision, halos, glare along with dry eye and it may continue for 6 months to 12 months, though this period is considered as the part of recovery and healing. There are also certain therapeutic treatments available for the patients, who experience these side effects.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>The probability of complication rate varies as the following.</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik is a laser eye surgery and the complications are common, just like any other surgery in the medical industry. Surgical complications of Lasik are possible, but are very rare. The possible complications after Lasik are corneal flap dislocation and infections. These conditions are considered as complications, as they demand one more phase of treatment, as leaving them untreated can be harmful.</p>\n<p>The fact remains that the complications after Lasik remain very very low, according to the statistics. The percentage of the patients, who experience these complications, is lesser than one. This 1% is very low, when a complex treatment, surgery is considered.</p>\n<p><strong>What FDA Reports Indicate?</strong></p>\n<p>FDA conducted PROWL (Patient Reported Outcomes With Lasik). These reports are exaggerated in the media, including social media. Though it specifies some more percentage of symptoms experiencing after the Lasik surgery, after a clear and deeper analysis, it is found that there are 5 to 10% of the Lasik patients, who experience a range of symptoms after the Lasik procedures.</p>\n<p>And other reports indicate that the success rate of the Lasik is more than 96% and so the probability of failure or Lasik surgery going wrong can be lesser than 4%.</p>\n<p>Leaving the social media, which always exaggerates a small thing into ten times complicated, it is always wise and better choice to go for the standard medical research reports and find the truths, with no additions or subtractions of interpretations.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Complications post Lasik surgery is natural fears and there is nothing wrong with the same, as the eyes are the most sensitive organs of human body. These fears become dominating as the data from different sources contract with each other. Even a small complication alerts us, as after all eye vision is essential for every [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-lasik-safe-long-term-2","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Is lasik safe long term?","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/is-lasik-safe-long-term-2","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik is always safe in long term and this statement sounds very subjective, as there are various factors effecting and justifying the statement. When the facts are considered, Lasik results tend to be longer, with careful evaluation prior to the surgery and post operation care, while standard procedure and skilled surgeon are considered as the primary requisites.</p>\n<p>The motto of going for Lasik is improved vision and reduces dependency of hassled contact lenses or glasses. There is a fair chance of achieving the vision of 20/25 or even better after this Lasik refractive eye surgery. The results are longer enough and any possible symptoms after the Lasik procedure, usually are not because of this procedure, but because of the other vision complications that tend to occur with the age and other factors.</p>\n<p><strong>Factors Influencing Long Term Lasik Results</strong></p>\n<p>There are various factors that influence the long term results of the Lasik surgery and also there are certain conditions, which are mis-interpreted as the short term results or side effects of the Lasik surgery.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>In most of the cases, the results after the Lasik depend over specific prescription or refractive errors. The success rate of this refractive surgery is more for the patients with lower reading or grade of nearsightedness. As opposed to this condition, like patients with higher degree of farsightedness or nearsightedness and especially when astigmatism condition is added would eventually have lower rates of success.</li>\n<li>There is also possibility that the Lasik procedure may end up with undercorrection or overcorrection. It is possible, usually, when the assessment procedure is not performed at standard levels. However, there is nothing to worry, as it can be converted to have longer term results, as another surgery can be attempted to correct this mistake.</li>\n<li>Though it is rare, it is technically possible that some of the patients have the eyes that may return to the vision level they had prior to the surgery, slowly. This factor or risk is possible because of certain conditions, like pregnancy, hormonal imbalances or abnormal wound healing.</li>\n<li>The best possible condition after the Lasik procedure in most of the cases can be presbyopia. Presbyopia is a condition, where the eye sight or vision gets deteriorated as the age gets progressed. There is a much higher probability that this condition can be considered as the side effect or shorter living results of the Lasik surgery.</li>\n<li>Other prominent condition is the condition of cataract, which is the risk of the eye vision that increases with the age of the patient. It is not because of the Lasik surgery performed, but another eye problem.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Hence there are various conditions or risks of eye vision, possible with any human being. Lasik is the laser eye surgery that can treat the conditions of farsightedness, nearsightedness and astigmatism conditions and it cannot guarantee to stop other risks or conditions to occur the eyes, which are absolutely from totally different sources.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik is always safe in long term and this statement sounds very subjective, as there are various factors effecting and justifying the statement. When the facts are considered, Lasik results tend to be longer, with careful evaluation prior to the surgery and post operation care, while standard procedure and skilled surgeon are considered as the [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-is-the-best-lasik-surgery","date":"2019-09-14","title":"What is the best lasik surgery?","category":"Comparisons","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/what-is-the-best-lasik-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik laser eye surgery is an advanced medical procedure to correct refractive error for the eyes. It allows you to improve the vision with reduced dependency over the contact lens and eye glasses. The laser surgery to improve the vision is not the only Lasik vision surgery, but there are many to choose one that suits you. Among the several laser variations of refractive surgeries, Lasik is usually referred as all kinds of laser eye surgery.</p>\n<p>Though laser is a common agent that is made use in the vision surgery, there are different surgery procedures, like Lasik, PRK, LASEK. Each of the eye refractive error patient should select any one of these procedures, based on their eye conditions and various factors related to the eyes.</p>\n<p>LASIK – The Laser-Assisted in-Situ Keratomileusis procedure is preferred by most of the eye patients, because of the better results that eventually can work for most of the activities. It has good track record, in terms of preference by people and success rate. Though there are a few side effects, like temporary visual disturbances and dry eyes, the same can be cleared in a few weeks. The best part is that the results are for long-term.</p>\n<p>The Lasik procedure involves the procedure that alters the cornea curvature, by removing corneal tissues in tiny amounts. The surgeon flattens cornea curve and turns it to steeper.</p>\n<p>PRK – Photorefractive Keratectomy involves the surgery procedure, which scraps top surface, the epithelium, away. This process of corneal abrasion needs only 3 to 4 days for healing, which involves short term blurred vision with moderate pain, before clear vision.</p>\n<p>The PRK procedure is suitable for the people from different professions like military or law enforcement, where they more likely get to be struck. The advantage is that the risk of the rupture of eyeball is very low. It can correct nearsightedness, when not in severe condition or degree.</p>\n<p>LASEK – Laser-Assisted Subepithelial Keratectomy procedure is quite the same as the Lasik surgery with small variation, creating flap is performed with microkeratome, a special cutting device and exposing cornea towards ethanol. This procedure removes only a very small part of cornea and so it is the best option for the people, who have only very thin corneas.</p>\n<p>Epi-Lasik – Epithelial Laser-Assisted in-Situ Keratomileusis procedure involves separation of the epithelium out of the stroma, which is a central part of the cornea. the procedure makes use of the epikeratome or a blunt blade device and attempts the reshape of the cornea, using a laser. The procedure of Epi-Lasik is quite the same as LASEK.</p>\n<p>Though there are multiple laser eye vision corrective surgeries, each of them is suitable for the people, as each of the eye condition is unique and hence the requirement is also unique. And only experienced surgeons can suggest you the best suitable laser eye surgery procedure, on the basis of the eye prescription and the general health condition.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik laser eye surgery is an advanced medical procedure to correct refractive error for the eyes. It allows you to improve the vision with reduced dependency over the contact lens and eye glasses. The laser surgery to improve the vision is not the only Lasik vision surgery, but there are many to choose one that [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-relex-smile-better-than-lasik","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Is relex smile better than lasik?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/is-relex-smile-better-than-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>Sometimes the vision surgeries ReLEx SMILE and Lasik are bit confusing to select the one between them. There are certain differences, in terms of both procedure and results. Let us explore both the pros and cons related to both Relex SMILE and Lasik laser eye surgeries to choose suitable one between the two.</p>\n<p><strong>The Procedures</strong></p>\n<p>The Relex SMILE procedure is comparatively very less invasive than Lasik. Relex SMILE makes use of the ReLex laser and Lasik uses the femtosecond laser and excimer laser. One most important thing to consider here is that this procedure is only for correction of nearsightedness and not for astigmatism and farsightedness.</p>\n<p>Relex SMILE procedure, though it is considered as a flap-less procedure, it is not so. Though it is very small incision, but an incision is required for the removal of the lenticule. But Lasik needs bigger incision comparatively and the recovery also stands accordingly. In the Lasik surgery, a flap is created in the cornea by the surgeon and then it will raised for the purpose of cornea reshaping.</p>\n<p><strong>Results and Reports</strong></p>\n<p>Since Relex SMILE is a newer procedure than Lasik, there is less data and statistics available, in terms of research and reporting. Considering the available few research and reports related to the differences between Relex SMILE and Lasik procedures, by the Krasnodar Branch of Fyodorov Eye Microsurgery, Federal State Institution, from Russia, they reveal the data as the following. The report indicates that the recovery after a day of the surgery, both the patients have found and experienced improvements in visual acuity. The report has also concluded that the However, there are no risks associated with the flap and there are hardly any complications with SMILE, since the incision is very tiny, about 20mm and there are no flaps associated.</p>\n<p><strong>Healing Time</strong></p>\n<p>Since no flaps are touched or connected with the procedure of the Relex SMILE, both healing and recovery are faster and the patient can get back to the day to day activities, even rigorous activities, like swimming faster than Lasik.</p>\n<p><strong>Recovery Time</strong></p>\n<p>Since the healing time is lesser, the overall recovery time also will be lesser compared to Lasik, since there is only a very small incision made, through which the removal of lenticule is attempted. And for the same reason, the risks and complications associated with the procedure are also minimal.</p>\n<p>When visual recovery is considered, most of the patients experience comfortable vision, while performing various eye vision demanded activities, like working with computer, smartphones and reading.</p>\n<p>Primarily both the procedures are for correction of the refractive vision errors. On an overall comparatively Lasik, Relex SMILE is costlier. Both of the procedures result in possible dry eye syndrome and also irritation in short term, during the recovery period. Both of them have faster recovery periods along with faster surgical times.</p>\n<p>Both of them are useful and selection of each should be done on the basis of the prescription primarily and also the condition of eye health and also general health condition. Relex SMILE stands as a specific procedure for limited vision refractive error correction and Lasik provides solution for wider refractive errors.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Sometimes the vision surgeries ReLEx SMILE and Lasik are bit confusing to select the one between them. There are certain differences, in terms of both procedure and results. Let us explore both the pros and cons related to both Relex SMILE and Lasik laser eye surgeries to choose suitable one between the two. The Procedures [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-is-the-latest-laser-eye-surgery-technology","date":"2019-09-14","title":"What is the latest laser eye surgery technology?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/what-is-the-latest-laser-eye-surgery-technology","contentHtml":"<p>When there are multiple laser eye surgery technologies available to get rid of the eye glasses, the obvious question that arises is which stands as the latest technology to exploit maximum technology benefits. The three surgeries available in the medical industry for vision correction are Lasik, PRK and SMILE and all these three procedures are enough safe, trusted and effective. And still the question continues, which is the latest one to choose?</p>\n<p><strong>First Generation – PRK</strong></p>\n<p>The first generation vision refractive error correction procedure stands is PRK or PhotoRefractive Keratectomy. The procedure is developed to treat astigmatism, farsightedness and nearsightedness.</p>\n<p>The procedure involves removal of the epithelium or outer cornea layer, gently by using a manual instrument. Then reshaping of the cornea is attempted to correct the vision, using a cool excimer laser.</p>\n<p>PRK procedure is preferred for the patients, who have irregular or thin corneas and who have chronic dry eye condition. Professionals, who have to work with direct eye contact, like fighters, boxers do prefer this procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Second Generation – LASIK</strong></p>\n<p>Laser-Assisted Stromal In-situ Keratomileusis is most widely known and most frequently performed vision correction procedure in the medical industry.</p>\n<p>The procedure involves creation of a small flap tissue with the help of femtosecond laser and then it is folded back. The underlying corneal tissue is then reshaped for correction of vision, by the surgeon. Lasik today stands as the standard procedure to improve the vision and if it is not suitable for the patient, usually, PRK or SMILE is considered for suitability. It is extremely trusted, safe and effective.</p>\n<p><strong>Third Generation – SMILE</strong></p>\n<p>Small Incision Lenticule Extraction, as the name suggests, a small incision is made and extraction of lenticule is performed. It is the latest laser technology for vision correction to date. It has been in practice, since 2012.</p>\n<p>One major technical difference between SMILE and its predecessors is that it does not make use of excimer laser, while performing this procedure. Very small or tiny incisions in the cornea are made using femtosecond laser and small pieces of corneal tissues are removed. It can reshape the cornea effectively and hence the vision gets improved.</p>\n<p>The best part of the SMILE procedure is that it is very less invasive surgery and eventually, the risks and complications associated with this surgery procedure become minimal. Incision is about 3mm for SMILE, compared to 8mm incision needed for the PRK procedure and 20mm incision is needed for the Lasik procedure. smaller incision also enables corneal stability after the surgery and corneal nerves are less disturbed. In addition to that SMILE procedure is performed quiet and it is odourless. SMILE procedure has been proven to be accurate and safe, through clinical trials.</p>\n<p>However, there is a small limitation to the SMILE procedure that it is yet available for treating only nearsightedness, but not for astigmatism and farsightedness. Let us expect the treatments for these two too in near future. So far SMILE is easier, faster and latest technology to date.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>When there are multiple laser eye surgery technologies available to get rid of the eye glasses, the obvious question that arises is which stands as the latest technology to exploit maximum technology benefits. The three surgeries available in the medical industry for vision correction are Lasik, PRK and SMILE and all these three procedures are [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-lasik-make-you-go-blind-2","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can lasik make you go blind?","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-lasik-make-you-go-blind-2","contentHtml":"<p>The direct answer is no practically and yes theoretically. Practically, there are no cases reported that the Lasik patient has gone blind after the Lasik procedure is performed. Theoretically, yes, it is possible, since Lasik is a surgery procedure. when enough care is not taken, one can go blind even without Lasik surgery. So, when enough post surgery care is taken, there is no probability to go blind after the Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Studies and Reports</strong></p>\n<p>According to the reports revealed by American Refractive Surgery Council, no actual cases indicating blindness as the result of Lasik are reported or recorded. The same council has revealed the success rate of the Lasik surgery as more than 96 percent. Having said this, it is also important to mention that infections and complications are possible that may result in degrades of vision. And the legal blindness is considered, when the vision reaches 20/200 or lesser.</p>\n<p>FDA (Food and Drug Administration) in the US has reported that there is a possibility of Lasik resulting in loss of vision, which may not be able to be corrected through contact lenses, glasses or any additional surgeries. It alerts with the worst possible outcome of Lasik, which is not practically happened, since enough care is taken by both the medical center and the patient, because eye is the most sensitive organ of the human body.</p>\n<p>The reports shared by the American Journal of Cataract and Refractive Surgery that Lasik stands as the most commonly performed and one of the most successful surgeries. While it is possible that the Lasik procedure may result, though in very rare cases, it would be loss of a very few lines of vision over vision chart and no way it results in legal blindness. Disabling vision is Lasik’s extremely rare complication and it can occur, lesser than 1%, according to Consumer Reports. Usually, there can be very small and temporary disturbances of vision, like halos, starbursts around lights or night vision problems.</p>\n<p><strong>How To Lower Risk Of Going Blind?</strong></p>\n<p>When the Lasik surgery is performed in a standard medical center that follows standard protocols to perform the surgery procedure, the probability of going blind after the surgery becomes nill. In addition, post operation care is the next factor that can decide the overall outcome of the Lasik procedure. Hence, all the guidelines and recommendations of the surgeons have to be noted and followed with no deviation and without neglecting.</p>\n<p><strong>What If Vision Deterioration Occurs?</strong></p>\n<p>In case the deterioration of vision is more, usually the cause is the infection or inappropriate procedure performed, without following standard protocols. Technically, it can be because of incorrect programming for guiding the laser or incorrect flap cut. So, the first and most important factor for the best outcome of the procedure is choosing the standard medical center.</p>\n<p>Hence the probability of going blind is extremely rare with the Lasik surgery and the success rate with improvement of vision is directly proportional to the selection of standard medical center, choosing experienced and skilled surgeon, followed by best post-operative care.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The direct answer is no practically and yes theoretically. Practically, there are no cases reported that the Lasik patient has gone blind after the Lasik procedure is performed. Theoretically, yes, it is possible, since Lasik is a surgery procedure. when enough care is not taken, one can go blind even without Lasik surgery. So, when [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-blink-during-lasik-3","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Can you blink during lasik?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/can-you-blink-during-lasik-3","contentHtml":"<p>Blinking is a natural process and we tend to blink from 5 to 15 times in one minute. Usually more than 99.9% of the times, it is done automatically, being unaware of the process. Blinking during Lasik is a frequently arise and common concern, before going for the Lasik surgery. But don’t worry it is not a problem. This problem is anticipated while designing the Lasik surgery and the solution has been set accordingly.</p>\n<p><strong>During the Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik procedure is performed to create the flap of the cornea and reshape the cornea. during this procedure, numbing drops are applied to the eyes, just before the actual procedure is started. These drops prevent the natural urge to blink the eyes. And there are enough arrangements are done to prevent the physical movement of the eyes and blinking. There is a small eye clip fixed over the eye that prevents the movement of blinking. So, there is nothing to worry, though one wants to blink, it would be difficult to implement. Yes, natural urge of blinking has the cause of dryness of eye and we tend to blink eyes, to moisture the eyelids and reduce dryness. That is an important concern and so the eyelids are frequently moisture for every few seconds, by applying some eye drops. So, there is no question of accidentally blinking the eyes during the procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Issues of Movement of Head and Body</strong></p>\n<p>There are enough arrangements done to prevent sudden movements of head and body and usually that is not a serious concern. The patient is laid down comfortably on cushioned and flat surface during the surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Eye Tracker</strong></p>\n<p>Today most lasers make use fo new and advanced feature, named as eye tracker to monitor the eye position automatically and adjust the movement of laser, by auto-adjusting itself for any involuntary or smaller movement of eye possible during the surgery. And this technology is quite important for custom Lasik procedure to perform accurate treatment with the laser.</p>\n<p>Eye tracking enables the process of photographing the eye every second at least 1000 times and it analyses the image for the eye position determination. In case the exact position of treatment is not found, the laser would then adjusts or adjusts towards compensating the small duration of the movement. In this way the natural body movements, like coughing, jumping or sneezing also can be managed without disturbing the process of treatment through laser movement.</p>\n<p>So, you do not need to worry about the possibility of blinking and even if the blinking happens, the movement and emitting light from the laser also will be adjusted accordingly, without damaging or disturbing the procedure. Not only that, body movements that are possible during the surgery can be managed with the same sophisticated tracking system. Just concentrate more on your preparations for the Lasik surgery, before, during and after the surgery. Thanks to technology as it makes the surgeon comfortable and patient too.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Blinking is a natural process and we tend to blink from 5 to 15 times in one minute. Usually more than 99.9% of the times, it is done automatically, being unaware of the process. Blinking during Lasik is a frequently arise and common concern, before going for the Lasik surgery. But don’t worry it is [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-does-it-take-to-recover-from-lasik-4","date":"2019-09-14","title":"How long does it take to recover from lasik?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/how-long-does-it-take-to-recover-from-lasik-4","contentHtml":"<p>The total recovery time for the Lasik surgery is not very long and it varies from one patient to another patient. The best part is that the patients will experience improvement of vision in very short duration of time after the surgery. Recovery has to be analyzed in two ways, short term and long term.</p>\n<p><strong>Short Term Recovery</strong></p>\n<p>After the Lasik surgery, it takes a few days of time to get back to the regular and day to day activities. These few days of time is considered as short term recovery, during which the surgical site would be healed to an optimal level.</p>\n<p>Immediately after the surgery, the patient experiences blurry vision and so cannot drive back home. So, the patient needs to come with a company, to drive back home safely. The patient will be sent back home with detailed and strict instructions to relax for at least 4 to 5 hours, after reaching home.</p>\n<p>The first few days after Lasik, the patient experiences small discomfort or mild pain and some irritation within the eye. During these days the patient is given with the protecting shield or patch to cover the eyes to wear especially, while sleeping. It is important to wear during sleep to prevent any possible accidental rubbing the eyelid and rubbing. Eyes become sensitive to the light and blurry vision is what one experiences, in first few days of surgery.</p>\n<p>You need to attend certain check-up appointments and visits to the hospital in 24 to 48 hours, after the surgery. Medicated eye drops are prescribed for preventing possible inflammation and infection. During this period of short term recovery, the patient should not wear contact lenses, though the vision is still blurry.</p>\n<p><strong>Long Term Recovery</strong></p>\n<p>Most commonly long term recovery after the Lasik surgery takes total 6 months for complete healing. It is common to experience many fluctuations during this recovery period. The progress of recovery is checked consistently through follow-up visits and become critical to total recovery and confirmation for the same. Usually, most of the patients start experiencing better vision after four weeks after the surgery.</p>\n<p>The six month period of recovery usually includes many of restrictions for proper healing. The most important thing is that high impact activities must be avoided in these six months recovery period for better healing. Each and every post-operative instruction must be followed without fail.</p>\n<p>Every human and so every eye is unique and there are 3 to 5% of chances for need for enhancement procedure. Need for enhancement procedure is decided by your doctor, on the basis of recovery achieved by far.</p>\n<p>So, on an overall the surgery will give fruitful results completely after 6 months and till this period additional care is mandatory during the short term period. During the long term recovery period, special care is required, when any tough or hard activities attempted. And most importantly, if anything unusual is experienced by the eyes, the patient has to address the same usual thing to one’s surgeon and it must be done immediately.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The total recovery time for the Lasik surgery is not very long and it varies from one patient to another patient. The best part is that the patients will experience improvement of vision in very short duration of time after the surgery. Recovery has to be analyzed in two ways, short term and long term. [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"does-laser-eye-surgery-hurt-2","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Does laser eye surgery hurt?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/does-laser-eye-surgery-hurt-2","contentHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery is performed though different technologies and procedures to correct the refractive errors of the eye and both Lasik and PRK do not hurt the eyes both during the procedure or right after the surgery, usually. It is because the surgeon applies numbing eye drops to relax the eyes and alleviate any possible pain to the eye, while the procedure was performed. However, discomfort is possible, because of dryness of the eyes.</p>\n<p><strong>During the Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>During the procedure the eyes are less hurt because of the laser beam and a very small incision made. However, to relieve the patient from the pain, medication may be prescribed by the surgeon, even before the procedure starts. And only topical anaesthetic drops are required and there are hardly any stitches required post the surgery. So, there is no pain experienced and there can be very small pressure over the eyes. The actual treatment using laser needs only 30 to 40 seconds, during which the laser light is focused over the eyes and pressure is felt during this period. And this pressure and its effect are short lived.</p>\n<p><strong>After the Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>After the process of reshaping the cornea, the flap would be replaced back in its place and so it serves the purpose of bandage naturally and helps the process of healing. The experiences after different laser surgeries are different. For instance, when PRK procedure is considered, discomfort is experienced during very small period and stops right after closing the epithelium. When LASEK procedure is considered, the period of recovery and so pain also are shorter. Both PRK and LASEK procedures are less painful compared to the other procedure, though both the pains are mild. Any of the laser procedure takes very less time, starting from 10 minutes to maximum 30 minutes.</p>\n<p>After a few hours of the Lasik surgery, mild itching sensation and discomfort are possible temporarily inside the eyes. Apart from that, some haziness or blurry vision can also be experienced right after the surgery. So, to get relieve from these mild pain and discomfort, surgeons prescribe some eye drops. In case the eyes are hurt badly or any severe pain is experienced, then the patient has to contact the doctor immediately and address the issue for instant treatment.</p>\n<p>Apart from mild pain, dry eye condition is the most commonly experienced symptom after the surgery, though it is temporary and it may hurt the eyes. And this condition is also treatable and relieved from the pain by applying eye drops prescribed by the surgeon. These drops must be applied consistently, as specified by the surgeon for consistent lubrication over the surface of the eyes.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Laser eye surgery is performed though different technologies and procedures to correct the refractive errors of the eye and both Lasik and PRK do not hurt the eyes both during the procedure or right after the surgery, usually. It is because the surgeon applies numbing eye drops to relax the eyes and alleviate any possible [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"does-lasik-eye-surgery-last-2","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Does lasik eye surgery last?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/does-lasik-eye-surgery-last-2","contentHtml":"<p>According to the experts, Lasik eye surgery lasts long, as it corrects the vision perception permanently. However, there is always misconception and myth in terms of understanding, whether Lasik surgery lasts or not.</p>\n<p>Lasik eye surgery corrects the vision perception, like astigmatism, farsightedness or nearsightedness, through reshaping the cornea with the help of laser and eliminates the cornea imperfections that result in astigmatism, farsightedness and/or nearsightedness. Since these imperfections are eliminated, there is no question of getting this problem occasionally. However, occasionally, the conditions of farsightedness or nearsightedness, the condition or problem progresses actually. Just like every living thing, the human organ, eye also keeps changing over the lifetime course. So expecting to use contact lens or pair of glasses for lifetime is not reasonable. The eyes keep changing after Lasik also, but they never get back to the condition, as bad as they had been in the condition, before going to the procedure.</p>\n<p>The myth of Lasik being not lasting has some basis, called reality of presbyopia. Lasik surgery cannot prevent this condition and this condition can occur naturally to anyone, increasing with the age, especially beyond 40s. during the Lasik surgery, cornea is reshaped and it does not touch the lens of the eye. However, the problem associated with lens, which is placed behind the cornea cause the condition of presbyopia. According to the experts, even we born and maintain our eyes with perfect vision, it is more likely that most of us need reading glasses after our 40s. And the same condition can prevail to the people, who have gone through Lasik surgery also. The logic here is that the Lasik surgery does not influence the lens and so presbyopia condition and so it cannot worse or pre-pone the condition.</p>\n<p>As it is mentioned above, Lasik can treat the correction of existing vision and cannot prevent the future changes that are quite common with the age, like cataract problems and presbyopia. Hence, it is important to note that in case there are problems arise after Lasik, in terms of vision, it can be because of cataract, presbyopia or other problems associated with the vision.</p>\n<p>Ideally, the surgery procedure of Lasik has been designed and developed for lasting the results for a lifetime. The regression possible is however, from 3% to 5% of the Lasik laser eye surgery patients. Most commonly, people with higher prescription or longsighted would have regression. So, in ideal conditions, like when the surgery is performed with the protocols followed by experienced and skilled surgeon and enough post-operative care has been taken, the Lasik lasts lifetime, unless other eye related problems arise.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>According to the experts, Lasik eye surgery lasts long, as it corrects the vision perception permanently. However, there is always misconception and myth in terms of understanding, whether Lasik surgery lasts or not. Lasik eye surgery corrects the vision perception, like astigmatism, farsightedness or nearsightedness, through reshaping the cornea with the help of laser and [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-lasik-permanent-2","date":"2019-09-14","title":"Is Lasik permanent?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/is-lasik-permanent-2","contentHtml":"<p>Ideally, Lasik laser eye surgery is permanent, as it reshapes the cornea permanently, towards correction of vision conditions, such as astigmatism, farsightedness and nearsightedness and reduces dependency on the contact lens and eye glasses. So, practically, in most of the cases, Lasik surgery outcomes, such as improved vision is permanent.</p>\n<p>In a very few cases, the problems of blurry vision, farsightedness, nearsightedness or other relative problems can occur, because of the changes occurring in the focussing lens of the eyes, no matter Lasik is performed or not.</p>\n<p><strong>What If Regression Occurs?</strong></p>\n<p>In case of any regression occurs because of any other changes within the eye, there is an option for the Lasik patients, called Lasik enhancement procedure and it can help to restore clear vision, for the patient. The probability of regression is different for both the genders. Average regression of vision is about -0.08 for men and -0.40 for women, after 18 years of age.</p>\n<p><strong>Studies and Reports</strong></p>\n<p>American Journal of Ophthalmology has studied the laser vision correction stability and permanence of Lasik after the surgery. It reported that approximately 6% of Lasik patients have got the need for Lasik enhancement procedure in 10 years duration after the surgery, because of myopic regression.</p>\n<p><strong>Vision Problems After Lasik</strong></p>\n<p>Coming to the practical results and general opinion of the Lasik patients, the benefits continue usually for more than 10 years. And because of the age and other factors, it is quite possible that poor eyesight and fading problems return. These problems are because of different causes.</p>\n<p>The major cause for fading of eyesight and blurry vision is because of the age, most commonly. The general prescription of the Lasik patient can be changed after long time of the surgery. If the problem occurs because of the same refractive errors, additional level of correction is possible to achieve complete outcomes of the surgery.</p>\n<p>There are many other causes also result in poor vision and blurry vision. Other important reason is age related problem, called presbyopia, which is decreased capability of natural focussing lens of the eye. It is no way related with the Lasik treatment and its surgical site, which is cornea. And one more important concern is the lifestyle that can fade away the natural capability of the eye vision. Less day to day care for the eyes and more severe eye straining activities can deteriorate the natural capability of eyes to provide clear vision.</p>\n<p><strong>Lasik as Permanent Solution</strong></p>\n<p>At least Lasik patient can expect that Lasik stands as a permanent solution to the vision problems that exist by then. And the Lasik procedure removes the tissue over the cornea to amend the underlying vision issues. It is theoretically and practically a permanent solution. The other eye problems are usually caused from other sources, not from the cornea, which is operated during the Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Ideally, Lasik laser eye surgery is permanent, as it reshapes the cornea permanently, towards correction of vision conditions, such as astigmatism, farsightedness and nearsightedness and reduces dependency on the contact lens and eye glasses. So, practically, in most of the cases, Lasik surgery outcomes, such as improved vision is permanent. In a very few cases, [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-is-the-maximum-eye-power-lasik-corrects","date":"2019-09-14","title":"What is the maximum eye power lasik corrects?","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2019/09/14/what-is-the-maximum-eye-power-lasik-corrects","contentHtml":"<p>A comprehensive eye exam is conducted to discover the existing refractive error and the eye doctor determines you have farsightedness (hyperopia), nearsightedness (myopia) and/or astigmatism and prescribes eyeglasses, by specifying the required lens power that can recover the refractive errors.</p>\n<p>The prescription of eyeglass qualifies for Lasik on the basis of different factors. The factors usually include the thickness as well as the shape fo the corneas. There are also other factors, like the brand of laser used for the laser surgery and specific kind of technology of Lasik used and parameters of treatment recommended for the laser surgery procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Maximum Eye Power for Lasik</strong></p>\n<p>In the United States, FDA approved excimer lasers for the Lasik surgery can correct the refractive error of -11.00 diopters, up to 5.00 diopters of astigmatism and +5.00 diopters of farsightedness.</p>\n<p>When the refractive error value is more, one has to notice that the risk of visual side effects, such as halos, night glare and many other issues can be more. So, the patient has to address and discuss these things with the surgeon, while preoperative consultation is made, especially, for the prescription of more than +4.00 D of hyperopia or -8.00 D of myopia.</p>\n<p>The best procedure is determined and recommended by the refractive surgeon, during the Lasik consultation, on the basis of whether the prescription is within the range of treatment recommended for Lasik surgery. In case the prescription of you is too high to go for Lasik procedure, alternate laser vision eye surgery procedures, like refractive lens exchange or phkic IOL implants would be recommended.</p>\n<p>Technically, the upper limit of power is basically dependent on corneal thickness, to go for Lasik surgery. So, usually, for correcting the powers that range in between +0.5D to +4.0 AND -0.5d TO -8.0, on an average, corneal thickness needed is approximately 530 microns. On the other hand, in certain cases, if the thickness of the cornea is much above the average, Lasik surgery procedure can correct the power of spectacles, above -8.0D and up to -10.0D. And in a very few cases, where the power of spectacle is in between -8.0 to -18.0, the alternative recommended by the surgeon is usually, ICL surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Is the Maximum Power Same Everywhere?</strong></p>\n<p>No, the maximum power that is allowed for the treatment of Lasik is not the same. It not only varies from one place to another place, but also from one eye doctor to another. Doctors have different criteria and consider different factors and determine maximum number allowed for the Lasik treatment. While some doctors limit till 10 diopters, others may stretch this maximum limit to 14 diopters. However, there is certain maximum limit set by FDA. For instance the maximum hyperopia power that can be approved according to the FDA is +6 D and usually many of the eye surgeons go till only +4 D as the limit to go for the Lasik surgery. And it also varies according to the laser machine used for the procedure. for example some better laser machines extend the capability of treating the power till +6 D.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>A comprehensive eye exam is conducted to discover the existing refractive error and the eye doctor determines you have farsightedness (hyperopia), nearsightedness (myopia) and/or astigmatism and prescribes eyeglasses, by specifying the required lens power that can recover the refractive errors. The prescription of eyeglass qualifies for Lasik on the basis of different factors. The factors [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-does-prk-recovery-take","date":"2019-09-11","title":"How long does PRK recovery take?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/11/how-long-does-prk-recovery-take","contentHtml":"<p>The PRK surgery is performed by using a laser to remove the outer cornea tissue layer completely and reshape the inner tissue of cornea. Each surgery has its own requirements and own recovery time.</p>\n<p><strong>Recovery Time</strong></p>\n<p>Recovery time is one of the most important deciding factor to choose the kind of laser eye surgery, though every laser procedure is inclined and preferred to get rid of the contact lenses and eye glasses. PRK procedure should be chosen after confirming the recovery time and ensure that enough time can be spent for recovery.</p>\n<p>The recovery time taken for PRK is slightly more compared to the other two prominent laser surgeries, SMILE and Lasik. The reason behind this is that outer cornea layer tissue is removed completely, rather than creation of a flap that gets folded back. The eye and surgical site area has to be healed completed and the tissue layers have to be regrown completely.</p>\n<p>The difference between the recovery timeline of PRK and Lasik vary slightly and the recovery is done as the following stages.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Post 1-3 days\n<ul>\n<li>Irritation and mild discomfort is experienced because of the removal of the tissue layer</li>\n<li>Pain and scratchiness are possible, but minor</li>\n<li>Never scratch or rub the eyes as it may complicate the entire process of healing</li>\n<li>More sensitivity to light</li>\n<li>The discomfort can be managed with the medication and eye drops for pain</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Post 4 days – 1 week\n<ul>\n<li>Vision gets a bit hazy or blurry</li>\n<li>Discomfort within the eye gets subsidised</li>\n<li>The vision reaches to 20/40 approximately</li>\n<li>Removal of protective contact lenses</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Post 1 week – 1 month\n<ul>\n<li>Vision gets better during day and night vision gets poor</li>\n<li>Avoid night driving as starbursts and halos of lights can be problem</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Post 1 month – 3 months\n<ul>\n<li>The cornea tissue will grown back and outer surface becomes smooth</li>\n<li>Vision gets improved</li>\n<li>Any minor or major discomforts, if exist, must be informed to the doctor for changing of medicine, if needed</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Post 3 months – 6 months\n<ul>\n<li>A state of clear and stable vision will be reached</li>\n<li>Accurate state of vision to be expressed to the doctor during the check up appointments</li>\n<li>Normal lifestyle is back with better vision</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Though recovery takes time considerable, patient experiences no risk of complications like risk of corneal flap etc. PRK is good option anyways for the patients who have thin corneas. Exploring all the existing contemporary laser eye surgical procedures is important and the best and viable decision can be taken by the surgeon, after primary examination of the patient’s eyes and overall health.</p>\n<p>Irrespective of the ease of procedure and recovery time, the long term results from the PRK procedure can be achieving the vision till 20/40 or 20/20.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The PRK surgery is performed by using a laser to remove the outer cornea tissue layer completely and reshape the inner tissue of cornea. Each surgery has its own requirements and own recovery time. Recovery Time Recovery time is one of the most important deciding factor to choose the kind of laser eye surgery, though [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-sleep-after-lasik-2","date":"2019-09-10","title":"Can you sleep after Lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/10/can-you-sleep-after-lasik-2","contentHtml":"<p>Usually after the Lasik procedure, the patient is suggested to have a nap and even sometimes a sleeping pill is also given to get one to sleep, after going home. However, the doctors suggest the patients to not to take nap at least for six hours, post to the procedure of Lasik.</p>\n<p>And it is to note that taking nap after the Lasik procedure is not the end of the world or threat to the eye health. Still, it is important to know what is acceptable and what should be healthier practice for post Lasik procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Why No Nap?</strong></p>\n<p>When we examine the technical reasons and procedure, the last step involved in the procedure of Lasik is replacing the top cornea layer and it is done with high precession, perfectly. Technically, it is important that this layer has to be aligned well, so that it could be barely predicted where the edge is present, even when seen using a microscope, post to the surgery.</p>\n<p>So, right after the surgery, it is important to wait for six hours for topcoat of epithelium to enable layer’s edge to be sealed. Since it is left in perfect state, any modification to that state is bad. After the six hour period the tendency to change its state would be reduced to an optimum level. And the most common and regular cause for microscopic is dryness.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Usually after the Lasik procedure, the patient is suggested to have a nap and even sometimes a sleeping pill is also given to get one to sleep, after going home. However, the doctors suggest the patients to not to take nap at least for six hours, post to the procedure of Lasik. And it is [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-do-you-have-to-wear-sunglasses-after-lasik","date":"2019-09-09","title":"How long do you have to wear sunglasses after Lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/09/how-long-do-you-have-to-wear-sunglasses-after-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>Most of the patients get back to their day to day activities, after a day or two of the Lasik eye surgical procedure. However, one should get back so, only after the confirmation from the surgeon. After the Lasik surgery, you are advised to wear the sunglasses, so that your eyes stay protected against the heat of the sunshine. This precaution is needed as eyes are sensitive to the intense light and even moderate heat. Sunglasses must be used, every time you step out of your house, during the day, no matter, there is sun or not.</p>\n<p><strong>Why Sunglasses?</strong></p>\n<p>Sunglasses not only protect the yes from the harmful and harsh ultraviolet rays, but also act as physical barrier to the eyes, preventing any possible dust particles to penetrate into your eyes. The same glasses also help your eyes to protect from the wind.</p>\n<p><strong>Sunglasses Indoor Also?</strong></p>\n<p>Yes, sunglasses are advised to be used indoor also, especially, during the night, before going bed. It is instructed by your surgeon, in order to prevent rubbing of your eyes.</p>\n<p><strong>How Long To Wear Sunglasses?</strong></p>\n<p>Wearing the sunglasses is mandatory both the indoor and outdoor, for the first 24 hours post surgery, at all times. After one day of surgery, you need to wear the sunglasses only outdoors to protect your eyes against dust and wind and not needed for indoors. And you have to make sure that you don’t drive with sunglasses, during nights. Typically, the period of wearing the sunglasses post surgery is not more than a couple of weeks. However, it is usually advised by your doctor to wear the sunglasses if you go for outing in the bright sun. This care is advised for a few months after the surgery, until complete recovery of the eyes. The accurate period of being cautious in the hot sun is different for individuals, and it is receive the instructions and guidelines from your surgeon, right after the surgery.</p>\n<p>On an overall, you would be the best person, understanding the best time and period, until you feel comfortable with your vision, with or without glasses.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Most of the patients get back to their day to day activities, after a day or two of the Lasik eye surgical procedure. However, one should get back so, only after the confirmation from the surgeon. After the Lasik surgery, you are advised to wear the sunglasses, so that your eyes stay protected against the [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-is-the-best-corrective-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-08","title":"What is the best corrective eye surgery?","category":"Comparisons","path":"/blog/2019/09/08/what-is-the-best-corrective-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>In case a person does not want to wear contacts or glasses for life long, then one decides to go through the laser eye surgery, as the possible and best solution. There are three viable and potential laser eye surgeries available in the contemporary medical industry and selecting the best and suitable one stands as the first significant deciding factor.</p>\n<p>The three laser eye surgeries are Lasik, SMILE and PRK and are the safe, trusted and effective in terms of correcting one’s vision. And now the question is which procedure to choose?</p>\n<p><strong>PRK</strong></p>\n<p>Photorefractive Keratectomy stands as the first generation of vision correction using laser. The procedure can correct astigmatism, farsightedness and nearsightedness.</p>\n<p><strong>The Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>The procedure of PRK involves removing the outer cornea layer or epithelium, through a manual instrument. Then the cornea is reshaped by using a cool excimer laser for correction of the vision.</p>\n<p><strong>Is PRK a Good Option?</strong></p>\n<p>Some patients, who have irregular or thin corneas or suffer from chronic dry eye become potential candidates for the PRK. Usually fighters and boxers or anyone with similar lifestyles have possibility of direct contact to the eyes. In a nutshell, patients, who have dry eyes, thin corneas and high-risk occupations, can prefer PRK procedure and anyways they do not get qualified for the Lasik procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Downsides of PRK</strong></p>\n<p>Among the three procedures, PRK stands at last position in terms of faster recovery time, as it takes very long time to heal. It needs the outer layer of the cornea to grow back and it takes minimum a week and usually more than a week to get back to normal conditions. If the procedure is conducted for both the eyes, the patient has to take an off for a week, from driving or work. And compared to the other two, this procedure results in higher post-surgery discomfort.</p>\n<p><strong>LASIK</strong></p>\n<p>Laser-Assisted Stromal In-situ Keratomileusis is the most familiar surgery to the people, in and out of the medical industry, as it is most commonly performed procedure today. LASIK is preferred to treat astigmatism, farsightedness and nearsightedness at mild to moderate levels.</p>\n<p><strong>The Procedure</strong></p>\n<p>The procedure involves creation of a small flap of corneal tissue, with the help of femtosecond laser and the same would be folded back. Then the underlying corneal tissue will be reshaped, using an excimer laser for correction of vision.</p>\n<p><strong>Is LASIK a Good Option?</strong></p>\n<p>From surgeon point of view, a person, who has enough or adequate corneal thickness is qualified for the Lasik procedure. It is because a flap is created and it needs adequate corneal thickness. So, technically a candidate is qualified for LASIK only under this condition, though most of the patients prefer this procedure, since it is mostly familiar. Hence, people with no adequate corneal thickness can prefer alternative procedures, either PRK or SMILE procedures. However, LASIK stands as a preference for most of the people, since it is safe, effective and trusted compared to the other.</p>\n<p><strong>Downsides </strong></p>\n<p>LASIK is safe and effective and at the same time, is has a downside that the procedure involves complex tasks, such as creation of flap and usage of two lasers. Hence technically, potential complications related to flap are possible post-surgery. Possible flap related complications are irregular astigmatism, microscopic wrinkles like striae, dry eye syndrome and epithelial ingrowth. Though these complications are rare and nullified by partnering with experienced surgeons, these are technically possible.</p>\n<p><strong>SMILE</strong></p>\n<p>Small Incision Lenticule Extraction, which is the latest laser procedure, has been approved by the FDA and is in practice widely in the US from 2012.</p>\n<p><strong>The Procedure and Benefits</strong></p>\n<p>The procedure is performed to cut very small or tiny incision within the cornea and then a lenticule or small corneal tissue pieces are removed, suing femtosecond laser. It eventually reshapes the cornea and the result is the vision improvement. The major difference between SMILE and other two procedures is that it does not make use of excimer laser, during the procedure. So, this procedure ends up quiet and odourless.</p>\n<p>Comparatively LASIK, SMILE is less invasive surgery. The incision needed for SMILE is only 3mm compared to 8mm for PRK and 20mm in Lasik procedures. Hence it results in less disturbed corneal nerves and more corneal stability after the surgery.</p>\n<p>There are no flap related complications with SMILE procedure, unlike with Lasik, after the surgery. SMILE is as accurate and safe as Lasik.</p>\n<p><strong>Downsides</strong></p>\n<p>SMILE procedure is performed for only nearsightedness currently but not for astigmatism or farsightedness. The recovery time is slightly more than Lasik procedure.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>In case a person does not want to wear contacts or glasses for life long, then one decides to go through the laser eye surgery, as the possible and best solution. There are three viable and potential laser eye surgeries available in the contemporary medical industry and selecting the best and suitable one stands as [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-blink-during-lasik","date":"2019-09-06","title":"Can you blink during Lasik?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/06/can-you-blink-during-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>This is a natural question and concern arises, at least after deciding for the surgery. There is nothing to worry, because moving and blinking the eye during the Lasik surgery result no risks. Usually, a human being blinks the eyes for 5 to 15 times in a minute. So, the patient does not need to worry about this fact, because there are certain alternatives employed to manage eye blinking.</p>\n<p><strong>How Eye Blinking Is Managed?</strong></p>\n<p>Prior to initiating the surgery process, your eyes will be applied with numbing drops, so that you feel comfortable. It is also useful to relieve from the natural urge for eye blinking. During the surgical procedure, a small device is employed on your eyes to keep holding the eyelids open, so that the eyes are not accidentally blinked and there will be no interference from the eyelids. So, during the surgery, cornea gets numbed and you don’t feel the urge to blink the eyes.</p>\n<p><strong>What About Body and Body Parts?</strong></p>\n<p>During the surgery, not only the eye blink, but also any movement of body and head are not serious concerns. Lasik eye surgery is a very brief surgery that lasts for 10 to 12 minutes, for both of the eyes. Lasik surgeon uses restrictive instrument to hold your eyelids open during the procedure; so blinking is not a concern.</p>\n<p>Also, there is an advanced technological feature called eye tracker is available for most of the lasers employed for the Lasik surgeries. The technological feature helps to monitor the eye’s position and enables the laser to adjust accordingly towards compensation of any involuntary and small eye movements, possible, while the surgery is performed. This technology gets essentially employed to ensure that the Lasik eye surgery is performed most accurately.</p>\n<p>The technology is employed by photographing the eye, nearly 1000 times in one second so that the images are enabled to determine the accurate position of the eyelid and cornea. Laser is applied, only analysing that the focussing area is safe enough, otherwise it keeps waiting. So, you need to explore the possibilities, while discussing with your Lasik surgeon.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>This is a natural question and concern arises, at least after deciding for the surgery. There is nothing to worry, because moving and blinking the eye during the Lasik surgery result no risks. Usually, a human being blinks the eyes for 5 to 15 times in a minute. So, the patient does not need to [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-watch-tv-after-laser-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-06","title":"Can I watch TV after laser eye surgery?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/06/can-i-watch-tv-after-laser-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Surgery is a complex procedure in medical industry, but thanks to the advancement of the technology, as it reduced the discomfort to a great level for the patient. Till the surgery, it is the expertise of the surgeon and after the surgery, it is the care of the patient, during the recovery period, which define the success of the surgery. Don’t worry, recovery from the Lasik eye surgery does not trouble you long.</p>\n<p><strong>Watching Television</strong></p>\n<p>Watching television, reading books, working on computer, driving are the regular activities, which are difficult to avoid. And the good news is that you can perform all these daily activities, including watching television after 24 hours post to the surgery. Generally, the no screen period is 24 hours. This period is enough technically, for the cornea to regain its normal strength and gets better with the natural healing process.</p>\n<p><strong>That Is All?</strong></p>\n<p>Yes, that is the minimum time given to resume back to the daily activities. And it is important to remember that during these activities, eyes get strained more, compared to the other day to day activities. So, usually your surgeon instructs you to lubricate your eyes, before starting any of these activities.</p>\n<p><strong>How Long To Lubricate Eyes?</strong></p>\n<p>Though it takes a couple of weeks to recover your eyes to resume to full fledged daily activities, lubricating your eyes is important. The total period of lubrication of eyes process is different for different people, as it depends on the expertise of the surgery, care taken during the recovery process. The period of lubrication usually is decided by your surgeon, by considering the condition of the eyes and overall health condition.</p>\n<p><strong>And Not To Forget</strong></p>\n<p>And the fact of effect of the television screen should not be forgotten. Continuous watching of the television definitely disturb even the healthy eye and so the eyes in the recovery period. So, even you are allowed to watch the television after 24 hours of the surgery, you need to be mindful always that watching television should be minimized to a possible extent. So, be cautious to watch television only for a few hours, until complete recovery from the surgery.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Surgery is a complex procedure in medical industry, but thanks to the advancement of the technology, as it reduced the discomfort to a great level for the patient. Till the surgery, it is the expertise of the surgeon and after the surgery, it is the care of the patient, during the recovery period, which define [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"which-eye-laser-surgery-is-the-best","date":"2019-09-06","title":"Which eye laser surgery is the best?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/06/which-eye-laser-surgery-is-the-best","contentHtml":"<p>If one looks for the best laser eye surgery, probably the one has to realize the fact that the best option for the same person may not be the best option for someone else. When someone wants to go for laser eye surgery to correct the refractive errors, the best deciding factor is one’s eyes condition and the respective refractive error. It is because each of this procedure is suitable for patients, having slightly different vision needs. So, one cannot choose the laser eye surgery that has more success rate, but something that one has to go for is the unique eye condition.</p>\n<p>After selecting the viable procedures suitable for the eye condition, the second factor is to choose the best possible surgery that suits the budget.</p>\n<p>Having decided the budget, one has to look for the nearby hospitals that offer the same procedures. On the other hand, if the budget is flexible, on can prefer travelling to a little further, in order to find the best medical center that offer qualitative medical services, for better success rate of the surgery. If budget permits, it is always a moving a bit longer can be a better option, instead of compromising with the local hospital.</p>\n<p><strong>Types of Laser Eye Surgeries</strong></p>\n<p>Laser vision correction can be technically performed for two different purposes called,</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Flap Surgery – This surgery is performed in two different ways, called,\n<ol>\n<li>Microkeratome Lasik</li>\n<li>Intralase Lasik, which is also known as Sub-Bowman’s Lasik</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Surface Surgery – This surgery is performed to achieve the respective objectives, called,\n<ol>\n<li>PRK</li>\n<li>LASEK</li>\n<li>Epi-LASIK</li>\n<li>SMILE</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>All these surgeries can be performed by either through wavefront guided or non-wavefront-guided.</p>\n<p>Among all the three laser eye surgeries, Lasik is the most commonly performed surgery, however, it is not suitable for the patients, who have thin cornea. the alternatives in such cases are PRK and SMILE. So, if the Lasik is suitable for the one, one can go through the Lasik surgery, otherwise the only option that would be left is SMILE or PRK.</p>\n<p>When it comes to pros and cons, these are almost more or less the same for all the three laser eye surgeries. So, among all these laser surgeries, the best surgery for you is the one that suits you.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>If one looks for the best laser eye surgery, probably the one has to realize the fact that the best option for the same person may not be the best option for someone else. When someone wants to go for laser eye surgery to correct the refractive errors, the best deciding factor is one’s eyes [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-does-it-take-to-recover-from-lasik-2","date":"2019-09-05","title":"How long does it take to recover from Lasik?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/05/how-long-does-it-take-to-recover-from-lasik-2","contentHtml":"<p>The accurate period for recovery after the Lasik eye surgery is performed is varied, from one individual to another individual. However, under ideal conditions, significant improvement is experienced by the patient in two days. When it comes to the improvement and feel of clear vision, it takes 2 to 7 days after the surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>What Are The Factors?</strong></p>\n<p>The success of the Lasik eye surgery and so the period of recovery depends on various factors. The most important factors are the general overall health condition of the patient, experience of the surgeon, who performed the surgery and also on kind of refractive procedure performed.</p>\n<p><strong>What About Complete Recovery?</strong></p>\n<p>After 7 days, one can experience and feel better vision. Since the treatment is a surgical procedure, it takes over 6 months of duration for complete recovery.</p>\n<p><strong>What Immediately Next To The Surgery?</strong></p>\n<p>Right after the surgery, first few hours are very crucial for the overall success and safety of the eyes. So, doctor gives very concrete and strict instruct that must be followed. You will not be allowed to drive to head home after completion of the surgery. You need to arrange for the transportation to get back home. Most likely, you will need to go for an appointment for check up, within 48 hours, post to the surgery. The check up is done to examine the vision and eyes. Any possibilities of inflammation and infection can be prevented by administering medicated eye drops. Even your vision is a bit blurry, your doctor does not allow to wear any kind of contact lenses.</p>\n<p><strong>Short Term Recovery</strong></p>\n<p>First few days post to the surgery, you may feel eye pain, because of possible irritation and may result in weeping. It may make you feel as if there is a small piece of sand in your eyes. You need to wear a shield or patch over the eyes, especially, while sleeping, since you need to prevent rubbing the eyelids and eyes.</p>\n<p>There is a possibility of subconjunctival haemorrhage, usually, on the basis of the kind of Lasik performed during the surgery, since a suction device is used on the eyes, during initial stages of the surgical procedure. It is going to be mild and fade day by day, lasting for a couple of weeks.</p>\n<p>So, recovery is a crucial period for the patient, as every minute one has to be careful and get reminded with the instructions given by the doctor. After short term recovery, you can proceed with your day to day activities.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The accurate period for recovery after the Lasik eye surgery is performed is varied, from one individual to another individual. However, under ideal conditions, significant improvement is experienced by the patient in two days. When it comes to the improvement and feel of clear vision, it takes 2 to 7 days after the surgery. What [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-are-the-best-eye-drops-after-lasik","date":"2019-09-05","title":"What are the best eye drops after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/09/05/what-are-the-best-eye-drops-after-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>After the Lasik eye surgery, dry eye become common. As part of the Lasik surgical procedure and treatment, it is necessary that one maintains the eyes dry-free, by lubricating the eyes to the possible ways. The symptom of dry eyes can continue for a few weeks to a few months and sometimes longer. As long these dry eyes are existing, the lubrication process has to go on.</p>\n<p>Since dry eyes may result in lesser visual outcomes and discomfort, eye drops are suggested by the eye surgeons or even similar therapies so that eye moisture can be maintained.</p>\n<p>Dry eyes are caused by tear film and it has three important components, mucus, oil and water. The eye drops are suggested to the unique condition of the patient, on the basis of particular condition of dry eye. The recommendation would be on the basis of which layer lacks or combination of these layers. And selection of the best eye drop for your unique condition is identified after conducting dry eye evaluation. The evaluation involves close eye surface examination and special testing.</p>\n<p>Most of the surgeons recommend artificial tears, like Refresh Plus and Refresh Optive Lubricant Eye Drops. These both are recommended especially for post-Lasik dryness and are preservative-free. The doctor also suggests certain instructions to follow.</p>\n<p>Apart from these tears, some of the surgeons may also recommend Restasis eye drops that help the body formulate further more tears and reduce the inflammation to a better extent. These drops may be suggested as alternative to the above eye drops also. Dry eyes are also treated with other kind of remedies, such as punctual plugs and they help to block drainage channels of tear so that eye moisture can be increased. These plugs also help function as anti-inflammatory medications, like corticosteroids, suggested in the form of eye drops.</p>\n<p>The staff explain how one experiences, after applying these eye drops, like blurry of vision or slight stinging sensation, after instilling. You will be given oral instructions to apply the eye drops. Detailed written instructions are given to you for proper usage and application of these eye drops.</p>\n<p><strong>Instructions to Instill Eye Drops</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Sit relax and tilt the head back and focus your eyes over the ceiling</li>\n<li>Open the eye drops bottle and hold it over the eyes and never touch the dropper’s tip, with the fingertips or anything else</li>\n<li>Pull down on the lower eye lid gently using a finger</li>\n<li>Place the dropper very close to the eye and ensure not to touch the eyelid, eye, eyelashes, etc. It is important to avoid any contamination, possible.</li>\n<li>Squeeze and release one drop from the bottle into the eyelid’s lower pocket</li>\n<li>Then release the lower eyelid and ensure to close the eyes and open after 30 seconds for even distribution of the fluid in the eye</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These are the eye drops you usually use after the Lasik surgery, but ensure to use only after recommendation by your Lasik surgeon and make sure that you follow the instructions of applying the eye drops into the eyes.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>After the Lasik eye surgery, dry eye become common. As part of the Lasik surgical procedure and treatment, it is necessary that one maintains the eyes dry-free, by lubricating the eyes to the possible ways. The symptom of dry eyes can continue for a few weeks to a few months and sometimes longer. As long [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-barrage-laser-painful","date":"2019-09-04","title":"Is barrage laser painful?","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2019/09/04/is-barrage-laser-painful","contentHtml":"<p>Barrage laser is performed to strength certain areas of retina, which are weakened or to seal retinal tears. The threat of pain is common in potential patients, who are going to receive the treatment, may be because of the intense laser beams of laser light focusing directly over the retina.</p>\n<p>There is nothing to worry about the pain, as there is hardly any pain felt by the patient during the procedure, since some special contact lens would be placed on the eye. The eye can feel only flashes of light, instead of intense laser beam. However, occasionally, there is subtle pain possible felt within the eye. Though the pain is very less, some kind of discomfort is felt by the patient, because it is unknown and never experienced pain. As this pain is never felt by the body, nervous system gets alert completely. However, this pain is very subtle. The patient may feel and see everything in magenta tint after the procedure and it gets continued for 3 to 4 minutes. After a few minutes, the vision and everything becomes normal.</p>\n<p>During the procedure, high intensity light is focused on the eyes and it allows the surgeon and if possible the patient can also look all the interior of the eye, over the screen. For instance, the patient can see the clear structure of the veins and many more detailed stuff over the screen. However, because of a little discomfort within the internal part of the eye, one may or may not be able to look at the internal structure of the eye.</p>\n<p>The patient could have the capability to perform the day to day activities after the surgery including the driving of the car. However, on the same day of the procedure, someone is needed to drive to take you home, as immediately after the procedure, the eyes do not get ready to function as normal.</p>\n<p>Hence it is not the pain but a slight discomfort experienced during barrage laser procedure and it is absolutely safe.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Barrage laser is performed to strength certain areas of retina, which are weakened or to seal retinal tears. The threat of pain is common in potential patients, who are going to receive the treatment, may be because of the intense laser beams of laser light focusing directly over the retina. There is nothing to worry [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"does-laser-eye-surgery-last-forever-2","date":"2019-09-03","title":"Does laser eye surgery last forever?","category":"LASIK Technology","path":"/blog/2019/09/03/does-laser-eye-surgery-last-forever-2","contentHtml":"<p><strong>Laser Surgery and Lasik Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>Laser surgery opens the doors for many queries and uncertainties, naturally, because of the laser treatment involved and especially, more for Lasik, since it deals with the eyes, which are most sensitive parts of the body. With the advancement of the technology and laser treatment in other parts of the medical industries, should clear at least 50 percent of these queries and uncertainties. Rest of the 50 percent of them, must be addressed without fail.</p>\n<p><strong>Lasik Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>Ideally and technically, Lasik eye surgery stands as the permanent and the best-chosen treatment for three major vision problems, such as astigmatism, hyperopia (farsightedness), and myopia (nearsightedness). The role of the laser is to reshape the cornea physically, so that its ability of focus can be improved.</p>\n<p><strong>Does It Last Forever?</strong></p>\n<p>According to the statistics, most of the patients will not need to go for any new set of eyeglasses or contact lenses after going through the Lasik surgery, since it is a permanent procedure. The outcome of the surgery would be the best, in cases the follow-up procedures are taken care well. The objective of the follow-up procedure is to ensure no further vision problems, by attempting to correct minor changes or affects, experienced after the surgery. When the surgery is followed by timely follow-up procedure, it is most likely that you would never need to consult any further ophthalmologist, except for regular checkups.</p>\n<p>So, in most of the cases, it has been proved that the Lasik laser refractive procedure can be considered as the permanent solution for the most frequent eye problems, such as nearsightedness, farsightedness or astigmatism.</p>\n<p>One important aspect that is worth mentioning and understanding here is that the success of the Lasik contributes 50 percent of the overall success of the correction of the eye problem. The rest of the 50 percent of success is contributed by the overall health condition and follow-up procedures, post the surgery. There would be hardly any chances of farsightedness or nearsightedness, post the Lasik surgery, when there is stability found in the prescription, before attempting to the surgery.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Laser Surgery and Lasik Surgery Laser surgery opens the doors for many queries and uncertainties, naturally, because of the laser treatment involved and especially, more for Lasik, since it deals with the eyes, which are most sensitive parts of the body. With the advancement of the technology and laser treatment in other parts of the [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-lasik-eye-surgery-temporary","date":"2019-09-03","title":"Is Lasik eye surgery temporary?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/03/is-lasik-eye-surgery-temporary","contentHtml":"<p>Lasik eye surgery, being a surgery operated with lasers, the second doubt one gets after its level of safety is, whether the surgery provides permanent solution to the vision problems or not. It is important to ensure whether the Lasik eye surgery offers either permanent or temporary results.</p>\n<p><strong>Analysis From Statistics</strong></p>\n<p>Statistics indicate that in most of the cases, the Lasik eye surgery offers permanent positive results, rather than temporary results. Statistics say that over 95% of the success depends on the success of the surgery and rest of 5% is dependent on various external factors. These factors can be the age, the gender, the previous eye vision condition and the overall health condition of the patient. And now the question following this confirmation would be what if results are temporary.</p>\n<p><strong>When The Results Can Be Temporary?</strong></p>\n<p>In a very few cases, the results can be temporary. The cases can be changes occurring in the natural lens exist with the eye, irrespective of the Lasik surgery conducted or not. The results of these changes could be return of astigmatism, farsightedness and / or nearsightedness, over time that causes blurry vision.</p>\n<p><strong>What Is The Solution?</strong></p>\n<p>In the cases, where the blurry vision is resulted, Lasik enhancement follow-up procedure stands as the solution. After this procedure, clear vision can be restored.</p>\n<p><strong>Which Statistics?</strong></p>\n<p>American Journal of Ophthalmology has also conducted a long-term study of laser vision correction and its stability. There were only approximately 6 percent of the patients needed to go for a Lasik enhancement, who underwent the Lasik eye surgery for myopia correction up to -10.0D, within 10 years.</p>\n<p>Journal of Cataract &amp; Refractive Surgery has published a study, related to a similar laser vision correction procedure called PRK and its stability, recently. Total 46 patients were considered and consistently monitored them for 18 years, by the researchers in the UK. All of them were nearsighted with prescription of an average of -4.86 D covered in the range of -2.75 to -7.37 D.</p>\n<p>In the same follow-up period of 18 years, patients, under 40 years of age, when the procedure of Lasik was conducted had -0.54 average regression. Only -0.05 D average regression was found for them, when the patients underwent the Lasik.</p>\n<p><strong>Does Gender Matter?</strong></p>\n<p>Yes, statistics say that there is a significant difference of the results, with the gender. Men have experienced -0.08 D average regression over the period of 18 years and women have got -0.40 D.</p>\n<p>So, in a nutshell, in most of the cases, the positive results after the Lasik eye surgery are permanent and in a very few cases results can be temporary, yet the temporary results can be well controlled.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik eye surgery, being a surgery operated with lasers, the second doubt one gets after its level of safety is, whether the surgery provides permanent solution to the vision problems or not. It is important to ensure whether the Lasik eye surgery offers either permanent or temporary results. Analysis From Statistics Statistics indicate that in [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"what-percent-of-lasik-surgeries-go-wrong-3","date":"2019-09-03","title":"What percent of Lasik surgeries go wrong?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/03/what-percent-of-lasik-surgeries-go-wrong-3","contentHtml":"<p>Though the success rate of the Lasik surgery is at very optimal levels, it is quite possible that we still look for the possible complications, because eye is the most sensitive organ in the body and the eyesight is the primary requisite for every moment and every micro-level task to perform by us. So, the idea of exploring and discovering the pros and cons of the Lasik surgery is always appreciable.</p>\n<p>There are tonnes of data and information about the Lasik surgery in the internet. Reviews, reports, opinions and medical center data are available and only authenticated data has to be considered. Authenticated data is available by the studies and reports by medical authorities and councils. According to the medical authorities, the total success rate of the Lasik is more than 96% and hence the percent of Lasik surgeries that can go wrong would be, eventually, lesser than 4%.</p>\n<p><strong>What Is Going Wrong?</strong></p>\n<p>Percent of Lasik surgeries going wrong does mean that the complications and risks are evident and the consequences are unpleasant in terms of vision. In fact the complications and risks are associated with any and every surgery in the medical industry. Let us see what are these side effects, complications and risks associated with Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p><strong>Side Effects </strong></p>\n<p>These side effects can be diminished very soon, in just a few days and maximum in a week or two. the statistical data in the form of published clinical data and peer-reviewed data conclude as the following.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Less than 5% of patients may need contacts lenses, eye glasses or additional Lasik treatment to get rid of higher-order aberrations over the cornea side effects and side effects and also to smooth out any remaining uncorrected refractive errors, like farsightedness, nearsightedness and astigmatism.</li>\n<li>Dry eye symptoms that are common after the procedure, and continue usually for first three months, post surgery.</li>\n<li>Some of the other side effects and symptoms, like glare, halos along with night vision problems are common and may continue for 6 to 12 months. These side effects can be diminished through certain therapeutic treatments.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Complication Rate</strong></p>\n<p>Complications are different from side effects or risks. The difference is that complications demand additional treatment or another phase of surgical procedure, but the risks and side effects don’t. Complications are very rare from Lasik and so the complicate rate is less, however, technically possible. The possible complications are…</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Infections</li>\n<li>Dislocation of the flap of the cornea, during the surgery</li>\n</ul>\n<p>They should be discovered and treated at the earliest to turn the outcome of Lasik from negative to positive. These complications are extremely rare and usually lesser than 1%.</p>\n<p>According to FDA, the percentage of Lasik patients reporting the symptoms, from smaller to bigger is in between 5 to 10% and these symptoms are faded away in a few weeks after the surgery. Hence, don’t worry, Lasik failure rate is very less and negligible on an overall.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Though the success rate of the Lasik surgery is at very optimal levels, it is quite possible that we still look for the possible complications, because eye is the most sensitive organ in the body and the eyesight is the primary requisite for every moment and every micro-level task to perform by us. So, the [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"is-there-an-age-limit-on-lasik-surgery","date":"2019-09-02","title":"Is there an age limit on Lasik surgery?","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2019/09/02/is-there-an-age-limit-on-lasik-surgery","contentHtml":"<p><strong>Lasik and Success</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik is a refractive eye surgery prominently heard in the medical industry, for better vision and healthy eyes. Usually, any candidate with normal health condition is suitable for this surgery. However, there are certain significant factors that determine the overall success of the surgery. The first factor is the age of the candidate, who goes through the surgery. Apart from the overall health condition of the candidate, age plays major role in the success of the surgery and healing of the problem.</p>\n<p><strong>Age Factor</strong></p>\n<p>Till the age of 18, the eyes would be in the stage of development. So, technically, the surgery is not attempted for the candidates, who haven’t crossed 18 years of age. It is not advised to select the candidate for the surgery, since the eyesight can be improved in the near future. Surgery can be considered for the candidates after 18 years, in case they have had 2 or more years of stable prescription. It indicates that the eyesight of the candidate has got stable and in the near future, there can be unlikely change of refractive errors. While 18 stand as the minimum limit of age, there is also approximate maximum limit of the age.</p>\n<p><strong>Maximum Age Limit</strong></p>\n<p>Usually, the risk of attempting the surgeries, especially, sensitive surgeries, like Lasik would be more for the candidate, if one crosses 40 years of age. It is because there is a fair chance of affecting by presbyopia that leaves one, hard to read small printed letters. So, the treatment for presbyopia can be more appropriate, if one suffers from the same, before going to the Lasik surgery.</p>\n<p>So, usually, the candidates, who are in between 18 years to 40 years of age are ideally suitable for the surgery. However, this is not a hard and fast rule. The health condition of the eye and the overall health condition of the candidate can allow the surgeons to choose them for this surgery. So, technically, there is no upper age limit to conduct Lasik surgery, provided other conditions and factors stand satisfactory.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Lasik and Success Lasik is a refractive eye surgery prominently heard in the medical industry, for better vision and healthy eyes. Usually, any candidate with normal health condition is suitable for this surgery. However, there are certain significant factors that determine the overall success of the surgery. The first factor is the age of the [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"are-you-awake-during-lasik-2","date":"2019-09-02","title":"Are you awake during Lasik?","category":"LASIK Insights","path":"/blog/2019/09/02/are-you-awake-during-lasik-2","contentHtml":"<p><strong>What Exactly Is The Procedure?</strong></p>\n<p>Before exploring the need for being sleep or awake, during the process of Lasik eye surgery, knowing the exact procedure of the surgery is important. The surgery of Lasik takes no more than 10 minutes. And no general anaesthesia is given for the surgery. Usually, the laser focused on the cornea to reshape it is just lesser than a minute, typically, per eye. Local anaesthesia is given to the patient with anaesthetic eye drops. It helps you not to feel painful, while the surgery is being conducted.</p>\n<p><strong>Is Anaesthesia Given?</strong></p>\n<p>General anaesthesia has its own benefits and risks, associated with any kind of surgery, including Lasik surgery and offer with no significant added benefits of curing, but increasing the cost of the surgery and hindrance in following up surgeon instruction during the lasik procedure.</p>\n<p>However, a mild sedative is preferred by the surgeons, in certain cases, where you are anxious or fear during the surgical procedure. The mild sedative is opted to help you relax.</p>\n<p>So, technically, it is important that you realize that taking anaesthesia is more harmful, compared to undergoing the surgery with no such sedative. Local anaesthesia helps you to feel no pain causing from the laser focussed on the cornea. So, getting mentally prepared that the undergoing the surgery with no general anaesthesia can reduce the overall recovery time and reduce the health risks, on an overall. When you are mentally prepared well and confident about the procedure, it helps to reduce nerves and feel comfortable.</p>\n<p><strong>What Lasik Surgery Patients To Say?</strong></p>\n<p>Most of the patients report that surgery is completed much before than the expected time and it is found to be very less stressful than it could be as anticipated.</p>\n<p><strong>I Still Have Fear</strong></p>\n<p>If you still fear about being awake during the surgery, it should be respected and considered, by the surgeon and proceed with increasing sedatives. However, consulting and discussing with the patients, who underwent the same procedure of surgery can be helpful, as they are the best people to share the experience. You can also learn that the post surgery risks are less for the surgery conducted with the least sedatives.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>What Exactly Is The Procedure? Before exploring the need for being sleep or awake, during the process of Lasik eye surgery, knowing the exact procedure of the surgery is important. The surgery of Lasik takes no more than 10 minutes. And no general anaesthesia is given for the surgery. Usually, the laser focused on the [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"has-anyone-went-blind-from-lasik","date":"2019-09-02","title":"Has anyone went blind from Lasik?","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2019/09/02/has-anyone-went-blind-from-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>According to many researches and respective reports, Lasik laser eye surgery is safe and none has gone blind, as none has reported going blind. However, there are certain cases, where blindness was resulted, after the Lasik surgery, for varied reasons.</p>\n<p>Some reports, though not authenticated by FDA and other legal medical councils, share that an old woman had experienced it after having Lasik surgery. The surgery has caused blindness and later the direct cause for the deterioration of eyesight was discovered to be mycobacterium chelonae infection. The infection has destroyed cornea. She experienced constant pain and vision is very much deteriorated. She has got the hope of corneal transplant to recover from vision deterioration.</p>\n<p>However, till now no authenticated medical council or FDA has reported that anyone went blind after the Lasik surgery. The same medical authorities and councils have informed about the complications possible through infections. The guidelines are also recommended to prevent the infections and so possibilities of going blind.</p>\n<p>If the refractive error is very small and manageable with the glasses, some of the medical authorities do not suggest Lasik laser or any other laser based surgeries. Though these are not very complicated surgeries, the possibility of infections and other complications are possible technically. The procedure itself causes no complications, but there must be standard protocols set and followed at every instance of it.</p>\n<p>In case the vision refractive error is more and has higher degree of prescription, one can go for Lasik. But very important factors to consider before going for Lasik are choosing the standard and trust-worthy medical center to undergo the surgery. On the other hand, one more important aspect to consider here is that the surgeon, who is going to operate the eye must be enough experienced and must be highly skilled.  When the surgery is performed with international standards and all the protocols are followed without fail by the surgeon, 90% of the surgery outcome is optimistic. The rest of the 10% success is in the hands of the patient, who takes care of the eye after the surgery. The results can be 100% successful and improvement of vision can be at optimal levels, only when the post-operative care is good enough.</p>\n<p>All the guidelines and recommendations provided by the surgeon, have to be followed without fail. Day to day activities can be resumed after a couple of days and hard and outdoor activities after a couple of weeks usually. Since, every person’s eyes conditions are unique, this generalized recovery period may not be the same for all patient. So, during post-surgery visits to the surgeon, it is quite important to address all kinds of activities that are part of the life of the patient and get to know the right time to resume all those activities.</p>\n<p>When you choose the right medical center with the skilled surgeon, the Lasik eye surgery will be successful and when the post surgery care is up to the standard level, your outcomes of Surgery will be purely optimistic and completely satisfactory.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>According to many researches and respective reports, Lasik laser eye surgery is safe and none has gone blind, as none has reported going blind. However, there are certain cases, where blindness was resulted, after the Lasik surgery, for varied reasons. Some reports, though not authenticated by FDA and other legal medical councils, share that an [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"who-qualifies-for-laser-eye-surgery","date":"2019-09-01","title":"Who qualifies for laser eye surgery?","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2019/09/01/who-qualifies-for-laser-eye-surgery","contentHtml":"<p><strong>LASIK</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik is a simple laser surgery attempted for correction of vision, by correction of hyperopia, myopia and astigmatism. It is one kind of refractive surgery. The surgery involves the process of reshaping the cornea of the eye so that the visual acuity can be improved. The objective of the Lasik treatment is to provide an alternative to contact lenses or eyeglasses.</p>\n<p><strong>Who is the right person?</strong></p>\n<p>Though Lasik surgery is not a very major surgery, since it deals with the sensitive organ of the body, the eye, it is important to get hundred percent positive result, without affecting the natural vision of the eye. So, candidates for the surgery are chosen so carefully to ensure that the result is 100 percent accurate. So, the candidate for the surgery needs to have the following parameters satisfied.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>To have minimum of 18 years of age, however, preferably, lesser than 40 years</li>\n<li>Have stable vision, for at least the recent one year</li>\n<li>Have prescription of stable contact lense or eyeglass, continued for at least 2 years to 3 years</li>\n<li>Have no findings or history of corneal disease that is active</li>\n<li>Must not be nursing or pregnant</li>\n<li>Have no significant or serious eye problems or medical problems, like keratoconus, macular degeneration, diabetic retinopathy, glaucoma or corneal ulcers</li>\n<li>Have eyeglass prescribed by eye surgeon and stands within certain limits</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Technically…</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The candidate is expected to have thick cornea reasonably, to the existing cornea, since reshaping of the cornea is involved in this refractive surgery. So, irregular shaped surfaces or very thin surfaces may affect the overall success and result and may even worsen the actual and present vision of the eye.</li>\n<li>The pupils of the candidate are expected not to be overly large, since it may increase the possible risks of halos, starbursts and glares. This risk is more, during the drives.</li>\n<li>The condition of the eye must be good for the candidate, to heal the problem properly. Candidates should not have any conditions, such as injury to the eye, infection, conjunctivitis or severe dry eyes. These conditions must be corrected prior to attempting the Lasik surgery.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The success of the Lasik surgery not only depends on the success of the surgery, but the overall health condition of the eye and body of the candidate.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>LASIK Lasik is a simple laser surgery attempted for correction of vision, by correction of hyperopia, myopia and astigmatism. It is one kind of refractive surgery. The surgery involves the process of reshaping the cornea of the eye so that the visual acuity can be improved. The objective of the Lasik treatment is to provide [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-you-go-blind-from-lasik","date":"2019-09-01","title":"Can you go blind from Lasik?","category":"Safety & Risk","path":"/blog/2019/09/01/can-you-go-blind-from-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>It is natural to think both pros and cons of any surgery, especially, sensitive surgeries, like Lasik eye surgery. It is almost unusual for any patient to go blind, after going through Lasik eye surgery. There are millions of procedures of Lasik have been taken place, with higher levels of effectiveness and safety, worldwide. There are hardly any cases, especially, when the patient attends all the visits of follow-up and follow the instructions of the surgeon, as directed.</p>\n<p><strong>Is It 100% Safe?</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik eye treatment is a surgery and like any other procedure of surgery, possibilities of occurrences of unexpected complications are unavoidable.</p>\n<p><strong>So, What Risks and Complications?</strong></p>\n<p>Most of the complications and risks post Lasik eye surgery are mild and can be successfully managed. The complications that are most commonly or frequently reported from this surgery are glare, halos, dry eyes or any small or minor disturbances of vision. However, most of these problems are temporary and can hardly be permanent. Though technically, significant vision loss is possible and other severe complications are possible, but are practically, very uncommon, because of the standard safety procedures taken place.</p>\n<p><strong>Suitability of Lasik</strong></p>\n<p>Usually suitability of Lasik eye surgery is decided by the surgeon, during the pre-op consultation. At the same time, associated risks, on the basis of the refractive error are also discussed, after analysis of your health, measurements of the cornea and overall health.</p>\n<p><strong>How To Increase Chances Of Success?</strong></p>\n<p>Every individual is unique and so the health conditions. It shows and indicates the fact that major to minor health issues and problems must be informed to the Lasik surgeon. It is quite important to ask plenty and every possible question and share one’s eye and body health condition, during preoperative consultation and eye exam. Both the attempts, no doubt, will decrease the possibilities of complications and risks thereby increasing the success of the surgery.</p>\n<p>Other important factor one has to explore before going through Lasik surgery is understand experience of the surgeon, which defines the least possible risk factor. You need to be aware of the other procedures for correction of vision, such as refractive lens exchange, phakic IOLs and PRK and the respective technologies adopted for each procedure.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>It is natural to think both pros and cons of any surgery, especially, sensitive surgeries, like Lasik eye surgery. It is almost unusual for any patient to go blind, after going through Lasik eye surgery. There are millions of procedures of Lasik have been taken place, with higher levels of effectiveness and safety, worldwide. There [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"which-type-of-lasik-surgery-is-the-best-2","date":"2019-08-29","title":"Which type of lasik surgery is the best?","category":"Comparisons","path":"/blog/2019/08/29/which-type-of-lasik-surgery-is-the-best-2","contentHtml":"<p>There are three vision corrective surgeries called Lasik, Lasek and PRK(Photorefractive Keratectomy) and all the three procedures attempt to reshape the cornea, though there are variations in the methods and approaches. So, an analysis is needed to find the best surgery of Lasik.</p>\n<p><strong>What is Laser Corrective Surgery for Eye?</strong></p>\n<p>According to the Centre for Excellence for Medical Multimedia, refractive surgery for correction of vision was started in ancient Greece and considering the modern refractive laser eye surgery, named PRK (photorefractive keratectomy) was performed in the year 1987. In these three decades, the eye procedure has been transformed completely to a bladeless procedure and is turned to be viable and customizable procedure. The procedure is developed to assure long-lastign and accurate correction of vision.</p>\n<p><strong>What Procedure for What Surgery…</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Laser Correction\n<ul>\n<li>Surface Surgery\n<ul>\n<li>LASEK</li>\n<li>PRK</li>\n<li>Epi-Lasik</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Flap Surgery\n<ul>\n<li>Intralase Lasik\n<ul>\n<li>Sub-Bowman’s Lasik</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Microkeratome Lasik</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>All these procedures are technically possible to be performed with wavefront-guided or non-wavefront-guided procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Risks and Complications</strong></p>\n<p>Though laser eye surgery is designed to be performed safe, no surgery can be assured to be totally risk-less. Before considering the laser surgeries, it is important to explore the possible risks and complications associated with these surgeries.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Astigmatism\n<ul>\n<li>The affected tissue has to be removed from the eye in order to change the shape of the cornea to correct refractive errors, like astigmatism, myopia. Astigmatism is possible in case the tissue is not evenly removed from the eye. This condition can be corrected with another surgery, glasses or contact lenses, further.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Overcorrection\n<ul>\n<li>When the tissue of the eye is removed in excess to revolve one refractive error, another refractive error can be created. This condition is difficult to resolve and fix.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Undercorrection\n<ul>\n<li>In case the procedure fails to remove all the affected tissue that caused the refractive error, the procedure is not complete. This condition further needs another surgery to complete correction.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Flap Complications\n<ul>\n<li>Flap complication is a condition of incorrect growth of the corneal tissues, under the flap that cause scare, for instance and there are many other complications related to the flap. It may possibility cause excess production of tear or potential infection. These flap complications can be arise both with the Lasek and Lasik procedures.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Light Halos and Glare\n<ul>\n<li>The condition of light halos and glare is possible, in which rings or glare are seen around the lights, post laser surgery. Most of the patients experience it in the conditions of low light, such as in night driving that gets affected from the brightness of the opposite vehicles or glare of street lights.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Temporary Dry Eye\n<ul>\n<li>Sometimes the regulation of production of the tears may be interrupted. It affects the overall vision and it demands frequent and regular usage of eye drops or artificial tears.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>LASIK</strong></p>\n<p>In the US, laser eye surgery is the most commonly performed surgery. Unlike the PRK, the procedure of Lasik is not painful or gives any kind of discomfort both after and during the surgical procedure.</p>\n<p>In the Lasik procedure, a small flap is created in the cornea, by folding it back for exposing through underlying tissue of cornea. Tissue reshaping is performed through excimer laser, followed by replacing of the corneal flap, after the respective and right amount of corneal tissue. The total procedure is completed in total 10 minutes of duration.</p>\n<p><strong>Side Effects</strong></p>\n<p>Post Lasik surgery, patients tend to experience the symptom of dry eye, since the production of tears is hindered temporarily. This condition can be bettered through eye drops, prescribed by your doctor. Apart from that any hazy or blurry vision has to be cleared in one day after the surgery. Anyhow some itching is possible and rubbing the eyes should be avoided to prevent any possible dislodging of the flap that may result in further and serious problems.</p>\n<p><strong>Results</strong></p>\n<p>Most of the patients after the Lasik procedure achieve the vision of 20/20 and some of them have small variations that may reach till 20/40 possibly.</p>\n<p><strong>LASEK</strong></p>\n<p>Lasik works better for most of the patients, except for the patients, who have thin corneas. Such thin corneas can be operated through Lasek surgery, assuring to yield the similar results, with less exposure of these thin corneas to damage, compared to the Lasik.</p>\n<p>In the Lasek procedure, instead of cutting the eye’s flap, alcohol solution is used by the ophthalmologists to lift the tissue’s top layer, farer from the site of the eye. The underlying corneal tissue will be exposed for reshaping, by folding this tissue back, using an excimer laser. Finally, outer tissue layer will be replaced.</p>\n<p><strong>Side Effects</strong></p>\n<p>Lasek procedure leaves different symptoms of side effects, compared to the Lasik procedure. Compared to Lasik procedure, the flap created after the procedure of Lasek tends to heal much slower. So, till a satisfied level of healing, the patient needs to wear a bandage in the form of special contact lens. The total healing takes about a week or more.</p>\n<p><strong>Results</strong></p>\n<p>After Lasek, patients can experience the vision of 20/20, with small tolerance in this vision that may reach to 20/40, in a very few cases.</p>\n<p><strong>PRK</strong></p>\n<p>PRK is preferred by the ophthalmologists for some patients, instead of Lasik procedure. It became less popular after Lasik has been developed. However, PRK experiences a good resurgence in these years recently.</p>\n<p>The procedure is performed by reshaping the underneath corneal tissue, instead of creation of flap on the eye’s surface. The cornea is reshaped directly externally, in this procedure. PRK has been third preference for many of the patients, because of increased discomfort level and demand more time for recovery. Usually, PRK is the preference as another option for the patients having thinner corneas, since any flap-related complications can be eliminated with it.</p>\n<p><strong>Side Effects</strong></p>\n<p>PRK has potential side effect of infection. Temporary dry eye and sensitivity to increased glare and light in conditions of low light are other side effects to expect occasionally.</p>\n<p><strong>Results</strong></p>\n<p>Like the other two procedures, patient can experience 20/20 vision after PRK with some possible tolerance and variation that can possibly reach the vision of 20/40.</p>\n<p><strong>Results after Surgery</strong></p>\n<p>After the laser surgical procedure, patients may have 20/20 vision and it is not uncommon that some degree of correction is also required through contact lenses or glasses after the surgery and yes far lesser prescription than before the surgery. And however, American Academy of Ophthalmology report that usually people after their forties need glasses for reading, irrespective of corrective surgery undergone, because of the age-related condition, called presbyopia. And presbyopia cannot be corrected with any surgical procedure, unfortunately.</p>\n<p><strong>Recovery</strong></p>\n<p>Recovery is an important factor and this period is proportional to the complication and intensity of the surgery performed. Recovery Time: Usually compared to the other two procedures, the recovery time is more for the PRK procedure. Post PRK, the eyesight is decreased a bit and starts recoverying and improving the vision, after a week or two. On the other hand, both Lasek and Lasik procedures heal the surgical site comparatively quickly and the eyesight gets improved from the very next day.</p>\n<p>After exploring all the three, it is easier to understand the best surgical procedure suitable and needless to mention, your doctor is the right person to recommend the suitable laser surgical procedure, based on your unique eyesight condition.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>There are three vision corrective surgeries called Lasik, Lasek and PRK(Photorefractive Keratectomy) and all the three procedures attempt to reshape the cornea, though there are variations in the methods and approaches. So, an analysis is needed to find the best surgery of Lasik. What is Laser Corrective Surgery for Eye? According to the Centre for [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-do-you-have-dry-eyes-after-lasik","date":"2019-08-28","title":"How long do you have dry eyes after lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/08/28/how-long-do-you-have-dry-eyes-after-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>Dry eyes are the complication resulted most commonly after the Lasik surgery, however, the condition is possible to set in control. The frequency of experiencing symptom is about 95% of the patients, who have undergone the Lasik surgery. The control of the condition is possible during the period of post-operation.</p>\n<p>In most of the cases, dry eye condition after Lasik procedure gets continuously better, over time. In certain instances and in case of less care or treatment of the dry eyes may also lead to chronic and severe dry eyes.</p>\n<p><strong>Long-Term Dry Eye</strong></p>\n<p>The condition of the long time dry eye is through rare, this condition is hard to predict after the Lasik procedure and the possible duration of the symptoms. The length of this condition may be long in the following conditions.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>When the patient is female</li>\n<li>In cases of correction of vision to a greater degree</li>\n<li>When the patient experienced the problem of dry eye, before attempting Lasik procedure</li>\n<li>When the patient is from Asia</li>\n<li>When the patient has prior experience of wearing the contacts</li>\n<li>When diabetes is attacked</li>\n<li>In case nearsightedness is experienced</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Why Dry Eye Condition After Lasik?</strong></p>\n<p>The cause for the dry eyes after the Lasik has not been completely understood by the researchers, however there are certain possible ideas. During the procedure of the Lasik, damage of corneal nerve is possible. It is because the cornea is reshaped by the surgeon, by removal of the tissues under the cornea. The nerve in this area may be cut to a certain extent and it is deliberately done as it does not affect the vision. However, it may result in break of communication, in between the tear glands and the cornea to some time. Ideally, this condition should be returned to a normal condition quickly.</p>\n<p>There is another cause for dry eyes, called inflammation, resulting from the surgery. The shape of the cornea can affect the interaction of the eyelid with the eye surface. It has direct relation and affect to the production of tear and also blinking. The result is the dry eye.</p>\n<p><strong>Possible Length of Period</strong></p>\n<p>According to the statistics of the patients, who have undergone the Lasik procedure, the condition is intense during the first month after the procedure and lasts in between 6 months to 12 months.</p>\n<p><strong>When to See Surgeon?</strong></p>\n<p>When the standard treatments are followed with the kinds of artificial tears, etc., properly, the dry eye problem can be resolved to a greater extent. In case the dry eye condition is severe and pain is felt, then you should see your doctor immediately. In case the condition is mild, it is fine to wait until your next appointment with the doctor.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Dry eyes are the complication resulted most commonly after the Lasik surgery, however, the condition is possible to set in control. The frequency of experiencing symptom is about 95% of the patients, who have undergone the Lasik surgery. The control of the condition is possible during the period of post-operation. In most of the cases, [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"how-long-does-it-take-to-get-clear-vision-after-lasik","date":"2019-08-24","title":"How long does it take to get clear vision after Lasik?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/08/24/how-long-does-it-take-to-get-clear-vision-after-lasik","contentHtml":"<p>How soon can one recover completely from the Lasik surgery and how soon will one be able to have better and clear vision? This is the first question arises by the patients and family members of the patients. The name of the surgery gives the hint for this answer. The surgery is performed through lasers, which involves no cutting or incisions physically. It indicates no cut and so faster cure than cutting and healing.</p>\n<p>Technically speaking, based on the patient’s severity of the vision problem and general health conditions and also on the success rate of the Lasik surgery, it takes one day to one week of time for complete visual recovery. Majority of the patients can get back to their regular and daily activities in one day or two, post surgery. Though almost every condition is unique and different, even legal driving vision can be achieved after 24 hours of duration. And it is the most welcoming benefit of choosing the Lasik surgery by many people. Faster recovery from the vision problems is the exciting advantage of this surgical procedure.</p>\n<p>Initially, after the Lasik surgery, vision may not be crisp and slight fluctuation may be felt. And it is quite normal and this condition is gradually improved day by day. Total recovery to get back to normal experience may take a week or two. Mostly, the visual acuity is checked by your doctor on the day after. The normal healing process is identified by the doctor and he or she ensures that the eyes are enough healthy to get completely recovered. Post operative visits are suggested after a couple of months to six months duration after the Lasik surgery. In most of the cases any kind of symptoms, such as glare, halos, dry eyes or any kind of visual disturbances can get fixed automatically. And if any of these symptoms continue, you should specify the same to your doctor, so that they can be fixed with the medication, recommended by the same doctor. However, the patient should continue to wet the eyes possibly with the artificial tears to help and fasten the healing process and ensure not to give stress to the eyes. Don’t worry about the side effects, if there are any of the side effects, those are rare and also temporary. Majority of the people experience clear and stable vision within a couple of months.</p>\n<p>So, it is clear that your vision will be better than the condition before the surgery in a couple of weeks and you would find that the Lasik surgery has improved quality of your life.</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>How soon can one recover completely from the Lasik surgery and how soon will one be able to have better and clear vision? This is the first question arises by the patients and family members of the patients. The name of the surgery gives the hint for this answer. The surgery is performed through lasers, [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"can-i-use-mobile-after-lasik-surgery","date":"2019-08-14","title":"Can I use mobile after Lasik surgery?","category":"Recovery","path":"/blog/2019/08/14/can-i-use-mobile-after-lasik-surgery","contentHtml":"<p>Both the procedures of Lasik eye surgery and laser corrections have varied durations for healing. Addressing about the general recovery time for Lasik eye surgery, usage of the mobile devices, televisions, computers, tablets and even any other kinds of digital screens must be avoided for a period of time. Not only the surgeries, but also the people have varied healing periods. Considering these two factors, technically a gap of 24 hours post operative duration is needed before attempting to use the mobile devices.</p>\n<p>To avoid any further complications and ensure to attain comfort to perform day to day activities, it is recommended that three days of gap should be given, before regular usage of the mobile phones and viewing any other digital screens.</p>\n<p>So, it refrains somebody from the delayed usage of the mobile phones, computers and tablets, for some time, it is quite significant to ensure that the eyes get relieved from any of these strains, caused from digital screens. When this is the general recommended duration, also make sure that you have a word with your doctor, before resuming to the regular usage of the mobile phones.</p>\n<p>Though this waiting period to resume to the regular mobile phone based lifestyle is not very long, it is necessary to understand that it is mandatory to follow and vital for complete recovery.</p>\n<p>Once you are confirmed to restart using the mobile phones, consider following a few tips, recommended by the experts. Take frequent breaks from using the digital screens, like mobile phones, televisions or computers. Ensure to use antibiotic and moisturizing the drops in the eyes, during these breaks. Keep blinking the eyes for many times, consciously, when you took the break. Get away from the computer and mobile screens and walk for at least one minute or 20 feet away from your desk at office or at home.</p>\n<p>There is nothing to worry, though you cannot catch and resume the usage of the mobile phones for a couple of days. Catch up your favourite music and refresh your mind. And take these days as the best personal time to plan your endeavours. In this day to day hurried life, take it as the best time to sleep as many times and as much time as you want, as it can lubricate the eyes automatically and fasten the process of healing.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>Both the procedures of Lasik eye surgery and laser corrections have varied durations for healing. Addressing about the general recovery time for Lasik eye surgery, usage of the mobile devices, televisions, computers, tablets and even any other kinds of digital screens must be avoided for a period of time. Not only the surgeries, but also [&hellip;]</p>\n"},{"slug":"lasik-laser-guidelines-army-marchant-navy-ssc-cpo-indian-railway-recruitment-central-armed-police-force-capf","date":"2018-11-21","title":"Lasik Laser Guidelines – Army, Marchant Navy, SSC, CPO, Indian Railway Recruitment, Central Armed Police Force (CAPF)","category":"Eligibility","path":"/blog/2018/11/21/lasik-laser-guidelines-army-marchant-navy-ssc-cpo-indian-railway-recruitment-central-armed-police-force-capf","contentHtml":"<p>The Indian Army, Navy, Air Force, and National Defence Academy (NDA) recruit Indian nationals for various positions in senior and junior capacities. The selection of the suitable candidates is strictly based on officially notified terms which include academic qualifications, reservation criteria, age limits and relaxation rules, physical fitness, and physical standards. All the above mentioned Defence services recruit eligible candidates in combat and noncombat roles. The recruitment for Armed Forces has high standards which include physical fitness, physical measurements in terms of height, weight, chest size, body mass index, eyesight, and overall state of physical fitness and health.</p>\n<p>Vision or eyesight is a very significant factor in making or breaking the candidates chances for recruitment to Armed Force Medical College(AFMC), Navy, Air Force, and NDA as entry level cadets, Junior Commissioned Officer (JCO), or other rank (OR) positions. The Indian military services are prestigious and physical and medical fitness requirements are strictly prescribed, particularly in terms of proper vision and eyesight. Candidates with normal vision of 20/20 in feet or 6/6 in metres do not face any disqualification issues during the physical endurance and medical examination rounds.</p>\n<p>Candidates who have eye conditions such as Myopia (short-sightedness) or Hypermetropia (long-sightedness) have to satisfy additional selection criteria. Those who received medical treatment including surgeries such as Laser Assisted in situ Keratomileusis (<a href=\"https://www.lasikindelhi.com/\">LASIK</a>) and / or Photorefractive Keratectomy (PRK) eye surgery also have to fulfil additional criteria. All these candidates are eligible for selection to Armed Forces in Engineering and Medical Services, but due to physical demands such candidates are selectively recruited. However, rules for filling up entry level positions in Navy, Air Force, NDA, JCO, and Other Rank (OR) do not permit candidates who received the above mentioned corrective surgeries and they are disqualified from appearing for further selection rounds.</p>\n<p>Vision Standards For NDA Recruitments</p>\n<p>National Defence Academy (NDA) recruits cadets for the three wings of the Indian Military i.e. the Army, Navy, and the Air Force. Candidates who passed 12th class or equivalent with Maths and Physics have to appear for written examination followed by physical standards test. The vision or eyesight requirements for these positions are listed below –</p>\n<p>Vision standard for Naval candidates</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Uncorrected without glass 6/6, 6/9</li>\n<li>Corrected with glass 6/6, 6/6</li>\n<li>Limits of Myopia –0.75</li>\n<li>Limits of Hypermetropia +1.5</li>\n<li>Binocular vision III</li>\n<li>Limits of colour perception I</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Vision standard for Air Force candidates</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Candidates who wear spectacles as a Habit are not eligible.</li>\n<li>Minimum distant vision 6/6 in one eye, and 6/9 in other eye</li>\n<li>Correctable for Hypermetropia up to 6/6 only.</li>\n<li>Color Vision: CP -I</li>\n<li>Myopia: Nil</li>\n<li>Retinoscopic Myopia – 0.5 in any Meridian</li>\n<li>Permitted Astigmatism : +0.75 D Cyl (within +2.0 D. Max) as per Maddox Rod Test</li>\n</ul>\n<p>LASIK/PRK Surgery Selection Criteria For Armed Forces</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Candidates should have undergone LASIK/PRK surgery after 20 years of age.</li>\n<li>LASIK/PRK for Myopia or Hypermetropia should be uncomplicated.</li>\n<li>The refraction flap should be stable for a 6 month period after surgery.</li>\n<li>Retina has to be in a clear and healthy condition.</li>\n<li>Corrected vision is 6/6 and 6/9 in better and worse eyes respectively.</li>\n<li>For Myopia or Hypermetropia, Maximum residual refraction in any meridian: +1.50</li>\n<li>The Army does not employ LASIK/PRK candidates for aircrew duties.</li>\n<li>Entry level candidates are also admitted into AFMC, Pune.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n","excerptHtml":"<p>The Indian Army, Navy, Air Force, and National Defence Academy (NDA) recruit Indian nationals for various positions in senior and junior capacities. The selection of the suitable candidates is strictly based on officially notified terms which include academic qualifications, reservation criteria, age limits and relaxation rules, physical fitness, and physical standards. All the above mentioned [&hellip;]</p>\n"}];
